<HEAD>APPENDIX.</HEAD>
<HEAD>The XIII Poems in the englisht Be Guilleville's 'Pilgrimage of the Soul.'<LB>Egerton MS. 615, Brit. Mus.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(1) The epistle of grace sent to the seek man. littera.<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[26 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1"><B>I'</B> Grac&euml; quen, and heuenly princesse,&mdash;</L>
<L>As depute<NOTE PLACE="foot">? MS. deprite.</NOTE> be the souereyn kyng eterne,</L>
<L>In erthe a-lowe to be the gyderesse</L>
<L>That<NOTE PLACE="foot">That = of him that. (Tags t r f &amp;c. are not printed.)</NOTE> liste the redy wey[&euml;]s for to lerne,</L>
<L N="5">In pilgrymag&euml; him selff to gouerne&mdash;</L>
<L>Gretyng, with yerde &amp; lore of disciplyne,</L>
<L N="7">To the that hast, and must be, one of myn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">It is me don to knowe &amp; vnderstonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, this deth&euml;s seruaunt, malady,</L>
<L>The hath arrest, and holdith now in hande,</L>
<L>And the oppressith, nought knowyng the forwhi.</L>
<L N="12">I wil therfore, as for thi remedy,</L>
<L>Ordeyne[n] in my best[&euml;] manere wise;</L>
<L N="14">I rede &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> that thi self &thorn;ou wel aduyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">I haue be with the whan thu knewe it nought,</L>
<L>Enserchyng, lo, thi poin[t]is of consc&iuml;ence,</L>
<L>Be wich I knewe the innermost of thought.</L>
<L>Thu hauest, thi self, with veari neclegence,</L>
<L N="19">And also for defawte of diligence,</L>
<L>Noght take heed to thi gouernaunce,</L>
<L N="21">Thi selff&euml; brought in anguysshe &amp; greuaunce.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="xxiv"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Thu hast, with surfeet, leuyng sobirnesse,</L>
<L>fful greuously encombred thi corage,</L>
<L>In lust dispending al thin besynesse,<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at thu were a childe of tender age,</L>
<L N="26">That the now doth ful gret disauauntage;</L>
<L>Wherfore the nature of thi maladye</L>
<L N="28">Wil ask&euml; sothly a fleobotomye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Also I see, &thorn;at ful art thu withinne</L>
<L>of c&oacute;rrupte humour al a-bowt[&euml;] spred,</L>
<L>That rennyth ay betwyn [&thorn;i] flesch and skynne,</L>
<L>That causith &thorn;at thu kepist now thi bedde:</L>
<L N="33">Than ydilnesse and slouth&euml; hath this bred;</L>
<L>Thu hast nought swet owt of thin eye one tere;</L>
<L N="35">Wich thing to the ful necessary were.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">For if thu myghtist, day&euml;s two or thre,</L>
<L>With mynde upon thi foul&euml; wrechidnesse</L>
<L>haue suche a sweet, it wolde avail&euml; the;</L>
<L>ffor leue it weel,&mdash;I sey it the expresse&mdash;</L>
<L N="40">but if thu do the rathere thi besynesse,</L>
<L>with suche a swet thi self[&euml;] to amende,</L>
<L N="42">This malady will of the make an ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">Take heed[&euml;] nowe, and to thi self conuerte,</L>
<L>And see what wrechidnesse is the withinne,</L>
<L>Or deth&euml; take thi liffe out of thin herte;</L>
<L>To be my reed, anon &thorn;at thu be-gynne</L>
<L N="47">To make the clen&euml; of thi sory synne,</L>
<L>As ferr&euml; [forth] as &thorn;ou canst think or spye,</L>
<L N="49">And wasshe hem out with ter&euml;s of thin eye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">For if &thorn;at deth the sudeynly assaile,</L>
<L>beleue it weel, he sparith no persone;</L>
<L>With him to trete, it may no thing avayle;</L>
<L>On the hath he no piete, thow thu grone;</L>
<L N="54">Complayntis sothly he rewardith none,
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="xxv"></L>
<L>But buskith you vnto the pitt&euml;s brynk:</L>
<L N="56">On this, I rede, thu besely bethink.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">Take heed, and here, how &thorn;at to euery wight</L>
<L>With-in[n&euml;]-forth he clepith preuely:<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Arayeth you, and be al redi dight,</L>
<L>ffor I wil come&mdash;beleve it sikerly&mdash;</L>
<L N="61">Or ye be ware, parauenture sudeynly:</L>
<L>And me by-for ther may [no] praiere spede</L>
<L N="63">Ne non ne wele: I spar&euml; for [no] mede."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">"Beholde and see, how &thorn;at this messageres,</L>
<L>lo, in await&euml;, [now] be leyd for the.</L>
<L>Sest thu noght Ag&euml;, with his whight&euml; eres,</L>
<L>hath had<NOTE PLACE="inline">[? hid]</NOTE> himselff ful nye,&mdash;canst thu not see?&mdash;</L>
<L N="68">And maladi[&euml;] hath arrest par-de.</L>
<L>Herist thu nowt, how thei crie lowde alwey,</L>
<L N="70">'what eilith vs, to tarye so al day?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">"How oft&euml; haue I warned the be-for,</L>
<L>Som while apert, somtym&euml; preuely,</L>
<L>That redy schuldist thu have be euermor:</L>
<L>Witnesse upon thi self, I say the, whi</L>
<L N="75">Thu might the nought excus&euml; vtterly:</L>
<L>Synderesis, she knowith euery deel;</L>
<L N="77">Sche will be thin app&eacute;lloure, wete it weel,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">"Aneinptes me, that alway wold thi prowe;</L>
<L>fful folili thu hast thi self mystake:</L>
<L>for thu behetest&mdash;this knowist well I-nowe&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle thin foli woldest thu for-sake,</L>
<L N="82">And woldest thi-self very clen&euml; make,</L>
<L>Puttyng [thi] flesch vnder subieccioun,</L>
<L N="84">To be gou&eacute;rned after thi reason.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="85">"But sekerly she euery deel reuerse</L>
<L>vsurped hath hire own&euml; ladi right,</L>
<L>By here delites and lust&euml;s full dyuers</L>
<L>Oppressyng her with alle hir mayn &amp; myght.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="xxvi"></L>
<L N="89">A fool is he (as semith in my sight)</L>
<L>That be no lore ne will his freend[is] knowe</L>
<L N="91">Till &thorn;at he be in myschief ouerthrowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">"But now I rede, take good entent &amp; hepe,<MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Puttyng awey thi slombre &amp; [thi] slouthe.</L>
<L>A fool he is, that leith him self to slepe,</L>
<L>To whom I springe, the veray sterre of trewthe.</L>
<L N="96">How ofte hast thu refused, for thi yowthe,</L>
<L>To her&euml; me? and sone hast thu for-yete</L>
<L N="98">Myn lusty song&euml;s veary hony-swete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">"Now sey me, be thi feith, whethir &thorn;ou were he</L>
<L>Alone of woman in this world I-bore,</L>
<L>So clene of wemme, that no thing is in the</L>
<L>To weyl&euml; ne to wepe thi synn&euml;s sore.</L>
<L N="103">Nay, sekerly&mdash;and &thorn;at me for-thinke sore&mdash;</L>
<L>That thu ne canst [nat] se thi wrechidnesse,</L>
<L>Thi synne, thi surfeet, and thin vnthriftynesse,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">"And hard conflicte of bataile, the withinne.</L>
<L>Thu fel&euml; myght (but if thu be vnwys),</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> sowle assailed is with synne,</L>
<L>And vnder-cast &thorn;ou art of hye malice,</L>
<L N="110">And subiecte, thu madist thi selfe, to vice,</L>
<L>Wich &thorn;at of god, the Juge omnipotent,</L>
<L N="112">Condempned is with-owt[en] iug&euml;ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">"Sham&euml; hath he &thorn;at at the cheker pleith,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at a powne saith to the kyng 'chek mate;'</L>
<L>And shame it is, whan that thi gost obeith</L>
<L>Vnto thi flessh, &thorn;at schuld obeye algate</L>
<L N="117">Vnto thi goost. And now, thowe it be late,</L>
<L>Yilte helpe thi self, and cast her vnder fote,</L>
<L N="119">Or elles &thorn;ou art lost: &thorn;ere is non other bote.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="120">"In batayl&euml;, as it hath ofte be-tydde</L>
<L>a myghti man to falle, it is no schame,</L>
<L>The first[&euml;] tyme, the secunde, and the thridde,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="xxvii"></L>
<L>And rysith weel&mdash;this holde I but a game;&mdash;</L>
<L N="124">But gretly, me thinkith, is he to blame,</L>
<L>And worthi as [a] fool to be reproeved,</L>
<L N="126">That not enforsith him to be releuyd.<MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">"Now youth&euml; may no lengere the excuse,</L>
<L>for age is come, and calengith his plase.</L>
<L>Yeld thi promyse! &thorn;ou myght it not refuse.</L>
<L>A fool is he &thorn;at desob&euml;yth grace,</L>
<L N="131">And is to meward fall&euml; in trespace,</L>
<L>And castith him nought &aacute;mendis to make:</L>
<L N="133">Suche one, what wondir is, though I forsake?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">"Ful long I haue a-beden and susteyned</L>
<L>to haue amend&euml;s for thi forfeture;</L>
<L>And or this tyme I haue me not compleyned.</L>
<L>I may no more the wrechidnesse endure:</L>
<L N="138">I rede the do<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to do.</NOTE> thi besynesse and cure;</L>
<L>Amende thi self; it is anow to me,</L>
<L N="140">That is the amend&euml;s &thorn;at I ask&euml; the.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">"Now chese thin port, at wich thu wilt aryve;</L>
<L>But to there ben, of solace and distresse:</L>
<L>At one, thow myght thi self[en] kepe a lyve,</L>
<L>And euere abide in ioye and lustynesse;</L>
<L N="145">That othir, is but care and wrechidnesse;</L>
<L>here com&euml; deth; and if &thorn;at he [schal] smyte</L>
<L N="147">Thi liffe, there is non leche that [may] respite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">"Se now thi self, that hauest no defence!</L>
<L>A-bove thin heed the swerd is redy drawe;</L>
<L>I red&euml; the to look thi consc&iuml;ence,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou hauest lyved a-geyn thi lorde-is lawe;</L>
<L N="152">And after this, a-nothir wey thu drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle thi tyme in foly so dispended,</L>
<L N="154">yit at the last[&euml;], lat it be amendyd.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="xxviii"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">"How oft&euml; tyme have I the tolde &amp; taught</L>
<L>The worthynesse of vertue, and the mede!</L>
<L>how ofte haue I the from the clowches caught</L>
<L>Of sathanas! yitte takist thu non heed.</L>
<L N="159">But now be ware, and nought withowt[&euml;] nede;</L>
<L>ffor sekirly the bowe is bent ful sore<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="161">To smyt&euml; the: than may I do no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">"The birde that syngith on a braunche on hye,</L>
<L>And schewith him self a lusty Jolyvet,</L>
<L>Vnto the deth is sinet sudeingly</L>
<L>Or he be ware, and tak&euml; with a net.</L>
<L N="166">I have the said, how deth hath the be-sette;</L>
<L>And almost vnder-myned is thi wall;</L>
<L N="168">But thu be ware, ful grevous is thi fall.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">"Allas! what thinkest thu? what wilt &thorn;ou sayn,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ilke day of anger and of dreed,</L>
<L>Vn-to the heigh&euml; Iug&euml; souereyne?</L>
<L>What dost &thorn;ou, man? whi takist thu non hede?</L>
<L N="173">If &thorn;ou wilt be releuyd in thi nede,</L>
<L>What helpith it, thus [for] to preche and teche?</L>
<L N="175">But schewe thi soore, to me &thorn;at am thi leche,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">"And [than] I schal a-voyde the of thi fylthe,</L>
<L>receyvyng the anon vnder my cure.</L>
<L>I schal the bringe in redynesse of tylthe,</L>
<L>So that [thu] schalt thi selff[e] weel assure,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at whan thi flesch is laid in sepulture,</L>
<L>Thu schalt be haved up in-to heven blisse;</L>
<L N="182">Eternall myrth&euml;s schalt &thorn;ou neuere mysse."</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(2) The chartre of pardon.</HEAD>
<P>[14 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Ihesu, kyng of hie heuen a-bove,<MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnto Michael my chief lieu-tenaunt,
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="xxix"></L>
<L>And alle thin &aacute;ssessour&euml;s wich I love,</L>
<L>That in my seruice be pers&eacute;ueraunt</L>
<L N="5">have euermore, and to me ful pleasaunt&mdash;</L>
<L>My gretyng;&mdash;and, upon the peyne of dreed,</L>
<L N="7">Vnto this present chartre take[th] heed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Me hath be-sought, this present ladi here,</L>
<L>Misericorde; and at hire gret instaunce,</L>
<L>And also eek myn own&euml; modier dere&mdash;<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That alway redi is, at hire pleasaunce,</L>
<L N="12">ffor synful men to mak&euml; purueaunce</L>
<L>Above thei have me bede; wich, of my grace,</L>
<L N="14">Graunted hath, hire prayer have his place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">Ther be pilgrym&euml;s (as thei certifie)</L>
<L>That to meward hire wei&euml;s had [i]take,</L>
<L>Wich have mysgon, and erred folily</L>
<L>Be steryng of the foul&euml; bestis blake,</L>
<L N="19">That som of hem hire iourney had forsake,</L>
<L>And efte hire iourney have a-geyn be-gunne,</L>
<L N="21">But sudei[n]gly hath failed him the sonne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Some have be lettid be foule temptac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>And steryng of hire fleschly wrechidnesse;</L>
<L>So, be disease and tribulac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Thei have [i]falle in-to huge hevynesse;</L>
<L N="26">And somme also to this worldes besynesse</L>
<L>So greuously hire hert&euml;s ouersette,</L>
<L N="28">So &thorn;at thei have of hire iourn&eacute;y be lette.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">But thei haue[n] repented wondir sore,</L>
<L>Some of hem, but at hir&euml; lyv&euml;s ende;</L>
<L>&amp; somme of hem, a litel what be-fore</L>
<L>Be-gan him self&euml; somwhat to amende,</L>
<L N="33">In wil theraftir neuer to offende,</L>
<L>But schreven hem of alle hire olde trespace,</L>
<L N="35">And put them self[&euml;] only in my grace.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="xxx"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">At the instaunce of myn owne modier swete&mdash;</L>
<L>To whom I may no maner thing denye,</L>
<L>And mercy also may I nought for-gete;</L>
<L>But vnto hir bone I wil myself applie:&mdash;</L>
<L N="40">This grace I graunte them of my Regalye,</L>
<L>That I schal hem receyve vnto my peas;</L>
<L N="42">Of hell&euml; peyne I graunte hem ful relees.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">So thei that han me, Ihesu, mercy cried</L>
<L>Or that the breeth out of the body yeed,<MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And alle hire wrechid lustys have defied</L>
<L>In veray faith (as techith hem the crede)</L>
<L N="47">So &thorn;at ye schal not a-geyn hem procede</L>
<L>As to iuge hem to hell&euml; [bittre] peyne,</L>
<L N="49">But that in this, your rygoure ye restreyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">And thow &thorn;at hir wikked<NOTE PLACE="foot">? wikke.</NOTE> workis counterpeise</L>
<L>hire good[&euml;] ded&euml;s whan thei schul be weye,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at the beter part hem self&euml; reyse</L>
<L>As for defawte of weighte, yit thus I seye</L>
<L N="54">And will, &thorn;at [to] this chartre ye obeye,</L>
<L>Wich I have graunted for my modier sake:</L>
<L N="56">To mercy also her have I [i-]take.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">Of tresour of my bitter pass&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>And of the merite of my modier der&mdash;</L>
<L>To whom non othir hath comparysoun&mdash;</L>
<L>With merite of myn seint&euml;s alle in fer,</L>
<L N="61">That to my biddyng ful obeysaunt were,</L>
<L>Of plente and of superh&aacute;bundaunce</L>
<L N="63">A forcet ful, wich puttith in the balaunce,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">The countirpeis a-geyn the fendis part,</L>
<L>So that he faile of his entenc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>To bring&euml; hem, so with his subtile art,</L>
<L>To be iuged [vn-]to dampnac&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="68">Withowt ony comfort of saluacioun,
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="xxxi"></L>
<L>With cursidnesse of alle the synn&euml;s sevene,</L>
<L N="70">Syn the<NOTE PLACE="foot">Since that, since the time.</NOTE> that he was chased owt of hevene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">And nought for-thi,&mdash;this is not myn entent,&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne for this cause my blood ne shadde I nought,</L>
<L>That ony wight in mysgou&eacute;rn&euml;ment</L>
<L>A-bid&euml; schulde, and trust[en] in his thought</L>
<L N="75">That this chart[r]e schulde [him] a-vaile[n] ought</L>
<L>As of this pardon to be partenere,</L>
<L N="77">Or of this grace &thorn;at I haue graunted her.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">Therfore, owt of this chartre I excepte<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To all&euml; which, vnto hir lyv&euml;s ende,</L>
<L>Have euermore in cursed synn&euml;s slepte,</L>
<L>Purposyng nowt hire lyv&euml;s to amende,</L>
<L N="82">Vpon trust here-of, hem self&euml; to defende</L>
<L>ffrom hell&euml; peyn&euml;, be this present grace,</L>
<L N="84">Alle tho &thorn;at schal be exiled fro my face;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="85">And this also, wich that be obstynat,</L>
<L>and never wil [vn]to my lawe obeye;</L>
<L>This also &thorn;at be veray desperat,</L>
<L>That wil no grac&euml; ne no mercy pray,</L>
<L N="89">But right so in hire cursed synn&euml;s deye:</L>
<L>To them is due the hot&euml; fier of helle,</L>
<L N="91">With Sathanas eternally to dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">Wherfore, no man so bold&euml; ne so hardy be,</L>
<L>Trustyng upon this present pardonaunce,</L>
<L>To surfeet or to synne in no degre,</L>
<L>Vpon the trust of fynal r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L N="96">Wich is my gifte; and aftir my pleasaunce</L>
<L>I geve it him &thorn;at schul myn mercy crave,</L>
<L N="98">withowt[en] wich, no wight [ne] wil I save.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. crave.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000034.tif" N="xxxii">
<HEAD>(3) Cantus peregrinorum.<MILESTONE N="29" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[5 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Honowred be thu, blissed lord on hye,</L>
<L>That of the blisful mayd&euml; were I-bore,</L>
<L>That with thi deth us boughtist myght[i]ly:</L>
<L>Thin own&euml; flesch and blood, &thorn;ou gaue us fore,</L>
<L N="5">And for us suffred peyn&euml;s wonder sore,</L>
<L>Bothe foot and hand [i]nayled to the rode,</L>
<L N="7">And bledest alle thin veray hert[es] bloode!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Honowred be thu, fadir souereigne,</L>
<L>That vowchedsaff suche raunsom [us] to sende</L>
<L>Thin own&euml; lov&euml;d sone to suffre peyne,</L>
<L>Oure mysease &amp; myschief [for] to amende!</L>
<L N="12">Thu holigost, &thorn;at art withowt[en] ende,</L>
<L>With fadier &amp; sone, one god in trinite,</L>
<L N="14">ffor euere honured be thi maieste!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">And thu, [o] blisful maide &amp; modier mylde,</L>
<L>Thu lady, qween of heven, emperice,</L>
<L>Whom Ihesu chees; and as thi own&euml; childe</L>
<L>Thow bare, his veray modiere &amp; noryce,</L>
<L N="19">Thu floure of vertue, modiere of delice,</L>
<L>Thu toure of trist, and [trew] tresoure of grace,</L>
<L N="21">honowred mote thu be in euery place!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Honowred be &thorn;ou, blissed lord Ihesu,</L>
<L>Suche grace and mercy have we found in the;</L>
<L>Suche godlihede, suche myght &amp; suche vertue,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at we in purg&aacute;tory haue be!</L>
<L N="26">Of alle oure peynes, relesed now be we,</L>
<L>Wich long[&euml;] tyme we have a-byden inne,</L>
<L N="28">But wonder schort, in r&eacute;gard of oure synne,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">With whiche we have the souereyn blisfulheed</L>
<L>fful grevously displeasyd &amp; offended,<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="xxxiii"></L>
<L>In word &amp; werk, &amp; with vnthryfty dede;</L>
<L>But thanked be thu, lord, it is amended;</L>
<L N="33">But now is alle oure noyows laboure ended;</L>
<L>To the we come, as fyne of oure labour,</L>
<L N="35">Whom willeth eueri trew&euml; trauayloure.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(4) What tyme &thorn;at the pilgrymes had songyne in this wise, hire aungeles wiche &thorn;at led them, ansuerid a-nothir song ful swete &amp; ful delicious, as it sewith: Cantus angelorum.</HEAD>
<P>[5 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">All-myghti lord, oure blisful lord Ihesu,</L>
<L>Thu myroure of the fadier in maieste,</L>
<L>In whom is seyn his myght and his vertue,</L>
<L>The welle of witte &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &amp; of.</NOTE> wisdaum is in the,</L>
<L N="5">To whom-is<NOTE PLACE="foot">whos.</NOTE> presence now retourned we be</L>
<L>With this pylgrym&euml;s which to the we bringe;</L>
<L N="7">To thin honoure ful ioyefully we synge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Toward&euml;s the, ful longe thei haue trauayled;</L>
<L>Thu wost thi selfe, how thei han be distressed.</L>
<L>The fals&euml; feend so sor&euml; hem asseyled,</L>
<L>And greuously diseased &amp; oppressed;</L>
<L N="12">But be thi grace, his malice was repressed,</L>
<L>And thrughe thy<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. his.</NOTE> mercy weel th[e]i be releved,</L>
<L N="14">And hire entent, fully thei han acheved.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">What laboure &amp; what anguysch have we had,</L>
<L>Sithe &thorn;at we took them in oure gouernaunce,</L>
<L>Thu wost Ihesu; and now, [lord,] we be gladde</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at we have don to thi pleasaunce;</L>
<L N="19">Wherfore thu wilt with reward us auaunce</L>
<L>Suche as the list a-bove[n] in thi blisse;</L>
<L N="21">Eternall Ioye, we schul it neuere mysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Lo, we presente in-to thin hand a-geyn,</L>
<L>alle-myghty lord, &thorn;at to vs &thorn;ou hast betake,
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="xxxiv"></L>
<L>honured be thu, Ihesu souereyn,</L>
<L>Of that we have lab&oacute;ur&euml;d for thi sake,</L>
<L N="26">Of this labour&euml;, now an ende thu make!</L>
<L>Thi cr&euml;atur&euml;s, vnto thi presence,<MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="28">Receyve hem of thin heighe benevolence!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">For thow [that] thei<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. thine.</NOTE> han erred or myswent,</L>
<L>Thei have it a-bought with wound&euml;s hard &amp; sore,</L>
<L>And purgeid with grete peyne &amp; [with] torment,</L>
<L>And duely to hem was Iug&euml;d therfore,</L>
<L N="33">Alle-thow thei hadde deserued much&euml; more,</L>
<L>The remenaunt is relessed, of thi grace;</L>
<L N="35">In heven is assigned hir&euml; place.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(5) The aungelys song within.<MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[7 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Al worshippe, wisdam, welthe and worthinesse,</L>
<L>All bounte, beawte, ioye and blisfulheed,</L>
<L>All honure, vertue, and alle myghtynesse,</L>
<L>All grace &amp; thankyng, vnto thin godheede,</L>
<L N="5">ffrom whom alle grace &amp; mercy doth procede!</L>
<L>Ay praised be thu, lord, in Trinite,</L>
<L N="7">And euere honured be thi maieste!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">That be mankynde oure nombre is encreased,</L>
<L>Of this that longe have be in pilgrymage;</L>
<L>And now is alle hire noyows laboure cessed,</L>
<L>That was be-gonne here first[&euml;] day&euml;s age.</L>
<L N="12">Here is the port of sekire &aacute;ryu&aacute;ge</L>
<L>Honured be thu, blissed lord on hye,<MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="14">And wolcome be ye to owre companye!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">Now passed be youre perilous auentures,</L>
<L>and alle youre Auenture hath an end&euml; take.</L>
<L>Right wolcome be ye, blissed cr&euml;atures!</L>
<L>Tyme it is, &thorn;at scrippe &amp; burdon ye forsake,</L>
<L N="19">ffor now ye schal no longere iourne make;
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="xxxv"></L>
<L>and aftir laboure, tyme is of quiete;</L>
<L N="21">Alle hevinesse &amp; Anguysch is for-gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">For ye have don a nobill victory,</L>
<L>And youre labour&euml; nobly d&iacute;spended,</L>
<L>That so ageyn youre treble enemye</L>
<L>Youre selff&euml; myghtely haue d&eacute;fendid;</L>
<L N="26">And &thorn;at ye have mysdon, it is amended</L>
<L>Be sustenaunce of purgatory peyne;</L>
<L N="28">Thanked be thu, [o] Ihesu souereyne!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">In heven blisse, here schul ye be with vs</L>
<L>Vnto the day of fynall iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L>To wich&euml; day ye schul a-byd&euml; thus,</L>
<L>And preis&euml; god with al youre hool entent,</L>
<L N="33">While &thorn;at youre bodi, be assign&euml;ment</L>
<L>Of god, is turned to correpc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="35">And fully schal haue hire purgacioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">For Reasoun [sayeth] wele, &amp; god-is lawe,</L>
<L>That he &thorn;at hath don alle his besynesse</L>
<L>(ffor god-is will) youre lust&euml;s to withdrawe&mdash;</L>
<L>Encombryng yow with muche vnthryftynesse,&mdash;</L>
<L N="40">That from &thorn;at fowle and wofull wrechidnesse</L>
<L>I-clensid be, and alle renewyd clene</L>
<L N="42">That manere weye, youre flesch is, &thorn;at I mene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">So at the last[&euml;] day thei schal a-ryse,</L>
<L>And come be-fore that Iug&euml; souereyn,</L>
<L>To yow conioyned in a wondere wise</L>
<L>In a good &aacute;ccorde withowt ony peyne,</L>
<L N="47">And in this ioye eternally remayne.<MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>What ioye is here, ye schul assaye &amp; see,</L>
<L N="49">Honured be the hey[&euml;] maieste!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000038.tif" N="xxxvi">
<HEAD>(6) [The Angels' Song. Honour to Jesus.]</HEAD>
<P>[5 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Honured be thu, blisful lord Ihesu,<MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>and preysed mote thu be in eueri place,</L>
<L>So full of myght, [of] mercy and vertue,</L>
<L>Of blisse, of bounte, of piete and of grace!</L>
<L N="5">Who is honur&euml;, may no thing deface;</L>
<L>Who is [ther] that withstond&euml; may thi myght?</L>
<L N="7">But serv&euml; the, of fors mote eueri wight.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Hon&uacute;red be thu, Ihesu, heven kyng,</L>
<L>That hast be-taken to my gouernaunce<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Suche one that hath, a-bove al othire thing,</L>
<L>Abowed to the with lowely obeysaunce,</L>
<L N="12">And loued the with sadde pers&eacute;ueraunce,&mdash;</L>
<L>Thi counseil and thin hey comaund&euml;ment</L>
<L N="14">Obseruyng with his hertely hool entent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">He hath nought walked be the wey[&euml;]s large,</L>
<L>That to the worlde so lusty be, &amp; grene;</L>
<L>But he hath be ententif to thi charge,</L>
<L>ffrom dedly synne to kepe him self&euml; clene,</L>
<L N="19">And gon to the wey of trauayle &amp; of tene,</L>
<L>Of penaunce and of tribulac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="21">In grevous form&euml;s of temptac&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">So hath he had in erthe his purgat&oacute;rye,</L>
<L>wich &thorn;at he hath susteyned wilfully;</L>
<L>Wherfor&euml;, now receyve him to thi glorye,</L>
<L>And take him up in[to] thi blisse an hye,</L>
<L N="26">with the to be in ioye eternally,</L>
<L>In what degre that to him is condigne,</L>
<L N="28">Right as thi selff&euml; liketh to assigne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Honoured be thu, Ihesu graciows,</L>
<L>That man became thi selfe, for mann&euml;s nede;</L>
<L>And man thu taughtist to be vertuows,</L>
<L>To serv&euml; the be veray love &amp; dreed,
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="xxxvii"></L>
<L N="33">Rewardyng hem with blisse for hir&euml; mede</L>
<L>That don hire devoire as thei may &amp; kan:</L>
<L N="35">Thanked be thu, [o] Ihesu, god and man!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(7) A lamentacioun of the grene tree, complaynyng of the losyng of hire appill.</HEAD>
<P>[40 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Ofader god, how fers &amp; how cruel,<MILESTONE N="63" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In whom the list or wilt, canst &thorn;ou the make!</L>
<L>Whom wilt thu spare? ne wot I neuere a deel,</L>
<L>Sithe thu thi sone hast to the deth be-take,</L>
<L N="5">That the offended neuere, ne dide wrake,</L>
<L>Or mystook him to the, or disobeyde,</L>
<L N="7">Ne to non othere dide he harm, or seide.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">I had ioye &eacute;ntiere, &amp; also gladnesse,<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ou be-took him me to clothe &amp; wrappe</L>
<L>In mann&euml;s flesch. I wend, in sothfastnesse,</L>
<L>Have had for euere Ioy&euml; be the lappe;</L>
<L N="12">But now hath sorwe caught me with his trappe;</L>
<L>Mi ioye hath made a permutacioun</L>
<L N="14">With wepyng &amp; eek lamentacioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">O holy gost, &thorn;at art alle comfortoure</L>
<L>Of woful hert&euml;s that wofull&euml; be,</L>
<L>And art hire veray helpe &amp; counceyloure,</L>
<L>That [eke] of hey vertue shad&oacute;wist me</L>
<L N="19">Whan &thorn;at the clernesse of thi diuinite</L>
<L>So shynyng in my feerful gost alight,</L>
<L N="21">Which that me sore agasted &amp; affright,&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Whi hast thu me not in thi r&eacute;membraunce</L>
<L>Now at this tym&euml;, right as thu had tho?</L>
<L>O whi is it noght [vn-]to thin pleasaunce</L>
<L>Now for to schadwe me as weel also,</L>
<L N="26">That hid from me myght be my son&euml;s woo?</L>
<L>Wherof, if &thorn;at I may no counfort haue,</L>
<L N="28">ffrom deth-is strok there may no thing me save.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="xxxviii"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">O gaubriel, whan &thorn;at thu come a place,</L>
<L>And madest vnto me thi salewyng,</L>
<L>And seidist thus: "heil, Mary, ful of grace!"</L>
<L>Whi ne had thu gov&euml; [to] me warnyng</L>
<L N="33">Of &thorn;at grac&euml; that veyn is and faylyng?</L>
<L>As thu now seest, &amp; sey it weel beforne,</L>
<L N="35">Sith my ioye is me rafte, my grace is lorne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">O thu elizabeth, my cosyn dere,</L>
<L>The word[&euml;s] &thorn;at thu spak in the mountayne</L>
<L>Be ended al in &aacute;-noth&eacute;re manere</L>
<L>Than thu had wened; my blissyng in-to peyne</L>
<L N="40">Retorned is; of ioye am I bareyne;</L>
<L>I song to sone; for I sang be the morwe,</L>
<L N="42">And now at evene I wepe and mak&euml; sorwe.<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)<NOTE PLACE="head">See <I>Minor Poems I</I>, p. 1-8.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="43">O woman, &thorn;at among the poepil speke,</L>
<L>how that the womb&euml; blissed was &thorn;at bere,</L>
<L>And the tet&yacute;s &thorn;at gave to sowk&euml; eek</L>
<L>The sone of god, the which &thorn;at hongith hire,</L>
<L N="47">What seist &thorn;ou now? whi comest &thorn;ou not nere?</L>
<L>Whi art thu not here? a, woman! where art thu,</L>
<L N="49">That noght ne seest my woful body nowe?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">O Symeon, &thorn;ou seidist me ful sothe,</L>
<L>"the strook &thorn;at perch&euml; schal my sones herte,</L>
<L>Myn sowle eek thirle it schal"; &amp; so it doth;</L>
<L>The wonde of deth [ne] may I not astirte;</L>
<L N="54">There may no martirdam me mak&euml; smerte</L>
<L>So sore as this mart&iacute;rdam smertith me:</L>
<L N="56">So schuld he sey, &thorn;at myght myn hurt&euml; see.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">O Ioachim, a, der&euml; fadir myn,</L>
<L>And thu seint anne, my dere modire also,</L>
<L>To what entent, or to what ende or<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. of]</NOTE> fyne</L>
<L>Engendred ye, me &thorn;at am greved soo?</L>
<L N="61">Mirthe to me is become a veray foo:
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="xxxix"></L>
<L>Youre fadire dauid, &thorn;at an harpowre was,</L>
<L N="63">Conforted men &thorn;at stod in hevy cas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">Me thinkith ye do not to me aright,</L>
<L>that were his s&uacute;ccessoures, sith instrument</L>
<L>Have ye non left, wherwith to hau&euml; light,</L>
<L>And me counfort in my woful turment.</L>
<L N="68">Me to [doon] es&euml;, have ye no talent,</L>
<L>And know&euml; my counfort[e]les distresse:</L>
<L N="70">Ye aught to wep&euml; for myn hevynesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">O blissed sone, on the wil I owt-throwe</L>
<L>My salt[&euml;] teres; for singulerly on the</L>
<L>My loke is sette. o, thinke how many a throwe</L>
<L>Thu on myn arm&euml;s lay, and on my knee</L>
<L N="75">Thu sat, &amp; had many a cusse of me;</L>
<L>Also, the to sowke, of my brestis yaf I,<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="77">Th&eacute; norissching [right] faire &amp; tenderly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">Now the, from me, withdrawith bitter deth,</L>
<L>And makith a wrong[ful] disseueraunce.</L>
<L>Think &thorn;ou not, sone, in me &thorn;at ony breth</L>
<L>Endur&euml; may, &thorn;at fele al this greuaunce.</L>
<L N="82">Mi martirdom, me hath at vtteraunce;</L>
<L>I ned&euml;s sterv&euml; mot, sith I the see</L>
<L N="84">Shamefully naked, streit upon this tree.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="85">And this me sleth, that in the open day</L>
<L>Thin hertis wond&euml; schewith him so wide,</L>
<L>That all&euml; men see and be-holde it may,</L>
<L>So larg&euml;ly, lo, open&egrave;d is thi side;</L>
<L N="89">O, wo is me, &thorn;at sith I may not hide!</L>
<L>And, among other of my smert[&euml;] grev&euml;s,</L>
<L N="91">Thu art now put also among [the] thev&euml;s,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">As thowe, my sone, had be a wiked wight.</L>
<L>And lest &thorn;at som men also, perauenture,
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="xl"></L>
<L>No knowleche had of thi persone a-right,</L>
<L>Pilate hath put up thi name in scripture,</L>
<L N="96">That know&euml; it may eueri cr&euml;ature,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at thi penaunce schuld[&euml;] not be hid.</L>
<L N="98">O, wo is me, &thorn;at see alle this beted!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">How may my eyn&euml; [&thorn;at] be-holde alle this,</L>
<L>Refreyn&euml; hem to schew&euml; by wepyng</L>
<L>Myn hert[es] greef? mot I not wepe? o, yis.</L>
<L>Sone, if thu hadist here, fadire lievyng,</L>
<L N="103">&THORN;at wold&euml; wepe and mak&euml; weymentyng</L>
<L>ffor cause he had[de] part in thi persone,</L>
<L N="105">That were [a] gret abreggyng of my mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">But thu, in erth&euml;, fadir had[dist] neuere;</L>
<L>No wight for the, suche cause hath for to wepe,</L>
<L>As now haue I. schalt thu fro me disseuere,</L>
<L>That art all hooly myn? my sorwes deepe</L>
<L N="110">Have all myn hert-is ioy&euml;s leyd to slepe.<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No wight with me, in the, my sone, hath part;</L>
<L N="112">Alle holy of my blod, dere child, &thorn;ou art.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">That dowbleth al my torment &amp; my greef;</L>
<L>Vn-to myn hert it is confus&iuml;on,</L>
<L>Thi harme to see, &thorn;at art to me so leef.</L>
<L>Myght not this raunsom or redempc&iuml;on</L>
<L N="117">Of man, have be withowt effusyon</L>
<L>Of thi blood? Yis, if it had be thi lust;</L>
<L N="119">But what &thorn;at it be do, suffre the must.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="120">O deth, &thorn;at so kithest thi bittirnesse,</L>
<L>ffirst on my sone, and afterward on me,</L>
<L>Bittere art thu, and ful of crabydnesse,</L>
<L>That thus my sone hast slayne with cruelte,</L>
<L N="124">And noght me slest! certayn I wil not flee.</L>
<L>Come of, come [of], and slee me here, as blyff;<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. be lyff]</NOTE></L>
<L N="126">ffro him depart&euml; wil I not a-lyffe.
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="xli"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">O mones, o sterr&euml;s, and thou<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. the]</NOTE> firmament,</L>
<L>how may ye nowe from wepyng yow restreyne,</L>
<L>And see youre cr&euml;ature in suche torment?</L>
<L>Ye owght, tourbled to be in euery veyne,</L>
<L N="131">And his dispietows deth with me compleyne.</L>
<L>Wepith and crieth as lowde as euere ye may!</L>
<L N="133">Oure cr&euml;ature with wrong is slayn this day!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">O Sonn&euml;, with thi cleer&euml; bemys bright,</L>
<L>That seest my child nak&eacute;d this non-is tyde,</L>
<L>Whi suffrist him [thou] in the open sight</L>
<L>Here of this men, vncovered to abide?</L>
<L N="138">Thu art, as muche or more, holde him to hide,</L>
<L>Than<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. Tham]</NOTE> Sem &thorn;at heled his fadir Noe</L>
<L N="140">Whan he aspyed &thorn;at naked so was he.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">If thu his son&euml; be, do like there-to!</L>
<L>let see with-drawe thi bem&euml;s bright[e]nesse:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art to blame, but if &thorn;at thu so do.</L>
<L>ffor schame, hide my sones nakidnesse!<MILESTONE N="65b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="145">Is there in the no droppe of kend&euml;nesse?</L>
<L>Remembre, he is thi lord &amp; cr&euml;ature;</L>
<L>Now covere him for thi worshippe and honoure!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">O erthe, what lust hast thu, so to susteyne</L>
<L>The crosse on which he &thorn;at the made, and it,</L>
<L>Is hong&euml;d, and adorn&euml;d the with grene</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at thu on weredist? how hast thu the qwitte</L>
<L N="152">Vnto thi lord? o, do this for him yitte!</L>
<L>Now qwak&euml; yow for dool, &amp; clev&euml; thu in two,</L>
<L N="154">And alle &thorn;at blood, restor&euml; thu me to,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">Which &thorn;ou hast drunken: it is myn, &amp; not thin.</L>
<L>Or elles thus, with owt[en] tarieng,</L>
<L>Tho bodies deed[&euml;] which &thorn;at in the lyne,</L>
<L>Cast owt: for thei be taste<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. tasted]</NOTE> of such dewyng</L>
<L N="159">hem owt to clothe<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. calle hem]</NOTE> a-geyn in hire clothing.</L>
<L>Thu Caluary, art hold&euml;, nam&euml;ly</L>
<L N="161">So for to do: parde, to the speke I.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="xlii"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">O der&euml; sone, my deth now neighith fast,</L>
<L>Sith to a-nothere thu hast goven me,</L>
<L>Than vnto the; And how may my liffe last,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me gevest to ony othere than to the,</L>
<L N="166">Thow [it] so be that he a virgyne bee?</L>
<L>if thu, be Iuste Balaunce, woldest wey all,</L>
<L N="168">The weight of him &amp; the is not egall.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">He a disciple is; thu art his lord;</L>
<L>Thu alwey art gretter&euml; than he is;</L>
<L>Be-twyn youre myghtis is there gret discorde.</L>
<L>My woful turnement<NOTE PLACE="inline">[torment]</NOTE> dowblyd is be this;</L>
<L N="173">I ned&euml;s morn&euml; must, &amp; fare a-mysse.</L>
<L>it semith &thorn;at thu makist d&eacute;partyng</L>
<L N="175">Of the &amp; me, for ay withowt endyng;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">And,<NOTE PLACE="inline">[? MS.]</NOTE> namely, sith thu me but "woman" callest,</L>
<L>As I to the were straunge &amp; al vnknowe;</L>
<L>There-throw, my sone, my Ioy&euml;s thu appallest;<MILESTONE N="66" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Weel fele I th&aacute;t deth h&iacute;s venge&aacute;bill bowe</L>
<L N="180">hath bent, &amp; me purp&oacute;sith doun to throwe;</L>
<L>Of sorwe, tak&euml; may I not Inowe,</L>
<L N="182">Sith [that] my nam&euml; don awey is nowe:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="183">Wel may men calle or nam&euml; me "marra"</L>
<L>Fro<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. For.</NOTE> hen[ne]s forth; and so men may me calle.</L>
<L>How schuld I longere be called 'M&aacute;ria,'</L>
<L>Sith 'I,' which is Ihesus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Sith he the which is called <ABBR>Ihc</ABBR>.</NOTE> is fro me falle</L>
<L N="187">This day, and my swetnesse [is] in-to galle</L>
<L>Turned, sith 'I'<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he.</NOTE> which was the b&euml;awte,</L>
<L N="189">Lo, of my name, this day beraft is me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="190">O Iohn, my der&euml; frende, thu hast receyved</L>
<L>A woful modier; &amp; an hevi sone</L>
<L>have I of the. deth hath myn other veyued:
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="xliii"></L>
<L>How may we two the deth eschewe or schone?</L>
<L N="194">We drery wight&euml;s two, where may we wone?</L>
<L>Thu art of counfort destitute, I se,</L>
<L N="196">And so am I! o, carefull now be we!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="197">Un-to oure hert&euml;s, deth hath sent his wonde;</L>
<L>Non of vs may allegen othir-is peyne;</L>
<L>So many sorwis in vs two abounde,</L>
<L>We haue no myght fro<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. for]</NOTE> sorwe vs to restreyne.</L>
<L N="201">I se non othir, but dey&euml; mot we tweyne;</L>
<L>Now let vs sterv&euml; here be companye:</L>
<L N="203">Sterv&euml; thu there, &amp; right here I wil dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="204">O Aungeles, the&iuml;<NOTE PLACE="inline">[though]</NOTE> ye morn&euml;, wayle &amp; wepe,</L>
<L>Ye do no wrong; for slayn is youre cr&eacute;atoure,</L>
<L>Be the poepil &thorn;at ye were wont to kepe,</L>
<L>To gide &amp; lede: thei to the ded&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="inline">[death's]</NOTE> schowre</L>
<L N="208">have put him. thow ye have wo &amp; langoure,</L>
<L>No wonder is it: who may blam&euml; yowe?</L>
<L N="210">And most chier he had, of hem &thorn;at him slowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="211">O special love, which &thorn;at me ioyned hast</L>
<L>Vnto my sone, ful strong is thi knettyng!<MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This day, there-inne fynde I a bitter tast;</L>
<L>ffor now I tast &amp; fel&euml; the streynyng</L>
<L N="215">Of deth, be thi deth: deth fele I me styng.</L>
<L>O pur&euml; modier, what schalt thu now seye?</L>
<L N="217">Pore Mary&euml;! thi witte is now awey.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="218">Maria, nay, but 'marred' I the call;</L>
<L>So may I weel; for &thorn;ou art, weel I wot,</L>
<L>Vessel of care &amp; woo, &amp; sorwes alle.</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou art frosty coold; now fery hoot;</L>
<L N="222">And right as &thorn;at a schippe, or barge or boot,</L>
<L>Among the waw&euml;s dryveth stern&euml;les,</L>
<L N="224">So dost thu, woful woman counfortles.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="225">And also of modier hast &thorn;ou lost the style;</L>
<L>No more may thu be called by that name.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="xliv"></L>
<L>O sones of Adam, al to long[&euml;] while</L>
<L>Ye tarie hens! hastith hedir for schame!</L>
<L N="229">See how my son&euml;, for youre gilt and blame,</L>
<L>lo, hangith here, bibl&eacute;d upon the crosse!</L>
<L N="231">Bymeneth him in hert, in chiere &amp; voysse!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="232">His blody strem&euml;s, se now, &amp; be-holde!</L>
<L>if ye to him have [any] affecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Now, for his woo, youre hert&euml;s owt[en] colde;</L>
<L>Schewyth youre kendnesse &amp; youre dileccioun,</L>
<L N="236">ffor youre gilt makith he correccioun,</L>
<L>And &aacute;mendith right be his own&euml; deth:</L>
<L N="238">That ye noght rewe on him, myn hert it sleth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="239">A, modier, &thorn;at so sone hire cot&euml; tare</L>
<L>Or rent&euml;! say ye neuere none or this,</L>
<L>ffor child [the] which [she] of hire body bare,</L>
<L>To yeve hire tete. and my child &thorn;at here is,</L>
<L N="243">his cote hath torne, for youre gilt, not for his,</L>
<L>[&amp;] hath of his blood spilt in gret foysoun;</L>
<L N="245">And alle his, lo, for youre redempc&iuml;oun!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="246">My der&euml; childe, my fruyt &thorn;at on [me] growed,<MILESTONE N="67" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Myn lusty appil, blisful faire and sweet,</L>
<L>Now deth hath him be-clapped with his clowde,</L>
<L>That him perced [vn]to the hert&euml; rote.</L>
<L N="250">Go to, thow man, &thorn;ere thu myght haue thi bote!</L>
<L>Go suke the Iuce! the is no thing so sweet;</L>
<L N="252">Go take thin part! I rede the not for-gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="253">Go nere, &amp; see how &thorn;at he is for-bete,</L>
<L>And alle for-persed sore and pietously!</L>
<L>See how there renn&euml; fyv&euml; strem&euml;s grete,</L>
<L>That yelde[n] owt the Iuce habundauntly!</L>
<L N="257">Go sowke therof! I say you faithfully,</L>
<L>In good tyme was he bore, &thorn;at hath &thorn;at grace,</L>
<L N="259">In tho woundes to make his duellyng place.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="xlv"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="260">O Aduersari, [t]how cruel dry&euml; tree,</L>
<L>To the speke I! nowe hast &thorn;ou thi entent;</L>
<L>My sweet[&euml;] fruyt &thorn;ou hast be-reved me</L>
<L>A-geyn my will, nothing of myne assent.</L>
<L N="264">I se how al to-Raced and to-rent</L>
<L>On the he hongith: is this weel I-doo?</L>
<L N="266">I bare him monethis nyne, but no thing so.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="267">O cruel tree, sith thu hast thi desire,</L>
<L>Whi wilt &thorn;ou not, to my fruyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">Scan "to my fruyt" as one measure.</NOTE> be fauor&aacute;bill,</L>
<L>To saue it hool? but feruentere than the fiere</L>
<L>he fyndeth, &amp; nothing [in thee] agr&euml;&aacute;ble.</L>
<L N="271">It is to me but alle discountfort&aacute;ble</L>
<L>To se myn herte attached the vpon,</L>
<L N="273">ffor he &amp; I, oure hert[&euml;] is but one.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="274">Now with my fruyt art &thorn;ou here openly,</L>
<L>That alle the world it may be-holde &amp; see</L>
<L>Restored, which (I sey the sekerly)</L>
<L>Is more of vertue and of dignyte</L>
<L N="278">Than was the fruyt &thorn;at spoyled was from the.</L>
<L>Thu hast thi will; thin honoure schal suffise</L>
<L N="280">To the: yelde me my fruyt in goodly wise!<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(8) The recordyng of aungeles song of the Natiuite of oure lady.<MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[7 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">HOnured be thu, blisseful lord benigne,</L>
<L>That now vnt&oacute; man wil be merci&aacute;ble</L>
<L>As he may se apertly be a signe,</L>
<L>A braunche, &thorn;at sprongen is ful profitable,</L>
<L N="5">fful fresch &amp; faire, &amp; heily commendable</L>
<L>Of Iesse-is Rote, &thorn;at called is marie,</L>
<L N="7">That schal the blisseful appil fructifie.
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="xlvi"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8"><B>A</B> blisful flour, owt of this spray schal springe;</L>
<L>The fruyt &thorn;er-of schal be ful prec&iuml;ous;</L>
<L>A caus&euml; haue [we] for to ioye &amp; synge,</L>
<L>In honure of &thorn;at maid&euml; grac&iuml;ous,</L>
<L N="12">That gret comfort schal cause[n] vnto vs;</L>
<L>ffor now schal faste oure company encrees,</L>
<L N="14">And god with man schal mak&euml; small&euml; pees.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">Now be we glad, in honure of this maide,</L>
<L>That schal be modier of the kyng eterne,</L>
<L>Be whom the raunsom fully schal be paid</L>
<L>ffor man, &thorn;at loken is in hell&euml; herne.</L>
<L N="19">Now schal we haue no power for to warne</L>
<L>Man for [to] entre in-to paradise;</L>
<L N="21">The lord wil sette him at so highe a price.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Thu, lucifer, &thorn;at list in helle I-bounde,</L>
<L>That whylom were one of oure companye,<MILESTONE N="96" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This maid&euml; schal the vtterly confounde,</L>
<L>And do the much&euml; schame &amp; vilanye,</L>
<L N="26">Which Eua hast deceyu&euml;d traytouresly,</L>
<L>And made hire trust[en] on thi fals behest,</L>
<L N="28">Wherby thu hast hire lynage alle arest.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Thu cursed caitiff! mawgre thi malice<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. malace.</NOTE>!</L>
<L>fful sone he schal be sette owt of thin hande;</L>
<L>Reseised schal he be with paradise;</L>
<L>Thu schalt not be of powire to with-stande;</L>
<L N="33">But, as an hound &thorn;at tied is with a bande,</L>
<L>So schalt thu eternally lyn in thi peyne;</L>
<L N="35">Ne no counfort getist thu, thow &thorn;ou pleyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">To gret distresse &amp; gret des&oacute;lacioun</L>
<L>A maid&euml; first was d&eacute;ceyv&euml;d be the:</L>
<L>Vnto thi schame and [thi] confus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>A blissed maid&euml; schal thi ladi be.</L>
<L N="40">But weel is him &thorn;at schal &thorn;at maid&euml; see,
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="xlvii"></L>
<L>And schal be schent to salue hire, &amp; grete,</L>
<L N="42">And say "heil, mary, maid&euml; faire &amp; sweet!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">Who euere it be, &thorn;at schal do this mess&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>fful weel is him that fynd&euml; may that grace:</L>
<L>It schal him weel suffis&euml; for his wage,</L>
<L>To see &thorn;at blissed sweet[&euml;] lady face.</L>
<L N="47">Now with alle ioy&euml;s, myrth&euml; &amp; sol&aacute;ce,</L>
<L>ffor loue of hire honure, we [synge] this day</L>
<L N="49">With alle the songes &amp; myrth&euml;s &thorn;at we may.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(9) The aungeles song.<MILESTONE N="97" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[2 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Honured be thu, blisful heuene queene,</L>
<L>And worschepid mot &thorn;ou be in eueri place,</L>
<L>That modier art, and veari maid&euml; clene!</L>
<L>Of god, oure lord, thu geten hast &thorn;at grace.</L>
<L N="5">Thu, cause of Ioy&euml;s art, and alle sol&aacute;ce,</L>
<L>Be merite of thi gret humilite,</L>
<L N="7">And by the floure of thi virginite.<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Honured be thu blissed ladi bright!</L>
<L>Be thi persone, embassh&euml;d is nat&uacute;re;</L>
<L>Of heuene blisse, augmented is the light,</L>
<L>Be presence of so fare a cr&euml;ature;</L>
<L N="12">Thi worthiness&euml; pasith all mes&uacute;re;</L>
<L>ffor vnto thin astate imperiall,</L>
<L N="14">No praisyng is, &thorn;at may be peregall.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(10) The aungeles songe in the feste of the Epiphanie of oure lord.<MILESTONE N="99" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[4 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">HOnured be this blissed holy fest&euml; day</L>
<L>In worshippe of the sweet[&euml;] welle of liffe,
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="xlviii"></L>
<L>With alle the ioyes &amp; mirth&euml; &thorn;at we may,</L>
<L>for Crist, the kirke hath chos&euml; to his wiffe;</L>
<L N="5">And fynally abated is &thorn;at striffe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him betwyn, &amp; man, hath long&euml; be;</L>
<L N="7">Honured be this blessed Trinite!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Owt of this welle, so noble licoure ran,</L>
<L>So faire, so fressh, so lusty, hony-sweet,</L>
<L>That sith this first day &thorn;at the world be-gan,</L>
<L>With suche a well&euml; might[&euml;] no man mete.</L>
<L N="12">Alle heuynesse &amp; malice is for-gete</L>
<L>As toward man; excused clene is hee;</L>
<L N="14">honured be the blissed Trinite!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">This day, so lowe he wold him self incline,</L>
<L>The thrid[d&euml;] fest&euml; with his highe persone</L>
<L>To honure, turnyng watir in-to wynne.</L>
<L>This day was Ihesu baptised of seint Iohn;</L>
<L N="19">The fadir-is voice was herd owt of his trone:</L>
<L>"This is my loued sone, &thorn;at liketh me."</L>
<L N="21">honured be the souereyn Trinite!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">And &thorn;at he schuld haue recorde Autentyk,</L>
<L>The thrid[d&euml;] persone, on oure lord a-light,</L>
<L>The holy gost, vn-to a dowe I-lyk,</L>
<L>That pleyn[&euml;]ly was seyn of eueri wight.<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="26">Thus blissed hath he watir, god al-myght,</L>
<L>In honure of this [highe] solemnite.</L>
<L N="28">Honured be the blissed Trinite!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(11) the aungeles song on pask day.</HEAD>
<P>[5 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">HOnur&egrave;d be thu, Ihesu saueour,<MILESTONE N="100" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at for mankend&euml; were do on the rode;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto woldest do vs &thorn;at honure,</L>
<L>To fede vs with thi flesche &amp; with thi bloode.</L>
<L N="5">was neuere to vs flesch&euml; halfe so goode;
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="xlix"></L>
<L>ffor wonderly oure ioyes it doth renewe.</L>
<L N="7">honured be thu, blissed lord Ihesu!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Whan thu were died, to hell&euml; &thorn;ou descended,</L>
<L>And fette hem owt &thorn;at [longe] lay there in peyne;</L>
<L>ffor be thi deth, oure mis was alle a-mended.</L>
<L>The thrid day, thu a-roos to lyffe a-geyne</L>
<L N="12">With highe tryumphe, &amp; ioy&euml; souereyn:</L>
<L>As champioun [the chef] of hie vertue,</L>
<L N="14">Honured be &thorn;ou, blissed lord Ihesu!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">The grevous iourney &thorn;at thu took on hande,</L>
<L>hath clerly maad, to eueri wight appere,</L>
<L>In sothfastnesse to see &amp; vnderstonde,&mdash;</L>
<L>To &thorn;at only was thi talent &amp; thi chiere</L>
<L N="19">So suffisaunt, lo,&mdash;that oure raunsoum were</L>
<L>Superhabundaunt over &thorn;at was due;</L>
<L N="21">Honured be thu, blisseful lord Ihesu!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">On thursday, a noble soper &thorn;ou made,</L>
<L>Where thu ordeyned first thi sacrament;</L>
<L>But much&euml; more it doth oure hert&euml;s glade,</L>
<L>The worthi dyner of this day present,</L>
<L N="26">In which &thorn;ou schewest thi self omnipotent,</L>
<L>Rising from deth to lyve, it is ful trewe:</L>
<L N="28">Honured be thu, blisful lord Ihesu!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Now for this fest&euml; schal we say the graces,</L>
<L>And worthi is, with alle oure diligence,</L>
<L>And thank the here, &amp; [eke] in all&euml; places,</L>
<L>Of thi ful bountevous benevolence,</L>
<L N="33">Thi myght, thi grace, thi souereyn excellence:</L>
<L>Thu art the ground &amp; welle of alle vertue:</L>
<L N="35">Honured be thu, blisfull lord Ihesu!<MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio">
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000052.tif" N="l">
<HEAD>(12) The song of graces of alle seintes upon Paske day.<MILESTONE N="101" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[4 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">HOnured be thu, blisfull lord a-bove,</L>
<L>That vowchidsaff&euml; this iourny to take,</L>
<L>Man to become, only for man-is love,</L>
<L>And deth to suffre, for my synn&euml;s sake;</L>
<L N="5">So hast thu vs owt of the bond&euml; schake,</L>
<L>Of Sathanas, &thorn;at held us longe in peyne:</L>
<L N="7">Honured be thu, Ihesu souereyne!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Full evele I dede, whan I the appil took;</L>
<L>I wend to haue had therbi prosperite;</L>
<L>It satte so ny my sid&euml;s, &thorn;at thei ooke;</L>
<L>To greet myschief I fill from hey degre,</L>
<L N="12">And alle my issue, for be-cause of me;</L>
<L>Now hast &thorn;ou, lord, restored all a-geyn:</L>
<L N="14">Honured be thu, Ihesu souereyne!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">So rich&euml;ly &thorn;ou hast refressh&egrave;d vs,</L>
<L>And vs counf&oacute;rted with thi feste riall;</L>
<L>So swet a fruyt, &amp; so delic&iuml;ows,</L>
<L>So faire it is, and so celestiall,</L>
<L N="19">That oure disease now is forgotten all,</L>
<L>This fruyt hath so vis&iacute;ted eueri veyne:</L>
<L N="21">Honured be thu, Ihesu souereyne!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">This may be called weel the fruyt of liff.</L>
<L>The fruyt of deth, was wherof I asaide;</L>
<L>That, be thi Iug&euml;ment diffinitiffe,</L>
<L>ffoure thowsande yere I was ful ille araide,</L>
<L N="26">Til &thorn;at this fruyt, &thorn;at born was of a maide,</L>
<L>hadd&euml; reformed: therefor lat vs seyn,</L>
<L N="28">Honured be thu, Ihesu souereyn!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000053.tif" N="li">
<HEAD>(13) The aungeles song &amp; alle othir seintes in the feste of Pentecost.<MILESTONE N="102" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[3 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">HOnured be thu, holy gost in hie,</L>
<L>That vn-to poeple of so pore astate</L>
<L>hast youe thi grace, to stond&euml; myghtely</L>
<L>Ageyn tyraunt&euml;s fiers &amp; obstynate,</L>
<L N="5">ffor to endwe them with thi principate</L>
<L>To leve hire erroure, &amp; hire liffe to amende:</L>
<L N="7">honured be thu, lord, with-owt[en] ende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Thu gave hem wete &amp; cunnyng [for] to preche,</L>
<L>And corage for to stand[&euml;] be the lawe,</L>
<L>Alle maner poepil, to wisshe &amp; to teche,</L>
<L>ffrom vices alle hir lust&euml;s to with-drawe,</L>
<L N="12">And of hire lord [&amp;] god to stande in awe,</L>
<L>To his pleasaunce hire hert&euml;s to intende:</L>
<L N="14">Honured be thu, lord, with-owt[en] ende!<MILESTONE N="102b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">This ffischeres alle be &aacute;voyded of slowthe:</L>
<L>ffor blaundisshing, for manasyng, ne for drede,</L>
<L>Thei spared nought, but stod&euml; by the trowthe;</L>
<L>Of peyn&euml;s &amp; torm&eacute;nt toke thei non heed,</L>
<L N="19">But fayne to see hire heed &amp; hire sides blede,</L>
<L>[aferd] fful myghtly thi lawys to offende:</L>
<L N="21">Honured be thu, lord, with-owt[en] ende!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(14) The pietous complainte of the Soule.<MILESTONE N="8" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[52 stanzas of 7 lines each, <I>ababb, cc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Blisful lord on heigh, what schall I do,</L>
<L>or in what place may I my self&euml; hide?</L>
<L>Refute ne wot i non to draw&euml; to.</L>
<L>no doute I must my Iug&euml;ment a-byde;</L>
<L N="5">my foo is alwei redy be my side,</L>
<L>me schapyng to appel&euml; and accuse;</L>
<L N="7">I can no worde myn selff&euml; to excuse.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="lii"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8"><B>I</B> am aryved to a perilous port,</L>
<L>ne knowe I nought to whom I may retourne;</L>
<L>I am arrest; now kan I non confort;</L>
<L>mawgre my selfe, right here mot I soiourne;</L>
<L N="12">For my mysshappe, A cause haue I to mourne;</L>
<L>And in my skrippe now fynde I no vetayle,<MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="14">ne my burdon&euml; doth me nought avayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">Burdone ne skrippe may I no lengere bere,</L>
<L>Myne enemy so sore assaileth me;</L>
<L>I holde it best to cast awey this gere,</L>
<L>And shape my selfe preu&eacute;ly for to flee.</L>
<L N="19">O blisful lord, I wis it wele nought be,</L>
<L>And weel &thorn;ou woot, how &thorn;at me hath bywiled</L>
<L N="21">Myne enemy that hath now me defiled.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Wherfore now I am brought to iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L>Sithe I am falle in myschieff and porcert,</L>
<L>Ne I ne may, to myn accus&euml;ment,</L>
<L>Ne can nought say but aftir my desert,</L>
<L N="26">And my trespace, that know&euml; is apert,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at I shall myne<NOTE PLACE="inline">MS. alle myne</NOTE> r&eacute;warde vnderfonge:</L>
<L N="28">Allas! whi have I be synfull so longe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">But best it is, if reason say me trowthe,</L>
<L>That of some helpe I make me purveaunce;</L>
<L>Parde, some wight on me wil hav&euml; rewthe;</L>
<L>Asay I shal; but, for my sustenaunce,</L>
<L N="33">My burdone must I bere for suffisaunce,</L>
<L>For, myght withowt[en] it [ne] haue I none;</L>
<L N="35">I bere it nought; it berith my persone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">Allas, but I haue now experience</L>
<L>Off wis[&euml;]dam, my selff&euml; to demeane,</L>
<L>To &eacute;xcuse me have I none audience,</L>
<L>And alle my witte availeth not a beane;</L>
<L N="40">Thus is myne hope alle discounf&oacute;rted clene,
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="liii"></L>
<L>I kan nought do but cry&euml; &amp; compleyne,</L>
<L N="42">That charite nought rekkith of my peyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">Whi saith Powle, that othere yiftes alle</L>
<L>Schul fail&euml; here, but only charite</L>
<L>A-bydyng is, for he kowd&euml; nought falle.</L>
<L>Whethir this be soth? but nay, as it semith me,</L>
<L N="47">He wold[&euml;] than myne [good] adu&oacute;cat be,<MILESTONE N="9" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And somwhat say<NOTE PLACE="inline">MS. say I</NOTE> to help&euml; in myne cause,</L>
<L>For I kan nother spek&euml; word ne clause.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50"><B>I</B> am adred that charite is deed,</L>
<L>And slayne in erthe, of wikked[&euml;] men there,</L>
<L>Withowt[en] eyre or issue of hire seed,</L>
<L>Left here on high&euml;:&mdash;lo, this is my fere;</L>
<L N="54">And if I wiste that sche on lyv&euml; were,</L>
<L>I wold not spare to call&euml; and [to] crie,</L>
<L N="56">If I hire, in on&yacute; place myght a-spie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57"><B>O</B> charite, so good &amp; so gracious!</L>
<L>Thu hast be euere to tho &thorn;at have nede!</L>
<L>I that am in this brik&euml; perilous,&mdash;</L>
<L>That, in myne schippe, my self[&euml;] for to fede</L>
<L N="61">Haue I no bred now of thin alm&euml;sdede,&mdash;</L>
<L>Somwhat thu helpe, myn hunger to abate,</L>
<L N="63">Havyng reward vnto my pouer astate.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64"><B>I</B> mean&euml; thus: if ony part of grace</L>
<L>Reserued be, in tresoure or ell&euml;s where,</L>
<L>That thu, for me purvey&euml; and purchase</L>
<L>Wolde vouch&euml;saff, gret wondere but there were</L>
<L N="68">I-nowgh for me: nought ell&euml;s I require;</L>
<L>Do somwhat, than, aftir thi propirte,</L>
<L N="70">And schewe whi thu art cleped charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">But now, allas, ful weel I may recorde,</L>
<L>Whil I had myght and space of tyme I-nowgh,</L>
<L>Of this mattere, towchid I no word,</L>
<L>Ne, to seint, I tho my self[&euml;] drowgh,
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="liv"></L>
<L N="75">That in myne nede for me may spek&euml; now,</L>
<L>As for no service that I have to him do:</L>
<L N="77">Wot I not, whom to make my mon&euml; to.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">If I, to ony seint in spec&iuml;al</L>
<L>Had ony thing [i]forsed myne entent</L>
<L>With ony service, othir gret or small,</L>
<L>I wold me have avayl&egrave;d in present;<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="82">But thus have I be slowe and necligent,</L>
<L>That I no freend have made, ne no seint pleased;</L>
<L N="84">Wherfore, as now, am I [right ill] disseased.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="85">To hem am I a straunger and vnknowe;</L>
<L>I knowe nought, to whom I shal my selffe dresse</L>
<L>To ask&euml; helpe, as I suppose and trowe,</L>
<L>Ther is none that wold done that besynesse;</L>
<L N="89">And nought for this, I be-hot&euml; expresse,</L>
<L>Vnto hem I will [both] compleyne and crye,</L>
<L N="91">To make my caus&euml; knowen openly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">To the, Ihesu, the sone of god above,</L>
<L>That were of mary, verray maid&euml;, borne</L>
<L>In very flesch and blood, for mann&euml;s love,</L>
<L>To the, will I now &aacute;ppel&euml; beforne,</L>
<L N="96">Syn thu art man, and forthermore</L>
<L>Oure brothir, and a part of our&euml; kynde:</L>
<L N="98">Good is to us that we thi fauoure fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">This dare I say, sithe that thu wilfully</L>
<L>Where done to deth, only for mann&euml;s sake,</L>
<L>And of thi selfe whas none encheasoun whi,</L>
<L>This knowe I weel, &thorn;ou wilt it nought forsake,</L>
<L N="103">To alle that will vnto thi grace him take,</L>
<L>And ask&euml; it: as oft&euml; I haue lerned,</L>
<L>Was neuere yitte none, to whom it was warned.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">This woot I weel, I haue ful sore offendid</L>
<L>Thi maiestes; wherof I me repente.</L>
<L>Ful late it was, or I my selfe amended,
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="lv"></L>
<L>But yitte ne come it neuere in myne entente</L>
<L N="110">To disallow&euml; thi gou&eacute;rn&euml;mente;</L>
<L>That 'lord and kyng' I have call&euml;d the euere;</L>
<L N="112">Thi law&euml;s also ne forsoke I neuere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">My scrippe of feith&euml;, haue I nought for-lete,</L>
<L>but hool, right as it was [i]tak&euml; me,</L>
<L>I have it kepte; but that no thinges gret[e]<MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>(This knowe I weel) susteigned I for the,</L>
<L>Nor do that I was bound of du&euml;te.</L>
<L>Yitte wote I weel, so gret is nought my synne,</L>
<L N="119">as grace &amp; mercy is, Ihesu withinne.<NOTE PLACE="inline">MS. the withinne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="120">Away, yit nought, eueri deel that grace</L>
<L>Dispendid is, that tho in thi persone</L>
<L>was plentevous whan, with so pale a face,</L>
<L>For me thu heng&euml; on the crosse alone;</L>
<L N="124">But, for we beggyng wrecchis euerychone</L>
<L>Be procuryng alway for our purveaunce,</L>
<L>Thi grace thu woldest hiden now purchaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">Yitte may we, by the pers&egrave;d hol&euml;s well,</L>
<L>And be tho also that large be, &amp; wide,</L>
<L>Behalde and see, that certeyn eueridell</L>
<L>Now spended is, though that thu woldest it hide;</L>
<L N="131">For thowe there ran a Rever from thi side,</L>
<L>That alle the world hath fully ouerflowen,</L>
<L N="133">Thi grace is hool, as euery man may knowen.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">Sithe yitte thi grace is nought dispendid all,</L>
<L>With that thu hast me schewid to the tyme present,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="inline">? Now</NOTE> come, and with the thus argue I schall,</L>
<L>"Sithe it alway hath ben [so] affluent,</L>
<L N="138">Discreasyng nought, ne none appeyr&euml;ment</L>
<L>Be-fallith it, thoughe neuere so larg&euml;ly</L>
<L N="140">Thou yeve it where thu list habundauntly,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">Thu owist to defend&euml; me this day,</L>
<L>kepyng my cause, that stondith al in dowte
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="lvi"></L>
<L>A-geyn my foo, with all that euere he may.</L>
<L>Thi grace, me to be-revyn is a-bowte,</L>
<L N="145">And, me for to passen al with-out;</L>
<L>Ful ofte he hath grev&egrave;d me here-be-fore,</L>
<L N="147">And hopith now that all I haue forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">Though &thorn;at my speche be sownyng to foly,<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yitte, blissed Lord, displease it nought to the,</L>
<L>That to haue spok&euml; of adu&oacute;cacie,</L>
<L>So that thu schuldest myn adu&oacute;cat be:</L>
<L N="152">Thu Art the souereigne iuge of equite,</L>
<L>And nought for-thi, to hem that to the truste,</L>
<L N="154">Here aduocat thu art, whan that the liste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">For, sothe it is, where synne and wrechidnesse</L>
<L>A-boundeth most, there nedeth most[&euml;] grace,</L>
<L>To tho that ask&euml; th&euml; for-gev&euml;nesse,</L>
<L>It sittith the nought to wrye awey thin face;</L>
<L N="159">Thi charite will cleyme there is a place:</L>
<L>But this were southe, gret peril must redounde.</L>
<L N="161">Al mortal men with mischief to confounde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">Now maide &amp; modier, of this worlde Princesse,</L>
<L>So ful of grac&euml; fulfilled thu were</L>
<L>Whan gaubriel his massage gan expresse,</L>
<L>And 'Aue' was resownyng in thin ere,</L>
<L N="166">By wich oure lord, blissed saueoure thu bere,</L>
<L>And of thi blood he took his humanite,&mdash;</L>
<L N="168">My cause also I &aacute;ppele vnto the,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">As aduocate for man, &amp; procuresse</L>
<L>Approovid oft&euml; be experience,</L>
<L>So be myne helpe to &aacute;voide and represse</L>
<L>Myne enemy, wich that be violence</L>
<L N="173">Wold schend[&euml;] me, but if<NOTE PLACE="inline">[? for]</NOTE> thi r&eacute;sistence,</L>
<L>Now be myne helpe, o blisful qwene!</L>
<L N="175">So lat somwhat<NOTE PLACE="inline">[? some]</NOTE> of thi grace on me be sene!
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="lvii"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">Sith that thi sone and thu of one accorde</L>
<L>Be vearili, (as reason is that ye be),</L>
<L>I, that for dreed vnnethe kan speke a worde,</L>
<L>But tremble as doth a leef vpon a tree,</L>
<L N="180">Thu, ladi ful of merci and piete,</L>
<L>Now must thu be myne helpe and myne socoure</L>
<L N="182">Of refute, in this &aacute;uent&oacute;ur&euml;s howre!<MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="183">For, but thu wilt my caus&euml; [now] defende</L>
<L>A-geyn[&euml;s] him wich is thyne enemy,</L>
<L>that redi is, to greve and to offende</L>
<L>Bothe the, and all&euml; that wolde hertely</L>
<L N="187">The serv&euml;, and thi blisful sone also,</L>
<L>he will hem cast&euml; in-to hell&euml; dike,</L>
<L N="189">And berith me an hande &thorn;at I am him like.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="190"><B>I</B> &aacute;m like, now that I haue done a-mys,</L>
<L>Eternal deth deserued with my dede;</L>
<L>But, grac&iuml;ous queen[&euml;] of heuene blisse,</L>
<L>Thu be myne helpe and counfort in this nede,</L>
<L N="194">But I record&euml;&mdash;and this is my dreed,&mdash;</L>
<L>That wonder sympill&euml;<NOTE PLACE="inline">? synfullye</NOTE> I have the served,</L>
<L>So that I haue no thing of the deserved.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="197">And nought for-thi, thes burdon is my trest,</L>
<L>In wich I have my solace &amp; my disport;</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="inline">? On</NOTE> this pomel will I my self[&euml;] rest,</L>
<L>That specially to me geuith gret counfort;</L>
<L N="201">My febill gost it helpith to support,</L>
<L>That is, thi self&euml;, moder, maide and wiffe,</L>
<L N="203">The sustenaunce and solace of my liffe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="204">And I schal neuere trow&euml; ne suppose,</L>
<L>Sithe he, the wich of merci is the welle,</L>
<L>Within thi sid&euml;s wold him self&euml; close,</L>
<L>Right as thi childe, in veari flesch &amp; falle,</L>
<L N="208">That he schuld lete the foul&euml; feend of helle
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="lviii"></L>
<L>To execute malice, or elles vengeaunce,</L>
<L N="210">On hem &thorn;at the besek&euml; with instaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="211">There is no lyon, ne cruel lyonesse,</L>
<L>So fiers ne so dispietous of corage,</L>
<L>That hire malice attempren<NOTE PLACE="inline">? nil tempren</NOTE> and oppresse</L>
<L>Ne will cessyn of hir&euml; felle corage</L>
<L N="215">To the, that low&euml;ly hem selfe will wage</L>
<L>With mek&euml; hert&euml; to the ground obeye:<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="217">Such is the nature, as this clerk&euml;s say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="218"><B>I</B> am the same that heighli hath mys-wrought</L>
<L>A-geyn thi childe Ihesu, and also the;</L>
<L>Yit knowe I wel that "lyon" is he nought,</L>
<L>Nor thu no "lyoness&euml;" [fiers] may be.</L>
<L N="222">In you there is no malice ne cruelte;</L>
<L>But mercie, pite, goodness&euml; &amp; grace,</L>
<L N="224">In you thei have hire veray propir place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="225">Wherfore I schal the pray[&euml;] and be-seke,</L>
<L>That thu, a-geyn me, nothing be amoeved,</L>
<L>With lowely hert&euml; sith I my-self meke.</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at I have thi sone and the agreved,</L>
<L N="229">Be the is alle my trust to be releuyd,</L>
<L>And that thu schalt my quarell take an hande,</L>
<L N="231">This foul&euml; wight&euml;s malic&euml; withstande.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="232">For weel I wott&euml;, thu wold[est] renome,</L>
<L>As for myne caus&euml;, wilt thu nought refuse,</L>
<L>Ne that thi grace thu wilt nought warn&euml; me,</L>
<L>But that thu wilt thin own&euml; maner vse,</L>
<L N="236">My quarell now to help&euml; and excuse,</L>
<L>And be my socour in this perilows day,</L>
<L N="238">Chasyng this foul&euml; gost from me a-way.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="239">For alwey hath he be myn enemy</L>
<L>Sith I was child, and [eke] tendre in yowthe.</L>
<L>Me think thu schuldest let[t&euml;] him for-thi</L>
<L>To pr&oacute;cede in his acc&iuml;on as nowthe,
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="lix"></L>
<L N="243">Or suffre him accus&euml;, thow he cowthe;</L>
<L>Thu schuldest<NOTE PLACE="inline">[? He schold&euml;]</NOTE> nought ber&euml; no fals witnesse,</L>
<L N="245">That is him-self conuicte of cursidnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="246">For sekirly this is the comon lawe,</L>
<L>That he ne schulde non accion procede,</L>
<L>That on&euml;s owt of courte hath be with-drawe<MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Convicte as fals,&mdash;now here-to takith hede!</L>
<L N="250">This knoweth wel euery wight (it is no dreed),</L>
<L>Thi sone him banysshed from heuen blisse,</L>
<L N="252">as for enfamed; he and all&euml; his.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="253">Michael, prouost, on the I take recorde!</L>
<L>Thi selffe dedist this execuc&iuml;on.</L>
<L>Thow I my selff wolde lyen ony worde,</L>
<L>Yit am I nought of this oppin&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="257">To couere so be excusac&iuml;on</L>
<L>Of this infame, the malise of my synne:</L>
<L N="259">This were a fol&euml;s purpoce to be-gynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="260">But this put I in thi discreac&iuml;on,</L>
<L>That suche a fals deform&egrave;d one as he,</L>
<L>I may refus&euml; be excepc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>That this quarel schal nought receyued be</L>
<L N="264">Here in this courte; ne to accus&euml; me</L>
<L>He schuld not be admitted, as be right,</L>
<L N="266">But I-put away, this foul&euml; fals[&euml;] wight.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="267">For whi, sere prouost Michael grac&iuml;ows,</L>
<L>And alle the Aungeles of thi company</L>
<L>That him enfamed, hath foriuged thus,</L>
<L>And fals convict&euml; cleere and openly,</L>
<L N="271">And him [sente] into peyne eternally,</L>
<L>In hell&euml; to be [kepte] without[en] ende,</L>
<L N="273">With tho that so be d&eacute;formed in kende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="274">Ful mek[&euml;]ly at on&euml;s I reclayme</L>
<L>you alle to do your devere in this case:</L>
<L>This cursed gost, whom malice doth enflame,
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="lx"></L>
<L>Here in this court, his malice haue no place:</L>
<L N="278">This aske I you of right, and also of grace,</L>
<L>That ye, his cry &amp; [eke] his bost abate,</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;at he neu&eacute;re more bere aftir estate.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L N="281">Seint Michael, if &thorn;ou rekkest nought at alle,</L>
<L>Ne nought rewardest [on] myne heuynesse,</L>
<L>Alle manere of hope awey from me is falle,<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So am I than encombred with distresse;</L>
<L N="285">For Danyell the prophete seith expresse,</L>
<L>That in his myschief and suche aduersite</L>
<L N="287">He fonde none othir helpe but only the.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dan. x. 13: but lo, Michael, one of the chief princes [angels], came to help me. x. 21: And there is none that holdeth with me in these things, but Michael your prince. xii. 1: And at that time shall Michael stand up, the great prince which standeth for the children of thy people.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L N="288">Wherfore, if I haue the displeased ought,</L>
<L>So that of me thu takest now none heed,</L>
<L>Aftir this oure, I mote with alle my thought</L>
<L>The done pleasaunce, for betere I schal spede;</L>
<L N="292">For who &thorn;at well be holpen at his nede,</L>
<L>Ful sekere, Placebo mvst go before,</L>
<L N="294">As doth the Crosse in the litel childes lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L N="295">Baptist, an holy man, martir, seint Iohn,</L>
<L>and alle prophet&euml;s of oure lord on heighe,</L>
<L>And ye euaungelist&euml;s euerichon,</L>
<L>And also aposteles, alle the company,</L>
<L N="299">With alle myne herte I pray you humb[le]ly,</L>
<L>Of youre merit&euml;s superh&aacute;bundaunce,</L>
<L N="301">As grauntith me of almesse some pietaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L N="302">In youre tresoure suche plente is bestowe,</L>
<L>Of wich you nedith nought a deel I-wis,</L>
<L>And lorne it may not be&mdash;this weel I knowe,&mdash;</L>
<L>Discreasyn may it nought&mdash;the sothe it is&mdash;</L>
<L N="306">For whi, of almesse-dede (I pray you this)
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="lxi"></L>
<L>That I some manere of porc&iuml;on may haue,</L>
<L N="308">Where-with I may my self[&euml;] helpe and saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L N="309">Ye that haue suffird hard and grevous peyne</L>
<L>Of martirdam, for ihesu crist-is love,</L>
<L>Wich, weel I wott&euml;, was not done in veyne,</L>
<L>Yit merite is youre med&euml; muche a-bove;</L>
<L N="313">I that am pore, and gret[e]ly be-hove,</L>
<L>Of helpe I pray you, and [of] alm&euml;s-dede,</L>
<L N="315">Of youre meriteis, helpith at this nede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L N="316">And sith&euml; thei schul end&euml;les endure,<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thei wast&euml; nought be dymynuc&iuml;on:</L>
<L>To me, that am so pore a cr&euml;ature,</L>
<L>Of almesse grauntith now a porc&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="320">I you require, with hool affecc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>That blisful that sittith an highe in trone,</L>
<L N="322">Appelith him as t&ouml;ward my persone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L N="323">Ye c&oacute;nfessour&euml;s, and ye othir seintes,</L>
<L>And uirgin&euml;s &thorn;at to Crist be so dere,</L>
<L>Entendith to my pietous complayntes,</L>
<L>Be moevid [now] with rewthe vpon my chiere;</L>
<L N="327">For woman none, the wich that is ful nere</L>
<L>To childe-beryng, so of her peyn&euml;s dredeth,</L>
<L N="329">As I woot that my iug&euml;ment procedeth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L N="330">And if that ye, of youre meriteis grete,</L>
<L>Somwhat departen to so pouere a wight,</L>
<L>ye wil vouchesaff such grac&euml; me to gete,</L>
<L>This foul&euml; gost to putte owt of my sight,</L>
<L N="334">Yitte wolde I hope to Ihesu ful of myght,</L>
<L>Of malice wich he hath a-geyn me spoke,</L>
<L>He schuld be<NOTE PLACE="foot">Scan "He schuld be" as one measure.</NOTE> atteynt, &amp; alle his barr&euml;s broke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L N="337"><B>I</B> have not whom, my selff to turn&euml; to,</L>
<L>In spec&iuml;al to speke, or elles compleyne,
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="lxii"></L>
<L>That may me ony helpe and socoure do,</L>
<L>My symple cause to forthere or susteyne:</L>
<L N="341">That doth me sor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="inline">[MS. me sore doth]</NOTE> grev&euml; and constreyne.</L>
<L>The holy Court of Seint&euml;s I appele,</L>
<L>Betakyng you my quarell eueridell.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L N="344">Ye know&euml; weel [right] now what is my nede</L>
<L>Ageyn the malice of myne enemy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is a-bowte to noy&euml; and mysbede</L>
<L>Me, nedi wrecch&euml;: help[&euml;] me forththi!</L>
<L N="348">Geve audience vnto my pietows cry,</L>
<L>And to my Kyng now reconsil&euml; me,</L>
<L N="350">Schewyng the feruoure of youre charite!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L N="351">The relieff of youre excellent merites,<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ye preciows seint&euml;s chosen euerichon,</L>
<L>A-geyn the malice of this perilous wites</L>
<L>Wich &thorn;at the feend [now] puttith me upon,</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;at whil I was levyng in flesch and bon,</L>
<L>With his disceipt&euml;s and his fraud&euml;s fele</L>
<L N="357">He drowe me to, &amp; now me doth appele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L N="358">Seint Poule him-selff[&euml;] writith in this wise,</L>
<L>And saith that "veray parfight charite</L>
<L>Is a thing &thorn;at may to muche poepil suffice";</L>
<L>Sche aboundith nought in propirte.</L>
<L N="362">Sithe it behouith, than, in communalte</L>
<L>Among the nedi to be d&iacute;spended,</L>
<L N="364">Let myne estate somwhat be &aacute;mendid!<NOTE PLACE="end"><I>Minor Poems</I>, I, 38/417. Le Sire de Fournivall Tresourer, was appointed of Henry IV's Council on 27 Nov., 8 Hen. IV, 1406.&mdash;<I>Proc. Privy Council</I>, i. 295 (ed. Nicolas, 1834). See also <I>Rot. Parl.</I> iii. 572 <I>b.</I></NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
