</P>

</DIV2></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="text"><PB REF="00000066.tif">

<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="1">
<HEAD>The Regement of Princes.<LB>BY THOMAS HOCCLEVE.[Harl. MS. 4866. Leaf 1 in a hand about 1700 A.D.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>Heere begynnyth the Book how<LB>Pryncys sholden be governyd.<MILESTONE N="1a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">The first leaf has been torn out of Harl. 4866, but the first 8 stanzas have been copied on another leaf of parchment by a later hand about 1700 A. D.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Oxford.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Signature of Edward Harley, 2nd Earl of Oxford, who made the collection of Harleian MSS. If the 'B H' is not the press|mark, I don't know what it is. On the fly-leaf is "See another copy of this book in this [Harley] Library marked 35 A. 17."</NOTE><LB>B. H.</P>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Mvsyng vpon the restles bisynesse</L>
<L>Which that this troubly<NOTE PLACE="foot">troubly Reg. 17 D vi, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> world hath ay on honde,</L>
<L>That othir thyng than fruyt of byttirnesse</L>
<L>Ne yeldeth nought, as I can vndirstonde,</L>
<L N="5">At Chestre ynn&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Chestres Inne R.</NOTE> right fast<NOTE PLACE="foot">fast R H.</NOTE> be the stronde,</L>
<L>As I lay in my bed vp-on a nyght,</L>
<L>Thought me bereft of sleep with<NOTE PLACE="foot">the R.</NOTE> force and myght.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">And many a day and nyght that wykked hyne</L>
<L>Hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde R, had H.</NOTE> beforn vexid my poor&euml; goost</L>
<L>So grevously, that of anguysh and pyne</L>
<L>No richere man was nougher<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer R.</NOTE> in no coost;</L>
<L N="12">This dar I seyn, may no wight make his boost</L>
<L>That he with thought was bettir<NOTE PLACE="foot">bette R.</NOTE> than I aqveynted,</L>
<L N="14">For to the deth it wel nigh hath me feynted.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="2"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">Bysily in my mynde I gan revolue</L>
<L>The welthe onsure of everye creature,</L>
<L>How lightly that ffortune it can dissolue,</L>
<L>Whan that hir lyst that it no lenger<NOTE PLACE="foot">no lenger R, not long H.</NOTE> dure;</L>
<L N="19">And of the brotylnesse of hyre nature,</L>
<L>My tremlyng hert so gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete . . lyfe R, gret . . lyf H.</NOTE> gastnesse hadde,</L>
<L N="21">That my spiritis were of my lyf&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete . . lyfe R, gret . . lyf H.</NOTE> sadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Me fel to mynde<NOTE PLACE="foot">mynde R, my mynde H.</NOTE> how that, not long ago,</L>
<L>ffortun&euml;s strok doun threst estaat royal</L>
<L>Into myscheef<NOTE PLACE="foot">The deposition of Richard II, A. D. 1399.</NOTE>; and I took heed also</L>
<L>Of many anothir lord that had a fall;</L>
<L N="26">In mene<NOTE PLACE="foot">mene R, many H.</NOTE> estaat eek sikernesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">sikirnesse R, siknnesse H.</NOTE> at all</L>
<L>Ne saw I noon; but I sey att&euml; laste,</L>
<L N="28">Wher s&euml;wrte, for to abyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sewete for to abide R, tabyde H.</NOTE> hir caste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Yn poore<NOTE PLACE="foot">In pouere R, Yn the poore H.</NOTE> estaat sche pyght hir paviloun,<MILESTONE N="1b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is in a later hand than the rest of the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>To covere hire from the storm<NOTE PLACE="foot">To kever hir fro the stroke.</NOTE> of descendyng;</L>
<L>For [that] sche kneew no lowere discencion,</L>
<L>Save oonly deth, fro which no wight lyvyng</L>
<L N="33">Defendyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Defende R.</NOTE> hym may; and thus, in my musyng,</L>
<L>I destitut was of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of R, for H.</NOTE> joye and good hope,</L>
<L N="35">And to myn es&euml; no thyng koude I groope.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">For right as blyv&euml; ran it in my thought,</L>
<L>Though I be poore, yet som what leese I may;</L>
<L>Than deemed I that seur&euml;te<NOTE PLACE="foot">seurtee R.</NOTE> would nought</L>
<L>With me abyde, it is nought to hir pay,</L>
<L N="40">Ther to soiurne as sche descend&euml; may;</L>
<L>And thus vnsikir of my smal lyfloode,</L>
<L>Thought leyd on me full<NOTE PLACE="foot">full R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> many an hevy loode.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="3"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">I thought eek, if I in-to povert creepe,</L>
<L>Than am I entred in-to sykirnesse;</L>
<L>But swich seurete myght I ay wayle and weepe,</L>
<L>ffor poverte breedeth but<NOTE PLACE="foot">but R, nought but H.</NOTE> hevynesse.</L>
<L N="47">Allas! wher is this worldis stabilnesse?</L>
<L>Heer vp, heer doun; heer honour, heer repreef;</L>
<L>Now hool, now seek; now bounte, now myscheef.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">And whan I hadd&euml; rolled vp and doun<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Boecius de' consolatione Philosophi&aelig;; maximum genus infor|tunii est, fuisse felicem &amp;c.<NOTE PLACE="foot">felicem &amp;c. R, homines H.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>This world&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">worldes R, world H.</NOTE> stormy waw&euml;s in my mynde,</L>
<L>I seey weel povert was exclus&iuml;on<NOTE PLACE="foot">pouertee was conclusion R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of all weelfar&euml; regnyng in mankynde;</L>
<L N="54">And how in book&euml;s thus I wryten fynde,</L>
<L>"The werst&euml; kynde of wrecchedness&euml; is,</L>
<L N="56">A man to hav&euml; been weelfull or this."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">&para;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The old writing, c.</I> 1430-40, <I>of Harl.</I> 4866 <I>begins here.</I></NOTE>"Allas!" &thorn;oghte I, "what sykirnesse ys &thorn;at<MILESTONE N="2a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To lyue ay seur of greef and of nuisaunce?</L>
<L>What schal I do? best is I stryu&euml; nat</L>
<L>Agayne &thorn;e pays<NOTE PLACE="foot">peys R.</NOTE> of fortun&euml;s balaunce;</L>
<L N="61">ffor wele I wote, &thorn;at hir brotel constaunce,</L>
<L>A wyght no whil&euml; suffer can soiourne</L>
<L N="63">In a plyt; &thorn;us nat wiste<NOTE PLACE="foot">o plite / thus I wist nat R.</NOTE> I how to torne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">&para; ffor whan a man wene&thorn; stond most constant,</L>
<L>&THORN;an is he next&euml; to his ouer throwyng;</L>
<L>So flyttyng is sche, and so wariant,</L>
<L>Ther is no trust vp-on hir fair lawhyng;</L>
<L N="68">After glad loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">looke R.</NOTE> sche schapi&thorn; hir to styng;</L>
<L>I was a-drad so of hir gerynesse,</L>
<L N="70">That my lif was but a dedly gladnesse."
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="4"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">&para; Thus ilk&euml; nyught I walwyd to and fro,</L>
<L>Sekyng rest&euml;; but, certeynly sche</L>
<L>Appeerid noght, for &thorn;oght, my crewel fo,</L>
<L>Chaced hadde hir &amp; slepe a-way fro me;</L>
<L N="75">And for I schuld&euml; not a-lon&euml; be,</L>
<L>Agayn my luste, Wach profrid his seruise,</L>
<L N="77">And I admittid hym in heuy wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">&para; So long a nyught ne felde I neuer non,</L>
<L>As was &thorn;at sam&euml; to my iug&euml;ment;</L>
<L>Who so &thorn;at thoghty is, is wo-be-gon;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;oghtful wight is vessel of turment,</L>
<L N="82">&THORN;er nys no greef to him equipolent;</L>
<L>He graue&thorn; deppest of seekenesses<NOTE PLACE="foot">sikenesses R, seekenesse H.</NOTE> alle;</L>
<L N="84">fful wo is him &thorn;at in swich thoght<NOTE PLACE="foot">caas R.</NOTE> is falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="85">&para; What whyght &thorn;at inly pensif is, I trowe,<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His moste desire is to be solitarie;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is is so&thorn;, in my persone I knowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">knawe H.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor euere whil &thorn;at fretynge aduersarie</L>
<L N="89">Myn hert[e] mad&euml; to hym tributarie,</L>
<L>In sowkynge of &thorn;e fresschest of my blod,</L>
<L N="91">To sorwe soule,<NOTE PLACE="foot">soole R (alone).</NOTE> me thoght it dide me good.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Vnde Mar|cialis Cocus: Ille dolet vere qui sine teste dolet.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">&para; ffor &thorn;e nature of heuynesse is &thorn;is:</L>
<L>If it habound&euml; gretly in a wight,</L>
<L>&THORN;e place eschewit he where as ioye is,</L>
<L>ffor ioye &amp; he not mowe accorde a-ryght;</L>
<L N="96">As discordant as day is vn-to nyught,</L>
<L>And honur, aduersarie is vn-to schame,</L>
<L N="98">Is heuyness&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuynes H, So heuynesse is R.</NOTE> so to ioye and game.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="5"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">&para; Whan to &thorn;e &thorn;oghtful whi&yogh;t is tolde a tale,</L>
<L>He heeri&thorn; it as &thorn;ogh he &thorn;enn&euml;s were;</L>
<L>Hys heuy thoght&euml;s hym so plukke &amp; hale</L>
<L>Hyder and &thorn;edir, and hym greue &amp; dere,</L>
<L N="103">&THORN;at hys er&euml;s auayle hym nat a pere;</L>
<L>He vnderstonde&thorn; no &thorn;ing what men seye,</L>
<L N="105">So ben his wytt&euml;s fer gon hem to pleye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">&para; &THORN;e smert of &thorn;oght, I by experience</L>
<L>knowe as wel as any man do&thorn; lyuynge;</L>
<L>His frosty swoot &amp; fyry hote feruence,</L>
<L>And troubly drem&euml;s, drempt al in wakynge,</L>
<L N="110">My mayzed heed sleeplees han of konnynge,</L>
<L>And wyt dispoylyd, &amp; so me be-iapyd,</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at after de&thorn; ful often haue I gapid.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[HOCCLEVE'S MEETING AND DIALOGUE WITH AN OLD BEGGAR.]</HEAD>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">&para; Passe ouer whanne &thorn;is stormy nyght was gon,<MILESTONE N="3a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And day gan at my wyndowe in to prye,</L>
<L>I roos me vp, for boot&euml; fonde I non</L>
<L>In myn vnresty bed lenger to lye;</L>
<L N="117">In-to &thorn;e feld I dressed me in hye,</L>
<L>And in my wo, y herte-depe<NOTE PLACE="foot">in my wofull hert deepe R.</NOTE> gan wade,</L>
<L N="119">As he &thorn;at was bareyne of &thorn;oght&euml;s glade.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="120">&para; By &thorn;at I walkyd hadde a certeine tyme,</L>
<L>Were it an houre, I not or more or lesse,</L>
<L>A poore olde hor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hore R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> man cam walkyng by me,</L>
<L>And seyd&euml;, "good day, syre, &amp; god yow blysse!"</L>
<L N="124">But I no word; for my seekly distresse</L>
<L>ffor-bad myn eres vsen hire office,</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">this R, &thorn;us H.</NOTE> olde man helde me lewed &amp; nyce,
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="6"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">&para; Tyl he tooke hed&euml; to my drery chere,</L>
<L>And to my deedly colour pale &amp; wan;</L>
<L>Thanne thoghte he &thorn;us:&mdash;&thorn;is man &thorn;at I se here,</L>
<L>Al wrong is wrestid, by oght &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrest by ought that R, wrestid by oght H.</NOTE> I se can:</L>
<L>He sterte vp to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto R.</NOTE> me, &amp; seyde, "scleepys &thorn;ou, man?</L>
<L>Awake!" &amp; gan me schak&euml; wonder faste,</L>
<L N="133">And with a sigh I answerde att&euml; laste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="134">&para; "A! who is &thorn;er?" "I," quod &thorn;is old&euml; greye,</L>
<L>"Am heer," &amp; he me told&euml; the<NOTE PLACE="foot">the R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> manere</L>
<L>How he spak to me, as ye herd me seye;</L>
<L>"O man," quo&thorn; I, "for crist&euml;s lou&euml; dere,</L>
<L N="138">&para; If &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt aght done at my preyere,</L>
<L>As go &thorn;i way, talk&euml; to me no more,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;i word&euml;s al annoyen me ful sore;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="141">&para; "Voyd&euml; fro me; me list no compaignye;<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Encress&euml; noght my grife; I haue I-now."</L>
<L>&para; "My sone, hast &thorn;ou good lust &thorn;i sorwe drye,</L>
<L>And mayst releu&euml;d be? what man art &thorn;ou?</L>
<L N="145">Wirke after me! it schal be for &thorn;i prow;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nart but &yogh;ong, and hast but litel seen,</L>
<L N="147">And ful seelde is, &thorn;at &yogh;ong folk wys&euml; been.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="148">&para; "If &thorn;at &thorn;e lik&euml; to ben esyd wel,</L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then R.</NOTE> suffre me with &thorn;e to talke a whyle.</L>
<L>Art &thorn;ou aght lettred?" "ya," quod I, "som dele."</L>
<L>"Blissed be god! &thorn;an hope I, by seint Gyle,</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at god to &thorn;e &thorn;i wit schal reconsyle,</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at me &thorn;inke&thorn; is fer fro &thorn;e went,</L>
<L N="154">&THORN;orgh &thorn;e assent of &thorn;i greuouse turment.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="7"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="155">&para; "Lettered<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lettred R, Letterd H.</NOTE> folk han gretter discrecioun,</L>
<L>And bet conceyu&euml; konne a mannes saw,</L>
<L>And ra&thorn;er wole appli&euml; to resoun</L>
<L>And from foly&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">folye R, foly H.</NOTE> soner hem with-draw,</L>
<L N="159">&THORN;an he &thorn;at no&thorn;er reson can, ne law,</L>
<L>Ne lerned ha&thorn; no maner of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of <I>om.</I> R H.</NOTE> lettrure:</L>
<L>Plukke vp &thorn;in herte! I hope I schal &thorn;e cure."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="162">&para; "Cur&euml;, good man? ya, &thorn;ow arte a fayre leche!</L>
<L>Cur&euml; &thorn;i self, &thorn;at tremblest as &thorn;ou gost,</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;in art wole enden<NOTE PLACE="foot">enden R, ende H.</NOTE> in &thorn;i speche;</L>
<L>It li&thorn; not in &thorn;i power, por&euml; gost,</L>
<L N="166">To hel&euml; me; &thorn;ou art as seek almost</L>
<L>As I; first on &thorn;i self ky&thorn;&euml; &thorn;in art;</L>
<L N="168">And if aght leue, late me &thorn;anne hau&euml; part.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="169">&para; "Go forth &thorn;i way, I &thorn;e preye, or be stylle;<MILESTONE N="4a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou dost me more annoy &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;ou wenest;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art as ful of clap as is a mylle;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dost nought<NOTE PLACE="foot">nought R, not H.</NOTE> heer, but greuest me &amp; tenest.</L>
<L N="173">Good man, &thorn;ou woste but lytyl what &thorn;ou menest;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e, li&thorn;e not redress&euml; my nuysance,<NOTE PLACE="foot">noiaunce R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;ou mayste be wele will&eacute;d perchaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="176">&para; "It most&euml; be a greter<NOTE PLACE="foot">moste be a gretter R, most be a grete H.</NOTE> man of myght</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;at &thorn;ou art, &thorn;at schold&euml; me releue."</L>
<L>&para; "What, sone myn! &thorn;ou felist not a-right!</L>
<L>To herkene me, what schal it harme or greue?"</L>
<L>"Peter!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the</I> 17<I>th cent. hand:</I> "Peter Goodman was perhaps som olde man w<SUP>t</SUP>. whom hee consulted concerning his pension &amp;c." Peter = by St. Peter.</NOTE> good man, &thorn;ogh we talke here tyl eue,</L>
<L>Al is in veyne; &thorn;i myght may nat atteyne</L>
<L N="182">To hel&euml; me, swich is my woful peyne."
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="8"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="183">&para; "What &thorn;at I may or can, ne wost &thorn;ou noght;</L>
<L>Hardyly, son&euml;, telle on how it is!"</L>
<L>&para; "Man, at a word, it is encombrous &thorn;oght</L>
<L>&THORN;at cause&thorn; me &thorn;is sorowe &amp; fare<NOTE PLACE="foot">fare R.</NOTE> amys."</L>
<L N="187">&para; "Now, sone, &amp; if &thorn;er no &thorn;ing be but &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Do as I schal &thorn;e seye, &amp; &thorn;in estat</L>
<L N="189">Amende I schal, but &thorn;ou be obstinat,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="190">&para; "And wilfully rebelle &amp; dissobeye,</L>
<L>And liste not to my lor&euml; the conforme;</L>
<L>ffor in swiche cas, what scholde I speke or seye,</L>
<L>Or in my best&euml; wys&euml; &thorn;e enforme?</L>
<L N="194">If &thorn;ow it wayue, &amp; take an o&thorn;er forme</L>
<L>After &thorn;i childissh mysrul&euml;d conceyt,</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;ou dost vn-to &thorn;i self, harm &amp; deceit.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="197">&para; "O &thorn;ing seye I, if &thorn;ou go fe&euml;rlees<NOTE PLACE="foot">without a 'fere' or companion, felaweles H.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al solytarie, &amp; counsel lakke, &amp; rede,</L>
<L>As me &thorn;inke&thorn;, &thorn;i gyse is doutelees,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou likly art to bere a dotyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">fonned R.</NOTE> heed.</L>
<L N="201">Whil &thorn;ou art soul&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">soole R, soul H.</NOTE> &thorn;oght is wastyng seed,</L>
<L>Swich in &thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;at in grete foysoun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou redeles, nat canst<NOTE PLACE="foot">kanst not R.</NOTE> voyde his poysoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="204">&para; "The boke sei&thorn; &thorn;us,&mdash;I redde it yore agon,&mdash;</L>
<L>'Wo be to hym &thorn;at list to ben allone!<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ve soli! quia, si cadat, non habet subleuantem.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor if he fall&euml;, helpe ne ha&thorn; he non</L>
<L>To rys&euml;'; &thorn;is seye I by &thorn;i persone;</L>
<L N="208">I fonde &thorn;e soul, &amp; &thorn;i wytt&euml;s echone</L>
<L>ffer fro &thorn;e fled, &amp; disparpled ful wyde;</L>
<L N="210">Wherefore it seme&thorn;, &thorn;e nedi&thorn; a gyde,
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="9"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="211">&para; "Which &thorn;at &thorn;e may vnto &thorn;i wytt&euml;s lede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">That R.</NOTE> graspist heer &amp; &thorn;ere, as do&thorn; &thorn;e blynde,</L>
<L>And ay mys-gost; &amp; &yogh;it haue I no drede,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou receyu&euml; wold in-to &thorn;i mynde</L>
<L N="215">My lore, &amp; execute it, &thorn;ou schalt fynde</L>
<L>&THORN;ere-in swiche es&euml;, &thorn;at &thorn;i maladye</L>
<L N="217">A-bregge it schal, &amp; &thorn;i mal&eacute;ncolye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="218">&para; "fful holsum were it, stynten of &thorn;i wo,</L>
<L>And take vnto &thorn;e, spirit of gladnesse;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prouerbia. Animus gau|dens etatem floridam fa|cit; spiritus autem tristis desiccat ossa.</NOTE></L>
<L>What profyt fyndest &thorn;ou to mourn&euml; so?</L>
<L>Salamon sei&thorn;, &thorn;at sorowe &amp; heuynesse,</L>
<L N="222">Bon&euml;s of man drye&thorn; by his duresse,</L>
<L>And hert&euml; glad maki&thorn; florissching age;</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;erfore I red&euml; &thorn;ou &thorn;i wo a-swage.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="225">&para; "He sei&thorn;, 'as motth&euml;s to a clo&thorn;e annoyen,<MILESTONE N="5a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of his woll&euml; maken it al bare,</L>
<L>And also as worm&euml;s a tre destruen</L>
<L>&THORN;orogh hir percyng, ri&yogh;t so sorowe and care<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Item sicut tinea vesti|mento, &amp; ver|mis ligno, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="229">By-reuen man his hel&thorn;e &amp; his welfare,</L>
<L>And his day&euml;s a-bregge, &amp; schorte his lyf;</L>
<L N="231">lo! what profyt is for to be pensyf?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="232">&para; "Now, god&euml; son&euml;, telle on &thorn;i greuaunce;</L>
<L>What is &thorn;i cause of &thorn;oght in special?</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou of worldly good&euml;s h&aacute;bundaunce,</L>
<L>And carist how &thorn;at it i-kept be schal?</L>
<L N="236">Or art &thorn;ou nedy, &amp; hast nou&yogh;t but smal,</L>
<L>And thristist sore<NOTE PLACE="foot">trustest sone R.</NOTE> a rych&euml; man to be?</L>
<L N="238">Or louest her&euml; &thorn;at not loue&thorn; &thorn;e?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or elles lovest thou hir that loveth not the R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="10"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="239">&para; "I haue herd seyn, in kepyng of richesse</L>
<L>Is thoght and wo, &amp; besy a-wayte al-way;</L>
<L>The pore &amp; nedy ek ha&thorn; heuynesse,</L>
<L>ffor to his purpos not atteyne he may;</L>
<L N="243">&THORN;e louer also seen men day by day,</L>
<L>Prolle after &thorn;at, &thorn;at he schal neuer fynde;</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;us &thorn;oght turmenti&thorn; folk in sondry kynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="246">&para; "If &thorn;ou &thorn;e fele in any of &thorn;ese i-greued,</L>
<L>Or elles what, tell on, in godd&euml;s name.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seest al day, &thorn;e begger is releued,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sitte and begge&thorn;, blynd, crokyd &amp; lame;</L>
<L N="250">And whi? for he ne letti&thorn;, for no schame,</L>
<L>his harm&euml;s &amp; his pouert to by-wreye</L>
<L N="252">To folk, as &thorn;ey gon by hym in &thorn;e weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="253">&para; "ffor, and he kepe hym cloos, &amp; holde his pees,<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And noght out schewe how seek he inward is,</L>
<L>He may al day so sytten help&euml;lees;<NOTE PLACE="foot">helpeles R, helplees H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, son&euml; myn, al&thorn;ogh he faire<NOTE PLACE="foot">fare R.</NOTE> a-mys</L>
<L N="257">&THORN;at hydith so, god wot &thorn;e wyt is his;</L>
<L>But &thorn;is begger his hurt&euml;s wol not stele,</L>
<L>He wele telle al and more; he can nou&yogh;t hele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="260">&para; "Ryght so, if &thorn;e liste haue a remedye</L>
<L>Of &thorn;yn annoy &thorn;at prikke&thorn; &thorn;e so smerte,</L>
<L>The verray cause of &thorn;in hyd maladye</L>
<L>&THORN;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thow R, &THORN;e H.</NOTE> most discouer, &amp; telle oute al &thorn;in herte.</L>
<L N="264">If &thorn;ou it hyd&euml;, &thorn;ou schalt not astarte</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne fall&euml; schalt in som myschaunce;</L>
<L N="266">ffor-&thorn;i amend&euml; &thorn;ou &thorn;i gouernaunce.
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="11"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="267">&para; "Be war of &thorn;oght, for it is perillous;</L>
<L>He &thorn;e streight wey to discomf&oacute;rt men lede&thorn;;</L>
<L>His violence is ful outrag&euml;ous;</L>
<L>Vnwise is he &thorn;at besy &thorn;oght ne drede&thorn;.</L>
<L N="271">In whom &thorn;at he his mortel venym schede&thorn;,</L>
<L>But if a vomyt after folwe blyue,</L>
<L N="273">At &thorn;e port of despeir he may arryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="274">&para; "Son&euml;, swych thoght&euml; lurkynge &thorn;e with-ynne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huntith after &thorn;i confusioun,</L>
<L>Hy tyme it is to voyde &amp; late hym twynne,</L>
<L>And walke at larg&euml; out of &thorn;i prisoun.</L>
<L N="278">Be war &thorn;e fend&euml;s sly conclusioun,</L>
<L>ffor if he may &thorn;e vnto d&eacute;speir brynge,</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;ou morn&euml; schalt, &amp; lawgh he wol, &amp; synge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="281">&para; "Som man, for lak of occupacioun,<MILESTONE N="6a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Muse&thorn; for&thorn;er &thorn;anne his wyt may strecche,</L>
<L>And, at &thorn;e fend&euml;s instigacioun,</L>
<L>Dampnable errour holde&thorn;, &amp; can not flecche</L>
<L N="285">ffor no counseil ne reed, as dide a wrecche</L>
<L>Not fern agoo, whiche &thorn;at of heresye</L>
<L N="287">Conuyct, and brent was vn-to ashen drye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">This stanza has been crossed out with the pen.</NOTE>(42. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="288">&para; "The precious body of oure lorde ihesu</L>
<L>In forme of brede, he leued no[t]<NOTE PLACE="foot">not R, no H.</NOTE> at al;</L>
<L>He was in no &thorn;ing abassht, ne eschu</L>
<L>To seye it was but brede material;</L>
<L N="292">He seyde, a prest&euml;s power was as smal</L>
<L>As a Rak&eacute;rs, or swiche an o&thorn;er wi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="294">And to mak it, hadde no gretter my&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="12"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="295">&para; "My lorde &thorn;e princ&euml;&mdash;god him saue &amp; blesse!&mdash;</L>
<L>Was at his deedly castigacioun,</L>
<L>And of his soul&euml; hadde grete tendernesse,</L>
<L>Thristyng&euml; sor&euml; his sauacioun:</L>
<L N="299">Grete was his pitous lamentacioun,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;is renegat not wold&euml; blynne</L>
<L N="301">Of &thorn;e stynkyng errour &thorn;at he was inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="302">&para; "This good lorde hi&yogh;te hym to be sweche a mene</L>
<L>To his fader, oure lig&euml; lorde souereyne,</L>
<L>If he renounc&euml; wolde his errour clene,</L>
<L>And come vn-to oure good byleue ageyne,</L>
<L N="306">He schulde of his lif seure ben &amp; certeyne,</L>
<L>And s&uacute;fficiant lyflode eek scholde he haue,</L>
<L N="308">Vn-to &thorn;e day he clad were in his graue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">The three following stanzas are all crossed out with the pen.</NOTE>(45. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="309">&para; "Also &thorn;is nobyl prince &amp; wor&thorn;y knyght&mdash;<MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>God quyte hym his charitable labour!&mdash;</L>
<L>Or any stikk&euml; kyndled were or light,</L>
<L>The sacrement, oure blissed saueoure,</L>
<L N="313">With reuerenc&euml; grete &amp; hye honoure</L>
<L>He fecch&euml; leet, &thorn;is wrecch&euml; to conuerte,</L>
<L N="315">And make oure fei&thorn;e to synkyn in his herte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="316">&para; "But al for noght, it wold&euml; not bytyde;</L>
<L>He heeld for&thorn; his oppynyoun dampn&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>And cast oure holy cristen fei&thorn; a-syde,</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at was to &thorn;e fende accept&aacute;ble.</L>
<L N="320">By any outward tokyn reson&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>If he inward hadde any repentaunce,</L>
<L N="322">&THORN;at wote he, &thorn;at of no &thorn;ing ha&thorn; doutaunce.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="13"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="323">&para; "Lat &thorn;e diuin&euml;s of hym speke &amp; muse</L>
<L>Where his soule is by-come, or whider gon;</L>
<L>Myn vnkonyng of &thorn;at me schal excuse,</L>
<L>Of whiche mater&euml; knowleche haue I non.</L>
<L N="327">But wold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolde R, wold H.</NOTE> god, tho cristes foos echon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at as he heeld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">helde R, held H.</NOTE> were I-seru&euml;d soo,</L>
<L N="329">ffor I am seur &thorn;at &thorn;er ben many moo,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="330">&para; "The more ruthe is: allas! what men ben &thorn;ey</L>
<L>&THORN;at hem delyten in swiche surquidrie?</L>
<L>ffor mann&euml;s reson may not preue oure fey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey wole it dispreuen or denye.</L>
<L N="334">To oure lorde god &thorn;at sytte in heuenes hye,</L>
<L>Schal &thorn;ey desyre for to ben egal?</L>
<L N="336">Nay, &thorn;at was neuer, certes, ne be schal.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="337">&para; "&THORN;&aacute;t oure lord god sei&thorn; in holy scripture<MILESTONE N="7a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>May not be fals; &thorn;is knawit euery whi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But he be mad; &amp; &thorn;ogh a creature</L>
<L>In his godd&euml;s werk<NOTE PLACE="foot">werkes R.</NOTE> feel&euml; not a-ryght,</L>
<L N="341">Schal he rebelle ageyn his lord&euml;s myght,</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;is wyd&euml; world ha&thorn; made of noght,</L>
<L N="343">ffor reson may not knytte it in his thoght?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="344">&para; "Was it not eek a moustre as in nature</L>
<L>&THORN;at god I-bor&euml; was of a virgine?</L>
<L>&YOGH;it is it so&thorn;, &thorn;ogh man be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by R.</NOTE> c&oacute;niecture</L>
<L>Of reson, or what he can &yacute;magine,</L>
<L N="348">Not sauoure it, ne can it d&eacute;termyne.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at al myghty is, do&thorn; as hym lyste;</L>
<L N="350">He wole his konnynge hydde be, &amp; nat wyste.
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="14"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="351">&para; "Oure fei&thorn; not were vnto vs merit&oacute;rie<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Fides non habet meri|tum ubi hu|mana ratio pr&aelig;bet ex|perimentum.</NOTE></L>
<L>If &thorn;at we myghten by reson it preue;</L>
<L>Lat vs not fro god twynnen<NOTE PLACE="foot">twynne R.</NOTE> &amp; his glorie;</L>
<L>As holy chirche vs byt, lat vs be-leue;&mdash;</L>
<L N="355">But we &thorn;ere-to obeye, it schal vs greue</L>
<L>Importably; lat vs do as sche byt,</L>
<L N="357">Oure goed&euml; fadres olde<NOTE PLACE="foot">For our faders all R.</NOTE> han folwyd it.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="358">&para; "Presumpc&iuml;oun, a! benedicite!</L>
<L>Why vexest &thorn;ou folk with &thorn;i franesie?</L>
<L>&thorn;ogh no &thorn;ing ell&euml;s were, I seye for me,</L>
<L>But se how &thorn;at &thorn;e wor&thorn;i prelacie,</L>
<L N="362">And vnder hem &thorn;e suffissant clergye,</L>
<L>Endowyd of profound intelligence,</L>
<L N="364">Of al &thorn;is land werreyen &thorn;i sentence;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="365">&para; "That selu&euml; sam&euml; to me were a bridel,<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By whiche wolde I gou&eacute;rned<NOTE PLACE="foot">gouerned R, gouernend H.</NOTE> ben &amp; gyed,</L>
<L>And ellis al my labour were in ydel.</L>
<L>By holy churche I wole be iustified;</L>
<L N="369">To &thorn;at, al holly is myn herte applied,</L>
<L>And euer schal; I truste in godd&euml;s grace,</L>
<L N="371">Swiche surquidrie in me schal haue no place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="372">&para; "Sone, if god wol&euml;, &thorn;ou art non of &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at wrapped ben in &thorn;is dampnac&iuml;oun?"</L>
<L>&para; "I?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ey R.</NOTE> criste forbede it, sire!" seyde I &thorn;o;</L>
<L>"I &thorn;anke it god, non inclinac&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="376">Haue I to labour in probac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Of his hy knowleche &amp; his myghty werkys,</L>
<L N="378">ffor swiche mater vn-to, my wit to<NOTE PLACE="foot">full R.</NOTE> derk is.
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="15"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="379">&para; "Of oure fei&thorn; wol I not despute at all;</L>
<L>But, at a<NOTE PLACE="foot">o R.</NOTE> word, I in &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e auter fully bileue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">beleue R, I bileue H.</NOTE> &amp; schal,</L>
<L>With godd&euml;s helpe, while life is to me lent;</L>
<L N="383">And, in despyt of &thorn;e fend&euml;s talent,</L>
<L>In al o&thorn;er articles of &thorn;e fei&thorn;</L>
<L N="385">Byleue, as fer as &thorn;at holy writ<NOTE PLACE="foot">I beleeue as holy writte R.</NOTE> sei&thorn;."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="386">&para; "Now good thrifte come vn-to &thorn;e, son&euml; dere!</L>
<L>&THORN;i gost is now a-wakyd, wel I se,</L>
<L>And som-what eke amendid is &thorn;i chere;</L>
<L>And firste I was ful sore a-gast of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="390">Lest &thorn;at &thorn;ou thorgh thoght-ful aduersyte,</L>
<L>Not haddest standen in &thorn;i fey&thorn;e a-ryght;</L>
<L N="392">Now is myn hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H.</NOTE> waxen glad &amp; lyght.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="393">&para; "Hast &thorn;ou in me ony gretter sauour<MILESTONE N="8a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest first whan &thorn;ou me sy,</L>
<L>Whan I opposyd &thorn;e of &thorn;i langour?</L>
<L>&para; Seye on &thorn;e so&thorn;&euml;." "Ya, somdele," quod I.</L>
<L N="397">&para; "My sone, in fayth, &thorn;at is seyde ful feyntly;</L>
<L>Thi sauour yit ful smal is, as I trowe;</L>
<L N="399">But or oght longe, I schal &thorn;e so&thorn;&euml; knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58. Beggar.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This and the 15 following stanzas occur as a separate poem in Laud 735, lf. 67, &amp;c. (Bodl. Lib.), and I so printed em in my <I>Queene Elizabethes Achademy</I> (E. E. T. Soc.), p. 105.</NOTE>)</HEAD>
<L N="400">&para; "I wote wel, sone, of me &thorn;us wold &thorn;ou &thorn;inke:&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is old&euml; dotyd Grisel holte him wyse,</L>
<L>He wene&thorn; maken in myn heed to synke</L>
<L>His lewed clap, of which set I no pryse;</L>
<L N="404">He is a nobil prechour at deuyse;</L>
<L>Gret noyse ha&thorn; &thorn;orgh hys chynn&euml;d<NOTE PLACE="foot">thynne R.</NOTE> lipp&euml;s drye</L>
<L N="406">&THORN;is day out past, &thorn;e deuel in his eye.
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="16"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="407">&para; "But &thorn;ogh I olde &amp; hore be, son&euml; myin,</L>
<L>And por&euml; be my clethyng &amp; aray,</L>
<L>And not so wyde a gowne haue, as is &thorn;in,</L>
<L>So smal I-pynchid, ne so fresche and gay,</L>
<L N="411">Mi redde, in happ&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">happe R, hap H.</NOTE> &yogh;it the perfet<NOTE PLACE="foot">profite R.</NOTE> may;</L>
<L>And likly, &thorn;at &thorn;ou demest for folye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">folie R, foly H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="413">Is gretter wysdom &thorn;an &thorn;ou canste espye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="414">&para; "Vndir an old pore habyt, regne&thorn; oft</L>
<L>Grete vertu, &thorn;ogh it moustre por&euml;ly;</L>
<L>And where as gret array is vp on loft,</L>
<L>Vice is but seelden hid; &thorn;at wel wote I.</L>
<L N="418">But not report, I pray &thorn;e, inwardly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fresch array I generally depraue;</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;is wor&thorn;i men mowe it wel vse &amp; haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="421">&para; "But &thorn;is me &thorn;inki&thorn; an abus&iuml;oun,<MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To se on<NOTE PLACE="foot">one R.</NOTE> walke in gown&euml;s of scarlet,</L>
<L>xij &yogh;erd&euml;s wyd, wit<NOTE PLACE="foot">with R.</NOTE> pendant sleues downe</L>
<L>On &thorn;e grounde, &amp; &thorn;e furrour &thorn;er-in set</L>
<L N="425">Amountyng vnto <I>twenty</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. xx<SUP>ti</SUP></NOTE> pound or bet;</L>
<L>And if he for it payde haue, he no good</L>
<L N="427">Ha&thorn; lefte him where-wit for to bye an hood.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="428">&para; "ffor &thorn;ogh he iett&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">gode R.</NOTE> forth a-mong &thorn;e prees,</L>
<L>And ouer lok&euml; euerey por&euml; wight,</L>
<L>His cofre and eke his purs ben penylees,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; no mor&euml; &thorn;an he go&thorn; in ryght.</L>
<L N="432">ffor lond, rent, or catel, he may go light;</L>
<L>&THORN;e weght of hem schal not so moch&euml; peyse</L>
<L N="434">As do&thorn; his gowne: is swiche array to preyse?
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="17"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="435">&para; "Nay sothely, sone, it is al a-mys me &thorn;inky&thorn;;</L>
<L>So pore a wight his lord to counterfete</L>
<L>In his array, in my conceyit it stynkith.</L>
<L>Certes to blam&euml; ben &thorn;e lord&euml;s grete,</L>
<L N="439">If &thorn;at I durst&euml; seyn, &thorn;at hir men lete</L>
<L>Vsurp&euml; swiche a lordly apparaille,</L>
<L N="441">Is<NOTE PLACE="foot">It is R. Cp. our modern slang "it is not good enough."</NOTE> not wor&thorn;, my childe, with-outen fayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="442">&para; "Som tyme, afer men myghten lord&euml;s knowe</L>
<L>By there array, from o&thorn;er folke; but now</L>
<L>A man schal stody and musen a long<NOTE PLACE="foot">muse a longe throwe R.</NOTE> throwe</L>
<L>Whiche is whiche: o lordes, it sit to yowe</L>
<L N="446">Amend&euml; &thorn;is, for it is for youre prowe.</L>
<L>If twixt yow and youre men no difference</L>
<L N="448">Be in array, lesse is youre reuerence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="449">&para; "Also ther is another new&euml; get,<MILESTONE N="9a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A foul wast of cloth and an excessyf;</L>
<L>Ther goth no lesse in a mann&euml;s tipet</L>
<L>Than of brood cloth a yerd&euml;, by my lif;</L>
<L N="453">Me thynkyth this a verray inductif</L>
<L>Vnto stelthe: ware hem of hempen lane!</L>
<L N="455">ffor stelthe is medid with a chekelew bane.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="456">&para; "Let euere lord, his own&euml; men deffende</L>
<L>Swiche gret array, and &thorn;an, on my peryl,</L>
<L>This land within a whil&euml; schal amende.</L>
<L>In goddys nam&euml;, putte it in exyl!</L>
<L N="460">It is synn&euml; outrag&iuml;ous and vyl;</L>
<L>Lord&euml;s, if ye your &eacute;stat and honour</L>
<L N="462">Louen, fleemyth this vicius errour!
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="18"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="463">&para; "What is a lord withouten his meynee?</L>
<L>I putt&euml; cas, &thorn;at his foos hym assaille</L>
<L>Sodenly in &thorn;e stret,&mdash;What help schal he,</L>
<L>Wos sleeu&euml;s encombrous so syd&euml; traille,</L>
<L N="467">Do to his lord? he may hym nat auaille;</L>
<L>In swych a cas he nys but a womman;</L>
<L N="469">He may nat stand hym in steed of a man.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="470">&para; "His armys two han ryght y-now to done,</L>
<L>And sumwhat more, his sleeu&euml;s vp to holde;</L>
<L>The taillours, trow I, moot heer-after soone</L>
<L>Shape in &thorn;e feeld; thay shal nat sprede and folde</L>
<L N="474">On hir bord, thogh &thorn;ei neuer s&oacute; fayn wolde,</L>
<L>The cloth &thorn;at shal ben in a gown&euml; wroght;</L>
<L N="476">Take an hool cloth is best, for lesse is noght.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="477">&para; "The skynner vn-to &thorn;e feeld moot also,<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His hous in london is to streyt &amp; scars</L>
<L>To doon his craft; sum tyme it was nat so.</L>
<L>O lord&euml;s, yeue vnto your men hir pars</L>
<L N="481">That so doon, and aqwente hem bet with mars,</L>
<L>God of bataile; he loueth non array</L>
<L N="483">That hurtyth manhode at preef or assay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="484">&para; "Who now moost may bere on his bak at ones</L>
<L>Of cloth and furrour, hath a fressch renoun;</L>
<L>He is 'a lusty man' clept for &thorn;e nones;</L>
<L>But drapers &amp; eek skynners in &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L N="488">ffor swich folk han a special orisoun<NOTE PLACE="foot">orisoune R, orsoun H.</NOTE></L>
<L>That troppid is with curses heere &amp; there,</L>
<L N="490">And ay schal, til &thorn;ei paid be for hir gere.
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="19"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="491">&para; "In day&euml;s old&euml;, whan smal apparaille</L>
<L>Suffisid vn-to hy estat or mene,</L>
<L>Was gret houshold wel stuffid of victaille;</L>
<L>But now housholdes ben ful sclender &amp; lene,</L>
<L N="495">ffor al &thorn;e good &thorn;at men may repe or glene,</L>
<L>Wasted is in outrag&euml;ous array,</L>
<L N="497">So that houshold&euml;s men nat hold&euml; may.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="498">&para; "Pryde hath wel leuer bere an hungry mawe</L>
<L>To bedd&euml;, than lakke of array outrage;</L>
<L>He no prys settith<NOTE PLACE="foot">setteth R, setthit H.</NOTE> be mesur&euml;s lawe,</L>
<L>Ne takith of hym cloth[&euml;], mete, ne wage:</L>
<L N="502">Mesure is out of londe on pylgrymage;</L>
<L>But I suppose he schal resorte as blyue,</L>
<L N="504">ffor verray need&euml; wol<NOTE PLACE="foot">wole R, wel H.</NOTE> vs ther-to dryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="505">&para; "Ther may no lord tak vp no<NOTE PLACE="foot">a R.</NOTE> new&euml; gyse<MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But &thorn;at a knau&euml; shal &thorn;e same vp take.</L>
<L>If lord&euml;s wolden [cessyn] in &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L>ffor to do swich&euml; gown&euml;s to hem make</L>
<L N="509">As men did in old tyme, I vndertake</L>
<L>The sam&euml; get<NOTE PLACE="foot">jette R.</NOTE> sholde vp be take and vsid,</L>
<L N="511">And al &thorn;is costelew<NOTE PLACE="foot">costeleue R, costlew H.</NOTE> outrage refusid.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="512">&para; "Of lancastre duk Iohn, whos soule in heuene<NOTE PLACE="marg">This was John of Gaunt, father to Henry the fourth, and Grandfather to Henry the fyuth. hee dyed anno 1399. (<I>In the</I> 1700 <I>hand.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L>I fully deme, And trust&euml; sit ful hye&mdash;</L>
<L>A noble prince I may allegge &amp; neuene,</L>
<L>(Other may no man of hym testifye)&mdash;</L>
<L N="516">I neuer sy a lord that cowde hym gye</L>
<L>Bet like his &eacute;stat; al knyghtly prowesse</L>
<L N="518">Was to hym girt: o god! his soul&euml; blisse!
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="20"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="519">&para; "His garnament&euml;s weren noght ful wyde,</L>
<L>And yit &thorn;ei hym becam wond&eacute;rly wel.</L>
<L>Now wold[&euml;] god &thorn;e waast of cloth &amp; pryde</L>
<L>Y-put were in exyl perpetuel,</L>
<L N="523">ffor &thorn;e good and profet<NOTE PLACE="foot">profite R.</NOTE> vniuersel.</L>
<L>And lordes myght helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">do R.</NOTE> al this, if &thorn;ei wolde</L>
<L N="525">The olde get take, and it furth vse &amp; holde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">jette vp take, and it forth holde R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="526">&para; "Than myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">myght H R.</NOTE> siluer walk&euml; mor&euml; thikke</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e peple &thorn;an &thorn;at it do&thorn; now;</L>
<L>Ther wold I fayne &thorn;at were y-set &thorn;e prikke,&mdash;</L>
<L>Nat for my self; I schal doo wel ynow,&mdash;</L>
<L N="530">But, son&euml;, for &thorn;at swich&euml; men as thow</L>
<L>That with &thorn;e world wrastlen, myght han plente</L>
<L N="532">Of coyn, where as ye han now scarsetee.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="533">&para; "Now hath &thorn;is lord<NOTE PLACE="foot">thise lordes R.</NOTE> but litil neede of broomes<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To swepe a-way &thorn;e filthe out of &thorn;e street,<NOTE PLACE="marg">hos versus Io. Stow citat in Chronicae sua, fol. 559 sub nomine Tho. Hoc|clive. (<I>In the</I> 1700 <I>hand.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L>Syn syd&euml; sleu&euml;s of pen&yacute;lees gromes</L>
<L>Wile it vp likk&euml;, be it drye or weet.</L>
<L N="537">O engelond! stande vp-ryght on thy feet!</L>
<L>So foul a wast in so symple degree</L>
<L N="539">Bannysshe! or sore it schal repent&euml; the.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="540">&para; "If a wight vertuous, but narwe clothid<NOTE PLACE="foot">with narwe clothes R.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>To lord&euml;s curt&euml;s now of<NOTE PLACE="foot">courtes now a R.</NOTE> day&euml;s go,</L>
<L>His compaignye is vn-to folk&euml;s lothid;</L>
<L>Men passen by hym both&euml; to and fro,</L>
<L N="544">And scorne hym, for he is arrayed so;</L>
<L>To hir conceit is no wight vertuous,</L>
<L N="546">But he &thorn;at of array is outrageous.
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="21"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="547">&para; "But he that flater can, or be a baude,</L>
<L>And by tho tweyn&euml;, fressch array him gete,</L>
<L>It holden is to him honur &amp; laude.<NOTE PLACE="foot">laude R, laue H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Trouth and clenness&euml; musten men for-gete</L>
<L N="551">In lord&euml;s court&euml;s, for they hert&euml;s frete;</L>
<L>They hyndren folk: fy vpon tong&euml;s trewe!</L>
<L N="553">They displesaunce in lord&euml;s court&euml;s breewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(80. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="554">&para; "Lo, son&euml; myn, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">this R.</NOTE> tale is at an eende:</L>
<L>Now, good&euml; sone, haue of me no desdeyn,</L>
<L>Thogh I be old, and myn array vntheende;</L>
<L>ffor many a yong man, wot I wel certeyn,</L>
<L N="558">Of corage is so prowde and so hauteyn,</L>
<L>That to &thorn;e poore and old mann&euml;s doctrine,</L>
<L N="560">fful seelde him deyneth bowen or enclyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(81. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="561">&para; "Senek sei&thorn;, 'age is an infirmitee<MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca ad Lucillum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at lech&euml; non can cur&euml;, ne it hele,</L>
<L>ffor to &thorn;e de&thorn; next negh&euml;burgh is he;</L>
<L>Ther may no wight &thorn;e chartre of lyf ensele,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nil cercius morte <I>etc.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="565">The ende is de&thorn; of male &amp; of femele;</L>
<L>No thyng is mor&euml; certein &thorn;an de&thorn; is,</L>
<L N="567">Ne more vncertein &thorn;an &thorn;e tyme I-wis.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(82. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="568">&para; "As touchyng ag&euml;, god in holy writ<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Exodus. honora pa|trem &amp; ma|trem, vt sis longeuus su|per terram.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ryght &thorn;us sei&thorn;: 'fader &amp; moder honure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Non-Chaucerian ryme -<I>oure</I> with -<I>ure</I>, as in the "Mother of God," &amp;c. See Forewords to Hoccleve's <I>Minor Poems</I>, Part I, p. xxxix.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mayste be longlyued:' &thorn;us he byt.</L>
<L>&THORN;an moot it folwen vpon &thorn;is scripture,</L>
<L N="572">Age is a guerdoun to a cr&euml;ature,</L>
<L>And longlyu&euml;d is non with-outen age;</L>
<L N="574">Where-for I seye, in eld is auauntage.
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(83. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="575">&para; "And &thorn;e reuard of god may not be smal,</L>
<L>His &yogh;ift&euml;s ben ful noble &amp; profitabil;</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i ne lakk&euml; &thorn;ou not age at al;</L>
<L>Whan you&thorn;e is past, is ag&euml; sesonable.</L>
<L N="579">Age ha&thorn; in-sighte how vnsure &amp; vnstable</L>
<L>&THORN;is world&euml;s cours is, by lengthe of his yeeres,</L>
<L>And can deffende hym from his scharp&euml; breres.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(84. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="582">&para; "Lord, whe&thorn;er it be maystrie to knowe</L>
<L>Whan a man ofte ha&thorn; sundry wey&euml;s ride</L>
<L>Which is &thorn;e best&euml;? nay, for so&thorn;e I trowe;</L>
<L>Right so he &thorn;at ha&thorn; many a world abyde</L>
<L N="586">&THORN;er he in you&thorn;&euml; wroght&euml; mis or dyde,</L>
<L>His age it see&thorn;, &amp; byt him it eschue,</L>
<L N="588">And seeki&thorn; wey&euml;s couenable &amp; due.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(85. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="589">&para; "Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast assayd&euml; bo&thorn;&euml; two,<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sad age, I seye, after &thorn;i skittish you&thorn;e,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou must nedys atteyn&euml; ther-to,</L>
<L>Or steru&euml; &yogh;ong, &thorn;an trowe I &thorn;ou wolt bowe &thorn;e</L>
<L N="593">To swich&euml; conceyt&euml;s as I haue now&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">youe&thorn;e R.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ank&euml; god deuoutly in &thorn;in herte</L>
<L N="595">&THORN;at he ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;e &thorn;i youthe asterte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(86. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="596">&para; "Youth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">your H.</NOTE> ful smal<NOTE PLACE="foot">small R, smal H.</NOTE> reward hath to goodnesse,</L>
<L>And peril dredith he non, wot I wel;</L>
<L>Al his deuocioun and holynesse</L>
<L>At tauerne is, as for &thorn;e most&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">most H R.</NOTE> del;</L>
<L N="600">To Bachus signe &amp; to &thorn;e leu&euml;sel</L>
<L>His you&thorn;e him hali&thorn;; &amp; whan it him happi&thorn;</L>
<L N="602">To chirch&euml; gon, of nycet&euml; he clappi&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="23"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(87. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="603">&para; "The caus&euml; why men oghten &thorn;ider gon,</L>
<L>Nat conceyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">conceyue R, cause H.</NOTE> can his wyld&euml; steerissh heed</L>
<L>To folwen it. Also bote is it non</L>
<L>To telle it him, for thogh men sowen seed</L>
<L N="607">Of vertu in a yong man, it is deed</L>
<L>As blyue, his rebel goost it mortifie&thorn;;</L>
<L N="609">Al &thorn;ing sauf folye in a yong man die&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(88. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="610">&para; "Whan I was yong I was ful rech&euml;lees,</L>
<L>Prowde, nyce, and riotous for &thorn;e maystrie,</L>
<L>And, among o&thorn;er, conscienc&euml;lees;</L>
<L>By &thorn;at sette I naght &thorn;e wor&thorn; of a flye;</L>
<L N="614">And of hem haunted I &thorn;e compaignie</L>
<L>&THORN;at went on pylgrymag&euml; to tauerne,</L>
<L N="616">Which be-for vnthrift beri&thorn; &thorn;e lanterne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(89. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="617">&para; "There offryd I wel mor&euml; &thorn;an my ty&thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wit-drowe holy chirche his<NOTE PLACE="foot">holy chirches R.</NOTE> du&euml;tee;</L>
<L>My frend&euml;s me counseyl&euml;d often si&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I, with lownesse &amp; humylitee,</L>
<L N="621">To my curat go scholde, &amp; make his gree;</L>
<L>But straw vnto hir reed! wolde I nat bowe</L>
<L N="623">ffor aght &thorn;ey kouden preyen all, or wowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(90. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="624">&para; "Whan folk wel rulyd dressyd hem to bedde,</L>
<L>In tym&euml; due by red&euml; of nature,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e tauern&euml; quykly I me spedde,</L>
<L>And pleyde at dees while &thorn;e nyghte wolde endure.</L>
<L N="628">&THORN;ere, &thorn;e former of euery creature</L>
<L>Dismembred y with o&thorn;&euml;s grete, &amp; rente</L>
<L N="630">Lyme for lyme, or &thorn;at I &thorn;enn&euml;s wente.
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(91. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="631">&para; "And ofte it fals was &thorn;at I swoer or spak,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e desire feru&eacute;nt of couetyse</L>
<L>ffonde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fonde I R.</NOTE> in peri&uacute;rie no defaute or lak,</L>
<L>But euer entyced me &thorn;at in al wyse</L>
<L N="635">Myn o&thorn;&euml;s gret&euml; I scholde excercyse;</L>
<L>And specially for lucre, in al manere</L>
<L N="637">Swere and for-swere with bold&euml; face &amp; chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(92. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="638">&para; "But &thorn;is condic&iuml;oun, lo, hadde I euere:</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh I prowde were in word&euml;s or in speche,</L>
<L>Whan strok&euml;s cam a<NOTE PLACE="foot">in R.</NOTE> place, I gan disseuere</L>
<L>ffro<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fro R, For H.</NOTE> my felaw&euml;s; soghte I neuere leeche</L>
<L>ffor hurt which I there<NOTE PLACE="foot">there R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> toke; what scholde I seche</L>
<L>A salu&euml;, whan I &thorn;er-of hadde no nede?</L>
<L N="644">I hurtlees was ay, &thorn;urgh impressyd drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(93. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Tho myghte I spende an <I>hundred</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">a C, H.</NOTE> mark by &yogh;ere,<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al thyng deduct,<NOTE PLACE="foot">quytta R.</NOTE> my sone, I gabb&euml; noght;</L>
<L>I was so prowde, I helde no man my pere;</L>
<L>In pryde &amp; leccherye was al my &thorn;oght;</L>
<L N="649">No more I hadd&euml; set &thorn;erby or roght,</L>
<L>A wif or mayde or nun&euml; to deffoule,</L>
<L N="651">Than scheete, or pley&euml;n<NOTE PLACE="foot">pleyn H, pleye R.</NOTE> at &thorn;e bal or boule.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(94. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="652">&para; "Ryght nyc&euml; girl&euml;s at my retenue</L>
<L>Hadde I an heep, wyu&euml;s &amp; o&thorn;ere mo;</L>
<L>What so &thorn;ey wer&euml;, I wolde non eschue:</L>
<L>And yeer&euml;s fel&euml; I contynued so;</L>
<L N="656">Allas! I no &thorn;ing was war of &thorn;e wo</L>
<L>&THORN;at folwyd me; I lookyd nat behynde;</L>
<L N="658">Conceyt&euml;s yong&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yonge R, yong H.</NOTE> ben ful derke &amp; blynde.
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(95. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="659">&para; "An office also hadde I lucratyf,</L>
<L>An wan y-nowgh, god wot, &amp; mochel more;</L>
<L>But neuer &thorn;oght I, in al my yong&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yonge R, yong H.</NOTE> lyf,</L>
<L>What I iniustly gat, for to restore;</L>
<L N="663">Wherefore I now repent&euml; wonder sore;</L>
<L>As yt mysgoten was, mys was despendid,</L>
<L N="665">Of whiche oure lord god gretly was offendid.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(96. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="666">&para; "He sy I nolde absteen&euml; for no good</L>
<L>Of myn outrag&euml;ous iniquitee;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at his lust was, with-drow &thorn;e flood</L>
<L>Of wel&thorn;e, &amp; at grounde ebb&euml; sette he me;</L>
<L N="670">With pouert for my gylt me feffed he,</L>
<L>Swiche<NOTE PLACE="foot">Such R.</NOTE> wrech&euml; toke he for my cursyd synne;</L>
<L N="672">No mor&euml; good haue I &thorn;an I stond inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(97. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="673">&para; "Gold, siluer, iewel, clo&thorn;, bedd&yacute;ng, array,<MILESTONE N="13a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne haue I non, o&thorn;ir &thorn;an &thorn;ou mayste se.</L>
<L>Parde! &thorn;is bare olde<NOTE PLACE="foot">this olde R.</NOTE> russet is nat gay,</L>
<L>And in my purs so gret&euml; somm&euml;s be,</L>
<L N="677">&THORN;at &thorn;ere nys countour in al cristente</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at hem can at any noumbre sette;</L>
<L N="679">&THORN;at schaltow se; my purs I wole vnschete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(98. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="680">&para; "Come hider to me, sone, &amp; look whedir</L>
<L>In &thorn;is purs &thorn;er be any croyse or crouche,</L>
<L>Sauf nedel and &thorn;rede, &amp; themel of le&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Here seest &thorn;ow naght &thorn;at man may handil or touche;</L>
<L N="684">&THORN;e feend, men seyn, may hoppen in a pouche</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at no croys &thorn;ere-inn&euml; may a-pere;</L>
<L N="686">And by my purs, &thorn;e same I may seye here.
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(99. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="687">&para; "O wher is now al &thorn;e wantoun moneye</L>
<L>That I was maister of, and gouernour,</L>
<L>Whan I knewe nat what pouert was to sey?</L>
<L>Now is pouert &thorn;e glas and &thorn;e merour.</L>
<L N="691">In whiche I se my god, my sauyour.</L>
<L>Or<NOTE PLACE="foot">or R, of H.</NOTE> pouert cam, wiste I nat what god was;</L>
<L N="693">But now I knowe, &amp; se hym in &thorn;is glas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(100. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="694">&para; "And wher&euml; be my goun&euml;s of scarl&eacute;t,</L>
<L>Sanguyn, murreye, &amp; blew&euml;s sadde &amp; lighte,</L>
<L>Gren&euml;s also, &aacute;nd &thorn;e fayre violet,</L>
<L>Hors and harneys, fresche and lusty in syghte?</L>
<L N="698">My wykked lyf ha&thorn; put al &thorn;is to flighte;</L>
<L>But certes &yogh;it me greue&thorn; most of al,</L>
<L N="700">My frendschipe is al clen&euml; fro me fal.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(101. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="701">&para; "O while I stode in wele, I was honoured,<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And many on, of my comp&aacute;ignie glad,</L>
<L>And now I am mys-lokyd on &amp; loured;</L>
<L>&thorn;ere rekke&thorn; non how wo<NOTE PLACE="foot">harde R.</NOTE> I be bystad.</L>
<L N="705">O lord! &thorn;is world<NOTE PLACE="foot">world R, wold H.</NOTE> vnstabyl is, &amp; vnsad,</L>
<L>&THORN;is world hunuri&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">honoureth R, hunri&thorn; H.</NOTE> nat mann&euml;s persone</L>
<L N="707">ffor him self, son&euml;, but for good<NOTE PLACE="foot">God R.</NOTE> allone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(102. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="708">&para; "fful so&thorn; fynde I &thorn;e word of salomon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to moneie obeien all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">all R, al H.</NOTE> &thorn;inges;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Salamon. Omnia pecunie obediunt: (R. in margin, not in H).</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at my coyn &amp; coynwor&thorn; is a-gon,</L>
<L>Contrarien &thorn;ei my wille &amp; my byddynges;</L>
<L N="712">&THORN;at in my wel&thorn;&euml; with here flaterynges</L>
<L>Helden with me what &thorn;at I wroght or seyde,</L>
<L N="714">Now disobeien &thorn;ey &thorn;at &thorn;anne obeyde.
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="27"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(103. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="715">&para; "Now seyn &thorn;ey &thorn;us&mdash;'I wist&euml; wel al-way</L>
<L>&THORN;at him destroy&euml; wolde his fool largesse;</L>
<L>I tolde hym so; &amp; euer he seyd&euml; nay:'</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;ey lyen, also<NOTE PLACE="foot">als H, as R.</NOTE> god me blisse;</L>
<L N="719">&THORN;ey me comforted ay in myn excesse,</L>
<L>And seyde I was a manly man with-alle:</L>
<L N="721">Hire hony wordys tornen me to galle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="104" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(104. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="722">&para; "God, whiche of his benyngn&euml; curteseye</L>
<L>And of his cheer&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">chere R, cheer H.</NOTE> louyng tendirnesse,</L>
<L>He of his synful ha&thorn; nat wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">wille R, 'wele' is H's often spelling of 'will': see l. 749.</NOTE> he die,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Scriptum est: Nolo mortem peccatoris, &amp;c. (R. in margin, not in H).</NOTE></L>
<L>But lyu&euml; for tamende his wykkednesse;</L>
<L N="726">Hym thanke I, and his infynyt goodnesse;</L>
<L>His grac&euml; liki&thorn; &thorn;at, &thorn;orght<NOTE PLACE="foot">thurgh R.</NOTE> worldly peyne,</L>
<L N="728">My soule eschap&euml; may &thorn;e fend&euml;s cheyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="105" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(105. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="729">&para; "Iob hadde an heuyer fal &thorn;an I, pardee!<MILESTONE N="14a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor he was clumben hyer in rychesse;</L>
<L>And paciently he his aduersite</L>
<L>Took, as &thorn;e byble ber&euml; can wytnesse;</L>
<L N="733">And after-ward, god al his heuynesse</L>
<L>Torned to ioye; and so may he do myne,</L>
<L N="735">Whan &thorn;at it lyki&thorn; to his myght dyuyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="106" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(106. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="736">&para; "Lord, as &thorn;e lyst,<NOTE PLACE="foot">thow lust R.</NOTE> ryght so &thorn;ou to me do,</L>
<L>But euer I hop&euml; seur ben of &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at &thorn;i mercy boght vs ha&thorn; vnto,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at vs list for to su&euml; &thorn;i grace.</L>
<L N="740">A! lord almyghty, in my lyu&euml;s space,</L>
<L>Of my gylt graunt&euml; &thorn;ou me r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L N="742">And &thorn;i strook take in greable<NOTE PLACE="foot">charitable R.</NOTE> souffraunce.
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="107" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(107. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="743">&para; "I coude of you&thorn;e han talkyd more &amp; tolde</L>
<L>&thorn;an I haue done, but &thorn;e day passi&thorn; swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And eke me leuer is by many folde<NOTE PLACE="foot">folde R, flode H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;y greef to know&euml;, whiche &thorn;at sit so ny &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="747">Telle on anon, my good&euml; sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> and I the</L>
<L>Schal<NOTE PLACE="foot">Shall R, And schal H.</NOTE> herken, as &thorn;ou [so longe] hast done me;</L>
<L N="749">And, as I can, wele I conseyl&euml; &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="108" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(108. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="750">&para; "Graunt mercy, der&euml; fadir, of youre speche;</L>
<L>Ye han ryght wel me comforted &amp; esyd;</L>
<L>And hertily I praye yowe, and byseche,</L>
<L>What I firste to yow spak be nat displesyd;</L>
<L N="754">It rewi&thorn; me if I yow haue disesyd,</L>
<L>And mekely yow byseche I of pardoun,</L>
<L N="756">Me s&uacute;bmittyng vn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto your R.</NOTE> correcc&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="109" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(109. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="757">&para; "I wot wel, first whan &thorn;at I with yow mette,<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I was ful mad, and spak ful rud&euml;ly,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh I nat slept&euml;, yit my spirit mette</L>
<L>fful angry drem&euml;s; &thorn;oght ful bysily</L>
<L N="761">Vexid my goost, so &thorn;at no &thorn;ing wyste I</L>
<L>What &thorn;at I to yow spak, or what I &thorn;oghte,</L>
<L N="763">But here &amp; &thorn;er&euml; I my seluen soghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="110" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(110. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="764">&para; "I preye yow demeth noght &thorn;at in dispyit</L>
<L>I hadd&euml; yow, for age or poueretee;</L>
<L>I mente it noght; but I stode in swiche plyit</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was no&thorn;ing likly vn-to me,</L>
<L N="768">&THORN;ogh ye had knowen al my pryuete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ye myghten my greef &thorn;us han abregged</L>
<L N="770">As ye han done; so sore I was aggregged.
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="111" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(111. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="771">&para; "ffadir, as wisly god me saue and spede,</L>
<L>Ye ben not he whom &thorn;at I wende han founde;</L>
<L>Ye ben to me ful welcome in &thorn;is nede;</L>
<L>I wot wel ye in hy vertu habounde.</L>
<L N="775">Your wys reed, hope I, hel&euml; schal my wounde;</L>
<L>My day of hel&thorn;e is present, as me &thorn;inki&thorn;;</L>
<L N="777">Youre confort deepe in-to myn hert&euml; synketh.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="112" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(112. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="778">&para; "Myn hert&euml; sei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">seeth R.</NOTE> &thorn;at youre beneuolence,</L>
<L>Of reuth&euml; meeu&euml;d, &amp; verray pytee</L>
<L>Of my wo, do&thorn; his peyne &amp; diligence</L>
<L>Me to releue of myn infirmytee.</L>
<L N="782">O good&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">goode R, good H.</NOTE> fadir, blissed mote ye be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at han swich reuthe of my woful estat,</L>
<L N="784">Which wel ny was of help&euml; desperat.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="113" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(113. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="785">&para; "But, fadir, thogh ther be dyuersitee<MILESTONE N="15a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>fful gret betwixt your excellent prud&eacute;nce</L>
<L>And &thorn;e foly&euml; &thorn;at regneth in me,</L>
<L>Yit god it wot, ful litil differ&eacute;nce</L>
<L N="789">Is ther betwixt &thorn;e hete and &thorn;e feru&eacute;nce</L>
<L>Of lou&euml; wich to agid folk ye haue,</L>
<L N="791">And myn, al-thogh ye deeme I hem depraue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="114" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(114. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="792">&para; "ffor if &thorn;at I &thorn;e soth&euml; schal confesse,</L>
<L>The lak of old&euml; menn&euml;s cherisshynge</L>
<L>Is cause and ground [eke]<NOTE PLACE="foot">cause of the ground R.</NOTE> of myn heuynesse,</L>
<L>And &eacute;ncheson of my wof&uacute;l murnynge;</L>
<L N="796">That schal ye knowe, if it be your lykynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e caus&euml; wite of myn aduersitee."</L>
<L N="798">"&THORN;is telle on, in &thorn;e name of crist," seyde he;
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="115" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(115. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="799">&para; "Sauf first, or &thorn;ow any forth&eacute;r preceede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">procede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>On tyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">O thyng R.</NOTE> of &thorn;e, wite wold I, my sone;</L>
<L>Wher dwelles<NOTE PLACE="foot">dwellest R.</NOTE> &thorn;ow?" [<I>Hoc.</I>] "fadir, with-outen drede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota Hee was an officer of y<SUP>e</SUP> Privie Seale; y<SUP>e</SUP> Clerke, i trow. (<I>In the</I> 1700 <I>hand.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e office of &thorn;e priuee seal I wone;</L>
<L N="803">And wryt&euml; &thorn;er, is my custume and wone</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e seel, and hau&euml; xx<SUP>ti</SUP> yeer</L>
<L N="805">And iiij,<NOTE PLACE="foot">foure R (read 'four&euml;').</NOTE> come estren, and that is neer."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="116" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(116. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="806">&para; "Now sekir, son&euml;, that is a fair tyme;</L>
<L>The token is goode of thy continuance.</L>
<L>Come hidir, goode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. leaves out 'goode.'</NOTE> and sitte a-doun heer by me,</L>
<L>ffor I mot rest awhile, it is my penance;</L>
<L N="810">To me thus long&euml; walke, it doth nusance</L>
<L>Vnto my crookid feeble lym&euml;s olde,</L>
<L N="812">That ben so stif, vnnethe I may hem folde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="117" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(117. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="813">&para; Whan I was set adon, as he me prayede,<MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Telle on," seyde he, "how is it with &thorn;e, how?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">now R.</NOTE></L>
<L>An<NOTE PLACE="foot">And R.</NOTE> I began my tale, and &thorn;us I seyde:&mdash;</L>
<L>"My lig&euml; lord, &thorn;e kyng wich &thorn;at is now,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Henricus iiij<SUP>us</SUP> [R.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="817">I fynd&euml; to me grac&iuml;ous ynow;</L>
<L>God yelde him! he ha&thorn; for my long seruise</L>
<L N="819">Guer-douned<NOTE PLACE="foot">Guerdouned R, Euer douned H.</NOTE> me in couenable wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="118" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(118. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="820">&para; "In th&eacute; schequ&eacute;r, he of his special grace,</L>
<L>Hath to me grauntid an annuitee</L>
<L>Of xx<SUP>ti</SUP> mark, while I haue lyu&euml;s space.<NOTE PLACE="marg">His annuitee of xx<SUP>ti</SUP> marks. (<I>In the</I> 1700 <I>hand.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L>Mighte I ay paid ben of &thorn;at du&euml;tee,</L>
<L N="824">It schuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde R, schuld H.</NOTE> stond&euml; wel ynow with me;</L>
<L>But pai&euml;ment is hard to gete adayes;</L>
<L N="826">And &thorn;at me put in many foule affrayes.
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="119" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(119. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="827">&para; "It goht<NOTE PLACE="foot">goth R.</NOTE> ful streite and scharp or I it haue;</L>
<L>If I seur were of it be satisfi&euml;d</L>
<L>ffro yeer to yeer, than, so god me saue,</L>
<L>My deep&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">depe R, deep H.</NOTE> rootid grief were remedi&euml;d</L>
<L N="831">Souffissantly; but how I schal be gy&euml;d</L>
<L>Heer-after, whan &thorn;at I no lenger serue,</L>
<L N="833">This heuyeth me, so &thorn;at I wel ny sterue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="120" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(120. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="834">&para; "ffor syn &thorn;at I now, in myn ag&euml; grene,</L>
<L>And beyng in court, with gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete, R, gret H.</NOTE> peyne vnneth</L>
<L>Am paid; in elde, and out of court, I weene</L>
<L>My purs for &thorn;at may be a ferthyng shethe.</L>
<L N="838">Lo, fader myn, &thorn;is dullith me to deth;</L>
<L>Now god helpe al! for but he me socoure,</L>
<L N="840">My futur yeer&euml;s lik ben to be soure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="121" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(121. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="841">&para; "Seruyse, I wot wel, is non heritage;<MILESTONE N="16a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan I am out of court an o&thorn;er day,</L>
<L>As I mot, whan vpon me hasti&thorn; age,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at no lengere I labour&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">laboure R, labour H.</NOTE> may,</L>
<L N="845">Vn-to my por&euml; cote, it is no nay,<NOTE PLACE="inline">[see l. 940]</NOTE></L>
<L>I mote me drawe, &amp; my fortune abyde,</L>
<L N="847">And suffre storm after &thorn;e mery tyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="122" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(122. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="848">&para; "&THORN;ere preue I schal &thorn;e mutabilitee</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wrech&eacute;d world&euml;s affeccioun,</L>
<L>Which, whan &thorn;at youthe is past, begynne&thorn; flee.</L>
<L>ffrendchipe, a dieu! farwel, dilecc&iuml;oun!</L>
<L N="852">Age is put out of youre proteccioun;</L>
<L>His loke vnlusty, &amp; his impotence,</L>
<L N="854">Qwenchi&thorn; youre loue &amp; youre beneuolence.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="123" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(123. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="855">&para; "That after-clap, in my mynd&euml; so deepe</L>
<L>Y-fycched is, &amp; ha&thorn; swich roote y-caght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al my ioye &amp; myrthe is leyde to slepe;</L>
<L>My schip is wel ney with dispeir y-fraght.</L>
<L N="859">&THORN;ey &thorn;at nat konn&euml; lerned be ne taght</L>
<L>By swiche ensaumples, smerte as &thorn;ey han seen,</L>
<L N="861">Me &thorn;inke&thorn;, certes, ouer blynd&euml; been.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="124" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(124. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="862">&para; "Allas! I se reuthe &amp; pit&eacute;e exiled</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is land; allas, compass&iuml;oun!</L>
<L>Whan schol ye &thorn;re to vs be reconsiled?</L>
<L>Youre absence is my greuous pass&iuml;oun;</L>
<L N="866">Resorte, I preye yow, to &thorn;is regioun;</L>
<L>O, come ageyn! &thorn;e lak of your pres&eacute;nce</L>
<L N="868">Manace&thorn; me to sterue<NOTE PLACE="foot">sterue R, streue H (compare H.'s 'flode' for 'folde,' l. 745, p. 28; 'triste' for 'thirste,' l. 901, p. 33).</NOTE> in indigence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="125" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(125. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="869">&para; "O fekil world! allas, &thorn;i variaunce!<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>How many a gentilman may men nowe se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at whilom in &thorn;e werr&euml;s olde of fraunce,</L>
<L>Honured were, &amp; holde in grete cheerte</L>
<L N="873">ffor hire prowesse in arm&euml;s, &amp; plente</L>
<L>Of frend&euml;s hadde in you&thorn;e, &amp; now, for schame,</L>
<L N="875">Allas! hir frendeschipe is crok&eacute;d &amp; lame.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="126" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(126. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="876">&para; "Now age vnourne a-wey putt&eacute;&thorn; fauo&uacute;r,</L>
<L>&THORN;at floury you&thorn;e in his seson conquerde;</L>
<L>Now al forgete is &thorn;e manly labo&uacute;r</L>
<L>&THORN;orgh whiche ful oft&euml; &thorn;ey hire foos afferde;</L>
<L N="880">Now be &thorn;o wor&thorn;i men bet with &thorn;e yerde</L>
<L>Of nede, allas! &amp; non ha&thorn; of hem routhe;</L>
<L N="882">Pyte, I trowe, is beried, by my trou&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="127" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(127. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="883">&para; "If sche be deed, god haue hire soule, I preye;</L>
<L>And so schal mo hereafter preye, I trowe.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at pretendi&thorn; him of most nobley,</L>
<L>If he hire lakk&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lak H R.</NOTE> schal wel wyte &amp; knowe</L>
<L N="887">&THORN;at crueltee, hire foo, may but a throwe</L>
<L>Hym suffre for to lyue in any wel&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="889">Hert&euml; petous, to body &amp; soule is hel&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">But ever after in sorwe and vnwelthe R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="128" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(128. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="890">&para; "Ye old&euml; men of arm&euml;s &thorn;at han knowe</L>
<L>By syghte &amp; by report hire wor&thorn;ynesse,</L>
<L>Lat nat mescheef tho men thus ouer-throwe!</L>
<L>Kythe vp-on hem youre manly gentillesse!</L>
<L N="894">Ye yong&euml; men &thorn;at entre in-to prowesse</L>
<L>Of armes, eek youre fadres olde hunurith<NOTE PLACE="foot">honoure R, hunrith H (as in l. 706, p. 26).</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Helpe hem your self, or sum good hem procurith!<NOTE PLACE="foot">self with some gode of youre R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="129" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(129. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="897">&para; "Knyghthode, awak&euml;! &thorn;ou slepist to longe;<MILESTONE N="17a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thy brothir, se, ny dyeth for myschief;</L>
<L>A-wake, and rewe vp-on his peyn&euml;s stronge!</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou heer-after come vn-to swych pref,<NOTE PLACE="foot">myschief R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="901">Thow wolt ful sor&euml; triste<NOTE PLACE="foot">thurst R (Compare H.'s 'streve' for 'sterve,' l. 868, p. 32).</NOTE> after releef;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art nat seur what that ye schal be-fall:</L>
<L N="903">Welth is ful slipir, be ware lest &thorn;ou fall!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="130" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(130. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="904">&para; "&THORN;ou &thorn;at yclomben art in hy<NOTE PLACE="foot">hye R.</NOTE> honoures,</L>
<L>And hast &thorn;is world&euml;s welth at thy deuys,</L>
<L>And bathist now in youth&euml;s lusty floures,</L>
<L>Be war, rede I! &thorn;ou standist on &thorn;e ys:</L>
<L N="908">It hath ben seen, as weleful<NOTE PLACE="foot">wilfull R.</NOTE> and as wys</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou, han slide: and &thorn;ou &thorn;at no pitee</L>
<L N="910">On othir folk hast, who schal rewe on &thorn;e?
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="131" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(131. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="911">&para; "Leeu&euml; me wel, &thorn;er is non erthly man</L>
<L>&THORN;at hath so stable a welth, but &thorn;at it</L>
<L>May fail&euml;, do he what &thorn;at he do kan:</L>
<L>God, as hym list, visitith folk, &amp; smyt.</L>
<L N="915">Wher-fore I deme and hold it grace &amp; wit,</L>
<L>In hy estat, man, god and himself knowe,</L>
<L N="917">And releeue hem &thorn;at myscheef hath doun throwe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="132" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(132. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="918">&para; "God will&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;e nedy be releeued;</L>
<L>It is on of &thorn;e werk&euml;s of mercy;</L>
<L>And syn tho men &thorn;at ben in arm&euml;s preeued,</L>
<L>Ben in-to pouert fall&euml;, trew&euml;ly</L>
<L N="922">Ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ye R, &thorn;e H.</NOTE> men of arm&euml;s oghten specialy</L>
<L>Helpe hem: allas! han ye no pitous blood</L>
<L N="924">That may yow stir&euml; for to do hem good?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="133" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(133. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="925">&para; "O now in ernest, der&euml; fadir myn<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This worthi men to me &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thise . . . a R.</NOTE> mirour shewe</L>
<L>Of sliper frenchipe, and vn-to what fyn</L>
<L>I draw&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">drawe R, draw H.</NOTE> schal with-in a yeer&euml;s fewe,</L>
<L N="929">Vp-on &thorn;is woful thoght I hakke &amp; hewe,</L>
<L>And mus&euml; so, that vn-to lite I madde,</L>
<L N="931">And leuer dy&euml; &thorn;an lyu&eacute;n I hadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="134" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(134. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="932">&para; "In faith, fadir, my lyflod&euml;, by-side</L>
<L>Thainuittee of which aboue I tolde,</L>
<L>May nat exceed&euml; yeerly in no tyde</L>
<L>Vj mark; &thorn;at sitti&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sitte R, sit H.</NOTE> to myn herte so colde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota hoc. (<I>In the</I> 1700 <I>hand.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L N="936">Whan &thorn;at I look abouten, and byholde</L>
<L>How scars it is, if &thorn;at that othir faille,</L>
<L N="938">That I nat gladd&euml; can,<NOTE PLACE="foot">glad kan be R, glad can H.</NOTE> but murne &amp; waille.
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="35"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="135" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(135. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="939">&para; "And as ferforth, as I<NOTE PLACE="foot">I R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> can deeme or gesse,</L>
<L>Whan I at hom&euml; dwell in my poore cote,</L>
<L>I fynd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fynde R, fynd H.</NOTE> schal as frendly slipirnesse</L>
<L>As tho men now doon, whos frendeschipe is rote.</L>
<L N="943">Nat wold I rekke as mochel as a mote,</L>
<L>Thogh I no more hadde of yeerly encrees,</L>
<L N="945">So that I myght ay pai&euml;d be doutlees.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="136" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(136. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="946">&para; "Two partes of my lif, &amp; mochil more,</L>
<L>I seur am, past ben; I ne doute it noght;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at I schold in my yeer&euml;s hore</L>
<L>ffor-go my du&euml;tee,<NOTE PLACE="foot">duetee R, deutee H.</NOTE> that I haue boght</L>
<L N="950">With my flessh and my blode, &thorn;at heuy thoght</L>
<L>Which I drede ay, schal fal, as I it thynke;</L>
<L N="952">Me hasteth blyue vn-to my pitt&euml;s brynke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="137" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(137. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="953">&para; "ffaylyng, fadir, myn annuite,<MILESTONE N="18a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffoot hoot in me crepith disese and wo;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei &thorn;at han by-for&euml; knowen me,</L>
<L>ffaillyng&euml; good, me fail&euml; wole also.</L>
<L N="957">Who no good hath, is fer his frend&euml;s fro;</L>
<L>In muk is al &thorn;is world&euml;s frendlyhede;</L>
<L N="959">My goost is wrapp&euml;d in an heuy drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="138" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(138. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="960">&para; "If &thorn;at I hadde of custume, or &thorn;is tyme,</L>
<L>lyued in indigences wrechednesse,</L>
<L>The lesse heerafter schuld it sit<NOTE PLACE="foot">sette R.</NOTE> by me;</L>
<L>But in myn ag&euml; wrastle with hardenesse,</L>
<L N="964">That with hym stroglid<NOTE PLACE="foot">stroglede R, stroglid H.</NOTE> neuere in grennesse</L>
<L>Of youth&euml;, &thorn;at mutac&iuml;on and chaunge</L>
<L N="966">An othir day me seem&euml; shulde al straunge.
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="139" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(139. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="967">&para; "He &thorn;at neuere knewe &thorn;e swetnesse of wele,</L>
<L>Thogh he it lakke ay, lesse hym greue it schal,</L>
<L>Than hym &thorn;at hath ben weleful yeer&euml;s fele,</L>
<L>And in effect hath felt no greef at al.</L>
<L N="971">O pouert! god me sheld&euml; fro thy fal!</L>
<L>O deth! thy strok yit is more agre&aacute;ble</L>
<L N="973">To me, &thorn;an lyue a lyf so miser&aacute;ble.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="140" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(140. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="974">&para; "VI marc, yeerly, and no more &thorn;an &thorn;at,</L>
<L>ffadir, to me, me thynkyth is ful lyte,</L>
<L>Consideryng, how &thorn;at I am nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">I suppose this line to be deliberately made of 9 syllables,&mdash;'how' serving, with a pause, for the usual 2,&mdash;to correspond with the 9-syllable line 974 which it rymes with, and in which 'Six,' with a pause, represents a measure or 'foot.'</NOTE></L>
<L>In housbondry&euml;, lerned worth a myte;</L>
<L N="978">Scarsely cowde I<NOTE PLACE="foot">knowe I to R.</NOTE> charre a-way &thorn;e kyte</L>
<L>That me bireu&euml; wold&euml; my pullaille;</L>
<L N="980">And more axith housbondly<NOTE PLACE="foot">husbonderye R.</NOTE> gouernaylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="141" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(141. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="981">&para; "With plow can I nat medlen, ne with harwe,<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne wot nat what lond, good is for what corne;</L>
<L>And for to lade a cart or fille a barwe,&mdash;</L>
<L>To which I neuer vsed vas<NOTE PLACE="foot">was R.</NOTE> to-forne,&mdash;</L>
<L N="985">My bak vnbuxum hath swich thyng forsworne,</L>
<L>At instance of writyng, his Werreyour,</L>
<L>That stowpyng hath hym spilt with his labour.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="142" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(142. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="988">&para; "Many men, fadir, wenen &thorn;at writynge</L>
<L>No trauaile is; &thorn;ei hold it but a game:</L>
<L>Aart hath no foo but swich folk vnkonynge:<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ars non habet inimi|cum nisi ignorantem.</NOTE></L>
<L>But who so list disport hym in &thorn;at same,</L>
<L N="992">Let hym continue, and he schal fynd it grame;</L>
<L>It is wel gretter labour &thorn;an it seemeth;</L>
<L N="994">&THORN;e blynd&euml; man of coloures al wrong deemeth.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cecus non i&uacute;dicat<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. continues: de coloribus; et nota hic de scriptoribus.</NOTE> &amp;c.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="143" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(143. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="995">&para; "A writer mot thre thyng&euml;s to hym knytte,</L>
<L>And in tho may be no disseuerance;</L>
<L>Mynde, ee, and hand, non may fro othir flitte,</L>
<L>But in hem mot be ioynt continuance.</L>
<L N="999">The mynde al hoole with-outen variance</L>
<L>On &thorn;e ee<NOTE PLACE="foot">On eye R.</NOTE> and hand awayt&euml; moot alway,</L>
<L N="1001">And &thorn;ei two eek on hym; it is no nay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="144" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(144. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1002">&para; "Who so schal wryt&euml;, may nat holde a tale</L>
<L>With hym and hym, ne syng&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">syng H R.</NOTE> this ne that;</L>
<L>But al his witt&euml;s hool&euml;, grete and smale,</L>
<L>Ther must appere, and halden hem ther-at;</L>
<L N="1006">And syn, he spek&euml; may, ne syng&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">syng H R.</NOTE> nat,</L>
<L>But both&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe R, both H.</NOTE> two he ned&euml;s moot forbere,</L>
<L N="1008">Hir labour to hym is &thorn;e alengere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">elengere R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="145" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(145. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1009">&para; "This artificers, se I day be day,<MILESTONE N="19a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e hotteste of al hir bysynesse</L>
<L>Talken and syng, and mak&euml; game and play,</L>
<L>And forth<NOTE PLACE="foot">forth R, for H.</NOTE> hir labour passith with gladnesse;</L>
<L N="1013">But we labour in trauaillous stilnesse;</L>
<L>We stowpe and stare vp-on &thorn;e shep&euml;s skyn,</L>
<L N="1015">And keep&euml; muste our song and word&euml;s in.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="146" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(146. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1016">&para; "Wrytyng also doth grete annoy&euml;s thre,</L>
<L>Of which ful few&euml; folk&euml;s taken heede</L>
<L>Sauf we oure self; and this&euml;, lo, &thorn;ei be:</L>
<L>Stomak is on,<NOTE PLACE="foot">one R.</NOTE> whom stowpyng out of dreede</L>
<L N="1020">Annoyeth soore; and to our bakk&euml;s, neede</L>
<L>Mot it be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> greuous; and &thorn;e thrid, our yen,</L>
<L N="1022">Vp-on &thorn;e whyt&euml; mochel sorwe<NOTE PLACE="foot">for to H.</NOTE> dryen.
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="147" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(147. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1023">&para; "What man &thorn;at <I>thre &amp; twenti</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">xx<SUP>ti</SUP>iij H.</NOTE> yeere and more</L>
<L>In wryting hath continued, as haue I,</L>
<L>I dar wel seyn it smerteth<NOTE PLACE="foot">smerteth R, smerth H.</NOTE> hym ful sore</L>
<L>In euere veyne and place of his body;</L>
<L N="1027">And yen<NOTE PLACE="foot">yen R, than H (the same mistake occurs in the <I>Minor Poems</I>, I).</NOTE> moost it greeueth trew&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="foot">trewly H, truly R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of any crafte &thorn;at man can ymagyne:</L>
<L N="1029">ffadir, in feth, it spilt<NOTE PLACE="foot">feith it sate R.</NOTE> hath wel ny myne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="148" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(148. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1030">&para; "Lo, fadir, tolde haue I yow &thorn;e substance</L>
<L>Of al my greef, so as &thorn;at I can telle;</L>
<L>But wel I wot it hath bene gret penance</L>
<L>To yow with me so long&euml; for to dwelle;</L>
<L N="1034">I am right sikir it hath ben an helle,</L>
<L>Yow for to herken me &thorn;us iangle &amp; clappe,</L>
<L N="1036">So lewdly in my term&euml;s I me wrappe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="149" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(149. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1037">&para; "But nath&euml;lees, truste I, your pac&iuml;ence<MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Receyu&euml; wole in gree my word&euml;s all;</L>
<L>And what mys-seyd I haue, of negligence,</L>
<L>Ye wole it lete asid&euml; slippe and fall.</L>
<L N="1041">My fadir dere, vn-to your grace I call;</L>
<L>Ye wote my grief; now redeth me<NOTE PLACE="foot">rede me for R.</NOTE> &thorn;e best,</L>
<L>With-outen whom my goost can han no reste."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="150" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(150. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1044">&para; "Now, son&euml; myn, hast &thorn;ou al seid and spoke</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;&eacute; good likyth?" [<I>Hoccl.</I>] "ya, fadir, as now."</L>
<L>[<I>Beg.</I>] "Sone, if oght in &thorn;in herte elles be loke,</L>
<L>Vnlokke it blyue! com of<NOTE PLACE="foot">forth R.</NOTE>; what seist &thorn;ou?"</L>
<L N="1048">[<I>Hoccl.</I>] "ffadir, I can no mor&euml; tell&euml; yow</L>
<L>&THORN;an I befor&euml; spoken haue and sayd."</L>
<L>[<I>Beg.</I>] "A goddes half, sone, I am wel appayd.
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="151" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(151. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1051">&para; "Conceyued haue I, &thorn;at &thorn;ou gret fere haast</L>
<L>Of pouert, for to fallen in &thorn;e snare;</L>
<L>Thow haast &thorn;er-inn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">inne R, in H.</NOTE> caght so deep a taast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of al ioy&euml; &thorn;ou art voide &amp; bare;</L>
<L N="1055">&THORN;ou ny dispeir&euml;d art of al wele-fare,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e strook of pouert art &thorn;ou fer fro;</L>
<L N="1057">ffor sham&euml;! why makest &thorn;ou al this wo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="152" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(152. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1058">&para; "I put cas,&mdash;as god &thorn;er-fro &thorn;e keepe!&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou were y-fall in indigent pouert;</L>
<L>Suldest &thorn;ou grucche, and thyn annoy by-weepe?</L>
<L>Nay! be &thorn;ou riche or poore, or seke or quert,</L>
<L N="1062">God thank alway, of thyn ese and &thorn;i smert;</L>
<L>Pryd&euml; &thorn;e noght for no prosperitee,</L>
<L N="1064">Ne heuye &thorn;e for non aduersite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="153" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(153. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1065">&para; "Pouert hath in himself ynow greuance,<MILESTONE N="20a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With-outen &thorn;at that man more him purch&aacute;ce;</L>
<L>Who-so it taketh in pacient suffraunce,</L>
<L>It is ful plesant beforn crist&euml;s face;</L>
<L N="1069">And whoso gruchith, forfetith &thorn;at grace</L>
<L>That he schuld han, if &thorn;at his pac&iuml;ence</L>
<L N="1071">Withstoode &thorn;e grief, and made it r&eacute;sistence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="154" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(154. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1072">&para; "My sone, as witnessith holy scripture,</L>
<L>Discreet and honest pouert manyfold</L>
<L>Commendid is; crist himself, I &thorn;e insure,</L>
<L>To loue and teche and prechen it hath wold.</L>
<L N="1076">He did al &thorn;is; be &thorn;ou neuer so bold,</L>
<L>A-gayn pouert heer-after grucche, I rede;</L>
<L N="1078">ffor forther-more in holy wryt I rede;
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="155" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(155. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1079">&para; "Beholde &thorn;e lyf [eek]<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyfe R.</NOTE> of our sau&euml;our,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; August|inus. Volue vitam salua|toris a tem|pore natiuita|tis sue usque ad crucis patibulum, Et non in|uenies in ea nisi stigmata paupertatis. Numquid ergo, homo melior est deo &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Right fro the tyme of his natiuite</L>
<L>Vn-to his deth, as &thorn;at seith myn Auctour,</L>
<L>And tokne in it schal &thorn;ou non fynde or se,</L>
<L N="1083">Bot of pouert, with which content was he.</L>
<L>Is man better than god? schal man eschewe</L>
<L N="1085">Swych lyf, syn god &thorn;at sam&euml; wolde ay swe?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="156" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(156. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1086">&para; "ffy! it is to gret an abusioun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus in sermone de vigile Natiui|tatis domini None magna abusio est, <I>et</I> nimis magna, vt vbi diues esse velit vilis vermiculus propter quem deus mages|tatis, &amp; domi|nus sabaoth, dignatus est voluntarie pauper fieri.</NOTE></L>
<L>To seen a man, &thorn;at is but worm&euml;s mete,</L>
<L>Desire rich&eacute;s,<NOTE PLACE="foot">richesse R, riche H.</NOTE> and gret possessioun,</L>
<L>Wher as our lord god wold hym entremete</L>
<L N="1090">Of no rich&eacute;s; he deyn&euml;d it nat gete;</L>
<L>He lyued poor&euml;ly, and pouert chees,</L>
<L N="1092">&THORN;at myghte han ben ful riche; it is no lees.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="157" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(157. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1093">&para; "The poor&euml; man slepith ful sikirly<MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca in prouerbiis: Securus enim a nocturnis furibus dor|mit pauper, <I>etiam</I> si clau|stra non mu|niat; diuiti vero opes sue latronis sem|per ymagin|antur occur|sum, &amp; iugi sollicitudine noccium sompnum adimunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>On nyght&euml;s, thogh his dor&euml; be noght shit,</L>
<L>Where-as &thorn;e riche, a-bedd&euml; bisily</L>
<L>Casteth and ymagineth in his wit,</L>
<L N="1097">That necessarie vnto him is it</L>
<L>Barr&euml;s and lokk&euml;s strong&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stronge R, strong H.</NOTE> for to haue,</L>
<L N="1099">His goed<NOTE PLACE="foot">goods R.</NOTE> from theeu&euml;s for to keep &amp; saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="158" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(158. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1100">&para; "And when &thorn;e deed sleep fallith att&euml; laste</L>
<L>On hym, he dremeth theeu&euml;s comen in,</L>
<L>And on his cofres knokke, &amp; leye on faste,</L>
<L>And some hem pyk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">of hem vnpyke R.</NOTE> with a sotil gyn,</L>
<L N="1104">And vp is broken, lok, hasp, barre &amp; pyn;</L>
<L>And in, &thorn;e hande goth, and &thorn;e bagge out taki&thorn;;</L>
<L>ffor sorwe of which, out of his slepe he waki&thorn;;
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="41"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="159" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(159. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1107">&para; "And vp he rysith, foot and hand tremblyng,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at assailed hym &thorn;e parl&euml;sye<NOTE PLACE="foot">As that hym shoke the palsye R.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>And at a stirt, withouten tarying,</L>
<L>Vn-to his cofre he dressith hym in hye;</L>
<L N="1111">Or he there come, he is in poynte to dye;</L>
<L>He it vndoth, and opneth, for to se</L>
<L N="1113">If &thorn;at his fals&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fals H R.</NOTE> godd&euml;s ther-in be:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="160" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(160. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1114">&para; "He dredith fynde it as &thorn;at he hath drempt.</L>
<L>This world&euml;s power &aacute;nd riche h&aacute;bundance,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Idem Sene|ca: Saeculi<NOTE PLACE="foot">Simili R.</NOTE> autem potes|tas sine ti|more periculi nunquam est, sed pauper|tas semper secura est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of drede of peryl neuere ben exempt;</L>
<L>But in pouert is ay<NOTE PLACE="foot">ay R, an H.</NOTE> sikir constance:</L>
<L N="1118">Who holdith hym content, hath sufficiance.</L>
<L>And son&euml;, by my rede &thorn;ou schalt do so,</L>
<L N="1120">And by desir of good nat sette a slo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="161" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(161. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1121">&para; "Wilful pou&eacute;rt in princes anc&iuml;en<MILESTONE N="21a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So ferforth was, &thorn;at &thorn;ey desired more</L>
<L>Good loos &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">than R, that H.</NOTE> good; bot now-of-dayes, men</L>
<L>Yerne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Renne R.</NOTE> and desiren after muk so sore,</L>
<L N="1125">&THORN;at they good fame han leyd a watir yore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">That her gode fame is leid a water thore R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And rekken neuer how longe it &thorn;er stipe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">slepe R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1127">Or thogh it drench&euml;, so &thorn;ei good may grype.<NOTE PLACE="foot">kepe R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="162" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(162. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1128">&para; "Of Si&yogh;il&euml; whilom<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cesile somtyme R.</NOTE> &thorn;er was a kyng</L>
<L>With erthen wessel serued at his table;</L>
<L>And men, wondryng faste<NOTE PLACE="foot">fast wondrede R.</NOTE> vpon this thyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota</NOTE></L>
<L>Seyd vn-to hym, it was nat honurable</L>
<L N="1132">To his estat, ne nothyng comendable,</L>
<L>Axynge hym why hym list be serued so;</L>
<L N="1134">To which demand&euml; he answerd&euml; tho:
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="163" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(163. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1135">&para; "He seyd: 'thogh I kyng be of si&yogh;il&euml;,</L>
<L>A potter was my fadir, is no nay;</L>
<L>How long I schal induren, or what while</L>
<L>In my prosperitee, nat knowe I may:</L>
<L N="1139">ffortun&euml;s variance I drede alway;</L>
<L>Ryght as sche mad&euml; me to clymbe on highte</L>
<L N="1141">Sodenly, so sche may me make alighte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="164" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(164. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1142">&para; " 'I thynke alway of my natiuitee,</L>
<L>And of my poor&euml; lenage &amp; my blode;</L>
<L>Erthen vess&eacute;l, to swich a man as me</L>
<L>fful sittyng is, and acceptable &amp; good.'</L>
<L N="1146">O, few&euml; ben ther now left of &thorn;e brood</L>
<L>That he cam of; he loued bet profyt</L>
<L N="1148">Commun, than his a-vantage or delyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="165" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(165. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1149">&para; "How seystow by affr&yacute;can Scipion?&mdash;<MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Affrican clept, for &thorn;at he affryk wan;&mdash;</L>
<L>To pouert hadde he swych affecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Of his own&euml; free wil &amp; lust, &thorn;at whan</L>
<L N="1153">He dyed, no good had &thorn;is worthy man,</L>
<L>Wher-with his body in the<NOTE PLACE="foot">in the erthe to R, vp on erth H.</NOTE> erth&euml; brynge,</L>
<L N="1155">But &thorn;e com&uacute;n cost made his enterynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="166" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(166. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1156">&para; "Be-forn &thorn;e senat was he bore on honde</L>
<L>Ones, after he affrik wonnen hadde,</L>
<L>That he was riche, as &thorn;ey cowde vnderstonde,</L>
<L>Of gold: to which, with wordes sobre and sadde,</L>
<L N="1160">Answerde he &thorn;us: 'thogh I be feble &amp; badde,</L>
<L>The sooth is, vnto youre subiecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="1162">I gat Affrik; of &thorn;at haue I renoun.
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="43"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="167" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(167. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1163">&para; " 'My nam&euml; was al &thorn;at I ther&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">there R, ther H.</NOTE> gat;</L>
<L>To wynne honour was only &thorn;e purpos</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at I took, or &thorn;at I cam ther-at;</L>
<L>Othir good hadde I non &thorn;an rich&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">riche R, rich H.</NOTE> loos;</L>
<L N="1167">ffor al &thorn;e good there was, opne or cloos,</L>
<L>Myn hert&euml; myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert myght H R.</NOTE> nat so wel content,</L>
<L N="1169">As &thorn;e renoun only, &thorn;at I ther hent.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="168" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(168. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1170">&para; "Of coueytise he was no &thorn;ing coup&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>He sett&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sette R, set H.</NOTE> nat &thorn;er by, &thorn;ou mayst wel se.</L>
<L>ffy on &thorn;e! gredynes insaciable,</L>
<L>Of many a man, &thorn;at can nat content be</L>
<L N="1174">Of muk, al thogh neuer so moch haue he!</L>
<L>The kynde is euere of wreched couetyse,</L>
<L N="1176">To coueyte ay, and haue, and nat suffyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="169" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(169. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I wold, [that] euery knyght dide now &thorn;e same,<MILESTONE N="22a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And were of good no mor&euml; coueytous</L>
<L>Than he was: what! to gete a noble fame,</L>
<L>To knyghthode is tres&oacute;r most prec&iuml;ous;</L>
<L N="1181">But I was neuere so auenterous,</L>
<L>Renoun to wynn&euml; by swerd&euml;s conquest,</L>
<L N="1183">ffor I was bred in &aacute; pesible nest.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="170" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(170. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1184">&para; "Vpon my bak come neuere haburgeoun,</L>
<L>Ne my knyf drew I neuere in violence;</L>
<L>I may nat contrefet&euml; Scipion</L>
<L>In arm&euml;s, ne his worthi excellence</L>
<L N="1188">Of wilful pouert; but of indigence</L>
<L>I am as riche as was euere any man,</L>
<L N="1190">Suffre it in pacience if &thorn;at I can.
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="171" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(171. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1191">&para; "No richer<NOTE PLACE="foot">No richer R, Now riche H.</NOTE> am I &thorn;an &thorn;ou ma&iuml;st se;</L>
<L>Of myne haue I<NOTE PLACE="foot">I R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> no thyng to tak&euml; to;</L>
<L>I lyue of almesse. if it stood with &thorn;e</L>
<L>So streyte, and lyuedest<NOTE PLACE="foot">livedest R, lyuest H.</NOTE> as &thorn;at I do,</L>
<L N="1195">I se &thorn;ou woldest sorowe swych&euml; two</L>
<L>As I; but &thorn;ou haast for to lyuen on</L>
<L N="1197">A poore lyf; and swych ne haue I non.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="172" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(172. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1198">&para; "Salamon yaf conseil, men shulden preye<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prouerbiis .30. Men|dicitatem &amp; diuicias ne dederis mihi, sed tamen victui meo necessaria.<NOTE PLACE="foot">tribue necessaria R.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>Two thyng&euml;s vn-to god, in soothfastenesse:</L>
<L>Now herkne, sone, he bad men &thorn;us to seye:</L>
<L>'Enhanc&euml; &thorn;ou me, lord, to no richesse,</L>
<L N="1202">Ne by mis&eacute;rie me so sore oppresse,</L>
<L>That need&euml; for to begg&euml; me compelle:'</L>
<L N="1204">In his prouerb&euml;s &thorn;us, lo! can he telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="173" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(173. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1205">&para; "But &thorn;is pouert men&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">men R.</NOTE> conseiled he<MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Men to desyr, &thorn;at was nec&eacute;ssarye</L>
<L>To foode and clooth, dredyng lest plentee</L>
<L>Of good hem myght&euml; mak&euml; to miscarie,</L>
<L N="1209">And fro the knowlegyng of god to varie;</L>
<L>And lest smert need&euml; made hem god reneye:</L>
<L N="1211">Now be war, son&euml;, lest &thorn;at &thorn;ou folye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="174" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(174. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1212">&para; "Sone, in &thorn;is men&euml; pouert holde I &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Sauf &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst nat taken it ful weel.</L>
<L>What thogh &thorn;ou les&euml; &thorn;in annuytee,</L>
<L>Yit mayst &thorn;ou leuen on &thorn;at othir del,</L>
<L N="1216">Thogh nat ful delecate schal be &thorn;i meel.</L>
<L>Of vj marc yeerly, mete &amp; drinke &amp; clooth</L>
<L N="1218">Thow get&euml; mayst, my child, with-outen oth."
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="175" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(175. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1219">&para; "Ya, fadir myn, I am nat so perfite</L>
<L>To take it so; I haue had h&aacute;bundance</L>
<L>Of welfare ay; and now stond in &thorn;e plite</L>
<L>Of scarsetee, it were a gret penance</L>
<L N="1223">ffor me: god scheld&euml; me fro &thorn;at strait chance!</L>
<L>Vj marc yeerly, to scars is to sustene</L>
<L N="1225">The charges &thorn;at I haue, as &thorn;at I wene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="176" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(176. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1226">&para; "Tow on my distaf haue I for to spynne,</L>
<L>Mor&euml;, my fadir, &thorn;an ye wot of yit,</L>
<L>Which ye schal know, or &thorn;at I fro yow twynne,</L>
<L>Yf your good lust be for to heren it;</L>
<L N="1230">But, for as moche as it nat to me sit,</L>
<L>Your tal&euml; for to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> interrupte or breke,</L>
<L N="1232">Here-after to yow wil I &thorn;er-of speke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="177" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(177. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1233">&para; "Yit o worde, fader<NOTE PLACE="foot">fader R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE>; I haue herd men seyn,<MILESTONE N="23a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Who-so no good hath, &thorn;at he can no good;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at fynde I, a plat sooth and a pleyn;</L>
<L>ffor al-thogh that myn heed, vndir myn hood,</L>
<L N="1237">Was neuere wys, yit while<NOTE PLACE="foot">while R, wil H.</NOTE> it with me stood,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I had siluer resonable,</L>
<L N="1239">My litil wytte was sumwhat couenable.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="178" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(178. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1240">&para; "But now, for that I haue but a<NOTE PLACE="foot">but a R, a large H.</NOTE> lyte,</L>
<L>And lykly am heer-aftir to han lesse,</L>
<L>My dul wit can to me no-thyng profyte;</L>
<L>I am so drad of mony&euml;s scantnesse,</L>
<L N="1244">That myn hert is al nakid of lightnesse.</L>
<L>Wisseth me how to gete a golden salue;</L>
<L N="1246">And what I haue, I wele it with yow halue."
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="179" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(179. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1247">&para; "Sone, as for me, nouthir avaunte ne rere;</L>
<L>But if disese algat&euml;s schal bityde,</L>
<L>ffor to be pac&iuml;ent, rede I thow leere;</L>
<L>ffor any thyng, with-holde hir on &thorn;i side;</L>
<L N="1251">My reed wole it nat, son&euml;, fro the hide;</L>
<L>Make of necessite, reed I, vertu;</L>
<L N="1253">ffor better rede can I non, by Ihesu.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="180" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(180. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1254">&para; "My son&euml;, they &thorn;at swymmen in richesse</L>
<L>Continuelly, and han prosperitee,</L>
<L>And neuere han felt but wel&euml;ful swetnesse,</L>
<L>Vnscourgid ay of any aduersitee,</L>
<L N="1258">Leest god forgete hem, oughten ferdful be;</L>
<L>Syn god in holy writ seith in &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L N="1260">'Whom so I loue, hym wole I chastyse.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quem diligo, castigo R, <I>in margin.</I></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="181" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(181. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1261">&para; "Seint Ambroses legend&euml; seith, how he<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ones to Rom&euml;-ward took his viage,</L>
<L>And in Tusci&euml;, t&oacute;ward &thorn;at contree,</L>
<L>With a riche ost he took his herbergage;</L>
<L N="1265">Of whom, as blyu&euml; fair in his langage,</L>
<L>Of his estate enqueren he be-gan;</L>
<L N="1267">And vnto &thorn;at, answerde anon this man:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="182" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(182. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1268">&para; " 'Right at my lust haue I al worldely welth;</L>
<L>Myn estat hath ben ay good, and yit is;</L>
<L>Richesse haue I, frendschipe, and bodyes helth;</L>
<L>Was neuere thynge me happid yit amys.'</L>
<L N="1272">And seint Ambrose,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ambrose R, Ambroses H.</NOTE> aston&euml;d sore of this,</L>
<L>Anon right rowned to his compaignye,</L>
<L N="1274">'Sires, it is tyme &thorn;at we henn&euml;s hye;
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="47"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="183" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(183. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1275">&para; " 'I am adrad, god is nat in &thorn;is place;</L>
<L>Go we fast henn&euml;s, lest &thorn;at hys vengeance</L>
<L>ffal on vs!' and with-in a litel space</L>
<L>After they were agone, schop this myschance;</L>
<L N="1279">The ground&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">grounde R, ground H.</NOTE> claue and made disseuerance,</L>
<L>And in sank man, womman, childe, hous, &amp; al</L>
<L N="1281">That to hym appertened, gret and smal.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="184" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(184. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1282">&para; "Whan &thorn;is come to Ambroses<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ambroses R, Ambrose H.</NOTE> audience,</L>
<L>He seid&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">seide R, seid H.</NOTE> to his felacheep&euml; &thorn;us:&mdash;</L>
<L>'Lo, bretheren! seeth heer in &eacute;xperience,</L>
<L>How merci&aacute;blely our lord Ihesus</L>
<L N="1286">Of his benyng&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">benigne R, benyng H.</NOTE> grace hath sparid vs!</L>
<L>He sparith hem that vnwelthy heer ben,</L>
<L N="1288">And to &thorn;e velthy<NOTE PLACE="foot">welthy R.</NOTE> dooth as &thorn;at ye seen.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="185" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(185. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1289">&para; "This lyf, my sone, is but a chirie faire;<MILESTONE N="24a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Worldly riches, haue ay in &thorn;i mem&oacute;rye,</L>
<L>Schal passe, al look it neuer on men so feire;</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;ou art heer in &thorn;is world transit&oacute;rie,</L>
<L N="1293">Enable &thorn;e to wynne eternel glorie</L>
<L>Wher no pouert is, but perfite richesse</L>
<L N="1295">Of ioye and blysse, and vertuous gladnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="186" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(186. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1296">&para; "O thyng tel I &thorn;e, son&euml;, &thorn;at is soth:</L>
<L>Thogh a man hadde als moch as men han al,</L>
<L>But vertu, &thorn;at good gye, al he mys dooth,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at swetness&euml; tourn&euml; schal to gal.</L>
<L N="1300">Whan &thorn;at richesse is on a man yfal,<NOTE PLACE="foot">falle R, fal H.</NOTE></L>
<L>If it be wrong dispendid or mys-kept,</L>
<L N="1302">Another day ful sore it schal be wept.
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="187" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(187. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Sum riche is large, and his good mys despendith</L>
<L>In mayntenance of syn and harlotrie;</L>
<L>To swich despenses his lust hym accendith;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at othir parte, his nygardie</L>
<L N="1307">Suffrith hys neghtburgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">neighbore R.</NOTE> by hym sterue &amp; dye,</L>
<L>Rathir &thorn;an with a ferthyng hym releeue:<NOTE PLACE="foot">releueeue H, releeue R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1309">Tho two condic&iuml;ons ben to repreue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="188" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(188. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Whoso moost hath, he moost of schal answere;</L>
<L>On day schal com&euml;, sum men schal par chaunce</L>
<L>Desire he neuere hadd&euml; ben rychere</L>
<L>Than heer han hadde his bar&euml; sustinaunce.</L>
<L N="1314">Whan &thorn;e day comth of ire and of vengeaunce,</L>
<L>Than schal men see,<NOTE PLACE="foot">see R, seeme H.</NOTE> how in &thorn;is world, I gesse,</L>
<L N="1316">Richesse is pouert, and pou&eacute;rt richesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="189" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(189. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1317">&para; "Whyl er, my son&euml;, tolde I naght to &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>What h&aacute;bundance in youth I hadde of good,</L>
<L>And how me blent&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">blent H R.</NOTE> so prosperitee,</L>
<L>&THORN;at what god was, y nothing vnderstood?</L>
<L N="1321">But ay whil &thorn;at I in my welth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">welthe R, welth H.</NOTE> stood,</L>
<L>After my flesshly lust my lif I ledde,</L>
<L N="1323">And of his wrech&euml; no &thorn;ing I me dredde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="190" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(190. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1324">&para; "And as I seid, he smot me with &thorn;e strook</L>
<L>Of pouert, in which I contynue yit,</L>
<L>Whos smert my good blood first so sor&euml; sook,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at I was acqueyntid wel with it,</L>
<L N="1328">&THORN;at nye it hadd&euml; refte<NOTE PLACE="foot">refte R, reste H.</NOTE> fro me my wit;</L>
<L>But sithen, thanke I god, in pac&iuml;ence</L>
<L N="1330">I haue it take, and schal, for myn offence.
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="191" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(191. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1331">&para; "If &thorn;e list fle, &thorn;at may pouert engendre,</L>
<L>ffirst synne eschue, and god honoure &amp; drede;</L>
<L>Also, for &thorn;i lyflode is scars and sclendre,</L>
<L>Despend&euml; nat to larg&euml;ly, I rede.</L>
<L N="1335">Mesure is good; let hir &thorn;e gye and lede;</L>
<L>Be war of outrage, and be sobre &amp; wys;</L>
<L N="1337">&THORN;us &thorn;ou exclud&euml; hym, by myn avys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="192" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(192. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1338">&para; "Nath&euml;lees &thorn;ou maist &aacute;geyn me replie,</L>
<L>'To sum folk, thogh &thorn;ei doon al as I seye,</L>
<L>Agayn pouert it is no remedye;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei mow it nat eschu&euml; by no waye.'</L>
<L N="1342">I graunt&euml; wel, but &thorn;an take heede, I preye,</L>
<L>The iug&euml;ment&yogh; of god ben to vs hid;</L>
<L N="1344">Take al in gree, so is &thorn;i vertu kyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="193" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(193. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1345">&para; "To &thorn;e plesaunce of god &thorn;ou &thorn;e conforme,<MILESTONE N="25a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>About&euml; &thorn;at be bisy and &eacute;ntentif;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mis-done hast, &thorn;ou blyue it reforme;</L>
<L>Swych laborer<NOTE PLACE="foot">a labour R.</NOTE> &thorn;e kythe heere in &thorn;is lyf,</L>
<L N="1349">&THORN;at god &thorn;i soul&euml;, which &thorn;at is his wyf,</L>
<L>Reiois&euml; may, for it is to him due,</L>
<L N="1351">And his schal be, but &thorn;ou &thorn;e deuors sue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="194" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(194. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1352">&para; "O &thorn;ou, fortun&euml;, fals and deceyu&aacute;ble!</L>
<L>fful so&thorn; it is, if &thorn;ou do a good deede,</L>
<L>&THORN;u nat purp&oacute;sist it schal be dur&aacute;ble;</L>
<L>Of good entent&euml; schal it nat procede.</L>
<L N="1356">Wel oghte vs &thorn;i promesses blynd&euml; drede;</L>
<L>He sliperly stant who &thorn;at &thorn;ou enhauncest,</L>
<L N="1358">ffor sodeynlich&euml; &thorn;ou hym disauauncest.
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="195" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(195. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1359">&para; "Hadde I done, son&euml;, as I &thorn;e consayle,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at fortun&euml;s d&eacute;ceyu&aacute;ble cheere</L>
<L>Lawhid on me, &thorn;an hadde I nat, san&yogh; fayle,</L>
<L>Ben in &thorn;is wrecched plyt as &thorn;u seest heere.</L>
<L>Not knew my &yogh;outhe<NOTE PLACE="foot">thought R.</NOTE> hir chaungeable maneere;</L>
<L>ffor whan I satte on hy vp-on hir wheel,</L>
<L N="1365">Hir gladsum look me mad&euml; truste hire wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="196" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(196. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1366">&para; "I cowd&euml; for no &thorn;ing han wend or deemed</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche a-bout&euml; baar dowble visage;</L>
<L>I wende sche hadd&euml; ben swiche as sche semed.</L>
<L>But nath&euml;les, &yogh;it is it auantage</L>
<L N="1370">To him &thorn;at woful is, &thorn;at hir vsage</L>
<L>Is for to flytt&euml; fro<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro R, for H.</NOTE> plac&euml; to place;</L>
<L N="1372">Hire variance is vn-to sum folke grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="197" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(197. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1373">&para; "Whom so &thorn;at ned&euml; greue&thorn; &amp; trauaylli&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hire change is vn-to hym no grief or wo;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e contr&aacute;rie of &thorn;at no &thorn;ing auaylli&thorn;,</L>
<L>As whan a man is wel, put hym &thorn;erfro.</L>
<L N="1377">What schal men calle hir? frende, or ellys fo?</L>
<L>I not; but call hire frend, whan &thorn;at sche esi&thorn;,</L>
<L>And calle hir fo, whan &thorn;at sche man displesi&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="198" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(198. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1380">&para; "But who so calle hir schal a sikir name?</L>
<L>Men mote hir clepe 'my lady chaungeabil,'</L>
<L>ffor hardily sche is &thorn;at selu&euml; same;</L>
<L>A! nay! I gabbe, I am vn-resonabil;</L>
<L N="1384">Sche is 'my lady stid&euml;fast and stabil,'</L>
<L>ffor I endure in pouert&euml;s distresse,</L>
<L N="1386">And sche nat liste remu&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">releeue R.</NOTE> my duresse.
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="199" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(199. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1387">&para; "I ymagyn&euml; whi &thorn;at nat hir list</L>
<L>With me now dele; age is colde &amp; drye;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;o two ben to a lady wist,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at I poore am eek for &thorn;e maystrie,</L>
<L N="1391">Swiche a man is vnlusty to hire ye,</L>
<L>And wers to grop&euml;: straw for impotence!</L>
<L N="1393">Sche loue&thorn; yong folk, &amp; large of dyspence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="200" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(200. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1394">&para; "Al &thorn;is &thorn;at I haue of fortun&euml; seyde,</L>
<L>Is but a iap&euml;, who<NOTE PLACE="foot">as who R.</NOTE> seith, or a knak:</L>
<L>Now I a whil&euml; bourdyd haue &amp; pleyde,</L>
<L>Resorte I wol to that &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> I first spake.</L>
<L N="1398">By-holde, &amp; cast &thorn;ou &thorn;ine y&euml; a-bak,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou god hast a-gilt in tym&euml; past,</L>
<L N="1400">Correct it, and to do so eft be a-gast.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="201" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(201. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1401">&para; "Of holy chirche, my son&euml;, I conceyue<MILESTONE N="26a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &yogh;it ne hast &thorn;ou non a-vanc&euml;ment:</L>
<L>Ye courteours, ful often ye deceyue</L>
<L>Youre soul&euml;s, for &thorn;e d&eacute;sirous tal&eacute;nt</L>
<L N="1405">Ye han to good; &amp; for &thorn;at &thorn;ou art brent</L>
<L>With couetys&euml; now, par auenture</L>
<L N="1407">Only for muk, &thorn;ou &yogh;ernest soul&euml;s cure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="202" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(202. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1408">&para; "fful many men knowe I, &thorn;at gane and gape</L>
<L>After som fat &amp; rich&euml; benefice;</L>
<L>Chirche or prouendre<NOTE PLACE="foot">prebende R.</NOTE> vnne&thorn;e hem may eschape,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei as blyue it henten vp and trice:</L>
<L N="1412">God graunt&eacute; &thorn;ei accepte hem for &thorn;e office,</L>
<L>And noght for &thorn;e profet &thorn;at by hem honge&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hongeth R, longe&thorn; H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1414">ffor &thorn;at conceyt&euml; nat to prestehode longe&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="203" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(203. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1415">&para; "A-day&euml;s now, my sone, as men may se,</L>
<L>O chirche vn-to a<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>o</I> R.</NOTE> man may not suffise;</L>
<L>But algate he mote han pluralite,</L>
<L>Elles he can not lyuen in no wyse.</L>
<L N="1419">Ententifly he kepi&thorn; his seruise</L>
<L>In courte; his labour &thorn;er&euml; schal not moule;</L>
<L N="1421">But to his cur&euml; loki&thorn; he ful foule.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="204" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(204. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1422">&para; "Thogh &thorn;at his chauncel roof be al to-torn,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e hye<NOTE PLACE="foot">hye R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> auter it reyne or snewe,</L>
<L>He rekki&thorn; noght, &thorn;e cost may be for-born</L>
<L>Cristes hous t&oacute; repare or mak&euml; newe;</L>
<L N="1426">And &thorn;ogh &thorn;er be ful many a vicious hewe</L>
<L>Vnder his cure, he taki&thorn; of it no kepe,</L>
<L N="1428">He rekke&thorn; neuer how rusty ben his schepe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">shepe R, chepe H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="205" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(205. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1429">&para; "The oyn&euml;ment of holy sermonynge<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hym lo&thorn; is vp-on hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, hym H.</NOTE> for to despende;</L>
<L>Som person is so threde-bare of konnynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at he can noght, &thorn;ogh he hym wys pretende,</L>
<L N="1433">And he &thorn;at can, may not his hert&euml; bende</L>
<L>&THORN;er-to, but from his cure he hym absenti&thorn;,</L>
<L>And what &thorn;er-of come&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">come&thorn; = com&thorn;.</NOTE> gredyliche he hentith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="206" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(206. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1436">&para; "How he despendi&thorn; it, be as be may,</L>
<L>ffor vn-to &thorn;at am I no-&thorn;ing pryuee;</L>
<L>But wel I wot, as nyc&euml;, fressh, and gay</L>
<L>Som of hem ben, as borel folk&euml;s be,</L>
<L N="1440">And &thorn;at vnsittynge is to hire degree;</L>
<L>Hem hoght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ought R, hoght H.</NOTE> to be mirours of sadnesse,</L>
<L N="1442">And wayu&euml; iolitee and wantonnesse.
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="207" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(207. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1443">&para; "But neuer&thorn;eles I wote wel &thorn;ere-agayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many of hem gye hem as hem oghte,</L>
<L>And ell&euml;s were it grete pitee certayn:</L>
<L>But what man wolt &thorn;ou be for hym &thorn;e boghte?"</L>
<L>(<I>Hoccl.</I>) "ffadir, I may not chese; I whilom &thorn;oghte</L>
<L>Han ben a prest; now past am I &thorn;e raas."</L>
<L>(<I>Beg.</I>) "&THORN;an art &thorn;ou, sone, a weddid man per caas?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="208" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(208. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1450">&para; "Ya, so&thorn;ly, fadir myn, ryght so I am.</L>
<L>I gasyd long&euml; firste, &amp; waytid faste</L>
<L>After some benefice; and whan non cam,</L>
<L>By proces I me weddid att&euml; laste;</L>
<L N="1454">And god it wot, it sor&euml; me agaste</L>
<L>To bynd&euml; me, where I was at my large;</L>
<L N="1456">But done it was; I toke on me &thorn;at charge."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="209" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(209. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1457">&para; "A, sone! I haue espied, and now se<MILESTONE N="27a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;e tow &thorn;at &thorn;ou speke<NOTE PLACE="foot">spakest R.</NOTE> of ryght now." (l. 1226)</L>
<L>"Now, by &thorn;e rod&euml;, fadir, so&thorn; seyn ye."</L>
<L>"Ya, son&euml; myn, &thorn;ou schalt do wel y-now;</L>
<L N="1461">Whan endyd is my tal&euml;, &thorn;an schalt &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Be put in swiche a way at<NOTE PLACE="foot">as (at = &thorn;at).</NOTE> schal &thorn;e plese,</L>
<L N="1463">And to &thorn;in hert&euml; do comforte and ese.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="210" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(210. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1464">&para; "So longe as &thorn;ou, sone, in &thorn;e priu&euml; sel</L>
<L>Dwelt hast, &amp; woldest fayn han ben auaunced</L>
<L>Vn-to som chirche or &thorn;is, I dem&euml; wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at god not wold&euml; hau&euml; &thorn;e enhanced</L>
<L N="1468">In no swich plyt; I hold&euml; &thorn;e wel chaunced;</L>
<L>God wot and knowith euery hyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">mannes R.</NOTE> entente;</L>
<L N="1470">He, for &thorn;i best, a wyf vn-to &thorn;e sente.
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="211" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(211. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1471">&para; "If &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest per cas ben a prest,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou woldest han as wantonly &thorn;e gy&euml;d</L>
<L>As do&thorn; &thorn;e nycest of hem &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest;</L>
<L>And god for-beed&euml; &thorn;ou &thorn;e haddist ty&euml;d</L>
<L N="1475">&THORN;er-to, but if &thorn;in hert&euml; myght han ply&euml;d</L>
<L>ffor to obserue it wel! be glade and merye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art as thou art,<NOTE PLACE="foot">as thou art R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> god &thorn;anke and herie!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="212" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(212. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1478">&para; "&THORN;e ordres of prestehode and of wedlok</L>
<L>Ben bo&thorn;&euml; vertuous, with-outen fabil;</L>
<L>But vnderstond&euml; wel, &thorn;e holy &yogh;ok</L>
<L>Of prestehode is, as it is resonabil</L>
<L N="1482">&THORN;at it so be, &thorn;e mor&euml; commendabil;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lesse of hem, of mede ha&thorn; h&aacute;bundance;</L>
<L N="1484">Men han meryt, after here gouernaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="213" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(213. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1485">&para; "But how ben &thorn;i felaw&euml;s lokyd to<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>At hoom? ben &thorn;ey not wel ben&eacute;fic&euml;d?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;is, fadir, &yogh;is! &thorn;er is on clept 'nemo';</L>
<L>He helpe&thorn; hem; by hym ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> &thorn;ei cheric&euml;d:</L>
<L N="1489">Nere he, &thorn;ey weren por&euml;ly cheuyc&euml;d;</L>
<L>He hem auanceth; he ful hir frende is;</L>
<L N="1491">Sauf only hym, &thorn;ey han but few&euml; frendes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="214" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(214. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1492">&para; "So many a man as &thorn;ei &thorn;is many a yeer</L>
<L>Han writen for, &yogh;it<NOTE PLACE="foot">&YOGH;it, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> fynd&euml; can &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">I R.</NOTE> non</L>
<L>So gentel, or of hir estat so cheer,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at onys liste for hem to ryde or gon,</L>
<L N="1496">Ne for hem speke a worde; but dombe as ston</L>
<L>&THORN;ei standen, where hir speche hem myght awayle;</L>
<L N="1498">ffor swiche folk is vnlusty to trauaile.
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="55"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="215" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(215. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1499">&para; "But if a wyght hau&euml; any<NOTE PLACE="foot">a H R.</NOTE> cause to sue</L>
<L>To vs, som lord&euml;s man schal vndertake</L>
<L>To sue it out; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;at is vs due</L>
<L>ffor oure labour, hym deyne&thorn; vs nat take;</L>
<L N="1503">He sei&thorn;, his lord to &thorn;anke vs wole he make;</L>
<L>It touchi&thorn; hym, it is a man of his;</L>
<L N="1505">Where &thorn;e reuers of &thorn;at, god wot, soo&thorn; is.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="216" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(216. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1506">&para; "His letter he taki&thorn;, and for&thorn; go&thorn; his way,</L>
<L>And bydde&thorn; vs to dowten vs no-thyng</L>
<L>His lord schal &thorn;anken vs an o&thorn;er day;</L>
<L>And if we han to su&euml; to &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L N="1510">His lord may &thorn;er&euml; haue al his askyng;</L>
<L>We schal be sped, as fer as &thorn;at oure bille</L>
<L N="1512">Wole specifie &thorn;e &eacute;ffecte<NOTE PLACE="foot">effect R, fecte H.</NOTE> of our wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="217" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(217. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1513">&para; "What schol we do? we dar non argument<MILESTONE N="28a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Make a-geyn him, but fayre &amp; wel him trete,</L>
<L>Leste he roporte amys, &amp; make vs schent;</L>
<L>To haue his wil, we suffren him, &amp; lete;</L>
<L N="1517">Hard is, be holden suspect with &thorn;e grete:</L>
<L>His tal&euml; schal he leeu&euml;d, but<NOTE PLACE="foot">bileeued and R.</NOTE> nat ourys,</L>
<L N="1519">And &thorn;at conclus&iuml;oun to vs ful soure is.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="218" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(218. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1520">&para; "And whan &thorn;e mater is to ende I-broght,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e straunger, for whom &thorn;e suyte ha&thorn; be,</L>
<L>&THORN;an is he to &thorn;e lord know&eacute;n right noght;</L>
<L>He is to him as vn-know&eacute;n as we;</L>
<L N="1524">&THORN;e lord not wot<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne wote not R.</NOTE> of al &thorn;is sotilte;</L>
<L>Ne we nat dar lete him of it to<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne we ne dar not lete hym of it R.</NOTE> knowe,</L>
<L>Lest oure compleynte oure seluen ouerthrowe.
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="56"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="219" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(219. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1527">&para; "And where &thorn;is bribour ha&thorn; no peny<NOTE PLACE="foot">peny R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> payed</L>
<L>In oure office, he sei&thorn; be-hynde our bak,</L>
<L>'He payde, I not what': &thorn;us ben we bytrayed,</L>
<L>And disclaundrid, and put in wyte and lak,</L>
<L N="1531">fful gilt&euml;les; &amp; eeke by swiche a knak</L>
<L>&THORN;e man for whom &thorn;e suyte is, is deceyu&euml;d,</L>
<L N="1533">He wene&thorn; we han of his gold receyu&euml;d.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="220" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(220. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1534">&para; "fful many swych&euml; p&uacute;rsuours &thorn;ere ben,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs take, &amp; &yogh;eue vs nat a myte:</L>
<L>&THORN;is maki&thorn; vs &thorn;at we may neuer &thorn;een.</L>
<L>Eek where as lord&euml;s bydde hir men vs quyte,</L>
<L N="1538">Whan &thorn;at we for hemself laboure and write,</L>
<L>And ben a-low&euml;d for oure pay&euml;ment,</L>
<L N="1540">Oure handes &thorn;er-of ben ful Innocent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="221" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(221. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1541">&para; "I sey&euml; nat, al<NOTE PLACE="foot">I sey not alle R.</NOTE> lordes men &thorn;us do<MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at sue vnto oure court; but many, I seye,</L>
<L>Han &thorn;us don oft&euml;. lo! my fadir, lo!</L>
<L>&THORN;us bothe oure &thorn;anke &amp; lucre gon a-weye:</L>
<L N="1545">God &yogh;eue hem sorowe &thorn;at so with vs pleye!</L>
<L>ffor we it fynden ernest at &thorn;e fulle;</L>
<L N="1547">&THORN;is makyth vs of oure lab&oacute;ur to dulle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="222" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(222. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1548">&para; "Now, fadir myn, how &thorn;inki&thorn; yow here-by?</L>
<L>Suppose ye not &thorn;at &thorn;is sitti&thorn; vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye that this sitteth vs not R, sit H.</NOTE> sore?"</L>
<L>"Yis, certes, son&euml;, &thorn;at ful wel wote I;</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou seyde, son&euml;? wolt &thorn;ou aght sey more?"</L>
<L N="1552">"Nay, sir, as now; but ay vp-on your lore</L>
<L>I herkne as bisily as I<NOTE PLACE="foot">I R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> best can."</L>
<L N="1554">"Son&euml;, &thorn;an lat vs spek as we by-gan:
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="57"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="223" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(223. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1555">&para; "Seye on &thorn;e so&thorn;e, I preye &thorn;e hertily,</L>
<L>What was &thorn;i caus&euml; why &thorn;ou toke a wyf?</L>
<L>Was it to get&euml; children lawfully,</L>
<L>And in clenness&euml; to led&euml; &thorn;y lyf;</L>
<L N="1559">Or, for luste, or muk<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or first for mukke R.</NOTE>? what was &thorn;i motyf?"</L>
<L>&para; "ffadir, no thyng wole I it queynt&euml; make:</L>
<L N="1561">Only for loue, I chees hire to my make."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="224" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(224. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1562">&para; "Son&euml;, qwat<NOTE PLACE="foot">what R.</NOTE> holdest &thorn;&oacute;u loue, I &thorn;e preye?</L>
<L>&THORN;ow demest lust and loue conuertible,</L>
<L>Per cas; as whan &thorn;e list with &thorn;i wyf pleye,</L>
<L>&THORN;i conceyt holde&thorn; it good and lisible</L>
<L N="1566">To doon; art &thorn;ou oght, son&euml; myn, sensible</L>
<L>In whiche cas &thorn;at &thorn;ou oghtest the for-bere,</L>
<L>And in whiche nat? canst &thorn;ou to &thorn;is answere?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="225" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(225. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1569">&para; "ffadir, me &thorn;inke&thorn; al is good y-nowe;<MILESTONE N="29a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>She is my wyf; who may &thorn;er-of me lette?"</L>
<L>"Nay, sone, a-byde; &amp; I shal tellen how,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;ou aght by godd&euml;s dred&euml; sette,</L>
<L N="1573">Thre causes ben, whiche I &thorn;e wole vnschette</L>
<L>And open a-non, whi &thorn;ou schalt with hire dele;</L>
<L N="1575">Now herkne, son&euml;, for &thorn;i soul&euml;s hele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="226" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(226. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1576">&para; &THORN;e first&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">first H R.</NOTE> caus&euml;, procreac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Of children is, vn-to godd&euml;s honour;</L>
<L>To kepe eke th&egrave; fro fornicac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e next is, &amp; &thorn;e thridde, of &thorn;at labour</L>
<L N="1580">Yild&euml; &thorn;i dette in whiche &thorn;ou art dettour</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i wyf; &amp; othire ententes al,</L>
<L N="1582">Ley hem apart, for aght &thorn;at may be-fal.<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle . . befalle R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="58"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="227" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(227. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1583">&para; "ffor &thorn;is&euml; causes thow hire vs&euml; muste;</L>
<L>And for non othir, on peyne of dedly synne."</L>
<L>"ffadir, right now me thoghte, how a-geyn luste</L>
<L>Ye helden, &amp; children be goten therinne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Therynne R, thinne H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where is no luste!" "o sone, or &thorn;at me a-twynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">twynne R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt wel vnderstond&euml; how &thorn;at I</L>
<L N="1589">Not holde agayn&euml;s luste al vttirly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="228" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(228. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1590">&para; "I wote wel, leefful luste is necessarie;</L>
<L>With-outen &thorn;at, may be non engendrure;</L>
<L>But vs&euml; luste for luste only, contrarie</L>
<L>To godd&euml;s hest&euml;s is; for I thensure,</L>
<L N="1594">&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou take of it litel heede or cure,</L>
<L>A man may wyth his wyf do lecherie:</L>
<L N="1596">The entente is al; be war ay of folye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">foly H, folye R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="229" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(229. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1597">&para; "Wedd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wedded R.</NOTE> folk many leden holy lyf;<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>flor &thorn;ogh hire flesschly lust&euml;s hem assaile,</L>
<L>And stire hem often, &thorn;e man to &thorn;e wif,</L>
<L>And she to him; &thorn;ei maken swiche batail</L>
<L N="1601">And strif a-gayn hir flesche, &thorn;at he shal fail.</L>
<L>Of his purpos; but som&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">som H R.</NOTE> folke, as beestes</L>
<L N="1603">Hire luste ay folwen; in hem non areeste is.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="230" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(230. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1604">&para; "A-day&euml;s now &thorn;er is swyche gouernaunce</L>
<L>Among hem &thorn;at han paramours &amp; wyues</L>
<L>&THORN;at, for luste of hire wommen &amp; plesaunce,</L>
<L>Nat suffice hem met&euml;s restauratyues,</L>
<L N="1608">But &thorn;ei receyuen eeke prouocatyues</L>
<L>Tengendre hem luste, feyntyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">feyntyng R, feytyng H.</NOTE> hire nature,</L>
<L N="1610">And suche &thorn;ing causi&thorn; hastyf sepulture.
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="59"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="231" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(231. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1611">&para; "&THORN;is knowe I so&thorn; is, &amp; knew it<NOTE PLACE="foot">it R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> fern a-gon,</L>
<L>And thei &thorn;at so don, hyli god offende:</L>
<L>Swich folk holde I homicid&euml;s echon;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei slen hemself, or god de&thorn; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">do for R.</NOTE> hem sende.</L>
<L N="1615">Mi sone, on godd&euml;s half I &thorn;e defende</L>
<L>Swiche medycyn&euml;s &thorn;at &thorn;ou noght receyue,</L>
<L N="1617">Syn &thorn;ei god wra&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wra&thorn;&thorn;en R.</NOTE> &amp; soule of man deceyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="232" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(232. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1618">&para; "Pas ouer &thorn;is: &thorn;ou seydest &thorn;enchesoun</L>
<L>Why &thorn;at &thorn;ou took vp-on &thorn;&egrave; maryage,</L>
<L>Was vn-to non o&thorn;er entenc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>But loue only &thorn;e sent&euml; &thorn;at corage:</L>
<L N="1622">Now, son&euml; myn, I am a man of age,</L>
<L>And many wedded couples haue I knowe,&mdash;</L>
<L N="1624">Non of myn ag&euml;, many mo, I trowe,&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="233" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(233. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1625">&para; "But I ne sawe, ne I ne spyd&euml; neuer,<MILESTONE N="30a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As longe as &thorn;at I hau&euml; lyued &yogh;it,</L>
<L>&THORN;e loue of hem departen or disseuere</L>
<L>&THORN;at for goode lou&euml; bounden were &amp; knyt;</L>
<L N="1629">God loue&thorn; loue, &amp; he wole for&thorn;ere it.</L>
<L>At long&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">longe R, long H.</NOTE> rennyng, lou&euml; beste schal preue;</L>
<L N="1631">&THORN;us ha&thorn; it ben, &amp; ay schal, I bileue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="234" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(234. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1632">&para; "But &thorn;ey &thorn;at marien hem for muk &amp; good</L>
<L>Only, &amp; noght for<NOTE PLACE="foot">for R, for &thorn;e H.</NOTE> loue of &thorn;e pers&oacute;ne,</L>
<L>Not haue I wist &thorn;ey any whyl&euml; stood</L>
<L>In rest&euml;; but of stryf is &thorn;ere swiche wone,</L>
<L N="1636">As for &thorn;e mor&euml; part, twixt hem echone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al hir lyf &thorn;ei lede in heuynesse:</L>
<L N="1638">Swich is &thorn;e fruyte to wedd&euml; for rychesse.
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="235" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(235. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1639">&para; "Among &thorn;e ryche also is an vsage,</L>
<L>Eche of hem his childe vn-to o&thorn;res wedde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ei be al to yong &amp; tendre of age,</L>
<L>No-wher my ripe ynow to go to bedde;</L>
<L N="1643">And hire conceyt in loue is leyde to wedde,</L>
<L>Men wit it wel, it is no quest&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="1645">Tyl yeer&euml;s come of hire discrecioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="236" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(236. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1646">&para; "And whan &thorn;ei han &thorn;e knoweleche of resoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;ei no&thorn;er fynden in hire herte</L>
<L>To lou&euml; o&thorn;er; al out of sesoun</L>
<L>&THORN;ei knyt ben, &thorn;at in-t&oacute; wedl&oacute;k so sterte:</L>
<L N="1650">&THORN;is make&thorn; many a couple for to smerte.</L>
<L>O couetyse! &thorn;in is al &thorn;e gilt</L>
<L N="1652">Of &thorn;is; &amp; mo deceyu&euml; &yogh;it &thorn;ow wilt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="237" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(237. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1653">&para; "Also &thorn;ey &thorn;at for luste chesen hir make<MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Only, as o&thorn;er while it is vsage,</L>
<L>Wayte wel, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">that R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> whan hir luste is ouerschake,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-with wole hir lou&euml;s hete asswage,</L>
<L N="1657">&THORN;anne is to hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, hym H.</NOTE> an helle, hire mariage</L>
<L>&THORN;anne &thorn;ei desyren for to be vnknyt,</L>
<L N="1659">And to &thorn;at ende studie in al hir wyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="238" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(238. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1660">&para; "Styntynge &thorn;e cause, &thorn;e &eacute;ffect<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e cause theffect R, cause &thorn;e feffect H.</NOTE> stynti&thorn; eek;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cessante causa.</NOTE></L>
<L>No lenger forster, no lenger lemman;</L>
<L>Loue on lust groundid, is not wor&thorn; a lek.</L>
<L>But who for vertu wedde&thorn; a womman,</L>
<L N="1664">And no&thorn;er for muk ne for lust, &thorn;at man</L>
<L>&THORN;e form&euml; due of matrimoign&euml; sue&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1666">And soul&euml;s hurt &amp; bodyes grief eschue&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="61"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="239" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(239. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1667">&para; "I dar not medle of lordes mari&aacute;gis,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ey hem knytten, hir mak&euml;s vnseen;</L>
<L>But as to me it seme&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">seemeth R, seme H.</NOTE> swiche vs&aacute;ge is</L>
<L>Not wor&thorn; a strawe; for, also mot I theen,</L>
<L N="1671">Report&euml;s not so sikyr iuges ben,</L>
<L>As man to se &thorn;e womann&euml;s pers&oacute;ne;</L>
<L N="1673">In whiche a choys, lat man hymself allone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="240" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(240. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1674">&para; "Weddyng at hoom in &thorn;is land, holsom were,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at a man hym wedd&euml; du&euml;ly;</L>
<L>To se &thorn;e flesche firste, it may no &thorn;ing dere,</L>
<L>And hym avis&euml; how hym lyki&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyki&thorn; = lyk&thorn;.</NOTE> &thorn;er-by</L>
<L N="1678">Or he be knyt; lo! &thorn;is conceyt haue I;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is mater&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">matere R, mater H.</NOTE> depper cowde I go,</L>
<L N="1680">But passe I wole, &amp; slippe away &thorn;er-fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="241" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(241. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1681">&para; "Now sythen &thorn;ou hast, to my Iug&euml;ment,<MILESTONE N="31a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e mary&euml;d vn-to godd&euml;s plesaunce,</L>
<L>Be a trewe housbounde, as by myn assent;</L>
<L>kep&euml; &thorn;i bond; be war of &thorn;encombraunce</L>
<L N="1685">Of &thorn;e feend, which, with many a circumstaunce</L>
<L>fful sly, him casti&thorn; &thorn;&euml; wrappe in &amp; wrye,</L>
<L N="1687">To stir&euml; &thorn;e for to done aduoutre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="242" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(242. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1688">&para; "Aduoutrie and periurie, and wylful slaghtre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; In canoni|bus. Adul|terare sponte periurare, &amp; hominem sponte occi|dere, equipa|rantur. Iero|nimus dicit, Adulterium secundum locum habet in penis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e book sei&thorn;, lik ben, &amp; o peys &thorn;ei weye.</L>
<L>War aduoutre! it is no pleye or laghtre</L>
<L>To don it; fle also &thorn;ise o&thorn;er tweye!</L>
<L N="1692">ffor &thorn;us wot I wel, seint Ierom can seye:</L>
<L>'In peyne, aduoutre ha&thorn; &thorn;e secounde place.'</L>
<L N="1694">&THORN;o &thorn;re to eschue, god &thorn;e graunt&euml; grace!
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="62"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="243" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(243. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1695">&para; "I, in &thorn;e bible, rede how &thorn;at abram<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Genesis xij<SUP>o</SUP>. Cum que prope esset ut ingrediretur Egiptum, dixit Saray vxori sue, "Noui quod pulcra sis mulier, &amp; quod cum te viderunt Egipcii, dic|turi sunt, 'vxor illius es,' &amp; inter|ficient me, &amp; te reserua|bunt; dic ergo, obsecro, quod soror mea sis, vt bene sit mihi propter te, &amp; viuat anima mea ob gra|ciam tui," &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Egipt went&euml;, with his wyf saray,</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei ny vn-to Egipt cam,</L>
<L>&THORN;us seyde he vnto his wyf by &thorn;e way:</L>
<L N="1699">'I wote wel &thorn;ou art fair; it is no nay;</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei of Egipt se &thorn;e, &thorn;ei wol seye,</L>
<L N="1701">"&THORN;ou art his wyf," &amp; for &thorn;e, do me deye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="244" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(244. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1702">&para; " 'Thei welen kyll&euml; me and &thorn;e reserue;</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i, vnto hem seye, I &thorn;e be-seche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art my sustre, leste I for &thorn;e sterue;</L>
<L>&THORN;us may I wel ben esyd by &thorn;i speche;</L>
<L N="1706">And &thorn;us &thorn;ou mayste leng&thorn;&euml; my lyf &amp; eche.'</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ei into Egipt entred were,</L>
<L N="1708">&THORN;e gipc&iuml;ans<NOTE PLACE="foot">Egipciens R.</NOTE> fast&euml; behelden here,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="245" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(245. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1709">&para; "And of hire beaute maden &thorn;ei report<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To phar&auml;o; &amp; sche as blyue is take</L>
<L>In-to his hous; &amp; done is gret comfort</L>
<L>Vnto Abram, for &thorn;is womman&euml;s sake;</L>
<L N="1713">And grete desport and cher&euml; men hem make.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Item, eo|dem capitulo: fflagellauit autem domi|nus pharao|nem flagellis maximis, &amp; domum eius, propter Saray vxorem Abra|ham; vocauit quoque pha|rao Abraham, eciam dixit ea: 'Quid|nam est hoc quod fecisti michi?' &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>But for saray, greuously phar&auml;o</L>
<L N="1715">Punysshyd was, &amp; eke his hous &thorn;erto.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="246" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(246. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1716">&para; "Phar&auml;o clepte abram, &amp; hym abreyde:</L>
<L>'What is it &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast don vn-to me?</L>
<L>'Why naddest &thorn;ou tolde vn-to me,' he seyde,</L>
<L>'How &thorn;at &thorn;is womman, wyf was vnto the?</L>
<L N="1720">ffor what enchesoun seydestow,' quod<NOTE PLACE="foot">koth (always).</NOTE> he,</L>
<L>'Sche was &thorn;y suster? tak&euml; &thorn;i wyf here,'</L>
<L N="1722">Quod he, 'and bo&thorn;&euml; go youre wey in fere!'
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="247" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(247. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1723">&para; "The bible maki&thorn; no man&eacute;r of mynde</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at phar&auml;o lay by hire oght;</L>
<L>But looke in lyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nicolaus de Lyra, the celebrated medieval commentator on the Scriptures.&mdash;T. Wright.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;er&euml; schalt &thorn;ou fynde,</L>
<L>ffor to han done it, was he in ful &thorn;oght;</L>
<L N="1727">But god preserued hire; he myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">myght H R.</NOTE> noght;</L>
<L>And sethyn, for wil, god hym punissched<NOTE PLACE="foot">for that will . . . punysshed R, punissche H.</NOTE> so,</L>
<L N="1729">How schal &thorn;e ded&euml; vnpun&yacute;sshed go?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="248" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(248. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1730">&para; "Also not knewe he &thorn;at a wif sche was.</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ann&euml;, &thorn;ey &thorn;at wyu&euml;s wetyngly<NOTE PLACE="marg">Non solum eternaliter, verum eciam temporaliter in ista vita, adulter mani|festus est pu|nitus, iuxta illud versus: 'Ex istis quidem,' &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Takyn and holde, and with hem don trespas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare Robert of Brunne's (<I>Handlyng Synne</I>, 1.7420-7, A.D. 1303) reproach to the nobles for ravishing maidens and wives, and then boasting of it. See also <I>H. S.</I>, lines 2928-83.</NOTE></L>
<L>Stonde in harde plyt; son&euml;, be ware, rede I;</L>
<L N="1734">If &thorn;ou &thorn;ere-inne agylte, eternelly<NOTE PLACE="foot">eternelly R, enternelly H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou smert&euml; schalt, &amp; in &thorn;is lif pres&eacute;nt</L>
<L N="1736">Han scharp aduersitee &amp; gret turment.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="249" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(249. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1737">&para; "And to abymalech, god bade he shulde<MILESTONE N="32a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Genesis xx<SUP>o</SUP>. Redde vxorem viro suo; si au|tem nolueris, scito quod morte morie|ris tu &amp; omnia que tua sunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ild&euml; sara also to hir housbonde;</L>
<L>ffor he and his, echon, if he ne wolde,</L>
<L>Shulden ben dede, he did hem vndirstonde.</L>
<L N="1741">Take heede, o son&euml;, &thorn;at &thorn;ou clere ay stonde,</L>
<L>ffor god stoppid eke the concepcioun</L>
<L N="1743">Of euery woman of his mancioun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Item in eodem. Con|cluserat au|tem dominus omnem vu|luam domus Abymalech, propter Sa|ram vxorem Abrahe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="250" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(250. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1744">&para; "Ne &thorn;at she was a wif, wist he no &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Ne nogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">nought R, nogh H.</NOTE> hir knew in no flesshly folye.</L>
<L>My god&euml; son&euml;, rede of dauid kyng,</L>
<L>How he bersabe toke, wyf of vrie,</L>
<L N="1748">Into his house, and did aduout[e]rie;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Regum ij<SUP>o</SUP> capitulis x<SUP>o</SUP> &amp; xj<SUP>mo</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>And how he made vri&euml; slayne to be,</L>
<L N="1750">And how &thorn;er-for&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fore R, for H.</NOTE> punysshed was he.
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="251" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(251. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1751">&para; "How was &thorn;e tribe also of beniamyn</L>
<L>Punysshid, &amp; put to destruccioun,</L>
<L>ffor aduoutr[i]&euml; which &thorn;ei lyued inne,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e abhomynable oppressioun<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iudicum xx<SUP>o</SUP> Egressi sunt &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1755">Of &thorn;e leuyt&euml;s wyfe: lo! mencioun</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of is made, if &thorn;ou loke holy writte,</L>
<L N="1757">In iudicium, ful redily<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iudicum full redily R, redy H.</NOTE> it syt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="252" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(252. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1758">&para; "Who-so lith with his neygh&euml;bur&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">neighbores R, neyghburs H.</NOTE> wyfe<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Deutro|nomi xxvij<SUP>o</SUP>. Maledictus qui dormierit cum vxore proximi sui. Ad corinthos vj<SUP>to</SUP>. Neque fornicarii, neque idolis seruientes, neque adul|teri, regnum dei posside|bunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is cursyd; &amp; who is any aduoutoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyngdome faill&euml; shal of endles lyfe;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at ne shal he be no p&oacute;ssessoure.</L>
<L N="1762">Alasse! this likerous dampn&aacute;ble errour,</L>
<L>In this londe hath so large a &thorn;rede I-sponne,</L>
<L N="1764">&THORN;at wers peple is non vndir the<NOTE PLACE="foot">the R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> sonne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="253" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(253. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1765">&para; "Of swich&euml; stories cowde I telle an<NOTE PLACE="foot">an R, and H.</NOTE> heepe,<MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But I suppos&euml; &thorn;is&euml; schol suffise;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i, son&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone R, persone H.</NOTE> wole I make a leepe</L>
<L>ffrom hem, and go wole I to &thorn;e empryse</L>
<L N="1769">&THORN;at I first took; if &thorn;u &thorn;e wel auyse,</L>
<L>Whanne I &thorn;e mette, &amp; sy &thorn;in heuynesse,</L>
<L N="1771">Of comfort, son&euml;, made I &thorn;e promesse:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="254" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(254. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1772">&para; "And of a trew&euml; man, be-heste is dette."</L>
<L>"ffader, god &yogh;ilde it &yogh;ow, and so &yogh;e diden;</L>
<L>Ye hyghten me in es&euml; me to sette."</L>
<L>"Now, sone, &amp; &thorn;ogh I long&euml; haue abiden,</L>
<L N="1776">Thi gryfe is noght out of my mynd&euml; slyden;</L>
<L>To &thorn;i greuanc&euml; wole I now resorte,</L>
<L N="1778">And schew&euml; &thorn;e how &thorn;ou &thorn;e schalt comforte.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="255" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(255. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1779">&para; "In schort, &thorn;is is of &thorn;i grief &eacute;nchesoun:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota [<I>in</I> 1700 <I>hand</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;in annuitee, &thorn;e pai&euml;ment,</L>
<L>Whiche for &thorn;i long seruyse is &thorn;i guerdoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dredest, whan &thorn;ou art from court absent,</L>
<L N="1783">Schal be restreyn&euml;d, syn &thorn;ou now present</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;&euml;s mayst it gete, it is so streit;</L>
<L N="1785">&THORN;us vnder-stode I, son&euml;, &thorn;i conceit;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="256" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(256. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1786">&para; "ffor of &thorn;i liflode is it &thorn;e substaunce;</L>
<L>Is it nat &thorn;us?" "&YOGH;is, soo&thorn;ly, fader, it."</L>
<L>"Now, sone, to remed&iuml;e &thorn;is greu&aacute;nce,</L>
<L>Canstow no wey&euml;s fynden in &thorn;i wyt?"</L>
<L N="1790">"No, certes, fader, neuere koude I &yogh;it.'</L>
<L>"May no lordschep&euml;, son&euml;, &thorn;e auayle,</L>
<L N="1792">ffor al &thorn;i long seruice &amp; &thorn;i trauaile?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="257" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(257. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1793">&para; "What, fadir? what? lord&euml;s han for to done<MILESTONE N="33a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So mych for hem-self, &thorn;at my mateere</L>
<L>Out of hir mynd&euml; slippith away soone.</L>
<L>The world is naght swich now, my fadir deere,</L>
<L N="1797">As ye han seene; farwel, frendely maneere!</L>
<L>So go[d] me amende, I am al destitut</L>
<L N="1799">Of my lyflod&euml;; god be my refut!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="258" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(258. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1800">&para; "I am vn-to so streyt a poynt ydryue,</L>
<L>Of thre conclus&iuml;ons moot I cheese one:</L>
<L>Or begge, or stele, or sterue; I am yschryue</L>
<L>So ny, &thorn;at o&thorn;er way ne se I noon.</L>
<L N="1804">Myn hert is also deed as is a stoon;</L>
<L>Nay, ther I faile, a stoon no thyng ne felith;</L>
<L>But thoght me brenneth, and freesyngly keelith
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="259" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(259. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1807">&para; "To begg&euml;, schame is myn impediment;</L>
<L>I wot wel, rather schulde I die and sterue;</L>
<L>And steltl&euml;s guerdon is swich pai&euml;ment,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer thynke I his wages disserue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">deserue R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1811">Wolde honest deth come, and me ouerterue,</L>
<L>And of my grau&euml; me put in seisyne,</L>
<L N="1813">To al my greef &thorn;at were a medecyne."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="260" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(260. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "What, sone! how now? I se, wel smal effecte,</L>
<L>Or ell&euml;s non, my word&euml;s in th&egrave; take;</L>
<L>Outhir ful symple is &thorn;in intellect,</L>
<L>Or hokirly thow hast hem ouershake,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;i goost slept hath; what, my sone! a-wake!</L>
<L>Whyl er &thorn;ou seydist &thorn;ou were of me glad,</L>
<L N="1820">And now it semeth &thorn;ou art of me sad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="261" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(261. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1821">&para; "I dem&euml; so, syn &thorn;at my longe sermoun<MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Profitith naght, it sor&euml; me repentith."</L>
<L>"ffadir, beth nat of &thorn;at opynyoun;</L>
<L>ffor as ye wele I do, myn hert assentith;</L>
<L N="1825">But ay among, fadir, thoght me tormentith</L>
<L>So sharply, &aacute;nd so trowblith and dispeireth,</L>
<L>That it my wit foule hyndryth and appeireth."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="262" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(262. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1828">&para; "O my good son&euml;, wolt &thorn;ou yit algate</L>
<L>Despeir&euml;d be? nay, son&euml;, lat be &thorn;at!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt as blyue entre in-to &thorn;e yate<NOTE PLACE="marg">Parascenes ad opus De regimine principis. (<I>In the</I> 1700 <I>hand.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;i comfort. now telle on pleyn and plat:</L>
<L N="1832">My lord &thorn;e princ&euml;, knowyth he &thorn;e nat?</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;ou stonde in his beneuolence,</L>
<L N="1834">He may be salue vn-to &thorn;in indigence.
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="263" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(263. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1835">&para; "No man bet, next his fadir, our lord lige."</L>
<L>"Yis, fadir, he is my good gracious lord."</L>
<L>"Wel, son&euml;, &thorn;an wole I me oblige,&mdash;</L>
<L>And god of heuen vouch I to record,&mdash;</L>
<L N="1839">&THORN;at if &thorn;ou wolt be ful of myn accord,</L>
<L>Thow schalt no cause haue mor&euml; &thorn;us to muse,</L>
<L N="1841">But heuyness&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuynesse R, heuynes H.</NOTE> voide, and it refuse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="264" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(264. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1842">&para; "Syn he &thorn;i good lord is, I am ful seur</L>
<L>His grac&euml; to &thorn;e schal nat be denyed;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost wele, he benyng is and demeur</L>
<L>To sue vnto; naght is his goost maistried</L>
<L N="1846">With daunger, but his hert is ful applied</L>
<L>To graunte, and nat &thorn;e needy werne his grace;</L>
<L N="1848">To hym pursue, and &thorn;i releef purchace.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="265" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(265. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1849">&para; "Compleyne vnto his excellent noblesse,<MILESTONE N="34a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As I haue herd &thorn;e vn-to me compleyne;</L>
<L>And but he qwenche &thorn;i gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete R, gret H.</NOTE> heuynesse,</L>
<L>My tong&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tunge R, tong H.</NOTE> take, and slitte in peeces tweyne.</L>
<L N="1853">What, son&euml; myn! for godd&euml;s der&euml; peyne,</L>
<L>Endite in frensch or latyn &thorn;i greef clere,</L>
<L N="1855">And, for to write it wel, do thi poweer.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="266" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(266. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1856">&para; "Of all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle R, al H.</NOTE> thre &thorn;ou oghtist be wele leerid,</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;ou so long in hem lab&oacute;ur&euml;d haast,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou of &thorn;e pryue seel art old I-yeerid."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Vide supra, folio 15 [<I>in</I> 1700 <I>hand</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>"Yit, fadir, of hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, hym H.</NOTE> ful smal is my taast."</L>
<L N="1860">"Now, son&euml;, &thorn;an, foul&euml; hast &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">thou foule hast R.</NOTE> in waast</L>
<L>Despent &thorn;i tyme; and nathelees, I trowe</L>
<L N="1862">&THORN;ou canst do bet &thorn;an &thorn;ou wilt do me knowe.
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="267" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(267. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1863">&para; "What schal I call&euml; &thorn;e? what is &thorn;i name?"</L>
<L>"Hoccleu&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Occleve R.</NOTE> fadir myn, men clepen me."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hoccleve [<I>in</I> 1700 <I>hand</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>"Hoccleu&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Occleve R.</NOTE> sone?" "I-wis, fadir, &thorn;at same."</L>
<L>"Sone, I haue herd, or this, men speke of &thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Chaucer [<I>in</I> 1700 <I>hand</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L N="1867">&THORN;ou were aqueynted with Caucher,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Chaucers R.</NOTE> pardee&mdash;</L>
<L>God haue his soul&euml; best of any wyght!&mdash;</L>
<L N="1869">Sone, I wole hold&euml; &thorn;e &thorn;at I haue hyght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">the hight R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="268" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(268. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1870">&para; "Al-thogh &thorn;ou sey&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ou in latyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">latyne, afyne R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne in frenssh nowther, canst but smal endite,</L>
<L>In englyssh tong&euml; canst &thorn;ou wel afyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">latyne, afyne R.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor ther-of can I eek&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Truly therof kan I R.</NOTE> but a lite;</L>
<L N="1874">Ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ye R.</NOTE> straw! let be! &thorn;i penn&euml; take, and write</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou canst, and &thorn;i sorowe tourne schal</L>
<L N="1876">Into gladnesse; I doute it naght at al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="269" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(269. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1877">&para; "Syn &thorn;ou maist nat be paied in thescheqer,<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnto my lord &thorn;e princ&euml; make instance</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i patent in-to &thorn;e hanaper</L>
<L>May chaunged be." "fadir, by your suffrance,</L>
<L N="1881">It may not so, bi-cause of &thorn;e ordenance;</L>
<L>'Longe aftir &thorn;is schal no grant chargeable</L>
<L N="1883">Out passe;' fadir myn, this is no fable."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="270" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(270. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1884">&para; "An egal change, my son&euml;, is in soothe</L>
<L>No charge, I wot it wel ynow in dede.</L>
<L>What, son&euml; myn! good hert take vnto &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Men seyn, who-so of euery grace hath drede,</L>
<L N="1888">Let hym beware to walk in any mede.</L>
<L>Assay! assay! &thorn;ou simple-hertid goost!</L>
<L>What grace is shapen &thorn;e, &thorn;ou naght ne woost."
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="271" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(271. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1891">&para; "ffadir, as siker as I stand&euml; here,</L>
<L>Whethir &thorn;at I be simple, or argh or bolde,</L>
<L>Swych an eschang&euml; get I non to yeere;</L>
<L>Do as I can, with &thorn;at I haue in holde;</L>
<L N="1895">ffor, as for &thorn;at, my comfort is but cold;</L>
<L>But wel I fynd&euml; your good wyl alway</L>
<L N="1897">Redy to me, in what ye can and<NOTE PLACE="foot">or R.</NOTE> may."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="272" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(272. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1898">&para; "That is sooth, son&euml;; now, syn &thorn;ou me toldist</L>
<L>My lord &thorn;e princ&euml; is good lord &thorn;e to,</L>
<L>No maistri<NOTE PLACE="foot">maistrie R.</NOTE> is it for &thorn;e, if &thorn;ou woldist</L>
<L>To be releeu&euml;d; wost &thorn;ou what to do?</L>
<L N="1902">Writt&euml; to hym a goodly tale or two,</L>
<L>On which he may desporten hym by nyghte,</L>
<L N="1904">And his fre grac&euml; schal vp-on &thorn;e lighte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="273" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(273. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1905">&para; "Sharp&euml; thi penne, and write on lustily;<MILESTONE N="35a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Lat se, my son&euml;, make it fresh and gay,</L>
<L>Out&euml; thyn art if<NOTE PLACE="foot">Uttre . . as R, Out . . if H.</NOTE> &thorn;ou canst craftily;</L>
<L>His hy&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hye R, hy H.</NOTE> prudence hath insighte verray</L>
<L N="1909">To iuge if it be wel y-made or nay;</L>
<L>Wher-for&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wherfore R, Wher for H.</NOTE> sone, it is vn-to the neede,</L>
<L N="1911">Vn-to &thorn;i werk, tak&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to take R.</NOTE> &thorn;e gretter heede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="274" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(274. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1912">&para; "But of a thyng be wel waar in al wise,</L>
<L>On flateri&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e nat founde;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prouerbi|arum xxix<SUP>o</SUP>. Qui blandis fictis que ser|monibus lo|quitur amico suo, expandit rethe gressi|bus suis.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er-of, son&euml;, Salamon &thorn;e wise,&mdash;</L>
<L>As &thorn;at I haue in his prouerb&euml;s found,&mdash;</L>
<L>Seith thus: 'thei &thorn;at in feyn&euml;d speche habounde,</L>
<L N="1917">And glosyngly vnto hir freend&euml;s talke,</L>
<L>Spreden a net bi-forne hem wher they walke.'
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="275" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(275. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1919">&para; "If a deceyuour yeue a man to sowke</L>
<L>Word&euml;s plesant, in hony al by-wrappid,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prouerbi|arum I. ffili mi, si te lactauerint peccatores, ne adquiescas eis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Good is a man eschew&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to eschewe R, eschew H.</NOTE> swich a powke;</L>
<L>Thurgh fauel ha&thorn; ful many a man mys-happid;</L>
<L N="1923">ffor when &thorn;at he hath ianglid al and clappid</L>
<L>With his freend, tretyng of pees openly,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieremie ix. In ore suo pa|cem loquitur cum amico suo, &amp; occulte ponit ei insi|dias.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1925">He in a-wayt lith of hym couertly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="276" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(276. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1926">&para; "&THORN;e most&euml; lak &thorn;at han &thorn;e lord&euml;s grete,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca li|bro vij<SUP>o</SUP> de beneficiis. Summa loca tenentibus maxime deest qui veritatem dicat. Adula|cionis certa|men omnibus officium est, vna omnium contencio quis blandis|sime fallat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is of hem that hir sooth&euml;s shuld hem telle;</L>
<L>Al in &thorn;e glos&euml; folk labour and swete;</L>
<L>Thei stryuen who best ryng&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">rynge R, ryng H.</NOTE> shal &thorn;e belle</L>
<L N="1930">Of fals plesance, in &thorn;at hir hert&euml;s swelle</L>
<L>If &thorn;at oon can bet than oth&eacute;r deceyue;</L>
<L N="1932">And swich deceyt, lord&euml;s blyndly receyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="277" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(277. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1933">&para; "The worldly rich&euml; men, han no knowleche<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Item Se|neca. Igno|rant seculi potentes vires suas, dum se credunt tam magnos quanti pre|dicantur.</NOTE></L>
<L>What &thorn;at thei bene of hir condicioun;</L>
<L>Thei ben so blent with fauell&euml;s gay speche,</L>
<L>Wich r&eacute;portith to hem, &thorn;at hir renoun</L>
<L N="1937">Is euerywher&euml; halwid in the toun,</L>
<L>That in hem-self they demen gret vertu,</L>
<L N="1939">Where as &thorn;er is but smal or naght a gru,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="278" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(278. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1940">&para; "ffor vnneth &aacute; good word men speke of hem:</L>
<L>This fals&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fals H R.</NOTE> tresoun comon is and rif;</L>
<L>Bet were it the ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">thou were R.</NOTE> at ierusalem,</L>
<L>Son&euml;, &thorn;an &thorn;ou were in it defectif.</L>
<L N="1944">Syn my lord &thorn;e prynce is, god help his lyf,</L>
<L>To th&egrave; good lord, good seruant &thorn;ou &thorn;e quyte</L>
<L N="1946">To him, and trewe, and it shal the profyte.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="71"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="279" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(279. Beggar and Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1947">&para; "Write him no thyng &thorn;at sowneth in-to vice;</L>
<L>Kyth&euml; thi loue in matere of sadnesse;</L>
<L>looke if &thorn;ou fynd&euml; canst any tretice</L>
<L>Groundid on his estat&euml;s holsumnesse;</L>
<L N="1951">Swych thing translate, and vnto his hynesse,</L>
<L>As humblely as &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst, present;</L>
<L N="1953">Do thus my sone." "fadir, I assent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="280" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(280. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1954">&para; "With hert as tremblyng as &thorn;e leef of aspe,</L>
<L>ffadir, syn ye me red&euml; to do so,</L>
<L>Of my symple conceyt wole I the claspe</L>
<L>Vndo, and lat it at his larg&euml; go.</L>
<L N="1958">But weylaway! so is myn hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert R H.</NOTE> wo,</L>
<L>That &thorn;e honour of englyssh tonge is deed,</L>
<L N="1960">Of which I wont was han consail and reed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="281" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(281. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1961">&para; "O, maister deere, and fadir reuerent!<MILESTONE N="36a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Mi maister Chaucer,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Chaucers R.</NOTE> flour of eloquence,<NOTE PLACE="marg">G. Chaucer [<I>in</I> 1700 <I>hand.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Mirour of fructuous entend&euml;ment,</L>
<L>O, vniuersel fadir in science!</L>
<L N="1965">Allas! &thorn;at &thorn;ou thyn excellent prudence,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i bed mortel mightist naght by-qwethe;</L>
<L>What eiled deth? allas! whi wolde he sle the?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="282" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(282. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1968">&para; "O deth! &thorn;ou didest naght harme singuleer,</L>
<L>In slaghtere of him; but al &thorn;is land it smertith;</L>
<L>But nath&euml;lees, yit hast &thorn;ou no power</L>
<L>His nam&euml; sle; his hy vertu astertith</L>
<L N="1972">Vnslayn fro &thorn;e, which ay vs lyfly hertyth,</L>
<L>With book&euml;s of his ornat &eacute;ndytyng,</L>
<L N="1974">That is to al &thorn;is land enlumynyng.
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="283" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(283. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="1975">&para; "Hast &thorn;ou nat eeke my maister Gower slayn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">J Gower [<I>in</I> 1700 <I>hand</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>Whos vertu I am insuffic&iuml;ent</L>
<L>ffor to descreyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">discrive R.</NOTE>? I wote wel in certayn,</L>
<L>ffor to sleen al &thorn;is world &thorn;ou haast yment<NOTE PLACE="foot">yment R, ment H.</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="1979">But syn our lorde Crist was obedient</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, in feith I can no ferther seye;</L>
<L N="1981">His cre&auml;tur&euml;s mosten &thorn;e obeye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="284" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(284. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1982">&para; "ffadir, ye may lawhe at my lewd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">nyce H.</NOTE> speche.</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;ow list; I am no thyng fourmeel<NOTE PLACE="foot">formell R.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>My yong&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yonge R, yong H.</NOTE> konyng may no hyer reche,</L>
<L>Mi wit is<NOTE PLACE="foot">is R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> also slipir as an eel;</L>
<L N="1986">But how I speke, algate I men&euml; weel."</L>
<L>"Sone, &thorn;ou seist wel I-nogh, as me seometh,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seemeth R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1988">Non oothir feele I, so my c&oacute;nceyt demeth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="285" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(285. Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1989">&para; "Now, farwel, sone! go hom&euml; to &thorn;i mete,<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It is hy tyme; and go wil I to myn;</L>
<L>And what I haue y-seid &thorn;e, naght forgete;</L>
<L>And swych as &thorn;at I am, sone, I am thyn.</L>
<L N="1993">Thow seest wel, age hath put me to declyne,</L>
<L>And pouert hath me maad of good al bare;</L>
<L N="1995">&para; I may naght but prey&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">prey H, pray R.</NOTE> for &thorn;i welfare."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="286" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(286. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="1996">"What, fadir? wolden ye thus sodeynly</L>
<L>Depart fro me? Petir! crist, for-beede!</L>
<L>Ye shal go dyn&euml; with me, trew&euml;ly."<NOTE PLACE="foot">trewly H, truly R.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sone, at a word, I moot go fro &thorn;e neede."</L>
<L>&para; "Nay, fadir, nay!" "Yis, sone, as god me speede!"</L>
<L>"Now, fadir, syn it may non othir tyde,</L>
<L N="2002">Almyghty god yow saue, and he your gyde!
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="287" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(287. Hoccleve and Beggar.)</HEAD>
<L N="2003">&para; "And graut&euml; grac&euml; me &thorn;at day to se,</L>
<L>That I sumwhat may quyt&euml; your goodnesse.</L>
<L>But, good&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">goode R, good H.</NOTE> fadir, whan and wher schul ye</L>
<L>And I efte met&euml;?" "Sone, in soothfastnesse,</L>
<L N="2007">I euery day heere at &thorn;e Carmes messe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The house and church of the Carmelites, or White Friars, stood on the South side of Fleet Street, between the Temple and Salisbury Court.&mdash;T. Wright. Not far, therefore, from Hoccleve's "cote" in Chester's Inn, Somerset House.</NOTE></L>
<L>It faileth naght o-boute &thorn;e hour of seuene."</L>
<L N="2009">"Wel, fadir, god bytake I yow, of heuene!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="288" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(288. Hoccleve.)</HEAD>
<L N="2010">&para; Recordyng in my mynd&euml; &thorn;e lessoun</L>
<L>That he me yaf, I hoom to met&euml; wente;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morowe sette I me adoun,</L>
<L>And penne and ynke and parchemyn I hente,</L>
<L N="2014">And to performe his wil and his entente</L>
<L>I took corage, and whiles it was hoot,</L>
<L N="2016">Vn-to my lord the princ&euml; thus I wroot<NOTE PLACE="foot">The original leaf 37&mdash;a Picture and 5 stanzas&mdash;has been torn from the Harl. MS. by some "furious Foole." The 5 stanzas are inserted here from MS. Reg. 17 D vi, leaf 40.</NOTE>:&mdash;</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[HOCCLEVE'S "REGEMENT" FOR HENRY V. WHEN PRINCE OF WALES.]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[Proem.]</HEAD>
<LG N="289" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(289,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This stanza is under an illumination of a little poet on his knees presenting his book bound in pink to a tall crownd man standing, clad in a blue cloak, collard and lined with ermine. His under robe is colourd lake, with a black belt, studded with gold. The robe has a white-borderd pocket-slit near the top of the left thigh. The poet is in a dull brick red gown, borderd with yellow, and has lake hose. At foot is a coat of arms hung on the ornament, a fret, or, on sable, quartering a lion rampant or, gules. The arms of? Rich. Durrundill.</NOTE> MS. Reg. 17, D vi, to st. 293.)</HEAD>
<L N="2017">Hy&euml; and nobl&euml; princ&euml; excellent,<MILESTONE N="40a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My lord the prince, o my lord grac&iuml;ous,</L>
<L>I, humble seruaunt and obedient</L>
<L>Vnto your &eacute;state hye &amp; glorious,</L>
<L N="2021">Of whiche I am full tendir &amp; full ielous,</L>
<L>Me recomaunde vnto your worthynesse,</L>
<L N="2023">With hert entier, and spirite of mekenesse.
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="74"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="290" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(290)</HEAD>
<L N="2024">Right humbly axyng of you [the] licence,<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That with my penne I may to you declare</L>
<L>(So as that kan my witt&euml;s innocence,)</L>
<L>Myne inward wille that thursteth the welefare</L>
<L N="2028">Of your persone; and ell&euml;s be I bare</L>
<L>Of blisse, whan &thorn;at the cold&euml; stroke of deth</L>
<L>My lyfe hath quenched, &amp; me byraft my breth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="291" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(291)</HEAD>
<L N="2031">Though that my livelode and possession</L>
<L>Be skant, I riche am of beneuolence;</L>
<L>To you therof kan I be no nygon:</L>
<L>Goode haue I none, by whiche your excellence</L>
<L N="2035">May ples&euml;d be; &amp;, for myne impotence</L>
<L>Stoppeth the way to do as I were holde,</L>
<L>I write as he &thorn;at your goode lyf&euml; fayn&euml; wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="292" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(292)</HEAD>
<L N="2038">Ar&eacute;stotle, most famous Philosofre,</L>
<L>His Epistles to Alisaundre sent,</L>
<L>Whos sentence is wel bette than<NOTE PLACE="foot">that R.</NOTE> gold in cofre,</L>
<L>And more holsomer grounded to trewe entent:</L>
<L N="2042">For all &thorn;at euer tho Epistles ment,</L>
<L>To sett&euml; was &thorn;is worthy Conquerour,</L>
<L N="2044">In reul&euml;, how to s&uacute;stene his honour.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="293" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(293)</HEAD>
<L N="2045">The tendir loue, and the feru&eacute;nt chiertee</L>
<L>That this worthy clerk ay to this kyng bere,</L>
<L>Trustyng his welth&euml; durable to be,</L>
<L>Vnto his hert[&egrave;] stak and satte so nere,</L>
<L N="2049">That by writ&yacute;ng his counseill yave he clere</L>
<L>Vnto his lord, to kepe hym fro myschaunce,</L>
<L N="2051">As witnesseth his booke of gouernaunce.
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="294" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(294) (<I>Harl.</I> 4866 <I>again.</I>)</HEAD>
<L N="2052">&para; Of which, and [eek] of Gyles of regyment<MILESTONE N="37a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of princes, plotmel thynke I to translate.</L>
<L>And thogh that<NOTE PLACE="foot">that R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> senple be my sent&euml;ment,</L>
<L>O worthi prince, I yow biseeche al-gate</L>
<L N="2056">Considerith, how endityng hath in hate</L>
<L>Mi dul conceyt, and nat accord&euml; may</L>
<L N="2058">With my childhode; I am so childissh ay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="295" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(295)</HEAD>
<L N="2059">&para; Also byseeche I that &thorn;e altitude</L>
<L>Of your estate&mdash;&thorn;ogh &thorn;at &thorn;is pamfilet</L>
<L>Non ordre hold&euml;, ne in him include&mdash;</L>
<L>Nat greu&euml;d be, for I can do no bet.</L>
<L N="2063">Anothir day, whan wit &amp; I be met,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bette . . mette R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Which longe is to, and han vs freenly<NOTE PLACE="foot">frendely.</NOTE> kist,</L>
<L N="2065">Descouere I wole, th&aacute;t now is nat wist.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="296" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(296)</HEAD>
<L N="2066">&para; Nath&euml;les, swich as is my smal konyng,</L>
<L>Withal so treewe an<NOTE PLACE="foot">and H, an R.</NOTE> herte, I wole it oute,</L>
<L>As &thorn;o two dide, or euere Clerc lyfynge;</L>
<L>But tremblyng is my spirit out of doute,</L>
<L N="2070">That to perform&euml; &thorn;at I am a-boute;</L>
<L>Allas! &thorn;e stuf of sad intelligence</L>
<L N="2072">Me faillith, to speke in so hy presence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="297" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(297)</HEAD>
<L N="2073">&para; Simple is my goost, and scars my letterure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">scarce my lettrure R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto your excellenc&euml; for to write</L>
<L>Myn inward loue, and yit in &aacute;uenture</L>
<L>Wyle I me putt&euml;, thogh I can but lyte.</L>
<L N="2077">Mi der&euml; maistir&mdash;god his soul&euml; quyte!&mdash;</L>
<L>And fadir, Chaucer, fayn wolde han me taght;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Chaucer [<I>in</I> 1700 <I>hand</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L N="2079">But I was dul, and lern&egrave;d lite<NOTE PLACE="foot">lerned right R.</NOTE> or naght.
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="76"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="298" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(298)</HEAD>
<L N="2080">&para; Allas! my worthi maister honorable,<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This land&euml;s verray tresor and richesse,</L>
<L>Deth, by thi deth, hath harme irreparable</L>
<L>Vnto vs doon; hir vengeable duresse</L>
<L N="2084">Despoil&egrave;d hath &thorn;is land of &thorn;e swetnesse</L>
<L>Of rethorik; for vn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro vs to R.</NOTE> Tullius</L>
<L N="2086">Was neuer man so lyk a-mong&euml;s vs.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="299" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(299)</HEAD>
<L N="2087">&para; Also, who was hi&euml;r in philosophie</L>
<L>To Aristotle, in our tonge, but thow?</L>
<L>The stepp&euml;s of virgile in poesie</L>
<L>Thow filwedist eeke, men wot wel y-now.</L>
<L N="2091">That combre-world, &thorn;at &thorn;e, my maistir, slow,</L>
<L>Wold I slayn were! deth was to hastyf</L>
<L N="2093">To renne on &thorn;e, and reu&euml; the thi lyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="300" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(300)</HEAD>
<L N="2094">&para; Deth hath but smal considerac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e vertuous, I haue espied,</L>
<L>No more, as shewith &thorn;e probac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Than to a vicious maistir losel tried;</L>
<L N="2098">A-mong an heep, euery man is maistried;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ecclesias|tici ijo. Mo|ritur doctus simul &amp; in|doctus.</NOTE></L>
<L>With hire, as wel &thorn;e porre as is &thorn;e riche;</L>
<L N="2100">lered<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lered R, lerd H.</NOTE> and lewde eeke standen al y-liche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="301" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(301)</HEAD>
<L N="2101">&para; She myghte han taried hir vengeance awhile,</L>
<L>Til that sum man had egal to th&egrave; be.</L>
<L>Nay, lat be &thorn;at! sche knew wel &thorn;at &thorn;is yle</L>
<L>May neuer man forth bryng&euml; lyk to the,</L>
<L N="2105">And hir offic&euml; need&euml;s do mot she;</L>
<L>God bad hir so, I truste as for thi<NOTE PLACE="foot">the R.</NOTE> beste;</L>
<L N="2107">O maister, maister, god &thorn;i soule reste!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000143.tif" N="77">
<LG N="302" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">The original leaf 39 of the Harl. MS. 4866 is out. It con|taind lines 2108-2160. They are inserted here from MS. Reg. 17 D vi.</NOTE>(302. <I>The Regement. From MS, Reg.</I> 17 D vi, to line 2160.)</HEAD>
<L N="2108">Now to my matere, as that I began:<MILESTONE N="42" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>There is a booke, Iacob de Cessoles,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ordre of Prechours, made, a worthy man,</L>
<L>That "the Chesse moralis&egrave;d" cleped is,</L>
<L N="2112">In which I purpose eke to laboure y-wis,</L>
<L>And here &amp; there, as that my litell witte</L>
<L N="2114">Afforth&euml; may, I thynk&euml; tr&aacute;nslate it.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="303" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(303)</HEAD>
<L N="2115">And al be it that in that plac&euml; square</L>
<L>Of the lyst&euml;s, I mane &thorn;e eschekere,</L>
<L>A man may lern&euml; to be wise &amp; ware,</L>
<L>I, that haue auentured many a yere,</L>
<L N="2119">My witte there-in is but litill the nere,</L>
<L>Save that somwhat I knowe a kyng&euml;s draught;</L>
<L N="2121">Of other draught&euml;s, lerned haue I naught.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="304" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(304)</HEAD>
<L N="2122">And, for that among the draught&euml;s euerychone</L>
<L>That vnto &thorn;e chess&euml; apperten&euml; may,</L>
<L>Is none so ned&euml;full vnto your persone</L>
<L>To knowe, as that of the cheert&euml; verray</L>
<L N="2126">That I haue hade vnto your noblesse ay,</L>
<L>And shall, yf your plesaunce it be to here,</L>
<L N="2128">A kyng&euml;s draught, reporte I shall now here.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="305" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(305)</HEAD>
<L N="2129">I am sure that the book&euml;s all&euml; thre,</L>
<L>Redde hath &amp; seen your Innat sapience;</L>
<L>And, as I hope, her vertues folwen ye;</L>
<L>But vnto you compile I this sentence,</L>
<L N="2133">That, at the goode luste of your excellence,</L>
<L>In short ye may behold and rede</L>
<L N="2135">That in hem thre is skatered ferre in brede.
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="306" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(306)</HEAD>
<L N="2136">And &aacute;lthough it be no man&eacute;r of nede<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yow to counseil&euml; what to done or leve,</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;at you liste of stories to take hede,</L>
<L N="2139">Somwhat it may profit&euml;, by your leve:</L>
<L>At hardest, when<NOTE PLACE="foot">whan that R.</NOTE> &thorn;at ye ben in Chambre at eve,</L>
<L>They ben good&euml; to driv&euml; forth the nyght;</L>
<L>They shull not harme, yf &thorn;ey be herd a-right.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="307" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(307)</HEAD>
<L N="2143">To your hyeness&euml;, thynke it not to longe,</L>
<L>Though in that draught I somwhat wad&euml; deepe;</L>
<L>The thew&euml;s vertuous that to it longe</L>
<L>Wacchen my gost, &amp; letten him to slepe.</L>
<L N="2147">Now God in vertu mayntene you and kepe!</L>
<L>And I besech&euml; your magnificence,</L>
<L N="2149">Yeve vnto me benign&euml; audience.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="308" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(308)</HEAD>
<L N="2150">For though I to the steppes clergyall</L>
<L>Of this&euml; clerk&euml;s thre [may] not atteyne,</L>
<L>Yit, for to putte in prees my c&oacute;nceyte small</L>
<L>Goode wille me arteth take on me the peyne;</L>
<L N="2154">But sor&euml; in me quappeth euery veyne,</L>
<L>So dredefull am I of myne ignoraunce;</L>
<L N="2156">The crosse of criste me sped&euml; and auaunce!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="309" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(309)</HEAD>
<L N="2157">Now, gracious prince, agayn that the corone</L>
<L>Honoure you shall with roial dignitee,</L>
<L>Beseche I hym that sitte on hye in trone,</L>
<L>That, when &thorn;at charg&euml; r&eacute;ceyued han ye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This line ends the extract from MS. Reg. 17 D vi. With the next line, Harl. 4366 begins again, and runs on to the end.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2161">Swych gouernanc&euml; men may feele and se<MILESTONE N="38a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In yow, as may ben vn-to his plesance,</L>
<L N="2163">Profet to vs, and your good loos avance.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000145.tif" N="79">
<HEAD>[&sect; 1. ON THE DIGNITY OF A KING.]</HEAD>
<LG N="310" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(310)</HEAD>
<L N="2164">&para; ffirst and foreward, the dignitee of kyng</L>
<L>Impressid be in the botme of your mynde,</L>
<L>Consideryng how chargeable a thyng</L>
<L>That ofice is; for so ye schul it fynde.</L>
<L N="2168">Vn-to good reul&euml; ye yow knytte and bynde;</L>
<L>Of godd&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">goddes R, god H.</NOTE> wrech&euml; haue ay drede and awe;</L>
<L>Do right to grete and smale, and keep&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">y<SUP>e</SUP> overline, later H, kepe your R.</NOTE> lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="311" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(311)</HEAD>
<L N="2171">&para; On&euml;s &thorn;er was a kyng, as I haue rad,</L>
<L>Whan his coron&euml; was vn-to hym broght,</L>
<L>Or he it tok, in thoght he stood al sad,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he seid&euml;, after he had thoght:</L>
<L N="2175">"O &thorn;ou corone, noble and faire y-wroght,</L>
<L>What man that &thorn;e receyueth or admittith,</L>
<L N="2177">More es&euml; &thorn;an he weneth from hym flittith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="312" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(312)</HEAD>
<L N="2178">&para; Who-so &thorn;e peril know, and charge and fere</L>
<L>That is in the, thogh &thorn;ou at therthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">thoght &thorn;ou at hert H, though thou at the erthe R.</NOTE> lay,</L>
<L>He wold&euml; noght the vp areyse or rere,</L>
<L>But lat &thorn;e ly&euml; stille, and go his way.</L>
<L N="2182">ffor sooth is &thorn;is, and hath &amp; schal ben ay,</L>
<L>This world&euml;s hook, enuye hath to his bayt,</L>
<L N="2184">And ay hath hye degree sore in a-wayt."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="313" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(313)</HEAD>
<L N="2185">&para; Now, noble princ&euml;, thogh I be nat wys,</L>
<L>Wel-willed am I, as I first yow tolde;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e name of ihesu, wirke after &thorn;e auys</L>
<L>That I compyle oute of this auctours olde.</L>
<L N="2189">And if I nat the wey of reson holde,<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffolwe me nat; and if &thorn;at I do, thenne</L>
<L N="2191">Do as I schal report&euml; with my penne.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000146.tif" N="80">
<HEAD>[&sect; 2. ON A KING'S KEEPING HIS CORONATION OATHS; AND ON TRUTH AND CAUTIOUS SPEECH.]</HEAD>
<LG N="314" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(314)</HEAD>
<L N="2192">&para; Tho oth&euml;s that at your creac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Shul thurgh your tong&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Shuly . . tong H, Shall . . tonge R.</NOTE> passe, hem wel obserue;</L>
<L>Lat no col&oacute;ur&euml;d excusac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Yow mak&euml; fro hem slippe aside or swerue;</L>
<L N="2196">Holde vp hir lyf,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hede R.</NOTE> lat hem nat in yow sterue;</L>
<L>It is nat knyghtly<NOTE PLACE="foot">knygly H, knyghtly R.</NOTE> from an oth to varie;</L>
<L N="2198">A kyng of trouth, oweth bene exemplarie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="315" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(315)</HEAD>
<L N="2199">&para; Lo! thus this Aristotle in his book seith</L>
<L>To Alisandre, and to be war hym bit,</L>
<L>That he ne breke his bond&euml;s ne his feith,</L>
<L>ffor vn-to folke vntrew&euml; longith it;</L>
<L N="2203">He seith &thorn;at grac&euml; nat in hym abit,</L>
<L>But wikked ende and cursid &aacute;uenture</L>
<L>Hym folowith, that forswere<NOTE PLACE="foot">to forswere R.</NOTE> hym hath no cure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="316" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(316)</HEAD>
<L N="2206">&para; By<NOTE PLACE="foot">By the H R.</NOTE> feith, is maad the congregac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Of peple, and of cit&egrave;s enhabitynge;</L>
<L>By feith, han kyng&euml;s dominac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>ffeith causith eek of men &thorn;e comunynge;</L>
<L N="2210">Castelx, by feith, dreden non &aacute;ssailynge,</L>
<L>By feith, &thorn;e Citees standen vnwerr&eacute;yed,</L>
<L N="2212">And kyng&euml;s of hir soget&yogh; ben obeyed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="317" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(317)</HEAD>
<L N="2213">&para; Who leeseth feith, gretter thyng may non leese.</L>
<L>Or a man speke, or bynde hym by his sel,</L>
<L>And hath his ful lib&eacute;rte, and may cheese</L>
<L>What he do schal, hym oghte auyse hym wel</L>
<L N="2217">Or he promette; and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> heet&euml; naght a deel<MILESTONE N="39a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By word ne bond, but if he wole it laste;</L>
<L N="2219">ffor who so dooth, schal smerten at &thorn;e laste.
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="81"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="318" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(318)</HEAD>
<L N="2220">&para; Litel encheson ha&thorn; he for to speke,</L>
<L>To whos word&euml;s is<NOTE PLACE="foot">is R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> &yogh;euen no credence:</L>
<L>Perillous is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">is it R.</NOTE> a man his feith to breke.</L>
<L>ffeith, by necessite ne indigence</L>
<L N="2224">Naght artid is: disceyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">disceyue H, disceyte R.</NOTE> &amp; apparence</L>
<L>Of trouthe outward, and inward fikilnesse,</L>
<L>Bulteth<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bulteth R.</NOTE> out schame, and cause&thorn; gret smartnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="319" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(319)</HEAD>
<L N="2227">&para; What was &thorn;e cause of &thorn;e destrucc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e peple of Scites &amp; of Arabiee,</L>
<L>But for hir kyng&euml;s, in decepcioun</L>
<L>Of men and Citees nyh to hir contre,</L>
<L N="2231">Hir othis vseden, by sotilte</L>
<L>Brekyng&euml; bond&euml;s &thorn;at stablisshed were</L>
<L N="2233">Mankynde to profit&euml;, and not to dere?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="320" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(320)</HEAD>
<L N="2234">&para; And for &thorn;at synn&euml;, godd&euml;s ri&yogh;twisnesse,</L>
<L>That punnysshith falshood and trecherie,</L>
<L>Nat myghte hem suffre endure in &thorn;at woodnesse;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey destroyed were, it is no lye.</L>
<L N="2238">Vntrouthe, allas! &thorn;e ordre of chyualrie</L>
<L>Dampneth it; thogh &thorn;at &thorn;e persone it vse,</L>
<L N="2240">Knyghthode itself mot algate it refuse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="321" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(321)</HEAD>
<L N="2241">&para; To god truste I, no lord in al &thorn;is lond</L>
<L>Is gilty of &thorn;at inconuenience;</L>
<L>ffy! what? a lord breke his byheste or bond?</L>
<L>Nay, god forbed&euml; &thorn;at that<NOTE PLACE="foot">such R.</NOTE> pestilence</L>
<L N="2245">In a lord dwelle, or hold&euml; residence;<MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor if &thorn;at he that wicked geste recette,</L>
<L N="2247">By suche a lorde wole honour no thing sette.
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="82"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="322" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(322)</HEAD>
<L N="2248">&para; Whan Marcus Regulus was, as I rede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De fideli|tate Marci Reguli.</NOTE></L>
<L>Venqwissh&egrave;d in a bataile of &thorn;e see</L>
<L>By hem of Cartage, hoom wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ey lede</L>
<L>This prisoner; and aftir, sent was he</L>
<L N="2252">By hem to Rom&euml;, his own&euml; contre,</L>
<L>Sworn to retourn&euml; to Cartage ageyn,</L>
<L N="2254">As tullius And eek seint Austyn seyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="323" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(323)</HEAD>
<L N="2255">&para; The caus&euml; whi &thorn;ey hym to Rom&euml; sente,</L>
<L>Was for to do to Romayns hir message,</L>
<L>Wityng of hem, if &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolde R, worde H.</NOTE> Assente,</L>
<L>That, syn<NOTE PLACE="foot">sithin R.</NOTE> ther wer&euml; Romayns in cartage</L>
<L N="2259">In prisoun, and Romayns hadde eek in cage</L>
<L>Cartagiens, suffre hem at larg&euml; goo,</L>
<L N="2261">And &thorn;e Romayns go schulden<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde R, schuld H.</NOTE> [fre] also.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="324" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(324)</HEAD>
<L N="2262">&para; Whan Marcus doon hadde as &thorn;at he was bode,</L>
<L>The senat axid hym what was his reed;</L>
<L>And he answerde, and seid&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">seid H, seide R.</NOTE> &thorn;us for gode:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Al &thorn;is, rede I, lat slepen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">slippen R.</NOTE> &amp; ben deed;</L>
<L N="2266">It may by no way sinke in-to myn heed,</L>
<L>That to vs Romayns were it couenable,</L>
<L N="2268">Swiche an eschaung&euml;; but<NOTE PLACE="foot">is but R.</NOTE> vnprofitable.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="325" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(325)</HEAD>
<L N="2269">&para; "We Romayns &thorn;at &thorn;ey han in prison loke,</L>
<L>Ben but &yogh;onge froth, vnlern&euml;d in batayle,</L>
<L>And othir feble folk with age I-broke,</L>
<L>Of whiche I am on; we may nat availe;</L>
<L N="2273">Of vs no losse is; but with-outen faile,<MILESTONE N="40a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;oure prisoners<NOTE PLACE="foot">prisoners R, prioners H.</NOTE> ben myghty men and wyse,</L>
<L N="2275">And folk in arm&euml;s preeu&euml;d at deuyse."
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="83"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="326" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(326)</HEAD>
<L N="2276">&para; His freend&euml;s wolde han holde hym still&euml; there,</L>
<L>But thei nat myghte; he wolde alwey retourne;</L>
<L>To breke his oth, his goost was ay in fere;</L>
<L>He &thorn;oghte noght in his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> contre soiourne.</L>
<L>Do qwat hem list, whether thei glade or mourne,</L>
<L>Vnto his foos as bliu&euml; he hym dressith,</L>
<L>And knewe wel to be deed, the book witn&eacute;ssith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="327" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(327)</HEAD>
<L N="2283">&para; He held<NOTE PLACE="foot">heled H, helde R.</NOTE> it bette his oth for to obserue,</L>
<L>And dye in honur, as &thorn;at a knyght oghte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sholde . . wolde . . be olde R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than by peri&uacute;rie his lif for to preserue;</L>
<L>Of suche vnknyghtly trikk&euml;s he nat roghte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sholde . . wolde . . be olde R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2287">I trow&euml; now-a-day&euml;s, thogh men soghte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sholde . . wolde . . be olde R.</NOTE></L>
<L>His heir ful hard were in &thorn;is land to fynde;</L>
<L>Men list not so ferforth to trouthe hem bynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="328" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(328)</HEAD>
<L N="2290">&para; &YOGH;it nat only to preyse is this Marcus</L>
<L>ffor trouth&euml;, but eek, as it semeth me,</L>
<L>His renoun oght&euml; doubled ben, as &thorn;us&mdash;</L>
<L>Where as theschang&euml; myghte han maad hym fre,</L>
<L N="2294">Qwit of his foos<NOTE PLACE="foot">fees (<I>altered to</I> foos) of R.</NOTE> prisoun, gretter cheerte</L>
<L>He hadde of the profet vn&iacute;uersel</L>
<L N="2296">Than of hym self: his deeth it preued wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="329" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(329)</HEAD>
<L N="2297">&para; Among&euml;s all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle R, al H.</NOTE> &thorn;ing&euml;s in a knyght,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota de Alexandri iuramento.</NOTE></L>
<L>Trouthe is a &thorn;ing that he ne lakk&euml; may,</L>
<L>If his honur schal bere his heed vp right.</L>
<L>Valerie tellith how, wi&thorn; greet array,<NOTE PLACE="marg">(R) De iura|mento regis Alexandri observato.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2301">Kyng Alisandre and his oost, on a day,<MILESTONE N="42(40)b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Meeued of ire and mal&eacute;ncolye,</L>
<L N="2303">Vn-to a citee dressid hym in hye,
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="84"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="330" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(330)</HEAD>
<L N="2304">&para; Which&euml; &thorn;at clept and called was Lapsat,</L>
<L>Purp&oacute;synge<NOTE PLACE="foot">H R insert "him."</NOTE> bete it to &thorn;e erthe adoun;</L>
<L>And or &thorn;at this kyng fully cam ther-at,</L>
<L>Ther was a Philosophere in &thorn;e toun,&mdash;</L>
<L N="2308">A man of excellent discrec&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>That to this kyng somtyme had maister be,&mdash;</L>
<L N="2310">fful sore abasshed of him &amp; his meyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="331" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(331)</HEAD>
<L N="2311">&para; Out of &thorn;e toun he spedde hym on his weie,</L>
<L>As hastely as &thorn;at he coude or myghte,</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e kyng, of grace hym for to preie;</L>
<L>And &aacute;s swithe as &thorn;e kyng hadde of hym sighte,</L>
<L>He knewe him and his menynge; and on highte<NOTE PLACE="foot">Harl. MS. "zighte," hight R.</NOTE></L>
<L>He seide him &thorn;us: "by &thorn;e godd&euml;s I swere,</L>
<L N="2317">Al &thorn;i labour schal nat be worth a pere;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="332" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(332)</HEAD>
<L N="2318">&para; At &thorn;i prayer&euml; do wole I no &thorn;ing."</L>
<L>This Philosophre of his ooth took good hede,</L>
<L>And seide, "o worthy conquerour and kyng,</L>
<L>Than prey I &thorn;e, vnto the toun &thorn;&egrave; spede,</L>
<L N="2322">And it destroy&euml; bothe in lengthe &amp; brede;</L>
<L>Haue on it no pitee, but al doun caste;</L>
<L N="2324">This pray I &thorn;e, &thorn;at may<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at it R.</NOTE> be done as faste."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="333" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(333)</HEAD>
<L N="2325">&para; And whan &thorn;e kyng his prayere vnderstood,</L>
<L>Al his angir and his irrous<NOTE PLACE="foot">errenous R.</NOTE> talent</L>
<L>Refreyn&egrave;d he; he wold&euml; for no good</L>
<L>On &thorn;e toun veng&euml; him, as he had ment;</L>
<L N="2329">He rathir chees be disobedient<MILESTONE N="41a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To his venge&aacute;ble wil, and his oth kepe,</L>
<L N="2331">Than be forsworn of &thorn;at he swoor so depe.
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="85"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="334" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(334)</HEAD>
<L N="2332">&para; Or a kyng swere, it is ful necessarie</L>
<L>A-vise hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem H, hym R.</NOTE> wel; for whan &thorn;at it is past,</L>
<L>He may his oth in no wise contrarie,</L>
<L>If he of sham or repreef be agast.</L>
<L N="2336">A kyng ow&eacute;th of word be stid&euml;fast;</L>
<L>No thing byhet&euml;, but he it perfourme,</L>
<L N="2338">If he wole hym vnto his state conforme.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="335" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(335)</HEAD>
<L N="2339">&para; A greet clerk, whiche clept is Crisostomus,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Crisosto|mus super Matthaeum omelia 12. Nisi consue|tudo interdi|catur non possunt am|putari per|iuria. Ex iuramento enim periu|rium genera|tur; sicut enim qui habet in con|suetudine multum loqui neccesse est vt aliquando importune loquitur, sic, qui habet consuetudi|nem iurare in rebus ydoneis frequenter &amp; in rebus superfluis &amp; nolens con|suetudine trahente periurat. In Canone xxij. q. ij &para; Isti tres. luramentum tres habet condiciones, videlicet, ve|ritatem, iudi|cium &amp; iusti|ciam: verita|tem silicet, vt iurans sciat vel credat verum esse quod iurat; Iudicium, id <I>est</I>, discre|cionem vt discrete iuret, non precipi|tanter.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where he of the<NOTE PLACE="foot">the, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> matir of sweryng tretith,</L>
<L>Thyse arn the word&euml;s that he writ to vs:&mdash;</L>
<L>"What man &thorn;e custume of oth&euml;s nat letith,</L>
<L N="2343">In sweryng oft&euml;, what he seith forgetith;</L>
<L>Vsage of othes, of periurie is cause."</L>
<L N="2345">And more he seith eke in &thorn;e sam&euml; clause.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="336" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(336)</HEAD>
<L N="2346">&para; He seith, "periurie engendrid is of othis;<NOTE PLACE="foot">othis R, this H.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor right as he &thorn;at custumably</L>
<L>Clappith and ianglith, and to stint loth is,</L>
<L>Moot othir whil&euml; speke vnsittyngly,</L>
<L N="2350">Right so, vsage of swering, enemy</L>
<L>To trouthe is, and makith men hem forswere;"</L>
<L N="2352">fful necessarie is, othis to for-bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="337" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(337)</HEAD>
<L N="2353">&para; Swering ha&thorn; this&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">thise R, this H.</NOTE> thre condic&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>ffolwynge, as trouth&euml;, doom, and rightwisnesse.</L>
<L>Oth axi&thorn; trouthe, and no decepc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>But swere in his entent&euml; sothfastnesse.</L>
<L N="2357">Doom moot discreetly, left<NOTE PLACE="foot">left R, lest H.</NOTE> al hastynesse,<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Swere, and nat needles; and iustice also,</L>
<L N="2359">Leeffuly swere, and iustly euermo.
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="86"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="338" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(338)</HEAD>
<L N="2360">&para; Quintilian seith, &thorn;at vn-to hygh degre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Quintili|anus dicit, iurare nisi vbi neccesse est, grani viro,&mdash;id <I>est</I>, nobili &amp; fa|moso,&mdash;pa|rum conuenit; verbum enim satis simplex in Rege vel in principe firmior sit quam iura|mentum in mercatore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnsittynge is to swere in any wise,</L>
<L>B&uacute;t it be causid of necessite;</L>
<L>ffor, as he sei&thorn;, and othir clerkis wise,</L>
<L N="2364">A kyng or princes word oght&euml; suffise</L>
<L>Wel mor&euml; than, oghte a march&aacute;ntes oth,</L>
<L N="2366">And to go ther ageyn be mor&euml; loth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="339" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(339)</HEAD>
<L N="2367">&para; And syn a princes oth, or his promesse,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei nat holden ben, him dishonure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">An instance of Hoccleve's false ryme of -<I>oure -ure.</I> See p. 21 above, and 'Minor Poems,' I, p. xxxix.</NOTE></L>
<L>His lettre and seel, whiche more open witnesse</L>
<L>Beren than &thorn;ei, good is take hede and cure<NOTE PLACE="foot">An instance of Hoccleve's false ryme of -<I>oure -ure.</I> See p. 21 above, and 'Minor Poems,' I, p. xxxix.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2371">That &thorn;ei be kept; writing&euml; wil endure;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Litera scripta ma|net.</NOTE></L>
<L>What a man is, it prest is for to preue;</L>
<L N="2373">Outhir, honure it shal him, or repreue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="340" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(340)</HEAD>
<L N="2374">&para; Now if it happe, as it ha&thorn; happed ofte,</L>
<L>A kyng in ned&euml; borwe of his march&aacute;ntis,</L>
<L>Greet wisdom were it tret&euml; faire &amp; softe,</L>
<L>And holde hem tru&euml;ly her couenantis;</L>
<L N="2378">ffor trust it wel, whan hir cou&eacute;nant is</L>
<L>Nat to hem kept, as &thorn;at hir bonde requerith,</L>
<L>The kyng ha&thorn; schame, and eke it hem mys-cherith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="341" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(341)</HEAD>
<L N="2381">&para; Loth wolde hem ben eft-son&euml;s for to lene;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at is brent, men seyn, dredith &thorn;e fire.</L>
<L>Be his day kept, he rekke&thorn; nat a bene,</L>
<L>But elles, siker, "don is in &thorn;e myre."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cp. 'Chaucer' and 'Towneley Plays,' &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2385">Wi&thorn;-outen dowte, a Marchant&euml;s desir<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Is with good herte his kyng honour and plese,</L>
<L>And, to his myght, refresche &amp; doon him ese.
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="87"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="342" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(342)</HEAD>
<L N="2388">&para; In hem is &thorn;e substaunce of euery lone:</L>
<L>What folk cheuyce, as mochil as doon they?</L>
<L>Excellent Prince, I dem&euml; your persone,</L>
<L>To hem and to al othir, in good fay,</L>
<L N="2392">Wole hold&euml; &thorn;at ye heeten hem alway,</L>
<L>And so to do, god, &thorn;e auctour of trouthe,</L>
<L>Yow graunte! and elles certes were it routhe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="343" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(343)</HEAD>
<L N="2395">&para; If &thorn;at a poor&euml; man breke his byheste,</L>
<L>Or do ageyn his oth, or seel, or lettre,</L>
<L>Men hente him by &thorn;e heed, and him arreeste,</L>
<L>And to pris&oacute;n he gooth; he gette no bettre,</L>
<L N="2399">Til his mainpernour his arrest vnfettre;</L>
<L>And yit he moot &thorn;e cours of lawe abyde,</L>
<L N="2401">Or his mainpernour mot deffende his syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="344" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(344)</HEAD>
<L N="2402">&para; Among the poor&euml; peple thus it goth,</L>
<L>Thei, for vntrouthe, han smert &amp; open schame;</L>
<L>And if a lorde his bond breke, or his oth,</L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;e it is a foul spot in his name;</L>
<L N="2406">Thogh men dare not opynly him diffame,</L>
<L>Thei &thorn;inke, al be it &thorn;at &thorn;ei no thing speke;</L>
<L N="2408">In swich&euml; lord&euml;s is vntrouthe I-reke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="345" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(345)</HEAD>
<L N="2409">&para; And syn a kyng, by wey of his office,</L>
<L>To god I-likned is, as in manere,</L>
<L>And god is trouthe itself, &thorn;an may the vice</L>
<L>Of vntrouth&euml;, naght in a kyng appeere,</L>
<L N="2413">If his offic&euml; schal to god referre.<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iacobus iij. Si quis verbo non offendit, perfectus est vir.</NOTE></L>
<L>A besy tong&euml; bringeth in swiche wit,</L>
<L N="2415">He &thorn;at by word naght gilte&thorn;, is perfit.
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="88"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="346" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(346)</HEAD>
<L N="2416">&para; A! lord, what it is fair and honurable,</L>
<L>A kyng from mochil spech&euml; him refreyne;</L>
<L>It sitte him ben of wordes mesur&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>ffor mochil clap wole his estate desteyne.</L>
<L N="2420">If he his tong&euml; with mesur&euml;s reyne</L>
<L>Gouern&euml;, than his honur it conserueth;</L>
<L N="2422">And by &thorn;e reuers, di&euml;th<NOTE PLACE="foot">deyeth R, dith H.</NOTE> it and sterueth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="347" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(347)</HEAD>
<L N="2423">&para; Bet is, &thorn;e peples er&euml;s thriste and yerne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Aristoteles (de regis con|tinencia a multiloquio dicit R): Melius est quod aures hominum sint sitibundi ad Regis elo|quia, quam suis affatibus sacientur: quia saturatis auribus ani|ma eciam saturatur. Prouerbia|rum x. In multilo|quio non deerit pecca|tum. &para; Ecclesias|tici capitulo xix<SUP>o</SUP>. Qui odit loquaci|tatem, extin|git maliciam. Prouerbia|rum xiij. &para; Qui custo|dit os suum, custodit ani|mam, qui autem &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hir kyng or princes word&euml;s for to here,</L>
<L>Than &thorn;at his tong&euml; goo so faste &amp; yerne</L>
<L>That menn&euml;s er&euml;s dul of his mateere;</L>
<L N="2427">ffor dullynge hem, dulle&thorn; &thorn;e herte in fere</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at yeuen to him audience;</L>
<L N="2429">In mochil spech&euml; wanti&thorn; not offence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="348" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(348)</HEAD>
<L N="2430">&para; Who so &thorn;at hati&thorn; mochil clap or speche,</L>
<L>Qwenchi&thorn; malice; and he &thorn;at his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his R, &thorn;is H, with 'his' in corrector's hand in margin.</NOTE> mouth kepi&thorn;,</L>
<L>Keepith his soule, as &thorn;at &thorn;e book&euml;s teeche.</L>
<L>Vnbridlid word&euml;s oft&euml; man by-weepi&thorn;;</L>
<L N="2434">Prudenc&euml; waki&thorn; whan &thorn;e tong&euml; sleepi&thorn;,</L>
<L>And slepith oft&euml; whan &thorn;e tong&euml; waki&thorn;;</L>
<L>Moderat speche engendrith reste, and makith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="349" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(349)</HEAD>
<L N="2437">&para; All&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alle R, Al H.</NOTE> natur&euml;s of best&euml;s and briddes</L>
<L>And of serpent&euml;s ben ymakid<NOTE PLACE="foot">ymaked R, makid H.</NOTE> tame,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iacobi iij. Omnes nature bestiarum, volucrum &amp; serpentum domantur. [R] Item in eodem: Lin|gua maculat totum corpus nostrum, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>But tonge of man, as it wel knowe &amp; kid is,</L>
<L>Nat may be tamed; o, fy! man, for schame!</L>
<L N="2441"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Leaf 45 is out of the Harl. MS. 4866. It contained lines 2441-2492. They are supplied here from MS. Reg. 17 D, vi, leaf 47 back, leaf 48.</NOTE>Silence of tunge is wardein of good fame;</L>
<L>And after repreef fissheth, clappeth, fouleth;</L>
<L N="2443">The tunge of man, all the body defouleth.
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="89"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="350" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(350)</HEAD>
<L N="2444">And that [&thorn;at] oute of tunge of kyng procedeth,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. Reg. 17 D 6.]</NOTE></L>
<L>The peple specially beren awey.</L>
<L>Wherfore, vnto a kyng &thorn;e more it nedeth</L>
<L>Avise hym what he spek&euml; shall alwey,</L>
<L N="2448">In mochell spech&euml; som behest&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. behest.</NOTE> may</L>
<L>Lightly astert&euml;, that may not be holde;</L>
<L N="2450">And than [&thorn;e] trouth&euml; begynneth to colde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="351" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(351)</HEAD>
<L N="2451">O worthy princ&euml;, this, loo, meveth me</L>
<L>Of trouth&euml; for to touch&euml; thus sadly,</L>
<L>For that I wold&euml; that the hye degree</L>
<L>Of Chiualri&euml; vniuersally</L>
<L N="2455">Bare vp his hede, &amp; bent&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bent.</NOTE> not awry;</L>
<L>Of his honour, vntrouthe a knyght vnlaceth,</L>
<L N="2457">And his renoun all vttirly defaceth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="352" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(352 abb aa cc.)</HEAD>
<L N="2458">And failyng it, the chief flour of his stile</L>
<L>Fadeth &amp; falleth, &amp; begynneth dye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to dye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Honoure appropred is to chiualry[e].</L>
<L>But now passe ouer; touche I wole a while</L>
<L N="2462">Of rightwisnesse, which that out of this ile</L>
<L>Purp&oacute;seth fully for to fare &amp; wende,</L>
<L N="2464">So is our reule vnthrifty &amp; vnthende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 3. OF JUSTICE.]</HEAD>
<LG N="353" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(353)</HEAD>
<L N="2465">Seint Ancelme seith, Iustice is liberte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Ansel|mus libro Cur deus homo. Justicia est animi liber|tas, tribuens vnicuique quod suum est secundum propriam dignitatem, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of will, yeuyng vnto euery wight</L>
<L>Th&aacute;t longeth to his propre dignite;</L>
<L>To god, obedience, as it is right;</L>
<L N="2469">And he &thorn;at poor is of degree &amp; myght,</L>
<L>Vnto his better, honour &amp; reuerence;</L>
<L N="2471">The grete eke to the smale, lore &amp; science.
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="90"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="354" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(354)</HEAD>
<L N="2472">To thyne egall, concorde; vnto thy foo,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. Reg. 17 D 6.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Suffraunc&euml;; &amp; to thy self, holynesse;</L>
<L>To the nedy, greved with wrecched wo,</L>
<L>Mercy in dede, &amp; rew&euml; his distresse</L>
<L N="2476">After thy power, &amp; releve in heuynesse;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est: Sola be|neuolencia sufficit aman|ti, si facultas deest bene|ficiendi, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>And rewe vpon hym, yf that thy myght faile,</L>
<L N="2478">For &thorn;at will shall &thorn;y ded&euml; countervayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="355" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(355)</HEAD>
<L N="2479">Who-so it be that Iustic&euml; verray<NOTE PLACE="marg">Si quis es qui iusticiam veram sectari desideras, time prius deum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Desireth folowe, first mote he god drede,</L>
<L>And loue as hertly<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. also hertily.</NOTE> as he kan &amp; may.</L>
<L>It not suffiseth to do no noyous dede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Scriptum est: Non nocere, non est ius|ticia, sed mali abstinencia, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2483">But who annoy&euml; hym wold it forbede;</L>
<L>For none anoy&euml; is no righwisnesse,</L>
<L N="2485">But it is abstinence of wickkednesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="356" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(356)</HEAD>
<L N="2486">Of counceill &amp; of helpe we be dettoures<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. doctoures.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Scriptum est: Ipso iure fra|ternitatis &amp; societatis humane con|silii &amp; auxilii debitores su|mus. Hoc enim volu|mus vt &amp; ipsi nobis impen|dant consili|um, quo nos|tra erudiatur ignorancia, &amp; auxilium quo iuretur infirmitas nostra.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eche to other, by right of bretherhede;</L>
<L>For whan a man y-falle in-to errour is,</L>
<L>His brother ought hym counceille &amp; rede</L>
<L N="2490">To correcte &amp; amende his wikked dede;</L>
<L>And yf he be vexed with maladie,</L>
<L N="2492">Mynystre hym helpe, his greef to remedie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="357" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(357)</HEAD>
<L N="2493"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Harleian MS. 4866 begins again.</NOTE>&para; Euery man owi&thorn; studien<NOTE PLACE="foot">to studie R.</NOTE> and muse<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl.4866 folio" N="43a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Vnusquis que fratrem suum docere studeat, que oporteat vel non oporteat facere, prouo|cans eum ad meliora, &amp; consulens que recta sunt coram Deo; et hoc non verbo tan|tum, sed opere &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>To teche his brothir what &thorn;ing is to do,</L>
<L>And what be-hou&euml;ly is<NOTE PLACE="foot">byhoveth for.</NOTE> to refuse;</L>
<L>That &thorn;at is good, prouokyng him &thorn;erto;</L>
<L N="2497">And &thorn;us he mote conseille his brothir, lo!</L>
<L>"Do &thorn;at right is, and good, to godd&euml;s pay,</L>
<L N="2499">In word nat only, but in werk al-way."
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="91"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="358" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(358)</HEAD>
<L N="2500">&para; Law&euml;ful iustice is, as in manere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Egidius in ij parte primi libri, capitulo xi<SUP>o</SUP>. Legalis iusticia est quodam modo omnis virtus; habere enim huiusmodi iusticiam est implere legem &amp;c. [R.] Si igitur lex iubet omne bonum, prohibet omne malum, implere le|gem est per|fecte virtuo|sum, et iuusticia est integra et perfecta ma|licia &amp;c. &para; Aristoteles capitulo de forma et modo iusticie. 'Iusticia est de natura dei,' &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al vertu; and who wole han &thorn;is iustice,</L>
<L>The lawe of crist, to kep&euml; mot he leere.</L>
<L>Now if &thorn;at law&euml; f&oacute;rbeede euery vice,</L>
<L N="2504">And c&oacute;mande al good &thorn;ing, and it cherice,</L>
<L>ffulfill&euml; law&euml;, is<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is R.</NOTE> vertu perfyt,</L>
<L N="2506">And in-iustice is of al vertu qwyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="359" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(359)</HEAD>
<L N="2507">&para; Iustice is of the kynde and the nature</L>
<L>Of god; and he ha&thorn; made it, and ordeyned</L>
<L>On rem&euml;s and on euery cr&euml;ature.</L>
<L>By iustice, is schedyng of blood refreyned,</L>
<L N="2511">And gilt pun&yacute;sched, whan it is compleyned.</L>
<L>Iustic&euml; d&eacute;ffendeth possessions,</L>
<L N="2513">And peple kepe&thorn; from oppressions.<NOTE PLACE="foot">oppressions R, appressions H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="360" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(360)</HEAD>
<L N="2514">&para; A kyng is made to kepen and maynteene</L>
<L>Iustice, for she makith ob&eacute;isant</L>
<L>The mysdoers &thorn;at proud&euml; ben &amp; keene;</L>
<L>And hem &thorn;at ben in vertu h&aacute;bundant</L>
<L N="2518">Cherisith; a kyng is, by couenant</L>
<L>Of ooth maad in his coronacioun,</L>
<L N="2520">Bound&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And bounden R.</NOTE> to iustices sauuacioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="361" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(361)</HEAD>
<L N="2521">&para; And a kyng, in fulfillinge of &thorn;at, is<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To god lik, whiche is verray rightwisnesse;</L>
<L>And men of ynd&euml; seyn and holden &thorn;is&mdash;</L>
<L>'A kyng&euml;s iustice is a greet richesse</L>
<L N="2525">Vnto his peple, as plentee or largesse</L>
<L>Of erthly good, and bettre &thorn;an reyn</L>
<L N="2527">ffallynge at eue from heuen,' &thorn;ei seyn.
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="92"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="362" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(362)</HEAD>
<L N="2528">&para; fful often sith&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sothe R.</NOTE> it is wist and seen,</L>
<L>That for &thorn;e wrong and &thorn;e vnryghtwisnesse</L>
<L>Of kyng&euml;s mynistres, &thorn;at kyng&euml;s bene</L>
<L>Holden gilty, where-as in soothfastnesse</L>
<L N="2532">Thei knowen no &thorn;ing of &thorn;e wikkednesse;</L>
<L>Vniust myn&iacute;stres ofte hir kyng accusen,</L>
<L>And thei &thorn;at iust ben, &oacute;f wrong hem excusen.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="363" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(363)</HEAD>
<L N="2535">&para; If &thorn;e ministres do naght but iustice</L>
<L>To poor&euml; peple, in contre as &thorn;ei go,</L>
<L>Thogh &thorn;e kyng be vniust, yit is his vice</L>
<L>Hid to &thorn;e peple; thei wene eueremo</L>
<L N="2539">The kyng be iust, for his men gye hem so.</L>
<L>But ministres to seelde hem wel gouerne;</L>
<L N="2541">Oppress&iuml;oun regneth in euery herne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="364" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(364)</HEAD>
<L N="2542">&para; A kyng, me thinke&thorn;, for &thorn;e seuerte</L>
<L>Of his good loos, by-houe&thorn; it enquere</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at han his &eacute;state in cheerte,</L>
<L>What fam&euml; &thorn;at his poore peple him bere;</L>
<L N="2546">He of iustice is bounden hem to were</L>
<L>And to diffende; and if &thorn;at &thorn;ei be greued,</L>
<L N="2548">By him thei mot be holpen and releued.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="365" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(365)</HEAD>
<L N="2549">&para; Excus&euml; schal hym naght his ignorance;<MILESTONE N="44a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He mot enquere of wrong, and it redresse;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at he peple ha&thorn; in gouernance,</L>
<L>He clept is kyng: if his men peple oppresse,</L>
<L N="2553">Witynge hym, and noght rekke of the duresse,</L>
<L>He may, be ryght, be clept no gouernour,</L>
<L N="2555">But of his peple a wilful d&eacute;stroyour.
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="93"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="366" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(366)</HEAD>
<L N="2556">&para; O worthi king! benyngne Edward &thorn;e laste!</L>
<L>Thow haddist ofte in herte a drede impressid,</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at &thorn;yn humble goost ful sore a-gaste;</L>
<L>And to know if &thorn;ou cursed were or blessid,</L>
<L N="2560">A-mong &thorn;e peple ofte hastow &thorn;e dressed</L>
<L>In-to contre, in symple array allone,</L>
<L N="2562">To her&euml; what men seide of &thorn;i persone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See, among others, "A Tale of King Edward and the Shepherd," in <I>Hartshorne's Metrical Tales</I> (from T. Wright).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="367" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(367)</HEAD>
<L N="2563">&para; Al-thogh a kyng haue h&aacute;bundance of myght<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sapientie. v<SUP>o</SUP> [<I>i.e.</I> cap. 6]. Quia non recte iudicas|tis [R. neque custodistis legem iusticie &amp;c.].</NOTE></L>
<L>In his land, at his lust knytte &amp; vnknytte,</L>
<L>Good is &thorn;at he his power vse ari&yogh;t,</L>
<L>That fro the wey of iustice he ne flitte,</L>
<L N="2567">Leste oure lord god hym from his grac&euml; schitte,</L>
<L>Of whom al rightwis power is deryued;</L>
<L N="2569">ffor if he doo, of blisse he schal be pryued.<NOTE PLACE="foot">pryved R, preyued H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="368" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(368)</HEAD>
<L N="2570">&para; I fynde how &thorn;at The&oacute;dorus sireene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Surcene R. (See Smith's <I>Dict. Greek and Roman Biography.</I> Theodorus 32. Cyrenaicus.)</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Refert va|lerius maxi|mus qualiter Theodorus sirenus cruci|figebatur quia regem de lisemaco arguebat pro suis defecti|bus &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at he to &thorn;e kyng of Lys&euml;mak</L>
<L>Tolde his defaut&euml;s, &thorn;e kyng leet for teene</L>
<L>Crucifie him; and as he heng &amp; stak</L>
<L N="2574">Vppon &thorn;e croys, &thorn;us to &thorn;e kyng he spak:</L>
<L>"This peyne, or othir like &thorn;er-to, moot falle</L>
<L N="2576">Vppon &thorn;i fals&euml; counsaillour&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">Counsaillours, H, counceilours R.</NOTE> alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="369" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(369)</HEAD>
<L N="2577">&para; "Nought rekke I thogh I rote an hy or lowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lowe R, lawe H.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As he &thorn;at of &thorn;e deth hath no gastnesse;</L>
<L>I dye an innocent, y do the knowe;</L>
<L>I dy&euml; to defend&euml; rightwisnesse.</L>
<L N="2581">Thy flatereres, en-haunced in richesse,</L>
<L>Dreden to suffre for ri&yogh;t suche a peyne,</L>
<L N="2583">But I thereby nat sett&euml; ressh&euml;s tweyne."
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="94"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="370" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(370)</HEAD>
<L N="2584">&para; Ther was a duke Romayn, clept C&aacute;milus,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota bene de generosi|tate &amp; iusticia ducis Camili, &amp; de falsitate cuiusdam Magistri qui pueros habe|bat informan|dum &amp; doctri|nandum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Leyde on&euml;s seeg&euml; vn-to a citee,</L>
<L>ffalisk<NOTE PLACE="foot">Falex R.</NOTE> nam&egrave;d, as sei&thorn; valerius,</L>
<L>Of whiche the men of moost auctorite,</L>
<L N="2588">And grettest of power and of degre,</L>
<L>To a Maister in &thorn;e citee dwellinge,</L>
<L N="2590">Bytook hir children, by wey of lernynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="371" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(371)</HEAD>
<L N="2591">&para; What doth me this maister, but on a day</L>
<L>Somme of tho children out of &thorn;e toun&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">towne R, toun H.</NOTE> ledde,</L>
<L>The most expert in science, and &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Streight to &thorn;e Romayn tent&euml;s he hym spedde;</L>
<L N="2595">And &thorn;e duke &thorn;us counsailled he, and redde:</L>
<L>"Haueth this children in possess&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="2597">And kepith hem in holde and in prisoun;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="372" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(372)</HEAD>
<L N="2598">&para; "The fadres of hem han in gouernaunce</L>
<L>ffalisk<NOTE PLACE="foot">Falex R.</NOTE> &thorn;e citee, at hir own&euml; list;</L>
<L>In hy and low, aftir hir ordenance</L>
<L>Is al &thorn;ing doon: Whan it is to hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, hym H.</NOTE> wist,</L>
<L N="2602">That &yogh;e hir children han vndir your fist,</L>
<L>Ye schul wel seen, hir children lyf to saue,</L>
<L N="2604">Hem and &thorn;e citee schul ye wynne &amp; haue."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="373" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(373)</HEAD>
<L N="2605">&para; The duke answerde anon to &thorn;is traytour:<MILESTONE N="45a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Thogh &thorn;ou be fals vn-to &thorn;yn own&euml; toun,</L>
<L>And rekkest nat of shame or d&eacute;shonour,</L>
<L>But per cas for to gete of me guerdoun</L>
<L N="2609">Desirest ffalisk&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">Falexes R.</NOTE> d&eacute;strucc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Nat were it knyghtly, me to &thorn;&egrave; consente,</L>
<L N="2611">That taken hast so traytourous entente.
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="95"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="374" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(374)</HEAD>
<L N="2612">&para; "We Romayns kepen ri&yogh;t&euml;s of bataile</L>
<L>As trew&euml;ly as &thorn;e right&euml;s of pees;</L>
<L>Our custume is, no children to assayle;</L>
<L>Thogh we &thorn;e toun hadde wonn&euml;, dout&euml;lees</L>
<L N="2616">Ther schulde no childe among&euml;s al<NOTE PLACE="foot">amonge all R, among as H.</NOTE> &thorn;e prees</L>
<L>ffor vs han greued be; we arm&euml;s bere</L>
<L N="2618">A-geyn the arm&euml;d men, hem for to dere,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="375" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(375)</HEAD>
<L N="2619">&para; "And naght a-geyn children vnd&eacute;fensable.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at in &thorn;e is, &thorn;i myght hastow do,</L>
<L>Thorgh wicked tresoun, false and d&eacute;ceyuable,</L>
<L>Thi citee to destroyen and for-doo;</L>
<L N="2623">But I, Romayn, agree me nat &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>By vertu of arm&eacute;s wole I it wynne,</L>
<L N="2625">ffor al &thorn;e myght of men &thorn;at ben &thorn;erinne."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="376" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(376)</HEAD>
<L N="2626">&para; The duke comaundeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaunded R.</NOTE> schortly for to seyn,</L>
<L>His hand&euml;s hym be-hind&euml; to be bounde,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;e children lede hym hoom a-geyn</L>
<L>To hir fadres; whiche, whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey han founde</L>
<L N="2630">So greet iustic&euml; in &thorn;is duke habounde,</L>
<L>The senat clept, and &thorn;is vnto hem tolde;</L>
<L N="2632">The hert&euml;s gan to change, of yonge &amp; olde;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="377" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(377)</HEAD>
<L N="2633">&para; All &thorn;ey seiden, of hy&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hye R, hy H.</NOTE> gentillesse,<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Groundid vppon iustice, did he &thorn;is,</L>
<L>And also of a chiualrous prowesse;</L>
<L>Thei seiden, "it to vs most sitting is</L>
<L N="2637">Oure &yogh;at&euml;s opne, &amp; offre vs to ben his;</L>
<L>Is non so good, as lat vs mollifie</L>
<L N="2639">Our hert&euml;s stout&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stout H, and stonde R.</NOTE> to his genterie,
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="96"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="378" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(378)</HEAD>
<L N="2640">&para; "And of his pees, requiren hym &amp; preye."</L>
<L>They diden so; but what was foluynge,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t haue I red, wher-fore I can nat seie;</L>
<L>But &thorn;is Iust duke, as by my s&uacute;pposynge,</L>
<L N="2644">Was to hem swiche, in wil &amp; in workynge,</L>
<L>That<NOTE PLACE="foot">That R, What H.</NOTE> he hem quitt&euml; so as my&yogh;te hem queme:</L>
<L>What schulde I elles of suche a lord&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lorde R, lord H.</NOTE> deme?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="379" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(379)</HEAD>
<L N="2647">&para; Of Lancastre good duke henri also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Henry, the first of the Plantagenet <I>dukes</I> of Lancaster, and father-in-law of John of Gaunt, one of the greatest men of the reign of Edward III.&mdash;T. Wright.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] De nobili Henrico quondam Lancastrie duce.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whos Iustice is writ&eacute;n and auctorised,</L>
<L>Whi schulde I nat &thorn;&egrave; rekene a-mong&euml;s &thorn;o</L>
<L>That in hir tyme han Iustice excercised?</L>
<L N="2651">&YOGH;it &thorn;at vertu only nat ha&thorn; suffised</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, but al &thorn;at longith to kny&yogh;thode</L>
<L N="2653">Was inned in &thorn;yn excellent manhode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="380" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(380)</HEAD>
<L N="2654">&para; I rede also how &thorn;at&mdash;hangynge a strif</L>
<L>Betwixt kyng Porrus and a lord clept ffabrice&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota de fidelitate cuiusdam domini vocati ffabricius, &amp; de falsitate cuiusdam medici.</NOTE></L>
<L>The leche of &thorn;ys kyng, a curs&euml;d caitif</L>
<L>Inuolued and y-wrapp&euml;d<NOTE PLACE="foot">ywrapped R, wrapped H.</NOTE> in &thorn;e vice</L>
<L N="2658">Of couetis&euml;, schoop hym for to trice</L>
<L>His own&euml; lord &thorn;e kyng, &amp; hym to kille,</L>
<L N="2660">If &thorn;at it hadd&euml; ben fabric&euml;s wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="381" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(381)</HEAD>
<L N="2661">&para; This leche vn-to fabrices house by nyght,<MILESTONE N="46a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As priuely as &thorn;at he coud&euml;, went,</L>
<L>And vnto him ensuryd &amp; be-hyght,</L>
<L>If him list to &thorn;e ded&euml; [then] consent,&mdash;</L>
<L N="2665">He was so glad to plese him &amp; content,<NOTE PLACE="foot">content R, concent H.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>His lorde &thorn;e kyng with venym wolde he fede,</L>
<L N="2667">So &thorn;at ther-&thorn;urgh he steruen shuld&euml; nede.
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="97"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="382" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(382)</HEAD>
<L N="2668">&para; This lorde, with &thorn;at, bad men his hand&euml;s teye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">teye R, cey H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lede vnto &thorn;e kyng &thorn;is traytrous<NOTE PLACE="foot">lede . . this traiterous R, led . . &thorn;eis traytours H.</NOTE> wight,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is treson vnto him be-wreye.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;is was done, &thorn;e Kyng seyde anone right,</L>
<L N="2672">"Se here a trowth and manhode of a knyght!</L>
<L>Men may the sonne as lightly his curse<NOTE PLACE="foot">cours R.</NOTE> reue,</L>
<L N="2674">As &thorn;is fabrices make his trowth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">trouthe R, trouth H.</NOTE> leue."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="383" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(383)</HEAD>
<L N="2675">&para; In Perse on&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">ones R, one H.</NOTE> &thorn;er was, by Iug&euml;ment<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota de iusticia cuiusdam Regis, qui quendam iudicem ex|coriari fecit, quia falsum reddidit iudicium [R. versus quen|dam, causa odij.]</NOTE></L>
<L>A man to de&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">dethe R, de&thorn; H.</NOTE> dampnyd in wrong wyse,</L>
<L>ffor wrath and hate, &amp; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">and R.</NOTE> irous talent</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;is ilk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ilke R, ilk H.</NOTE> man bare the Iustice;</L>
<L N="2679">And whan &thorn;e knoulech of &thorn;is false iowyse<NOTE PLACE="foot">iewyse R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was comyn vnto &thorn;e kyng&euml;s audience,</L>
<L N="2681">&THORN;is dome he &yogh;afe as blyue, and &thorn;is sentence:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="384" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(384)</HEAD>
<L N="2682">&para; He bad men fla<NOTE PLACE="foot">flee R.</NOTE> hym quyk out of his skynne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-with keuyr &thorn;e iudicial see,</L>
<L>And made his son&euml; to be set &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L>That iuge aftir his fadir shold&euml; be,</L>
<L N="2686">To &thorn;is ende and entenc&iuml;oun, &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Shuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Shulde R, shuld H.</NOTE> be ware how<NOTE PLACE="foot">how R, whow H. "Whow" occurs also in the (?Midland) quaint "Jacob's Well," <I>Fons Jacobi</I>, Salisbury Cathedral MS. 103, which explains Prof. Skeat's name. See <I>The Academy</I>, Aug. 27, 1892. (The MS. is now at press for the E. E. T. Soc.)</NOTE> he his dom&euml;s &yogh;afe,</L>
<L N="2688">And lene alwey to right-wyseness&euml; staffe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af rightwisnesses staf R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="385" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(385)</HEAD>
<L N="2689">&para; Naght ought a iug&euml;, for hatrede<NOTE PLACE="foot">hate H R.</NOTE> or loue<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Othir wey dem&euml; &thorn;en trouth<NOTE PLACE="foot">than trouthe R.</NOTE> requirith,</L>
<L>But, at &thorn;e reuerence of god aboue,</L>
<L>Right ay fauo&uacute;r, whan &thorn;at it apperith.</L>
<L N="2693">Dede of iustice a<NOTE PLACE="foot">ay R.</NOTE> conci&euml;nc&euml; clerith,</L>
<L>Chasyng a-way thought&euml;s on wrong I-groundid;</L>
<L>Who iuggith wrongfully, is feendly woundid.
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="98"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="386" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(386)</HEAD>
<L N="2696">&para; What Iuge in dome eke &yogh;euyth<NOTE PLACE="foot">yeveth R, &yogh;euyt H.</NOTE> iust sentence,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius. Qui recte iu|dicat, &amp; pre|mium remu|neracionis ex|pectat, frau|dem in deo perpetrat, quia iustici|am quam gratis partiri debuit, accep|tacio peccunie vendit.</NOTE></L>
<L>A-wayting vp-on a golden dragee,<NOTE PLACE="foot">draggee R.</NOTE></L>
<L>To god he doth displesaunce &amp; offence;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e iustic&euml; wich of du&euml;tee<NOTE PLACE="foot">duetee R, dutee H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2700">He shuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde R, shuld H.</NOTE> do, cursidly sellith he,</L>
<L>ffor loue of mede him prouoki&thorn; &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="2702">And ri&yogh;twysness&euml; no &thorn;ing so to do.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="387" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(387)</HEAD>
<L N="2703">&para; To swich a iug&euml; withdraw&euml; &thorn;e hope<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eodem capit|ulo: cui si spes peccunie subtrahatur, confestim a iusticia re|cedit. &para; Ysaye 33<SUP>o</SUP>. Qui excutit manus suas ab omni mu|nere, iste in excelsis habi|tabit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of money, and he fro iustic&euml; flytty&thorn;;</L>
<L>Wher he supposith mony [for] to grope,</L>
<L>Iust iug&euml;ment he in his hert admittith;</L>
<L N="2707">But who so &thorn;at his hand fro &yogh;iftys shittith,&mdash;</L>
<L>As vnto vs wyttenessith ysaye,&mdash;</L>
<L N="2709">He shal in heuen dwelle, &amp; sitten hye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="388" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(388)</HEAD>
<L N="2710">&para; Cristen men, &yogh;elde oughten iust iug&euml;ment<NOTE PLACE="marg">xj. q. iij. non licet &amp; xiiij. q. v. Sane, Iustum qui|dem iudicium gratis reddere debent Chris|tiani, quia non licet ven|dere iustum iudicium, quamiuis viro perito liceat vendere con|silium, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffrely, for vnleful is it to selle;</L>
<L>Thogh it be leful and conuenient,</L>
<L>A wyse man for rewarde his reed to telle.</L>
<L N="2714">A iuges purs, with gold&euml; noght shulde swelle;</L>
<L>If one iustice he shape his dome to bilde,</L>
<L N="2716">His iug&euml;ment&euml;s he &yogh;iftl&eacute;s must &yogh;ilde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="389" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(389)</HEAD>
<L N="2717">&para; And he &thorn;at doth of iustic&euml; rigoure,<MILESTONE N="47a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est: Qui ri|gorem iusticie excercere in|tendit, caueat ne puniendo delectet, vel iniurias suas vlcisci glori|entur; caueat eciam ne mo|dum excedat aut quantita|tem delicti.</NOTE></L>
<L>Let hym be ware he hau&euml; no delyte</L>
<L>In [&thorn;e] pun&yacute;sshyng of &thorn;e &oacute;ffendoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; I-do &thorn;e trespase, or the wyte;</L>
<L N="2721">Ner him reioyse of his anoyance plyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Never . . . noiaunce lite R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e maner excede in swich&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">suche R, swich H.</NOTE> case,</L>
<L N="2723">Or quantite of &thorn;e gilt, or &thorn;e trespace.
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="99"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="390" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(390)</HEAD>
<L N="2724">&para; Euen as a soule is bodies lyflynesse,</L>
<L>And when &thorn;at it<NOTE PLACE="foot">it, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> is twyn&euml;d from a wight<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Egidius in ij<SUP>da</SUP> parte primi libri capitulo xj<SUP>o</SUP>. Sicut anima est corporis vita, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>The hert is dede, so farith right-wisenesse;</L>
<L>ffor whan a reme is reulid by hir myght,</L>
<L N="2728">&THORN;en may the peple be ful gladde &amp; lyght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e londe may bathen in prosperite;</L>
<L N="2730">And lost is al, if &thorn;at absent be she.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="391" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(391)</HEAD>
<L N="2731">&para; Ther was a lawe I-made vppon a tyme<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota bene! qualiter satis|iactum erat legi per quondam consulem Romanum.</NOTE></L>
<L>At rom&euml;, by the consoul&euml;s assent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at who so wer&euml; gilty of &thorn;e cryme</L>
<L>Of &aacute;duoutri&euml;, and were &thorn;er-in hent.</L>
<L N="2735">His eyen both&euml; shulden<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe shuld R, both shuld H.</NOTE> out be brent.</L>
<L>Now fel it so, a man &thorn;at son&euml; was</L>
<L N="2737">To a conseil, was take in &thorn;is trespas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="392" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(392)</HEAD>
<L N="2738">&para; And whan &thorn;at &thorn;e myshappe of &thorn;is persone</L>
<L>Was to &thorn;e peple know&euml;n of &thorn;e toune,</L>
<L>Thei loueden his fadir so, echon,</L>
<L>And had him in so chere<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete R.</NOTE> affeccioun,</L>
<L N="2742">&THORN;ei seyden &thorn;at non execucioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">execucioun R, excusacioun H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shuld on &thorn;is son&euml; for this ded&euml; falle,</L>
<L N="2744">And &thorn;e consul&euml;s so &thorn;ei preyden alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="393" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(393)</HEAD>
<L N="2745">&para; To<NOTE PLACE="foot">To R, Tho H.</NOTE> which &thorn;e fadir gan repli&euml; &thorn;o,<MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us alleg&euml;d he for him, &amp; seyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyde R, leyde H.</NOTE>:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Considereth, sires, I am oon of &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;is lawe consentid and obeide;</L>
<L N="2749">And shulde I now &thorn;e sam&euml; breke," he seyde,</L>
<L>"ffor fauour of myself or any of myne?</L>
<L N="2751">Nay, sirr&euml;s, to &thorn;at may I not enclyne.
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="100"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="394" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(394)</HEAD>
<L N="2752">&para; "Maffeith<NOTE PLACE="foot">Parde R.</NOTE>! &thorn;at wer&euml; wrong and villonye!</L>
<L>&THORN;e lawe shal forth&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">forthe R, forth H.</NOTE> thogh it fille on me."</L>
<L>&THORN;e peple gan to rumble, &amp; clappe &amp; crye,</L>
<L>And the consul&euml;s preyed of &thorn;e Citee</L>
<L N="2756">The reuers; and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> thus ouercome was he;</L>
<L>So at the last he sye non othir wey,</L>
<L N="2758">But in party he must hir lust obeye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="395" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(395)</HEAD>
<L N="2759">&para; "Now," quod he, "sithen<NOTE PLACE="foot">sithen R, sen H.</NOTE> it may be no bet,</L>
<L>Sum what to yow, me conform&euml; wol I,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e law&euml; shal al noght be let,</L>
<L>Thogh &thorn;at it myght obseru&euml;d be fully:</L>
<L N="2763">Thus wol I, and none othir tru&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="foot">truly H R.</NOTE>:</L>
<L>Oon of myne eyen wol I now for-go;</L>
<L N="2765">Mi sone ano&thorn;ir; it shal be ri&yogh;t so.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="396" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(396)</HEAD>
<L N="2766">&para; "We two wol hau&euml; but o mann&euml;s sight."</L>
<L>Thus was done<NOTE PLACE="foot">it done R.</NOTE>; but naght al at the plesaunce</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e peple; but &thorn;ei none othir myght.</L>
<L>Now if to-morowe fil &thorn;er swich a chaunce,</L>
<L N="2770">Shulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Shulde R, Shul H.</NOTE> men fynd&euml; so iust gouernaunce?</L>
<L>Nay, nay! &thorn;is londe is al to scarce &amp; lyte,</L>
<L N="2772">To fynde oon &thorn;at so iustly wolde hym quyte.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 4. ON OBSERVING OF THE LAWS.]</HEAD>
<LG N="397" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(397)</HEAD>
<L N="2773">&para; Prince excellent, hau&euml; your law&euml;s chere;<MILESTONE N="48a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De legum obseruacione.</NOTE></L>
<L>Obserue hem, and offende hem by no wey!</L>
<L>Bi oth to kepe it, bounde is &thorn;e powere</L>
<L>Of kyng; and by it is kyng&euml;s nobley</L>
<L N="2777">Susten&euml;d; lawe is both&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe R, both H.</NOTE> lokke and key</L>
<L>Of su&euml;rt&euml;; whil law is kept in londe,</L>
<L N="2779">A prince in his estate may sikir stonde.
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="101"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="398" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(398)</HEAD>
<L N="2780">&para; And dout&euml;lesse, if &thorn;at fordone be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be R, by H.</NOTE> lawe,</L>
<L>A princes power may goo pley him &thorn;enne;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei &thorn;at nought ne haue, with knyfe I-drawe,</L>
<L>Wol on hem &thorn;at of good be myghty, renne,</L>
<L N="2784">And hurt hem, and hir houses fire &amp; brenne,</L>
<L>And robbe and slee, and do al swich folye,</L>
<L N="2786">Whan &thorn;er no lawe is, hem to iustifie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="399" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(399)</HEAD>
<L N="2787">&para; Now in gode feith, I pray god it amende,</L>
<L>Lawe is nye flem&euml;d out of &thorn;is cuntre,</L>
<L>ffor few&euml; be &thorn;at dreden it offende.</L>
<L>Correcc&iuml;oun and al is long on the:</L>
<L N="2791">Whi soffrest &thorn;ou so many an &aacute;ssemble</L>
<L>Of arm&euml;d folk? wel ny in euery shire,</L>
<L N="2793">Partye is made to venge her cruel ire;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="400" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(400)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thei, with her hande wrong, to hem done redresse;</L>
<L>Hem deyneth naght an accioun attame</L>
<L>At comun law&euml;: swich vnbuxumnesse</L>
<L>Suffr&eacute;d, vs mak&euml; wol of seuerte lame.</L>
<L N="2798">Who-so may &thorn;is correct, is worthi blame</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne doth naght. alasse! &thorn;is suffraunce</L>
<L N="2800">Wol vs destroy&euml; by continuance.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="401" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(401)</HEAD>
<L N="2801">&para; Is ther no law&euml; &thorn;is to remedie?<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I can no mor&euml;; but, and this forth growe,</L>
<L>This londe shal it repent and sore abye;</L>
<L>And al such mayntenance, as men wel knowe,</L>
<L N="2805">Susten&euml;d is naght by person&euml;s lowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lowe R, lawe H.</NOTE></L>
<L>But Cobbes<NOTE PLACE="foot">cobbes R, great men, lords. Compare 'wattes,' l. 2816, p. 102.</NOTE> gret&euml; &thorn;is ryot sustene;</L>
<L N="2807">Correct it, gode is, whil &thorn;at it is grene.
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="102"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="402" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(402)</HEAD>
<L N="2808">&para; ffor, and it hor&euml;, &thorn;is lande is but lost;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at our heede is, sore it shal repent;</L>
<L>And this tamend, axith no gretter cost</L>
<L>But to do lawe in no venge&aacute;ble entent,</L>
<L N="2812">Seye I; but for &thorn;e better, hem take and hent,</L>
<L>And punysshe hem by lawful ri&yogh;twysenesse,</L>
<L N="2814">And suffre naght ich othir &thorn;us to oppresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="403" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(403)</HEAD>
<L N="2815">&para; Smal tendirnesse is had now of our lawes;</L>
<L>ffor if so be &thorn;at oon of &thorn;e grete wattes</L>
<L>A dede do, which &thorn;at a-geyn &thorn;e lawe is,</L>
<L>No thyng at al he punysshid for &thorn;at is;</L>
<L N="2819">Ri&yogh;t as lop-webbys, fly&euml;s smale &amp; gnattes<NOTE PLACE="foot">R has in margin, in another hand: "Unde Solon, unus de vij sapientibus. Lex est aran&iacute;e tela, quia si incideret quid deb&iacute;le, retinetur; grave autem pertransit, tela cissa.:"</NOTE></L>
<L>Taken, and suffre gret&euml; fly&euml;s go,</L>
<L N="2821">ffor al &thorn;is worlde, lawe is now rewlyd so.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="404" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(404)</HEAD>
<L N="2822">&para; The riche and myghty man, thogh he trespace,</L>
<L>No man seith on&euml;s &thorn;at blak is his eye;</L>
<L>But to &thorn;e pore, is denyed al grace;</L>
<L>He snybbyd is, and put to tormentrie;</L>
<L N="2826">He naght a-stirt&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">asterte R, astirt H.</NOTE> may, he shal a-bye;</L>
<L>He caught is in the webbe, &amp; may naght twynne;</L>
<L>Mochil gode reule is sowe, &amp; spryngith thynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="405" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(405)</HEAD>
<L N="2829">&para; Of &thorn;is groweth strif&euml;, bataille, and discorde,<MILESTONE N="49a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And by &thorn;e gret&euml;, po&euml;r folk ben greuyd;</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at noble is of blode, and a lorde<NOTE PLACE="foot">lord R, a lorde H.</NOTE></L>
<L>In stile, and naght hath, sterid is, and meved</L>
<L N="2833">Vnto rapyn&euml;; &thorn;is is often preuyd;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore it felith. &thorn;us of law&euml; lak,<NOTE PLACE="foot">the lak R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2835">Norysshith wrong, and castith ri&yogh;t a-bak.
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="103"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="406" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(406)</HEAD>
<L N="2836">&para; When a kyng do&thorn; his peyne and diligence,</L>
<L>His reme by law&euml; and reson to gye,</L>
<L>He stondith mor&euml; in beneualence</L>
<L>Of god, and more his werk shal fructifie,</L>
<L N="2840">And shal haue gretter mede, it is no lye,</L>
<L>Than &thorn;ei &thorn;at swich a cure haue none on honde;</L>
<L N="2842">Thus fynde I wretyn, as I vndirstonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="407" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(407)</HEAD>
<L N="2843">&para; Who-so &thorn;at in hye dignite is sette,</L>
<L>And may do greuous wrong &amp; cruelte,</L>
<L>If he for-bere hem, to commend is bette,</L>
<L>And gretter shal his mede and meryte be,</L>
<L N="2847">&THORN;en &thorn;ei &thorn;at naght may kithe iniquite,</L>
<L>Ne naght may done; for were sum man<NOTE PLACE="foot">for if sum man were H, for yf sum man were H.</NOTE> of myght,</L>
<L N="2849">Often wolde he do, gr&eacute;t harme and vnryght.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="408" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(408)</HEAD>
<L N="2850">&para; Hye dignite, the philosofre write&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Princi|patus virum ostendit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Preueth a man, what he is in his dede.</L>
<L>When &thorn;at a prince in vertu him delitith,</L>
<L>&THORN;en is his peple warissh&euml;d of drede;</L>
<L N="2854">Then may thei sey and syng alowde, &amp; grede,</L>
<L>"Honour, long lyfe, ioie, and crist&euml;s blyssyng,</L>
<L>Mot haue oure sustenour, our prince &amp; kyng!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="409" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(409)</HEAD>
<L N="2857">&para; Whan &thorn;at an Emperour in day&euml;s olde<MILESTONE N="49b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Corown&euml;d was, aftir as blyue anone,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; In vita I hannis I lemosinani.</NOTE></L>
<L>Makers of tounb&euml;s cum vnto him sholde,</L>
<L>And ask him 'of what metal or what stone</L>
<L N="2861">His toumbe shulde ben'; &amp; forth &thorn;ei gone,</L>
<L>With swich deuyse as &thorn;e lorde list deuyse,</L>
<L N="2863">And vp &thorn;ei make it in her best&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">best H R.</NOTE> wyse.
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="104"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="410" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(410)</HEAD>
<L N="2864">&para; This was done, for to bring vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thus was it done to bryng in R.</NOTE> mem&oacute;rie</L>
<L>That he was naght but a man c&oacute;ruptible,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;is worldis ioye is transitorie,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e trust on it slippir and fallible;</L>
<L N="2868">And &thorn;is considered, ought him be peynyble</L>
<L>His rem&euml; wel for to gouerne and gye;</L>
<L N="2870">ffor who so lyue&thorn; wel, wel shal he dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="411" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(411)</HEAD>
<L N="2871">&para; Like a bridel is de&thorn;&euml;s r&eacute;membraunce,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ecclesias|tici vij<SUP>o</SUP> Medi|tacio mortis est quasi frenum homi|nem refren|ans, ne ex|cerceat vltra.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vicia, &amp;c. R.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at mann&euml;s hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> r&eacute;streyneth fro vice.</L>
<L>&THORN;at kyng &thorn;at knyghtly<NOTE PLACE="foot">knyghtly R, knyght H.</NOTE> is of gouernaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to seyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyen H, sey R.</NOTE> do&thorn; iustly his office,</L>
<L N="2875">Of loue and pes and rest he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> is noryce;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he is out of &thorn;is worlde went,</L>
<L>Thus seyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyen H, sey R.</NOTE> men &thorn;at goon by his monument:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="412" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(412)</HEAD>
<L N="2878">&para; "In heuen mote &thorn;is kyng&euml;s soul&euml; rest!</L>
<L>&THORN;is is a worthy kyng, gret was &thorn;e pees</L>
<L>&THORN;at men had in his tyme, he was &thorn;e best</L>
<L>That myght be; he kept his peple harmles;</L>
<L N="2882">In<NOTE PLACE="foot">"In" is the first measure or foot.</NOTE> his comyng, glad was al &thorn;e pres,</L>
<L>And sory weren of his d&eacute;partyng."</L>
<L>O, graciouse princ&euml;, swich be your wirkyng!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="413" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(413)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thus, my gode lorde, wynneth your peples voice;<MILESTONE N="50a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Vox populi vox dei.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor peples vois is goddes voys, men seyne.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at for vs starf vpon &thorn;e croyse</L>
<L>Shal white<NOTE PLACE="foot">quyte R.</NOTE> it yow, I doute it noght certeyne;</L>
<L N="2889">Your labour shal naght ydel be, ne veyne;</L>
<L>"No goode dede vnrewardid is, or quytte;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nullum bo|num irremu|neratum. &amp;c.<NOTE PLACE="foot">R adds: "nec malum impunitum.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L N="2891">Ne euyl vnpunysshid," seith holy writte.
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="105"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="414" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(414)</HEAD>
<L N="2892">&para; In your prosperite and in your welthe,</L>
<L>Remembreth euer a-monge, &thorn;at ye shul dye,</L>
<L>And wot naght whan; it come&thorn; in a stelthe;</L>
<L>Haue often him<NOTE PLACE="foot">him R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> by-fore your myndes ye;</L>
<L N="2896">ffor whan no hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> hyd&euml; may ne wrye</L>
<L>His secre<NOTE PLACE="foot">secrete R.</NOTE> thought&euml;s, god al wot &amp; weyeth;</L>
<L N="2898">Hym, loue &amp; drede; and his law&euml;s obeyeth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="415" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(415)</HEAD>
<L N="2899">&para; Now sen a kyng is to his law&euml;s swore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Quod elec|ciones sint in ecclesiis cathedralibus libere.</NOTE></L>
<L>And law&euml; biddeth free elec&iuml;oun</L>
<L>In chirches passe; my god&euml; lorde, &thorn;er-fore,</L>
<L>Let no fauour ne none affecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="2903">So meeue your wys&euml; circumspecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>To lette hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, hym H.</NOTE> of hir laweful liberte;</L>
<L N="2905">Lat hem reioyse hir propre du&euml;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="416" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(416)</HEAD>
<L N="2906">&para; The chapitre of a chirch&euml; C&aacute;thedral,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ei haue chosen hir heed &amp; pastour,</L>
<L>Which as hem thenke&thorn; sufficiant at al,</L>
<L>Hem for to rewle, and ben hir gouernoure,</L>
<L N="2910">Write&thorn; vnto &thorn;e pope in hir fauour,</L>
<L>Bisekyng humble[l]y<NOTE PLACE="foot">humbly R.</NOTE> his fadir-hede</L>
<L N="2912">It to conferme; and &thorn;at is a iust dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="417" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(417)</HEAD>
<L N="2913">&para; And if the law&euml; suffre yow to write<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor any man apart, herkenth now me;</L>
<L>Let vertu &thorn;enn&euml; &thorn;erto yow excite;</L>
<L>Lokith &thorn;at &thorn;e man haue abilite,</L>
<L N="2917">&THORN;at shal resseyu&euml; &thorn;at hy<NOTE PLACE="foot">by H, hye R.</NOTE> dignite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to seyn, he be clene of lyuyng,</L>
<L N="2919">Discrete, iust, and of s&uacute;ffisant konnyng.
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="106"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="418" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(418)</HEAD>
<L N="2920">&para; If &thorn;e pope to &thorn;at estate prouyde</L>
<L>A persone, at your prayer and instaunce,</L>
<L>Your sonde he take&thorn; to &thorn;e better syde;</L>
<L>He holdeth &thorn;e persone of suffic&iuml;aunce</L>
<L N="2924">To hau&euml; swich a cure in gouernaunce,</L>
<L>ffor so wittenessith<NOTE PLACE="foot">witnesseth R.</NOTE> &thorn;e suggestioun</L>
<L N="2926">&THORN;at to hym made is for prouis&iuml;oun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">his promocioun R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="419" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(419)</HEAD>
<L N="2927">&para; To kynges letters, yeven is credence;</L>
<L>Beth ware how &thorn;at ye wryte in swich matere,</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;at ye hurt and mayn&euml; conc&iuml;ence.</L>
<L>ffor if &thorn;at execute be your prayere,</L>
<L N="2931">&THORN;e persone vnworthy, ye shul ful dere</L>
<L>Rewe it; no smal charche<NOTE PLACE="foot">charge R.</NOTE> is the soul&euml;s cure</L>
<L N="2933">Of al a diocise, I yow ensure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="420" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(420)</HEAD>
<L N="2934">&para; Of swich writyng be of right s&uacute;ffrable,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e man able, swich charge to resseyue,</L>
<L>ffor whom ye writte, &thorn;at is comm&eacute;ndable;</L>
<L>And ell&euml;s wol<NOTE PLACE="foot">elles wole R, els wol H.</NOTE> it your soule deseyve.</L>
<L N="2938">Help him &thorn;at able is<NOTE PLACE="foot">abl' is.</NOTE>; and tunhable<NOTE PLACE="foot">tunhable H, unable R. The <I>t</I> of "th' unable" after <I>d</I>, is Midland, like the "qwat" for "what," and "whyte" for "quyte" above.</NOTE> weyue;</L>
<L>Weyu&euml; fauel with his pol&yacute;ssh&iuml;d speche;</L>
<L>And help him &thorn;at wel doth, and wel can teche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="421" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(421)</HEAD>
<L N="2941">&para; But certes, fauel hath caght so sad foote<MILESTONE N="51a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In lord&euml;s court&euml;s,<NOTE PLACE="foot">courtes R, court H.</NOTE> he may naght &thorn;ens slyde;</L>
<L>Who com or go, algate abyde he moote;</L>
<L>His craft is to susteyne ay &thorn;e wrong syde,</L>
<L N="2945">And fro vertu his lord&euml; to devide;</L>
<L>And, for soth<NOTE PLACE="foot">sothe R.</NOTE> saw&euml;s ben to lord&euml;s lothe,</L>
<L>Noght wol he soth seyn, he hath made his oth.
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="107"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="422" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(422)</HEAD>
<L N="2948">&para; Let fauel pass&euml;; foule mot he falle!<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Qualiter quidam miles in exilium se posuit, quia leges bonas per se factas<NOTE PLACE="foot">per eum editas R.</NOTE> vellet obser|uari.</NOTE></L>
<L>fforth in iustic&euml; wol I now procede:</L>
<L>&THORN;er was a knyght, I not what men hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym R, hem H.</NOTE> calle,</L>
<L>A iuste man and a trewe in al his dede,</L>
<L N="2952">Which on a tyme, as &thorn;ought him it was nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e froward peple by sharp law&euml;s bynde;</L>
<L>law&euml;s ful iust he made, and in streyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">steyte R, sharp H.</NOTE> kynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="423" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(423)</HEAD>
<L N="2955">&para; And when &thorn;ei weren byfore hem I-radde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem radde . . . madde R, him I-rad . . . mad H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e H, They R.</NOTE> made hem wondir wroth, &amp; seyden al</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weren not so nyc&euml; ne so madde<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem radde . . . madde R, him I-rad . . . mad H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hem assent, for ought that<NOTE PLACE="foot">that R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> may befalle<NOTE PLACE="foot">befalle . . . thralle R, befal . . . thral H.</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="2959">They wolden nat hem to &thorn;o law&euml;s thralle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">befalle . . . thralle R, befal . . . thral H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wold han artyd &thorn;is knyght hem repele,</L>
<L N="2961">Makyng ageyn him an<NOTE PLACE="foot">an R, and H.</NOTE> haynous querele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="424" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(424)</HEAD>
<L N="2962">&para; When he se &thorn;is, he blyu&euml; to hem seyde:</L>
<L>"I<NOTE PLACE="foot">I R, He H.</NOTE> mad hem naght, it was god &aacute;ppollo;</L>
<L>And on my bak," quod he, "&thorn;e charge he leyde</L>
<L>To kepe hem; sir&euml;s, what sey ye here-to?</L>
<L N="2966">As he me chargid hath, ri&yogh;t so I do."</L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;at, answerd anone &thorn;e prees,</L>
<L N="2968">"We wol hem naght admitten dout&euml;les."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="425" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(425)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Wel," quod<NOTE PLACE="foot">koth R (as usual).</NOTE> he, "&thorn;enne is gode, or ye hem breke,<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That vnto god apollo I me dresse,</L>
<L>To trete of &thorn;is matere, and with him speke,&mdash;</L>
<L>With-owtyn him I may it naght redresse,&mdash;</L>
<L N="2973">Biseche him wol I,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I R.</NOTE> of his gentilnesse,</L>
<L>Repele hem,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, him H.</NOTE> sen &thorn;at &thorn;ei to streyt&euml; be,</L>
<L N="2975">And do my deuer ri&yogh;t wel, &yogh;e shul see.
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="108"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="426" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(426)</HEAD>
<L N="2976">&para; "But or I go, ye shul vnto me swere</L>
<L>&THORN;e law&euml;s kep&euml; til I agayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">ageyn R, gayn H.</NOTE> come,</L>
<L>And Breke hem naght;" to which &thorn;ei gan answere,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ee, &yogh;ee, man, &yogh;ee! we graunt it al and summe."</L>
<L N="2980">&THORN;ei made her oth, and he his wey hath nomme.<NOTE PLACE="foot">some . . . nome R.</NOTE></L>
<L>He nought to Apollo, but to grec&euml; went,</L>
<L N="2982">And &thorn;er abode tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e de&thorn; him hent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="427" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(427)</HEAD>
<L N="2983">&para; And whan his last&euml; daye<NOTE PLACE="foot">that his last day R, his last daye H.</NOTE> gan to appere,</L>
<L>He bad men &thorn;rowe his body in &thorn;e see,</L>
<L>Lest vpon &thorn;e londe made were his bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e peple myghten vn-to hir Citee</L>
<L N="2987">His bon&euml;s cary, and at hir larg&euml; be</L>
<L>Quyte of hir oth, as to hir iug&euml;ment;</L>
<L N="2989">Thus he deuysid in his testament.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="428" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(428)</HEAD>
<L N="2990">&para; Syn I spoke haue of iustice, as ye knowe,</L>
<L>Vnto pite&mdash;which mot ben had al-gatis,</L>
<L>And nam&euml;ly in princes ought it growe&mdash;</L>
<L>Wol I me dress&euml;: she opne&thorn; the &yogh;ates</L>
<L N="2994">Of helth to him &thorn;at in sekenesse estate is;</L>
<L>Sche esith many a wyght &thorn;at is distressid,</L>
<L N="2996">&THORN;at nere hir help&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">nere hir helpe R, neuer hir help H.</NOTE> shulde be sore oppressid.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 5. DE PIETATE.<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. has in margin: "Scriptum est, Pietas est ex benigne mentis dulcedine grata omnibus auxiliatrix."</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG N="429" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(429)</HEAD>
<L N="2997">Pitee, naght ell&euml;s is, to vndirstonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page has an illuminated initial letter, which extends from the top to the bottom, and a heading as above.&mdash;G. England.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="52a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But good wille inward of deb&oacute;nair hert,</L>
<L>And outhewarde<NOTE PLACE="foot">outward R.</NOTE> spech, and werk of man, to fonde</L>
<L>To help him &thorn;at men sen in meschif smert.</L>
<L>Men selde<NOTE PLACE="foot">selde R, selden H.</NOTE> him seen in-to wykk&yacute;d de&thorn; stert,
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>&THORN;at pitous is; but &thorn;ei han cruel de&thorn;</L>
<L N="3003">Often whos cruelte cruelly sleth.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sleth R, fleth H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="430" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(430)</HEAD>
<L N="3004">Whilom &thorn;er was a tyraunt dispitouse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Refert Ho|rosius quali|ter quidam artifex subti|lis puniebatur per artem propriam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at so delited him in cruelte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of no &thorn;ing was he so d&eacute;sirous.</L>
<L>Now shope it so, a man &thorn;at to pyte</L>
<L N="3008">ffo was, and frende vnto iniquite,</L>
<L>A sotel werkeman in craft of metal,</L>
<L N="3010">Wrought in &thorn;is wyse as I yow tell&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">telle R, tel H.</NOTE> shal.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="431" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(431)</HEAD>
<L N="3011">His lorde &thorn;e king he &thorn;ought&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ought H, thought to R.</NOTE> plese and glade,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. has in margin: "Nota, de crudel, itate cujusdam artificis subtilis, et qualiter per artem suam propriam puniebatur; et hoc refert Horosius."</NOTE></L>
<L>And craft&euml;ly he made a bol<NOTE PLACE="foot">craftely . . . bole R (bull), craftly . . . bol H.</NOTE> of bras,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e syde of it he slily made</L>
<L>A litel wyket, &thorn;at ordeyn&euml;d was</L>
<L N="3015">To r&eacute;ceyue hem &thorn;at stode in de&thorn;&euml;s case,</L>
<L>Vndir &thorn;e which men shulden sharpe fire make,</L>
<L N="3017">Tho folk to de&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">dethe R, de&thorn; H.</NOTE> for to brenne &amp; bake.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="432" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(432)</HEAD>
<L N="3018">And &yogh;it more-ouer, &thorn;e kyng for to meve</L>
<L>The lesse vnto pitee, it made was so</L>
<L>By sotil art<NOTE PLACE="foot">craft R.</NOTE> &thorn;e dampn&euml;d folk to greve</L>
<L>&THORN;at whan to crye, hem c&oacute;mpellyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">compelled hem R.</NOTE> hir woo,</L>
<L N="3022">Hir woys was lyke a bol&euml;s euer-mo,</L>
<L>And nothyng lyke a mannys voise in soun,</L>
<L N="3024">As &thorn;e scriptur&euml; maketh menc&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="433" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(433)</HEAD>
<L N="3025">&para; But our lord god, of pite &thorn;e auctour,<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Displesid with &thorn;is cruel ordinaunce,</L>
<L>Swich rewarde shape vnto this<NOTE PLACE="foot">this R, his H.</NOTE> losengeour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it abatid al his countenaunce;</L>
<L N="3029">And for to preue his fendely purueaunce,</L>
<L>How sharp it was, &amp; coud&euml; folk distreyne,</L>
<L N="3031">The first he was &thorn;at entryd in &thorn;at peyne.
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="110"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="434" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(434)</HEAD>
<L N="3032">&para; ffor whan &thorn;e kyng, his cruel werk had seyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e craft of it commendith he ful wele;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e entent he fully helde a-gayne,</L>
<L>And seyd&euml;, "&thorn;ou &thorn;at art mor&euml; cruel</L>
<L N="3036">Than I, &thorn;e maydenhede of this Iuel</L>
<L>Shalt preue anone; &thorn;is is my Iug&euml;ment."</L>
<L N="3038">And so as blyue he was &thorn;er-in I-brent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="435" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(435)</HEAD>
<L N="3039">&para; Men may sen here, how fauel hym enclyneth</L>
<L>Ay to his lordys lust, what so it be;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Contra blanditores.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at ende he bysieth hym and clynyth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">pyneth R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And no considerac&iuml;oun hath he,</L>
<L N="3043">Thogh it be harm&euml; to his lordys degre,</L>
<L>Or a-geyn feith, honour, or conc&iuml;ence;</L>
<L N="3045">In fals plesaunce is al his diligence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="436" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(436)</HEAD>
<L N="3046">&para; To what &thorn;ing it be, if it his lorde lyke,</L>
<L>He him conformyth; he neuer denyeth</L>
<L>His lord&euml;s resouns, but a &thorn;ank to pike,</L>
<L>His lordys wil and witte he iustifieth;</L>
<L N="3050">Whil fauel liue&thorn;, no fals conseil dieth;</L>
<L>ffauel is wedded to plesaunt deseyt,</L>
<L N="3052">And in &thorn;at wedlok trewe is his conceite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="437" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(437)</HEAD>
<L N="3053">&para; Grounde of treson, o &thorn;ou cursyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">cruell R.</NOTE> fauel!<MILESTONE N="53a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>How long&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">longe R, long H.</NOTE> shalt &thorn;ou be a potestate?</L>
<L>In lord&euml;s courtes &thorn;ou pleyest<NOTE PLACE="foot">courtes . . . curt . . . pleyest R, pleyst H.</NOTE> &thorn;i parcel,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it strecchith to &thorn;i lordys mate;</L>
<L N="3057">ffor &thorn;u hast neuer &thorn;i lordys estate</L>
<L>To hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> chere, but al &thorn;i bysynesse</L>
<L N="3059">Is for &thorn;i lucre, and &thorn;i cofres warmnesse.
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="111"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="438" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(438)</HEAD>
<L N="3060">&para; ffauel was neuer frendly, man vnto;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dicit Sene|ca de qui|busdam qui Neronem sequebantur. Mel musce se|quuntur,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sequuntur R, sequitur H.</NOTE> ca|dauera lupi; predam se|quitur ista turba non hominem.</NOTE></L>
<L>lord&euml;s, beth ware! it nedith trew&euml;lye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">trewlye H, truly R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Senek, by hem &thorn;at folweden Nero,</L>
<L>Seith &thorn;us, "a ffly&euml; folwe&thorn; the honye;</L>
<L N="3064">&THORN;e wolf, careyn," he seith; so, wel wot I</L>
<L>&THORN;at company&euml; folweden her pray,</L>
<L N="3066">And naght &thorn;e man; &amp; so do men &thorn;is day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="439" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(439)</HEAD>
<L N="3067">&para; Whil &thorn;at &thorn;e swetnesse of riches endurith,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e riche is manny man plesaunt;</L>
<L>Only &thorn;e richess&euml; &thorn;er-to hem lurith;</L>
<L>What he comaundi&thorn;, &thorn;ei ben obysaunt<NOTE PLACE="foot">obedient R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3071">To do, whil &thorn;at he of goode is habundaunt;</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;e pray, &thorn;e ricchesse, is a-goo,</L>
<L N="3073">The man forsaken &thorn;ei for euermo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="440" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(440)</HEAD>
<L N="3074">&para; O ffauel! a blynde marchant art &thorn;ou oone,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronimus. Adulator secus est qui pro questu vel gracia transitoria sua &amp; alteri|us animam interficit.</NOTE></L>
<L>That, for wordly goode, &amp; grace and fauoure,&mdash;</L>
<L>Which fayl&euml; shal &amp; passe, and ouer goone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">passe in ouer goone H, faile and ouercome H.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Swich diligenc&euml; dost, and swich laboure,</L>
<L N="3078">&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i soul&euml; fro our saueoure</L>
<L>Twynnest, and slest &thorn;i lordis soule also,</L>
<L N="3080">And causyst hem to peyne eternal go.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="441" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(441)</HEAD>
<L N="3081">&para; &THORN;er is a long and a large difference<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Twix vertuous plesaunce and flaterie:</L>
<L>Good plesaunce is of swich beneuolence,</L>
<L>&THORN;at what gode dede he may in man espie,</L>
<L N="3085">He preysith it, and r&eacute;bukith folye;</L>
<L>But fauel take&thorn; al on othir parte;</L>
<L N="3087">In wrong preysyng is al his craft and arte.
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="112"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="442" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(442)</HEAD>
<L N="3088">&para; A gloser also kepith his silence<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Hugo de sancto vic|tore. Adu|lator est ille qui tacet &amp; dat consen|sum ne offendat quem optat<NOTE PLACE="foot">optat R, ortat H.</NOTE> habere pro|picium.</NOTE></L>
<L>Often, where he his lord seeth<NOTE PLACE="foot">seeth R, seith H.</NOTE> him mystake.</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;at his answere myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">myght H R.</NOTE> done offence</L>
<L>Vn-to his lorde, and him displesyd make,</L>
<L N="3092">He holt his pees; nat a worde dare he crake;</L>
<L>And for he naght ne seith, he his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his R, is H.</NOTE> assent</L>
<L N="3094">&YOGH;eue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Yeveth R, &thorn;en H.</NOTE> &thorn;erto, by mann&euml;s Iug&euml;ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="443" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(443)</HEAD>
<L N="3095">&para; Who-so &thorn;at wot &thorn;e purpose of a wyght,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Qui tacet, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is agroundid vppon wykydnesse,</L>
<L>And noght ne lettith it, vnto his myght,</L>
<L>ffauorith it, as &thorn;e boke can expresse;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Canonum xxiij. q. iij. capitulo. Qui potest.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3099">Who-so it<NOTE PLACE="foot">it R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> lokith, fynde it shal no lesse.</L>
<L>But of al &thorn;is now make I here an ende,</L>
<L N="3101">And to my tale of pite wol I wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="444" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(444)</HEAD>
<L N="3102">&para; A Princ&euml; mot be of condicioun</L>
<L>Pitouse, and his angir refreyne, &amp; ire,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Aristoteles, in principum regimine, capitulo de Regis proui|dencia.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lest &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> vnavisid commocioun</L>
<L>Hym chauf&euml; so, &amp; sette his hert on fire,</L>
<L N="3106">That hym to wenge<NOTE PLACE="foot">venge R.</NOTE> as blyu&euml; he desire,</L>
<L>And fulfille it in dede: hym owy&thorn; knowe.</L>
<L N="3108">His errour, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and R, an H.</NOTE> qwenche &thorn;at firy lowe.<MILESTONE N="54a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="445" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(445)</HEAD>
<L N="3109">&para; Aristotle amonestith wonder faste,</L>
<L>In his book whiche to Alisaundre he wroot,</L>
<L>If he wolde haue his regne endure and laste,</L>
<L>That for non ire he neuere be soo hoot,</L>
<L>Blood of man<NOTE PLACE="foot">of man to R, of a man H.</NOTE> schede; and god seith, wel I woot,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Michi vindictam. (R. adds: Item, Qui gladio per|cutit, &amp;c.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="3114">That vnto hym reseru&euml;d is vengeaunce;</L>
<L>Who-so &thorn;at sle&thorn;, schal haue &thorn;e sam&euml; chaunce.
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="113"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="446" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(446)</HEAD>
<L N="3116">&para; But this noght ment is by &thorn;e cours of lawe,</L>
<L>That put a man to deth for cryme horrible.</L>
<L>Whan he a man y-murdred ha&thorn; and slawe,</L>
<L>A man to sle by lawe, it is lisible;</L>
<L N="3120">That slaughtre beforn god is &aacute;dmittible,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; ffacilitas venie incen|tiuum pre|bet delin|quendi.</NOTE></L>
<L>And if a kyng do swich&euml; murdrers grace</L>
<L N="3122">Of lyf, he bolde&thorn; hem eft to trespace.<NOTE PLACE="foot">trespace R, strepace H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="447" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(447)</HEAD>
<L N="3123">&para; kyng of &thorn;is lond whilom, herde I seyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota con|tra conces|siones carta|rum pardo|nacionum de murdris.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor mann&euml;s deth a pardoun hadde e-graunted<NOTE PLACE="foot">be graunted R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto a man, whiche afterward ageyn</L>
<L>The sam&euml; gilt hadde in an othir haunted;</L>
<L N="3127">Aftir whos deth, he homly ha&thorn; avaunted</L>
<L>He nas naght so frendl&eacute;s, he wold&euml; do</L>
<L N="3129">Wel y-now thogh he hadde slayn othir two.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="448" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(448)</HEAD>
<L N="3130">&para; "Of frendes," quod he, "haue I larg&euml; wone,</L>
<L>That, for &thorn;at they haue had, and schul, of myne,</L>
<L>Byforne &thorn;e kyng for me schal knele echone;</L>
<L>They at &thorn;e full&euml; kunne his hert&euml; myne;</L>
<L N="3134">Thidir wil I goo, streght as any lyne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey &thorn;at now annoyen me or greue,</L>
<L N="3136">I schal hem qwite here-aftir, as I leue."<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="449" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(449)</HEAD>
<L N="3137">&para; He cam vnto &thorn;e kyng, and axid grace</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he wroght&euml; hadde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrought hade R.</NOTE> so synfully.</L>
<L>The kyng auys&euml;d hym wel on his face,</L>
<L>And seyd&euml;, "frend, me &thorn;ynketh how &thorn;at I</L>
<L N="3141">Haue vnto &thorn;e doon grace or &thorn;is, soothly;</L>
<L>I graunted on&euml;s a chartre to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3143">Of mann&euml;s deth, as it remembreth me.
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="114"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="450" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(450)</HEAD>
<L N="3144">&para; "Hast &thorn;ou now slayn an othir man also?"</L>
<L>Now stood a fool&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">foole R, fool H.</NOTE> sage &thorn;e kyng byside;</L>
<L>And or &thorn;e kyng spak any word&euml;s moo,</L>
<L>He to hym seid&euml;, "[Now,] for god &thorn;at dyde,</L>
<L N="3148">Whi demen ye &thorn;is man an homicide?</L>
<L>He slow hym naght, for ye your self<NOTE PLACE="foot">self R, <I>om.</I> H (<I>with a later</I> 'selfe' <I>overline</I>).</NOTE> hym slow,</L>
<L N="3150">And, by your leuen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leve R.</NOTE> I schal tellen how:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="451" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(451)</HEAD>
<L N="3151">&para; "If &thorn;at &thorn;e law&euml; myghte his cours han had,</L>
<L>This man here hadde ben, for &thorn;e firste man, deed;</L>
<L>fforyeue hym now; and yif &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> he be drad</L>
<L>To slee &thorn;e thridd&euml;, &thorn;an girde of myn heed.</L>
<L N="3155">Now be avis&euml;d wel; it is my reed,</L>
<L>How ye your pardoun graunt&euml;, leste errour</L>
<L N="3157">Of nyc&euml; pitee be your &aacute;ccusour."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="452" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(452)</HEAD>
<L>&para; This kyng wel &thorn;ought&euml; &thorn;at he seide hym trouthe,</L>
<L>And chartirles goo&thorn; &thorn;is man ful of drede;</L>
<L>And aftirward, of whos dissert was routhe,</L>
<L>The lawe hym yaf &thorn;at long&euml;d to his mede.</L>
<L N="3162">My tale is doon; now soo&thorn;ly it is nede</L>
<L>To graunt&euml;s to wi&thorn;stond&euml;, &thorn;at procure</L>
<L N="3164">Mesch&eacute;vous deth to many a cr&euml;ature.<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="453" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(453)</HEAD>
<L N="3165">&para; Pitee auailith mochil, but naght &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>ffor bet it is to sle &thorn;e mordreman,</L>
<L>Than suffre hym regn&euml;, for he ha&thorn; no fere</L>
<L>His hand to vs&euml; forth as he by-gan;</L>
<L N="3169">And in my c&oacute;nceit, feel&euml; wel I can,</L>
<L>That of suche pitee, is &thorn;e abstinence</L>
<L N="3171">Of gretter pite, for &thorn;e consequence.
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="115"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="454" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(454)</HEAD>
<L N="3172">&para; If right-ful deth of oo man, kepe and saue</L>
<L>Two innocent&euml;s lyu&euml;s, &thorn;inke&thorn; me</L>
<L>By resoun mor&euml; merit oghte hym haue</L>
<L>That c&oacute;mandith his<NOTE PLACE="foot">this R.</NOTE> gylty man deed be,</L>
<L N="3176">Than he &thorn;at lif hym graunte&thorn;: why lat se,</L>
<L>The gylty man is no wrong doon vnto,</L>
<L N="3178">But wrong is doon vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto R, to H.</NOTE> thise othir two.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="455" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(455)</HEAD>
<L N="3179">&para; Euery man woot wel, f&oacute;r to saue tweyne</L>
<L>Is gretter grac&euml; &thorn;an to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> saue but on.</L>
<L>Of murdre, is cause gret for to<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete to R.</NOTE> compleyne;</L>
<L>Tho pardons alle to lyghtly passe and goon;</L>
<L N="3183">Auyse hem &thorn;at fauo&uacute;re hem, by seynt Iohn;</L>
<L>Who so it be that &thorn;erto &thorn;e kyng meeveth,</L>
<L N="3185">Wel mor&euml; &thorn;an he woot, his soul&euml; greeveth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="456" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(456)</HEAD>
<L N="3186">&para; Avise a kyng eek, for any requeste</L>
<L>Vnto hym maad, by greet estat or mene,</L>
<L>That he fauo&uacute;re it noght; it is &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Tho r&eacute;quest&euml;s to werne and voyd&euml; clene,</L>
<L N="3190">Of swiche in sothe as murdrers ben, I mene;</L>
<L>But and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and, an, if.</NOTE> on be by malice of his foos</L>
<L N="3192">Endited, pardoun be to hym noght cloos.<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="457" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(457)</HEAD>
<L N="3193">&para; If &thorn;at be sooth, lat pitee walk at large,</L>
<L>ffor sche and mercy &thorn;erto wil assente;</L>
<L>It is a parcel of hir either charge;</L>
<L>Routh&euml; were it &thorn;e gilt&euml;les turmente;</L>
<L N="3197">Pitee schal soul of man to god presente,</L>
<L>And god, &thorn;at yaf vs ensample of pitee,</L>
<L N="3199">To pitous folk sauac&iuml;oun schal be.
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="116"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="458" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(458)</HEAD>
<L N="3200">&para; The pitous herte of Marcus Marcellus</L>
<L>Wele worthy is, be drawen in mem&oacute;rie;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De pietate Marci Mar|celli.</NOTE></L>
<L>He may ensample and mirrour be to vs;</L>
<L>ffor, as Valerie writith in a storie,</L>
<L N="3204">Whan &thorn;is Marc obtened hadde<NOTE PLACE="foot">opteynede R (? hadde obtened).</NOTE> &thorn;e vict&oacute;rie</L>
<L>By seg&euml; leyde to men of siracuse,</L>
<L N="3206">As I schal seyn, he heuyly gan<NOTE PLACE="foot">gan R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> muse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="459" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(459)</HEAD>
<L N="3207">&para; He wente hym vp on hy vppon a toure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tree R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where he byhold&euml; myghte al &thorn;e citee,</L>
<L>And how fortune hadde schape hym &thorn;at honoure.<NOTE PLACE="foot">that he did see R.</NOTE></L>
<L>With hert&euml; tendre than considered he,</L>
<L N="3211">And hadde of folk&euml;s deth&euml;s suche pitee,</L>
<L>That from wepynge he myghte hym not restreyne;</L>
<L N="3213">Al his tryumph&euml; was to hym but peyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="460" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(460)</HEAD>
<L N="3214">&para; Who-so hadde stonden by hym in &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>And hym avis&euml;d on his contenaunce,</L>
<L>Wolde han suppos&euml;d that &thorn;at othir side</L>
<L>Rathir hadde I-putte hym to &thorn;e outraunce,</L>
<L N="3218">Than he hadde had of hem so fair a chaunce:</L>
<L>O worthy knyght! who schal &thorn;i stepp&euml;s sue?</L>
<L N="3220">Thi s&uacute;ccessour halt hym to longe in mue.<MILESTONE N="56a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="461" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(461)</HEAD>
<L N="3221">&para; O citee! syn fortune was contrarie</L>
<L>To the in o part, yit hir gentilnesse</L>
<L>Purvey&euml;d &thorn;e a b&eacute;nigne aduersarie.</L>
<L>Thanke hir of &thorn;at, for thy disese is lesse,</L>
<L N="3225">ffalle in &thorn;e daunger of lamb&euml;s humblesse,</L>
<L>Than he with cruel wolu&euml;s al to-frete;</L>
<L N="3227">A lamb is naght so gredy on hir mete.
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="117"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="462" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(462)</HEAD>
<L N="3228">&para; Ther nys no &thorn;ing, as witnessith a<NOTE PLACE="foot">the R.</NOTE> storie,</L>
<L>Makyth a knyght so schynynge in renoun,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he of his foos hath &thorn;e vict&oacute;rie,</L>
<L>As rew on hym &thorn;at throwen is a-doun,</L>
<L N="3232">And of his blode eschue effusioun.</L>
<L>A bestes kynde is, &thorn;at is wilde and wood,</L>
<L N="3234">Vict&oacute;rie naght desire, but &thorn;e blood.<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. has in margin: Scriptum est, Ferarum genus est non victoriam sed sanguinem sitire.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="463" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(463)</HEAD>
<L N="3235">&para; Also, whan &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of hermenye<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De pietate<NOTE PLACE="foot">benignitate &amp; pietate R.</NOTE> pompei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Venquysshet was in batayle by pompeye,</L>
<L>This kyng fel doun vnto his foot in hye,</L>
<L>And from hym caste his dyademe aweye;</L>
<L N="3239">But pompeyus, as blyue, of his nobleye</L>
<L>Stirte vnto hym, and vp hym lifte &amp; hente,</L>
<L N="3241">And many a word benigne on hym dispente.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="464" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(464)</HEAD>
<L>&para; He dide his myght hym to conforte and qweeme;</L>
<L>And right anon, with-oute any delay,</L>
<L>Vpon his heed bad sette his dyademe</L>
<L>Ageyn; and so<NOTE PLACE="foot">so R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> was doon, it is no nay.</L>
<L N="3246">Whan Cesar, emperour, eek on a day<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De pietate cesaris im|peratoris.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pompey&euml; saw biforn hym lad &amp; bounde,</L>
<L N="3248">Cesar in ter&euml;s salt&euml; gan habounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">abounde R, hobunde H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="465" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(465)</HEAD>
<L N="3249">&para; Whan Alisaundre eek, as Vallerie ha&thorn; told,<MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De pietate Alexandri.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was, in a tyme, in &thorn;e feld wi&thorn; his host,</L>
<L>An ag&euml;d knyght of his, for verray cold,</L>
<L>His lyfly myght he loren hadde al-moost,</L>
<L N="3253">So greuous tempest tho fil in &thorn;at coost;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is wor&thorn;y kyng &thorn;is hadde aspied,</L>
<L N="3255">Out of his see he roos, and to hym hied,
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="118"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="466" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(466)</HEAD>
<L N="3256">&para; And by the hand &thorn;is old&euml; knyght he took,</L>
<L>Confortynge hym [right] in his <SUP>1</SUP>beste manere,</L>
<L>And ledde hym to his<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 best manere And ledde hym vnto his R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> tente, as seith &thorn;e book,</L>
<L>And in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> his real seege and his chaiere</L>
<L N="3260">As blyue hym sett&euml;: &thorn;us may kyng&euml;s leere,</L>
<L>Distress&euml;d knyghtes to help&euml; and releeue:</L>
<L>To take ensample of &thorn;is, it schal noght greue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="467" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(467)</HEAD>
<L N="3263">&para; What wonder was it, thogh &thorn;at knyght&euml;s tho</L>
<L>Desir&euml;den so noble princ&euml; serue,</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at hym leuer was for to for-go</L>
<L>His dignite, and hir hel&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">helthe to R.</NOTE> conserue,</L>
<L N="3267">Than his estat keepe, and hym suffre sterue?</L>
<L>Yit hoope I seen his heir in &thorn;is prouince;</L>
<L N="3269">And &thorn;at schal ye be, my good lord &thorn;e prince.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="468" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(468)</HEAD>
<L N="3270">&para; Before a iuge, eek in poynt to be deed,</L>
<L>Of Iul&iuml;us Cesar &thorn;er was a knyght,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Pietate Iulii Cesaris.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche, wi&thorn; an hye voys, for to saue his heed,</L>
<L>To his lord Cesar cryde a-lowd&euml; ryght,</L>
<L N="3274">By-sechynge hym &thorn;at, of his gracious myght,</L>
<L>He wolde hym helpe and rew<NOTE PLACE="foot">rewe R.</NOTE> on his estat;</L>
<L N="3276">And Cesar sente hym a good aduocat.<MILESTONE N="57a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="469" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(469)</HEAD>
<L N="3277">&para; And vnto &thorn;at, &thorn;is knyght as blyu&euml; &thorn;us</L>
<L>On height&euml; wel, &thorn;at al &thorn;e peple it herde,</L>
<L>With manly cheer&euml; spak to Iulius,</L>
<L>His lorde, and in &thorn;is wis&euml; hym answerde:&mdash;</L>
<L N="3281">"Han ye for-gote how scharp it wi&thorn; yow ferde,</L>
<L>Whan ye were in &thorn;e werr&euml;s of asie?</L>
<L N="3283">Maffeith! your lif stood &thorn;ere in iupartie;
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="119"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="470" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(470)</HEAD>
<L N="3284">&para; "And aduocat ne sente I non to yow,</L>
<L>But my-self put in prees, &amp; for yow faght;</L>
<L>My wound&euml;s beren good witnesse y-now</L>
<L>That I sooth seye; and, lest ye leeue it naght,</L>
<L N="3288">I schal yow schewe what harm&euml; haue I<NOTE PLACE="foot">I haue R.</NOTE> caght,</L>
<L>The doute out of youre hert&euml; for to dryue."</L>
<L N="3290">He nakid hym, and schew&euml;d hym as blyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="471" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(471)</HEAD>
<L N="3291">&para; Of whiche, Cesar ful sor&euml; was aschamed,</L>
<L>And in his hert&euml; sorwe made, and moone;</L>
<L>He heeld hym selfen worthy to be blamed.</L>
<L>"My freend,"<NOTE PLACE="foot">frend R, feend H.</NOTE> he seid&euml;, "let me now allone;</L>
<L N="3295">Adu&oacute;cat wole I be in my persone</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e; I am wel holden to do soo."</L>
<L N="3297">And &thorn;us, &thorn;is knyght, his deth he saued fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="472" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(472)</HEAD>
<L N="3298">&para; He dredde hym, if he nadd&euml; &thorn;us y-wroght</L>
<L>The peple hym wolde han<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolde hym haue R.</NOTE> for a proude man deemed,</L>
<L>And vngentil, and &thorn;at he cowd&euml; noght,</L>
<L>As that it scholde eeke haue vnto hym seemed,</L>
<L N="3302">Thanke hem &thorn;at wor&thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">worthy R, wor&thorn; H.</NOTE> wer&euml; to be qwemed;</L>
<L>"What princ&euml;," quoth he, "peyneth hym naght wynne</L>
<L>His knyght&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">knyghtes R, knyghes H.</NOTE> loue, his loue is to hem &thorn;ynne."<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="473" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(473)</HEAD>
<L N="3305">&para; Out of pitee, growith mercy and springi&thorn;,</L>
<L>ffor piteel&eacute;s man c&aacute;n do no mercy;</L>
<L>What prince hem lakkith, naght aright he kyngeth;</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben negh&euml;boures so nygh,</L>
<L N="3309">To pitee, mercy ioyn&euml; now wole I.</L>
<L>Excellent prince haue in hem good sauour,</L>
<L N="3311">And ell&euml;s al in waast<NOTE PLACE="foot">all in veyne R, in waast H.</NOTE> is your labour.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000186.tif" N="120">
<HEAD>[&sect; 6.] &para; De Misericordia.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Angustinus dicit, quod misericordia est aliene mi|serie ex corde vera com|passio, &amp; hec vertus con|sistit in duo|bus, scilicet, dando &amp; dimittendo.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="474" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(474)</HEAD>
<L N="3312">Mercy, aftir &thorn;e worde of seynt Austyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page has an illuminated border and initial.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of herte is a verray compass&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Of othir menys harm, and &thorn;at comth yn</L>
<L>By gyfte of god, and by remiss&iuml;oun;</L>
<L N="3316">As, if<NOTE PLACE="foot">if R, of H.</NOTE> ini&uacute;rie or oppressioun</L>
<L>Be doon to vs, &thorn;at gilt for-yeue vs oghte,</L>
<L N="3318">ffor loue of crist, &thorn;at, by deth, our lif boghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="475" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(475)<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Matthaei vij<SUP>o</SUP>. Qui enim dimittit iniuriam, &amp; si peccauerit ipse, dimit|tetur ei. &para; Vnde domi|nus in euan|gelio: Date &amp; dabitur vo|bis; dimitte &amp; dimitetur vobis; sed qui dimittit &amp; non dat, &amp; si plene non operatus est, eam meliorem tamen par|tem tenet misericordie. &para; Ambrosius. Quis fidelis sit, sobrius &amp; castus &amp; aliis vertuti|bus oneratus, si tamen mis|ericors non est miseri|cordiam non meritur. Di|cit enim Apos|tolus lacobus ij<SUP>o</SUP>. Iudicium sine miseri|cordia illi qui non facit misericor|diam.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="3319">Who-so, wronge to hym do&ouml;n, wole for-yeue,</L>
<L>His synn&euml; schal to hym for-yeuen be;</L>
<L>Thogh &thorn;at he no &thorn;ing of his good&euml;s yeue,</L>
<L>The better part yit of mercy halt he;</L>
<L N="3323">Thus fynde I writen of auctorite:</L>
<L>but fully may &thorn;ere no man do mercy,</L>
<L N="3325">But if &thorn;at he releu&euml; &thorn;e nedy.<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. has the lines of this stanza wrong: 3319, 3324-5, 3320-1.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="476" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(476)</HEAD>
<L N="3326">Thogh &thorn;at a man be sobre, chaast, &amp; trewe,</L>
<L>And be wi&thorn; many an hy vertu endow&euml;d,</L>
<L>And yeue, and naght for-yeue, it schal hym rewe:</L>
<L>Where as oure werkes most&euml; ben avow&euml;d,<MILESTONE N="58a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3330">The vnmerci&aacute;ble schal be disallow&euml;d:</L>
<L>Who naght for&yogh;eueth, mercy dooth he non;</L>
<L N="3332">And mercyles man, mercy schal for-gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="477" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(477)</HEAD>
<L N="3333">&para; Mercy, crist caus&euml;d to ben incarnate,</L>
<L>And humbled hym to take oure bre&thorn;erhede.</L>
<L>God in-mortel, rewynge oure seek estate,</L>
<L>Mortel be-cam, to purge oure synful dede;</L>
<L N="3337">Hym lothid naght his precious body sprede</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e croys, this lord benyngne and good;</L>
<L>He wroot oure chartre of mercy with his blood.
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="121"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="478" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(478)</HEAD>
<L N="3340">&para; Of hym, his handwerk and his cr&euml;ature,</L>
<L>ffor to be merciable, aright may lerne;</L>
<L>This lyf present schul but a whil&euml; dure,</L>
<L>And lastynge it, your mercy naght ne werne,</L>
<L N="3344">O worthy princ&euml;, for to god eterne</L>
<L>It ful plesant is; dooth your mercy here;</L>
<L N="3346">ffor to late is, aftir ye goo to beere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="479" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(479)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Take hede, exc&eacute;llent prince, of your graunt-syre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De miseri|cordia Iohan|nis ducis lancastrie, (cuius anime propicietur deus!) &amp; de misericordia domini nostri Regis hen|rici, filii sui.</NOTE></L>
<L>How in his werk&euml;s he was merci&aacute;ble;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at for mercy dyd&euml;, qwyte his hire!</L>
<L>He neuere was, in al his lyf, venge&aacute;ble,</L>
<L N="3351">But ay for-yaf the gylty and coup&aacute;ble.</L>
<L>Our lig&euml; lord your fadir, dith<NOTE PLACE="foot">doth R.</NOTE> &thorn;e same;</L>
<L>Now folwe hem two, my lord, in goddis name!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="480" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(480)</HEAD>
<L N="3354">&para; They often hadd&euml; gret cause hem to venge,</L>
<L>But hir spiritis b&eacute;nigne and pesible</L>
<L>Thoghten &thorn;at craft vnlusty and alenge,</L>
<L>And f&oacute;rbaar it; &thorn;ei knewe it vnlisible.<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3358">To mercy were hir hert&euml;s ay flexible;</L>
<L>ffor-why with mercy god schal qwyte hem wel,</L>
<L N="3360">Aftir &thorn;e word&euml;s write in &thorn;e gospell.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Beati misericordes &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="481" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(481)</HEAD>
<L N="3361">&para; It is to leue and deme, if a kyng schyne</L>
<L>In vertu, &thorn;at his son&euml; schuld&euml; sue,</L>
<L>And to his fadris maner&euml;s enclyne,</L>
<L>And wykked teich&euml;s and vices eschue:</L>
<L N="3365">Thus oghte it be, this to nat&uacute;re is due.</L>
<L>He mot considre of whom he took hys kynde,</L>
<L N="3367">And folwe his vertu, as men writen fynde.
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="122"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="482" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(482)</HEAD>
<L N="3368">&para; He moost is like to god, as seith Bernard,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ait beatus Bernardus, 'Ille maxime deum imitat, qui nichil iudicauerit preciosius quam mise|reri.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at holdeth no &thorn;ing mor&euml; precious</L>
<L>Than to be merciful; it is ful hard</L>
<L>To lakk&euml; mercy and ben vnpitous.</L>
<L N="3372">"Mercy wole I," seith oure lord glorious;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Matthaei. ij. clamauit deus, miseri|cordiam volo; qui quod vult deus, deo negat, a deo sibi quod desiderat, vult negari.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;at denyeth god, &thorn;&aacute;t he wolde haue,</L>
<L>God nayte<NOTE PLACE="foot">nay R.</NOTE> hym schal, &thorn;at he wil axe or craue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="483" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(483)</HEAD>
<L N="3375">&para; Senek seith how &thorn;e kyng and &thorn;e ledere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R, <I>om.</I> H] Seneca dicit, quod rex apium om|nino sine aculeo est; voluit enim natura nec seuum esse, nec ulcionum expetere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of bees is prikk&euml;les; he ha&thorn; right non</L>
<L>Wherwith to styngen, or annoye, or dere;</L>
<L>But othir bees, prikk&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">prikles R.</NOTE> han euerichon;</L>
<L N="3379">Nat&uacute;r&euml; wold&euml; sche schulde it<NOTE PLACE="foot">hir R.</NOTE> for-goon,</L>
<L>And do no cruelte vnto &thorn;e swarm,</L>
<L N="3381">But mekely hem gouerne, &amp; do non harm.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="484" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(484)</HEAD>
<L N="3382">&para; Of &thorn;is, ensample schuld&euml; kyng&euml;s take,</L>
<L>And princes, &thorn;at han peple for to gye;</L>
<L>ffor to hem longith it, for godd&euml;s sake,</L>
<L>To wayu&euml; cruelte and tyrannye,<MILESTONE N="59a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3386">And to pitee, hir hert&euml;s bowe &amp; wrye,</L>
<L>And reule hir peple esily and faire:</L>
<L N="3388">It is kyngly, be meeke and debonaire.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="485" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(485)</HEAD>
<L N="3389">&para; I rede of &aacute; kyng, &thorn;at Pirus was named,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De miti animo<NOTE PLACE="foot">De misericordia R.</NOTE> Regis Piri.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan hym was tolde, how &thorn;at men of Tarente</L>
<L>Hadde, at a fest&euml;, his estat diffamed,</L>
<L>He for &thorn;e sam&euml; folk&euml;s blyu&euml; sente;</L>
<L N="3393">And whan &thorn;ey cam, axid to what entente</L>
<L>They of hym spak so, and so foul&euml; ferde;</L>
<L>And oon of hem, as ye schulle here, answerde:<NOTE PLACE="foot">answerde R, answere H.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="123"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="486" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(486)</HEAD>
<L N="3396">&para; "My lord, if &thorn;at &thorn;e wyne noght faill&euml;d hadde,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at we spak, ner&euml; but game and play,</L>
<L>Hauynge reward&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">rewarde R, reward H.</NOTE> to &thorn;e word&euml;s badde</L>
<L>That we thoghte haue I-spoken in good fay."</L>
<L N="3400">The kyng took a laghtre, and wente his way,</L>
<L>And of al &thorn;at, he heeld hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, hym H.</NOTE> ful excused:</L>
<L N="3402">He seide it w&aacute;s wyne, &thorn;at so hem accused.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="487" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(487)</HEAD>
<L N="3403">&para; Wengeance, in &thorn;is good lord, hadd&euml; no stide;</L>
<L>Mercy and humble disposic&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Dispensid<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dispendede he R.</NOTE> with tho men, and grace hem dide,</L>
<L>And thriste vnd&iacute;r foote cruelte adoun.</L>
<L N="3407">O myghty princ&euml;! this condic&iuml;oun</L>
<L>To your highness&euml; is ful &aacute;cordant,</L>
<L N="3409">And vnto god al-myghty ryght plesant.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="488" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(488)</HEAD>
<L N="3410">&para; Power withouten mercy, a kyng tourneth<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Potestas sine miseri|cordia vertit Regem in tirannum: ita scriptum est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Into a tyraunt, war &thorn;at feendly spek!</L>
<L>ffor in what man &thorn;at cruelte soiourneth,</L>
<L>Vnto his soule it is an odious spek.<MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3414">Tho men of god han nouthir look ne bek,</L>
<L>But if &thorn;at it be bekk&euml;s of manace,</L>
<L N="3416">Where as his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his R, is H.</NOTE> mercy folwe&thorn; moch&euml; grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="489" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(489)</HEAD>
<L N="3417">&para; Salomon in his prouerbis expressith,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prouerbi|arum <I>capitu|lo</I> xx<SUP>o</SUP>. Misericordia &amp; veritas Regem cus|todiunt; &amp; roboratur clemencia thronus eius.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Mercy and trouth&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">trouthe R, trouche H.</NOTE> wardeynes ben of kyng&euml;s;</L>
<L>And with iustice also,' as he witn&eacute;ssith,</L>
<L>'His trone is streng&thorn;ed:' what man &thorn;at a kyng is,</L>
<L N="3421">But if &thorn;at he, amongis o&thorn;ir thyng&euml;s,</L>
<L>Endow&euml;d he wi&thorn; all&euml; &thorn;is&euml; thre,</L>
<L N="3423">Men seyn he halteth in his hyge<NOTE PLACE="foot">hye R.</NOTE> degre.
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="124"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="490" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(490)</HEAD>
<L N="3424">&para; A noble and glorious kynde of vengeance<NOTE PLACE="foot">signe of mercy R.</NOTE> is,</L>
<L>A knyght to spare, whan &thorn;at he sle&euml; may.</L>
<L>Ther was a duc callid pisistaris,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De miseri|cordia ducis Pisistaris.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at a yong doghtir hadd&euml;, a fair<NOTE PLACE="foot">faire R.</NOTE> may,</L>
<L N="3428">Whiche with hir modir walkid on a day&mdash;</L>
<L>Naght seith the book whider, ne what to done,</L>
<L N="3430">But &thorn;us it schoop, as I schal tell&euml; sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="491" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(491)</HEAD>
<L N="3431">&para; A yong, fresche, lusty, wel by-sey&euml;n man</L>
<L>So brente in loue, he went&euml; for to dye,</L>
<L>Rauyssht of &thorn;e beaut&eacute; of &thorn;is womman,</L>
<L>This tendir<NOTE PLACE="foot">tendre R, tedir H.</NOTE> yong morsel, &thorn;is doghter, I seye.</L>
<L N="3435">And as &thorn;is yong man mette hir in &thorn;e weye,</L>
<L>He at a leep was at hir, and hir kyste:</L>
<L N="3437">The modir, angry wood, whan sche it wiste,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="492" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(492)</HEAD>
<L N="3438">&para; Sche right<NOTE PLACE="foot">right R, righ H.</NOTE> anon hir lord, &thorn;e duc, be-soghte<NOTE PLACE="foot">besought R, be-soghe H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To putte hym to &thorn;e deth for his trespas.</L>
<L>He seyd&euml; nay; to do &thorn;at neuere he &thorn;oghte:</L>
<L>"Schulle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Shulde R, Schullen H.</NOTE> we sleen hem &thorn;at louen vs? allas!<MILESTONE N="60a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3442">What schuld we &thorn;anne in the contr&aacute;rie cas,</L>
<L>That is to seyn, do<NOTE PLACE="foot">done to R, to do H.</NOTE> to our enemys?"</L>
<L N="3444">Thus seide &thorn;is duc, merc&iuml;able and wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="493" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(493)</HEAD>
<L N="3445">Allas! whi was &thorn;is womman so venge&aacute;ble?</L>
<L>Certes, in &thorn;at sche lakked wommanhede.</L>
<L>This louer hadde ben deede, it is no fable,</L>
<L>If &thorn;is duc hadde ben like<NOTE PLACE="foot">like R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> to hir in dede;</L>
<L N="3449">But mercy hym for-bad, any blood schede;</L>
<L>Sche and pitee weren of oon accord,</L>
<L N="3451">And senten pac&iuml;ence vnto &thorn;is lord.
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="125"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="494" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(494)</HEAD>
<L N="3452">And for as mochil as &thorn;at pac&iuml;ence</L>
<L>To mercy as in lyne of blood atteyneth,</L>
<L>Now wole I do my payne and diligence,</L>
<L>To telle how hir benignyte restreyneth</L>
<L N="3456">The feruent het&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;e hert&euml; pyneth</L>
<L>Wrech&euml; cruel to take, and scharp vengeaunce,</L>
<L N="3458">Of &thorn;at &thorn;e herte of man felith greuaunce.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="7" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 7.] &para; De Paciencia.</HEAD>
<LG N="495" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(495)</HEAD>
<L N="3459">Greg&oacute;rie seith, pac&iuml;enc&euml; verray<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated with an initial G, and a scroll work border on three sides.&mdash;G. England.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius dicit, paci|encia vera est, aliena mala equanimiter pati, &amp; contra eum qui mala irrogat, nullo dolore mori. &para; Socrates dicit, Nemo bene sapiens est qui paci|enciam non habet; viri enim boni est scire<NOTE PLACE="foot">scire R, fore H.</NOTE> pati &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is, of harm doon to man, soft&euml; souffraunce,</L>
<L>And naght be wrooth, by no manere of way,</L>
<L>With hym &thorn;at hath y-doon a man nusance.</L>
<L N="3463">Socrates seith, no mann&euml;s gouernance</L>
<L>Is wys, but it be by suffranc&euml; preeued;</L>
<L>A good man souffrith wrong, and is not greued.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="496" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(496)</HEAD>
<L N="3466">&para; The kynde of pac&iuml;ence is to sustene<MILESTONE N="60b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Myghtily wrong&euml;s, and hem neuere wreke,</L>
<L>But hem for-yeue, and wratthe &amp; irous tene</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e hert&euml; for to spere and steke.</L>
<L N="3470">Hir kynde is noght to lete a word out breke,</L>
<L>That harmful is; for hert&euml; voyde of ire</L>
<L N="3472">Hath naght wherwith to sette a tonge afire.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="497" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(497)</HEAD>
<L N="3473">&para; O pac&iuml;ent, o humble kyng benyngne!</L>
<L>O kyng Dauid! &thorn;i pac&iuml;ent meeknesse</L>
<L>Naght meeued was ageyn Semey maligne,</L>
<L>Whos hy malice and crabbid wikkidnesse</L>
<L N="3477">Yaf greet enchesoun to thy worthynesse</L>
<L>To veng&euml; the; but &thorn;i benyngnite</L>
<L N="3479">ffor-bad &thorn;yn hand to kyth&euml; cruelte.
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="126"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="498" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(498)</HEAD>
<L N="3480">&para; As this kyng on&euml;s cam to bahurim,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Regum 2<SUP>o</SUP>. Capitulo 16. Venit ergo Rex Dauid vsque bahu|rim &amp; ecce egrediebatur &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Out cam &thorn;is man, malic&iuml;ous Semey,</L>
<L>Sone of Gera, and swiche despite dide hym</L>
<L>And to his men, as by hym wenten they,</L>
<L N="3484">Castyng&euml; ston&euml;s vnto hym alwey,</L>
<L>That wondir was; for which, on Abusay<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dixit au|tem Abusay filius Saruie: Quare male|dicit canis iste? &amp;c. Vadam &amp; am|putabo [ca|put ejus R], &para; Et ait Rex: 'dimitte eum vt maledicit juxta precep|tum domini. Si forte respi|ciat dominus affliccionem meam, &amp; reddet<NOTE PLACE="foot">reddet R, reddit H.</NOTE> mihi bonum pro malediccione hac hodierna &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wolde haue hym slayn; but &thorn;e kyng seid&euml;, "nay!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="499" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(499)</HEAD>
<L N="3487">&para; "Lat hym curse, aftir &thorn;e comaund&euml;ment</L>
<L>Of god; whan he seeth myn afflicc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>And my disese, and my grevous turment,</L>
<L>He wole, for &thorn;is day&euml;s malic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="3491">Par &aacute;ventur&euml;, do me som guerdoun."</L>
<L>Thus vndirstonde I, write is in &thorn;e bible,</L>
<L N="3493">Whiche is a book autentik and credible.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="500" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(500)</HEAD>
<L N="3494">&para; The paci&euml;nce of Iob, men may nat hyde,<MILESTONE N="61a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De pacien|cia Regis Alexandri.</NOTE></L>
<L>The comoun voys wole algate it by-wreye;</L>
<L>And Alisaundre, whos fame is sprad ful wyde,</L>
<L>fful pac&iuml;ent was, as &thorn;e book&euml;s seye.</L>
<L N="3498">A sad wys knyght of his with lokk&euml;s greye,</L>
<L>Grucchynge ageyn his fleschely lust&euml;s, seide</L>
<L N="3500">Vnto his lord, and &thorn;us he hym vp breyde:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="501" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(501)</HEAD>
<L N="3501">&para; "O Alisaundre! it is vncouenable,</L>
<L>The for to haue of peple regyment,</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;i lust, bestial and miserable,</L>
<L>Hath qweynt thy resoun and entend&euml;ment</L>
<L N="3505">So ferforth, &thorn;at the het&euml; violent</L>
<L>Of leccherye is in &thorn;e, lord and sire;</L>
<L N="3507">Repreef, I dred&euml;, qwyt&euml; schal &thorn;in hire.
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="127"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="502" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(502)</HEAD>
<L N="3508">&para; "ffy! scham&euml;les vnworthy gouernour!"</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e knyght&euml;s tal&euml; was al endid,</L>
<L>The kyng answerde, "I know&euml; myn errour;"</L>
<L>And pac&iuml;ently seide, "I haue offendid;</L>
<L N="3512">I woot it wel; and it schal be amendid."</L>
<L>A man also to Iulius Cesar on&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De pacien|cia Iulii Cesaris.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3514">Crabbidly seid, and schrewdly<NOTE PLACE="foot">sharply R.</NOTE> for &thorn;e non&euml;s,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="503" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(503)</HEAD>
<L N="3515">&para; And among othir word&euml;s &thorn;at he speek,</L>
<L>"Iulius," quod he, "make it noght so tow,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tough R (<I>rymes:</I> ynough, hough)</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor of thy birthe art &thorn;ou noght wort a leek:</L>
<L>Whens &thorn;at &thorn;ou cam, men knowen wel I-now:</L>
<L N="3519">Wenest &thorn;ou naght &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">that R, &thorn;an H.</NOTE> I can tellen how</L>
<L>Thy fadir was a bakere? o, lat be!</L>
<L N="3521">Ne make it nat so qweynt&euml;, I pray the!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="504" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(504)</HEAD>
<L N="3522">&para; Smylynge, vnto hym spak &thorn;is Emperour:<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Whethir supposist &thorn;ou bet, &thorn;at noblesse</L>
<L>Begynne in me, or noblesse and honour</L>
<L>Deffaile in &thorn;e?" this quest&iuml;oun, I gesse,</L>
<L N="3526">Was, in swiche cas, but answer of softnesse;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at was seide in repreef of his name,</L>
<L N="3528">His pac&iuml;ence, as who<NOTE PLACE="foot">who R, swo H.</NOTE> seith, took<NOTE PLACE="foot">took it R.</NOTE> in game.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="505" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(505)</HEAD>
<L N="3529">&para; To &thorn;e chiualrous wor&thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">Chyualerous worthy R, chiualours wor&thorn; H.</NOTE> Scipio<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Pacien|cia Scipionis affricani bel|licosissimi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Aufrik, also speek on&euml;s a wight,</L>
<L>And seide, "in arm&euml;s durste he but smal do;</L>
<L>He faght but smal whan he cam to &thorn;e fight."</L>
<L N="3533">And paciently answerde he anon right,</L>
<L>"My modir me bare, a childe feeble and smal,</L>
<L N="3535">And forth me broghte, and no fightere at al."
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="128"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="506" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(506)</HEAD>
<L N="3536">&para; Senek seith, how &thorn;e kyng Antigone</L>
<L>Herde on&euml;s folk speke of hym wikkedly,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De benig|nitate [&amp;] paciencia Regis Anti|gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor ther nas<NOTE PLACE="foot">nas R, nat H.</NOTE> but a curtyn, as seith he,</L>
<L>Twixt hym and hem; and whan hys tyme he sy,</L>
<L N="3540">Aside he drow the curtyn sodenly,</L>
<L>And seid&euml;, "gooth hens, lest &thorn;e kyng yow here,</L>
<L N="3542">ffor &thorn;e curtyn ha&thorn; herde al your matere."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="507" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(507)</HEAD>
<L N="3543">&para; Of duc Pisistaris eek wil I telle:</L>
<L>He hadde a freend, arispus was his name,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De pacien|cia &amp; miseri|cordia ducis pisistaris supra nomi|nati.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche on&euml;s hastily, with word&euml;s felle</L>
<L>Rebukid so &thorn;is duc, &thorn;at it was schame</L>
<L N="3547">To heren it; and yit, with sorwe and grame,</L>
<L>He in despyt spette in &thorn;is duk&euml;s face;</L>
<L N="3549">And he &thorn;erto no word spak in &thorn;at place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="508" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(508)</HEAD>
<L N="3550">&para; He had him so in port &amp; word and chere,<MILESTONE N="62a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ryght as hym hadde be do no vilenye,</L>
<L>But luked forth in a freendely manere.</L>
<L>Now ther were in this duk&euml;s companye</L>
<L N="3554">His son&euml;s two, that busked hem in hye</L>
<L>To this Arispus, and wolden ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">full R, su H.</NOTE> fayn,</L>
<L N="3556">Nad hir fadir hem let, haue hym Islayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="509" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(509)</HEAD>
<L N="3557">&para; The next&euml; day after, this Arispus</L>
<L>To tak&euml; gan considerac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>How that he to &thorn;e duke mys-bare hym thus,</L>
<L>And mad&euml; mor&euml; waymentac&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="3561">Than I can make of nominacioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">now mensioun R.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>He wolde han slayn himselfe, it is no lese,</L>
<L>But that this duke broughte al to rest &amp; pees.
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="129"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="510" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(510)</HEAD>
<L N="3564">&para; Whan he knew how it with Arispus stood,</L>
<L>He dressid him to him, and &thorn;at as swith&euml;,</L>
<L>And bad him to be glad of cheere and mood;</L>
<L>He seide, and swoor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">swore R, swoor H.</NOTE> to him oft&euml; sith&euml;,</L>
<L N="3568">"As freendly wole I be, and stande as ny the</L>
<L>As I dide euere;" and thus his pac&iuml;encie</L>
<L N="3570">And meknesse hath qwenchid al<NOTE PLACE="foot">all R, as H.</NOTE> &thorn;is offence.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="511" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(511)</HEAD>
<L N="3571">&para; Salomon seith, in him is sapience<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon. Ubi est hu|militas, ibi sapientia. Origines: si humilis non fueris in te non potuit habitare gra|cia spiritus sancti.</NOTE></L>
<L>That is indewed with benyngne humblesse.</L>
<L>Grace of &thorn;e holy goost, no residence</L>
<L>Holdith in &thorn;at man &thorn;at lakk&eacute;th meeknesse.</L>
<L N="3575">God took vppon him humble buxumnesse</L>
<L>Whan he him wrappid in our mortell rynde:</L>
<L N="3577">That oughte a myrour be to al man-kynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">At the bottom of this page is the figure of a man in a pink jacket, lying on his back upon a patch of grass, and holding in his hands the end of a rope noose, with which he is pulling into its place stanza 512, left out at first, and then written in the margin opposite st. 511.&mdash;G. E.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="512" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(512)</HEAD>
<L N="3578">&para; Plesant to god was &thorn;e virginite<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bernardus dicit, Beata maria, ex virginitate placuit deo, sed ex humil|itate conce|pit deum. [<I>Written over stanza</I> 512.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his modir; but verray god &amp; man</L>
<L>Conseyued was thoru&yogh; &thorn;e humilite</L>
<L>Whiche he be-heeld in &thorn;at blyssed woman.</L>
<L N="3582">O humble maid&euml;! who is it &thorn;at can</L>
<L>The debonaire humbless&euml; tellen al,</L>
<L N="3584">Restynge in &thorn;y clenness&euml; virginal?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="513" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(513)</HEAD>
<L N="3585">&para; Thogh &thorn;at &thorn;e humble were a foul habyt,<MILESTONE N="62b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Basilius. Humilis licet habitu vilis sit, gloriosus tamen est virtutibus. Superbus autem si de|corus vide|atur aspectu tamen operi|bus vilis est. &para; Isodorus. Quamuis summus es humilitatem tene. Salo|mon. Quan|to maior, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it in vertu&euml;s glorious is he;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e proud man stant in ano&thorn;er plyt;</L>
<L>Thogh his array be fair &amp; fresche to se,</L>
<L N="3589">His ded&euml;s and his werk&euml;s foul&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">foule R, foul H.</NOTE> be.</L>
<L>What hy&yogh;e estate &thorn;at a man represente,</L>
<L N="3591">Humble to be, let hym sette his entente!
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="130"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="514" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(514)</HEAD>
<L N="3592">&para; Humylite verray, as seith Ces&aacute;rie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cesarius. Nunquam sine caritate vera humili|tas aut fuerat aut poterat esse. &para; Ysodorus. Nullum pre|mium cari|tati equatur, caritas enim virtutum om|nium optinet principatum. A regno dei se separant qui semetipsos a caritate dissociant.</NOTE></L>
<L>May neuere be with-outen charite;</L>
<L>And sche is a vertu most necessarie:</L>
<L>Among&euml;s all&euml; vertu&euml;s &thorn;at be,</L>
<L N="3596">Sche on hem alle opteeneth dignite.</L>
<L>They fro &thorn;e regne of god hem-self dyuyde,</L>
<L N="3598">That charite wayven and caste a-syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="515" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(515)</HEAD>
<L N="3599">&para; Right as a man ne may nat thider goo<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Anselmus. Et sicut sine via nullus peruenit quo tendit, Ita, sine caritate que dicta est via ab aposto|lo, non recte ambulare possumus in via dei. &para; Augustin|us. Habe caritatem &amp; fac quod vis, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where he purposeth hym, but if a way</L>
<L>Be thiderward, seint Amselm sei&thorn;, right so,</L>
<L>With-outen charite, men goo ne may</L>
<L N="3603">Aryght vnto godward: men mowen ay</L>
<L>Doon as him list, if &thorn;ei ben charitable;</L>
<L N="3605">But lakkynge it, is no &thorn;ing profitable.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="516" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(516)</HEAD>
<L N="3606">&para; Only keepyng of charitee vs preeveth,<MILESTONE N="63a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That we disciples ben of god almyghty.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius in moralibus. Omnipoten|tis eterni dei nos esse dis|cipulos sola custodia cari|tatis probat. &para; Scriptum est, Nemo quidem sanc|torum ad celestem glor|iam, nisi pacienciam seruando peruenit.</NOTE></L>
<L>What &thorn;ing it be &thorn;at harmeth man or greueth,</L>
<L>By goodnesse ouercome it paciently;</L>
<L N="3610">No seint to heuene comyth, as rede I,</L>
<L>But by kepynge of pac&iuml;ence, and how</L>
<L N="3612">Men may it ler&euml;, wole I schew&euml; yow.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="517" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(517)</HEAD>
<L N="3613">Take heede how, whan &thorn;at crist oure sau&euml;our</L>
<L>Was bobbid, and his visage al be-spet,</L>
<L>And gret despit doon him, and d&eacute;shonour,</L>
<L>Bounden and scourg&euml;d &amp; greuo&uacute;sly bett,</L>
<L N="3617">Crown&euml;d with thorne, nayl&euml;d to &thorn;e gybett,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it, for al this torm&eacute;nt, no word he speeke,</L>
<L N="3619">So was he pac&iuml;ent, benigne, and meke.
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="131"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="518" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(518)</HEAD>
<L N="3620">And syn our lord god was of swiche suffr&aacute;nce,</L>
<L>Thanne is it to his cr&euml;atur&euml; schame,</L>
<L>On greef to hym doon, take any venge&aacute;nce.</L>
<L>Man oght&euml; rathir sorowe for the blame</L>
<L>That god schal konne him &thorn;at hath done &thorn;e grame,</L>
<L>Than for &thorn;e harme &thorn;at &thorn;e greu&eacute;d ha&thorn; hent:</L>
<L N="3626">So doth &thorn;e charit&aacute;ble and pac&iuml;ent.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="8" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 8.] De Castitate.</HEAD>
<LG N="519" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(519)</HEAD>
<L N="3627">To chastite purp&oacute;se I now to haste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page, 63 <I>a</I>, has an illuminated initial T, and scroll bordering on three sides.&mdash;G. E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche couenable is, and conuenient,</L>
<L>Vn-to a kyng for to sauoure and taaste.</L>
<L>What princ&euml; &thorn;at with vnclennesse is brent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est, Nisi pu|dicitia sedeat in mente, nulla perfec|tio sequitur in opere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3631">And ther-in settith his luste and talent,</L>
<L>No perfyt dede or werk him folwe may:</L>
<L N="3633">Mochil, is hert&euml; chaast, to goddys pay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="520" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(520)</HEAD>
<L N="3634">Right as &thorn;e persone of a prince outward</L>
<L>Hon&uacute;red is wi&thorn; cloth&euml;s prec&iuml;ous,</L>
<L>So aughte his hert&euml; clo&thorn;id ben inward</L>
<L>With vertu, and hym kyth&euml; vertuous.</L>
<L N="3638">ffresche apparaile and hert&euml; leccherous<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Unsittynly ben in a Princ&euml; ioynt,</L>
<L N="3640">Nam&euml;ly in a cristen kyng enoynt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="521" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(521)</HEAD>
<L N="3641">&para; In as mochel as dignite of a kyng</L>
<L>Excedith othir folk in reuerence,</L>
<L>The more hym oght&euml; peyne hym, lest al &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Othir folk passe in vertuous excellence.</L>
<L N="3645">Honour no&yogh;t ell&euml;s is in &eacute;xistence</L>
<L>Than reuerenc&euml; &yogh;euen in witnesse</L>
<L N="3647">Of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of R, Or H.</NOTE> vertu, as &thorn;e scriptur&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">scripture doth R.</NOTE> expresse.
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="132"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="522" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(522)</HEAD>
<L N="3648">&para; Honur, whiche was goten vertuously,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R, <I>om.</I> H] Boecius dicit, Honor vir|tuose adqui|situs, non primo per dignitatem adquirebatur, sed dignitatis honor per virtutem ad|quisitus erat, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne was naght first by dignite purch&aacute;ced,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at Boec&euml; telle&thorn; &eacute;xpresly,</L>
<L>But dignitees honour was &eacute;mbraced</L>
<L N="3652">With vertu; dignite had ben vnlaced</L>
<L>And vngirt of honour, nad vertu be;</L>
<L N="3654">ffor vertu hath hir propre dignite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="523" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(523)</HEAD>
<L N="3655">&para; Aristotle counseilled Alisaundre,</L>
<L>To leccherye he noght enclyn&euml; scholde,</L>
<L>ffor it [is] hogg&euml;s lif, whiche were esclaundre<NOTE PLACE="foot">disclaundre R.</NOTE></L>
<L>To him, if he tho wei&euml;s tak&euml; wolde</L>
<L N="3659">That beest&euml;s resonles vsen and holde;</L>
<L>ffor of body it is destrucc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="3661">And eek of al vertu corrupcioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="524" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(524)</HEAD>
<L N="3662">&para; Syn thei, &thorn;at naght were<NOTE PLACE="foot">were R, neuer H.</NOTE> of cristen bapteme,</L>
<L>Counseill&euml;d men eschu&euml; leccherie,</L>
<L>Than oghte vs cristen men &thorn;at vic&euml; fleeme,</L>
<L>And swich&euml; lust&euml;s in vs mortifie.</L>
<L N="3666">Who so entendeth in-to blisse stye,<MILESTONE N="64a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That firy sparkle algate he moste qwenche,</L>
<L N="3668">And lust&euml;s leue, of lady and of wenche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="525" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(525)</HEAD>
<L N="3669">&para; The scripture se&iuml;&thorn;, no fornicatour,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ad Ephe|sios. v<SUP>o</SUP>. ffor|nicator non habebit here|ditatem in regno christi &amp; dei. Ad Ebreos, iij<SUP>o</SUP>. fforni|catores &amp; adulteros iudicabit deus.</NOTE></L>
<L>The regne of crist and god shal &eacute;nherite;</L>
<L>It seith eek, that him and &thorn;e aduoutour</L>
<L>God dem&euml; shal; he can hir labour qwyte</L>
<L N="3673">fful scharply, that in tho tweyn&euml; delite,</L>
<L>And so he wol&euml;, but<NOTE PLACE="foot">but yf R.</NOTE> correccioun</L>
<L N="3675">Be mann&euml;s scheeld, &amp; his proteccioun.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="526" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(526)</HEAD>
<L N="3676">&para; Affrican Scipio, &thorn;at noble knyght,</L>
<L>Whan he was xx<SUP>ti</SUP> and iiij of age,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De casti|tate Scipionis Affricani.</NOTE></L>
<L>And by prowesse, and by manhode &amp; myght</L>
<L>Cart&aacute;giens putte hadde into seru&aacute;ge,</L>
<L N="3680">Ther was a mayde sent him into host&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>Of yeer&euml;s ripe I-now, and of beaute</L>
<L N="3682">Most excellent that men myghte owher se.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="527" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(527)</HEAD>
<L N="3683">&para; And whan &thorn;is worthi &yogh;ong prince honurable,</L>
<L>This woman sigh, of hir he took good &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>Thynkynge &thorn;at she was of beaute able,</L>
<L>The worthieste on lyu&euml; for to queeme;</L>
<L N="3687">And in him multiplied thought&euml;s breeme;</L>
<L>But nath&euml;les, for al &thorn;is besy &thorn;ought,<NOTE PLACE="foot">thought R, &thorn;ough H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3689">Enquere he gan, if she wyf were, or nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="528" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(528)</HEAD>
<L N="3690">&para; Sche trouth&euml;d was to Iudibal, men seide,</L>
<L>A lord of &thorn;at Citee; and Scipio,</L>
<L>On a mynystre of his &thorn;e charg&euml; leide,</L>
<L>ffor hir fadir and modir blyu&euml; goo.</L>
<L N="3694">Thei at his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> hest&euml; cam vnto him tho;<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And in hir clen&euml; virginal estat,</L>
<L N="3696">Restor&euml;d he &thorn;is mayde inuiolat.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="529" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(529)</HEAD>
<L N="3697">&para; The gold eek &thorn;at for hir redempcioun</L>
<L>Purvey&euml;d was, for-&yogh;af he vtterly,</L>
<L>In help and increes and promoc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Of hir wedlok. and whan Iudibal sy</L>
<L N="3701">And knewe how scipio thus nobl[el]y</L>
<L>Demen&euml;d him, he was ful wel apayed</L>
<L N="3703">Of &thorn;at he grucchid first, and was affrayed.
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="134"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="530" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(530)</HEAD>
<L N="3704">&para; He went vnto testat&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">thestates R.</NOTE> of &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>And tolde hem al &thorn;e cas, as it befil;</L>
<L>And thei &thorn;is lord yaf loude<NOTE PLACE="foot">laude R.</NOTE> and hy renoun</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at; and all&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle R, al H.</NOTE> with oon hert and wil,</L>
<L N="3708">Submitted hem to &thorn;is princ&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">(? vnto &thorn;is prince) to this prynces wille R.</NOTE> gentil;</L>
<L>Thus hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> chaast and tendre gentillesse</L>
<L N="3710">Conqu&eacute;reth hert&euml;s, rather &thorn;an duresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="531" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(531)</HEAD>
<L N="3711">&para; Or marcus marcellus had &thorn;e citee</L>
<L>Of Ciracus&euml; taken or y-nome,</L>
<L>He leet do crye among&euml;s his meyne,</L>
<L>That whan &thorn;e citee he had ouercome,</L>
<L N="3715">And his folk ther-in entred<NOTE PLACE="foot">entred R, entreted H.</NOTE> were &amp; come,</L>
<L>Noon be so hardy, &thorn;e wommen oppresse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">to oppresse R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3717">Ne touche hem by no wey of vnclennesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="532" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(532)</HEAD>
<L N="3718">&para; Ther was also a seemly fresshe yong man,</L>
<L>To whom natur&euml; swiche fauour had lent<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De casti|tate cuiusdam iuuenis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of schap and beaute, &thorn;at &thorn;er nas womman</L>
<L>That on&euml;s had a look on hym dispent,</L>
<L N="3722">But &thorn;at hir hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> yaf flesshely consent;<MILESTONE N="65a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And nath&euml;les eschu&euml;d he &thorn;e taast</L>
<L N="3724">Of vnclennesse, and kepte his body chaast.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="533" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(533)</HEAD>
<L N="3725">&para; By tokn&euml;s knew he hire vnclene entente,</L>
<L>And with his nayl&euml;s cracched he his face,</L>
<L>And scocched it with knyu&euml;s, and to-rente,</L>
<L>And it so wonderly &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;us, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> gan difface,</L>
<L N="3729">That his beaute refus&euml;d hadde hir place:</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is dide he, hir hert&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">hertes R, hert H.</NOTE> to remewe</L>
<L>ffrom him, and make hem vnclenn&eacute;sse eschue.
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="534" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(534)</HEAD>
<L N="3732">&para; Ierom tellith, agayn Iouinian,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De casti|tate cuiusdam temine Vlie numcupate.</NOTE></L>
<L>A faire womman, a maid&euml; clept Vlie,</L>
<L>Y-wedded was vnto an ag&euml;d man,</L>
<L>A Romayn, smyten with &thorn;e pall&euml;sie;</L>
<L N="3736">But sche in chastite was sette so hye,</L>
<L>That an ensaumple verrayliche was sche</L>
<L N="3738">To all&euml; tho &thorn;at lou&euml;d chastitee.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="535" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(535)</HEAD>
<L N="3739">&para; Hire housbonde herde on&egrave;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">ones hade R, herde oned H.</NOTE> an enemy,</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at he hadd&euml;, spoke<NOTE PLACE="foot">that said and spake R, &thorn;at he hadd spoke H.</NOTE> in his repreef,</L>
<L>That his breth stank, as &thorn;at he stode him by;</L>
<L>Wher-of he toke gret heuynesse and greef;</L>
<L N="3743">He goth hoom to his wyf, and &thorn;is mescheef</L>
<L>fful heuely to hire he gan compleyne,</L>
<L N="3745">And &thorn;us of hire he gan to aske and freyne:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="536" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(536)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Whi, wyf," quod he, "han ye noght or this tyme</L>
<L>I-warn&euml;d me how &thorn;at it wi&thorn; me stood?"</L>
<L>"Sire, it was nought," quod sche, "aspied by me;</L>
<L>I held your breth ay also suete and good</L>
<L N="3750">As other menn&euml;s ben; I vnderstood<MILESTONE N="65b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Non othir, ne yit do in sothfastnesse."</L>
<L N="3752">fful few&euml; men had sche kist, as I gesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="537" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(537)</HEAD>
<L N="3753">&para; She hily was to preyse and to commende,</L>
<L>That naght ne knewe by othir menn&egrave;s mouthes</L>
<L>Hir makis vice: it<NOTE PLACE="foot">it R, at H.</NOTE> was al wel, sche wende.</L>
<L>To fynd&euml; many swiche ful vnkouthe is;</L>
<L N="3757">Lat vs awayte wel whan &thorn;e wynd south is</L>
<L>And north at on&egrave;s blowynge on &thorn;e sky,</L>
<L N="3759">And fynd&euml; swiche an hepe &thorn;an hardily.
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="136"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="538" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(538)</HEAD>
<L N="3760">&para; Plato, his patrimoygne and his contree<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Platonis castitate.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lefte and for-sook, and dwelte in wildernesse,</L>
<L>ffor to restreyn&euml; fleschely nycete;</L>
<L>And his disciples lou&euml;d so clennesse,</L>
<L N="3764">And for to fallen hadden swiche gastnesse,</L>
<L>Hir ey&euml;n they out of hir heed&euml;s brente,</L>
<L>Lest sighte of hem, spott&euml; myght<NOTE PLACE="foot">myght spotte R.</NOTE> her entente.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="539" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(539)</HEAD>
<L N="3767">&para; Demostenes his hand&euml;s on&euml;s putte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Domes|tenes<NOTE PLACE="foot">Demostenis R.</NOTE> casti|tate.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a wommann&euml;s bosom iapyngly,</L>
<L>Of fac&euml; faire, but of hir body a slutte:</L>
<L>"With yow to del&euml;," seide he, "what schal I</L>
<L N="3771">Yow yeu&euml;?" "xl pens," quod sche, soothly.</L>
<L>He seyd&euml; nay, so dere he by&euml; nolde</L>
<L>A thyng for whiche &thorn;at him repent&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">repent H, R.</NOTE> schulde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="540" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(540)</HEAD>
<L N="3774">&para; I fynde, how two doughtres of a duchesse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De casti|tate duarum filiarum cuiusdam ducisse.</NOTE></L>
<L>The fleschely touches of men for to fle,</L>
<L>When men of Hongary hem wolde oppresse,</L>
<L>In c&oacute;nseruynge of hir virginite,</L>
<L N="3778">Thei hem purveyded a good sotilte:<MILESTONE N="66a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thei chikn&euml;s flesche putte vndirne&thorn;e hir pappes,</L>
<L N="3780">Hem to defend&euml; from vnclenly happes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="541" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(541)</HEAD>
<L N="3781">&para; Be-holde, of wommen here a noble wyle!</L>
<L>In schort avis&euml;ment, who can do bet?</L>
<L>Bi that &thorn;is flesche &thorn;us hadde leyen a while,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at it was y-chauf&euml;d wel and hete,</L>
<L N="3785">It stank so foul&euml;, &thorn;at it ha&thorn; I-lette</L>
<L>Tho men, &thorn;at wery &thorn;ei were of hir pray,</L>
<L N="3787">And f&oacute;rsook &thorn;e wommen, and went hir way.
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="542" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(542)</HEAD>
<L N="3788">&para; O wommanhode! in &thorn;e regne&thorn; vertu</L>
<L>So excellent, &thorn;at to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to R, so H.</NOTE> feble is my witt</L>
<L>To &eacute;xpresse it; wherefor I am eschu</L>
<L>To melde<NOTE PLACE="foot">medle R.</NOTE> or make a long sermoun of it.</L>
<L N="3792">Som mann&euml;s mouth yit wolde I were I-schet,</L>
<L>That vice of wommen spare&thorn; nought<NOTE PLACE="foot">not R, nough H.</NOTE> bywreye,</L>
<L N="3794">ffor all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle R, al H.</NOTE> sooth&euml;s ben nought for to seie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="543" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(543)</HEAD>
<L N="3795">&para; But for to talk&euml; forth of contynence</L>
<L>Or chastite,&mdash;who-so chaast lyu&euml; schal,</L>
<L>Moot scourge his fleschely lust with abstinence,</L>
<L>Thrist&euml; him dowyn, yeue him no place at al:</L>
<L N="3799">Met&euml;s &amp; drynk&euml;s make a soul&euml; thral,</L>
<L>If &thorn;e body be reul&euml;d by excesse;</L>
<L N="3801">ffor-thi it nedeth take of hem &thorn;e lesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="544" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(544)</HEAD>
<L N="3802">&para; Excesse of mete and drynke is womb&euml;s frende,</L>
<L>And wombe is next to oure membres priue;</L>
<L>Glotonye is ful plesant to &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>To leccheri&euml; redy path is sche.</L>
<L N="3806">The fend lyth in a-wayte of oure freelte,<MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And stireth a man to drink&euml;s delicat,</L>
<L N="3808">To make agayn&euml;s chastite debat.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="545" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(545)</HEAD>
<L N="3809">&para; A man schulde ete and drynke in swiche a wise</L>
<L>As may be to his helth&euml;s s&uacute;stenynge,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;e doctrine of Senek &thorn;e wise.</L>
<L>Sum man drynketh the wyn &thorn;at is wenynge;</L>
<L N="3813">Than<NOTE PLACE="foot">When R.</NOTE> he drynke&thorn; his witt: more is preysinge</L>
<L>And honurable, a man compleyne of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of R, or H.</NOTE> thrist,</L>
<L>Than dronken be, whan he &thorn;e cuppe ha&thorn; kist.
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="138"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="546" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(546)</HEAD>
<L N="3816">&para; Thus seid&euml; Ierom vn-to a virgyne:</L>
<L>"O doghter, syn thapostle sor&euml; dredde<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronimus ad filiam vir|ginem. 'O filia,' inquit, 'si apostolus castigauit corpus &amp; in seruitutem redegit.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Lust of his flesche, and dide his body peyne,</L>
<L>And heeld it lowe, and sympl&euml;ly it fedde,</L>
<L N="3820">Wherthoru&yogh; &thorn;e vice of vnclennesse he fledde,</L>
<L>Of continence how maist &thorn;ou siker be,</L>
<L N="3822">Of food&euml; delicat &thorn;at hast plente,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="547" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(547)</HEAD>
<L N="3823">&para; And specialy now in &thorn;i youth&euml;s hete<NOTE PLACE="foot">hete R, hede H.</NOTE>?"</L>
<L>ffor who so wilneth to be contynent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca. Si continenciam diligis, cir|cumcide su|perflua &amp; voluptuosa.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many a lust superflu mot he lete,</L>
<L>And lykerous; by mesure, his talent</L>
<L N="3827">Mes&uacute;re he moot; whan resoun is regent</L>
<L>Of man, &thorn;an regne&thorn; no delicacie;</L>
<L N="3829">Resoun, a man defendeth fro folye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="548" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(548)</HEAD>
<L N="3830">&para; The wyn&euml;s delicat, and swete and strong,</L>
<L>Causen ful many an inconuenience;</L>
<L>If &thorn;at a man outrageously hem fonge,</L>
<L>Thei birien<NOTE PLACE="foot">birien R, biren H.</NOTE> wit, and f&oacute;rbeden scilence</L>
<L N="3834">Of conseil; thei outraien pacience,<MILESTONE N="67a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thei kyndlen ire, and firen liccherie,</L>
<L N="3836">And causen both body and soul&euml; dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="549" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(549)</HEAD>
<L N="3837">&para; And trew&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="foot">trewly H, truly R.</NOTE> it is ful perilous</L>
<L>Vnto a princ&euml;, whiche &thorn;at hath a land</L>
<L>In gouernance, in &thorn;at be vic&iuml;ous;</L>
<L>It nedeth him take heede vnto his hand,</L>
<L N="3841">&THORN;at that vic&euml; him combre not; for and</L>
<L>It do, he schal noght regn&euml; but a throwe:</L>
<L N="3843">fful many a man ha&thorn; &eacute;xcesse ouerthrowe.
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="550" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(550)</HEAD>
<L N="3844">&para; Of babiloyn&euml;, &thorn;e kyng Baltasar,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Danielis vi<SUP>o</SUP>. Eadem nocte inter|fectus est Baltasar, Rex Caldeus, &amp; Darius medus successit in regno, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nat hadd&euml; ben I-pryu&euml;d of his lyf,</L>
<L>If he of dronkeness&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">drunkenesse R, dronkenes H.</NOTE> hadde be war;</L>
<L>But for &thorn;at he &thorn;erin was d&eacute;fectyf,</L>
<L N="3848">It of his deth was verray causatyf;</L>
<L>By nyghtertale he was slayn by kyng d&aacute;rie;</L>
<L N="3850">Thus payeth glotoun &eacute;xcesse hir sal&aacute;rie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="551" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(551)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thorugh drunkenesse, how took his deth Nabal?<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Regum I. capitulo xxv<SUP>o</SUP>. Cor Nabal iocundum erat ebrius enim nimis, &amp;c. Machabeo|rum xxviij<SUP>o</SUP>. &para; Et cum inebriatus esset Simon &amp; filii eius, surexit tholo|meus, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>And how slow Tholome also Symoun?</L>
<L>Allas! &thorn;at drynk&euml; so man seru&euml; schal!</L>
<L>How leid&euml; Loth&euml;s doghtres hem a-down</L>
<L N="3855">By hir fadir? whan his discrec&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Was dreynt with wyn, he with hem fleschely delte,</L>
<L N="3857">And &thorn;erof no thing ne wist&euml; nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">nor R, or H.</NOTE> feelte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="552" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(552)</HEAD>
<L N="3858">&para; How was eek Olofern&euml;, by Iudith<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Genesis xix<SUP>o</SUP>. Veni, inebriemus eum vino, dormiamus|que cum eo, vt reseruare possimus ex patre nostro semen, &amp;c. Iudith. capi|tulo 22<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>The womman slayn, but &thorn;orugh his drunkenesse?</L>
<L>What prince it be, &thorn;at spotted is &thorn;erwith,</L>
<L>His welthe ha&thorn; but a brotil stablenesse:</L>
<L N="3862">Of swich&euml; stories mo wolde I expresse,<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But for I noght ne can, I lete hem passe;</L>
<L N="3864">I am as lewed and dulle as is an asse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="553" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(553)</HEAD>
<L N="3865">&para; With litel food&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">foode R, food H.</NOTE> c&oacute;ntent is nat&uacute;re;</L>
<L>And bet &thorn;e body farith wi&thorn; a lite,</L>
<L>Than whan it charged is out of mes&uacute;re.</L>
<L>Look&euml; what &thorn;ing may &thorn;e body profite,</L>
<L N="3869">And &thorn;e soule in &thorn;e sam&euml; schal delite;</L>
<L>What &thorn;ing &thorn;at it distempereth &amp; dissesith,</L>
<L N="3871">The soule it hurteth, for it god displesith.
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="140"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="554" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(554)</HEAD>
<L N="3872">&para; Wratth&euml;, &thorn;e body of man inward fretith,</L>
<L>And god &thorn;er-wi&thorn; displesid is ful sore;</L>
<L>Envie also of god and man hir getith</L>
<L>Lik thank and ese, and schal do euermore;</L>
<L N="3876">And leccherie, as techi&thorn; smert&euml;s lore,</L>
<L>The body wastith, and &thorn;e soul&euml; grevith,</L>
<L N="3878">And food&euml; delicat &thorn;erto man meevith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="555" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(555)</HEAD>
<L N="3879">&para; Be-holde also, whan &thorn;at &thorn;e paunche is ful,</L>
<L>A fum&euml; clymbith vp in-to &thorn;e heed,</L>
<L>And maki&thorn; a man al lustles and al<NOTE PLACE="foot">all R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> dul;</L>
<L>He vexith<NOTE PLACE="foot">wexeth R.</NOTE> heuy as a peece of leed.</L>
<L N="3883">Who-so &thorn;at &thorn;an wold&euml; yeue him reed</L>
<L>To looke in a book of deuoc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="3885">I trowe in ydel were his moc&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="556" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(556)</HEAD>
<L N="3886">&para; But conseil him to trotte vnto &thorn;e wyn,</L>
<L>And, for al his excesse and his outrage,</L>
<L>He &thorn;erto wole assent&euml; wel and fyn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er&euml; wole he outen<NOTE PLACE="foot">uttre R.</NOTE> his lang&aacute;ge,</L>
<L N="3890">And do to Bachus and Venus hom&aacute;ge;<MILESTONE N="68a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor non of hem two can be wel from othir,</L>
<L N="3892">Thei loue as vel<NOTE PLACE="foot">wele R.</NOTE> as doth sustir &amp; brothir.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="557" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(557)</HEAD>
<L N="3893">And aftir moot he rown&euml; with a pilwe,</L>
<L>His lyfles resouns &thorn;er&euml; to despende.</L>
<L>We beest&euml;s resonable, allas! whi wil we</L>
<L>Ageyn resoun werrye, and hir offende?</L>
<L N="3897">O good&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">goode R, good H.</NOTE> god! thy grac&euml; to vs sende,</L>
<L>That we may fle suche superfluite,</L>
<L N="3899">And al &thorn;ing that is foo to chastite!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="9" TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000207.tif" N="141">
<HEAD>[&sect; 9.] De Regis Magnanimitate.</HEAD>
<LG N="558" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(558)</HEAD>
<L N="3900">Off magnanimite now wole I trete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated.&mdash;G. E.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is to seyn, strong herte or grete corage,</L>
<L>Whiche in knyghthode ha&thorn; stablisshed hir sete.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sete R, fete H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ye, gracious Prince, of blode and of lynage</L>
<L N="3904">Descendid ben, to haue it in vsage;</L>
<L>Mars ha&thorn; euer ben frend to &yogh;our wor&thorn;i lyne;</L>
<L N="3906">Ye moot of kynd&euml; to manhode enclyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="559" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(559)</HEAD>
<L N="3907">He &thorn;at is strong of corage and of herte,&mdash;</L>
<L>Yf he lordschip&euml;s haue, or grete richesse,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at fortun&euml;s stynge hym ouerthwerte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fortune . . ouerthwert R, fortunes . . ouerthwete H.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Is alwey on<NOTE PLACE="foot">one R.</NOTE> in welthe and in distresse;</L>
<L N="3911">He, lucre and los, weyeth in euenesse;</L>
<L>He setti&thorn; litel by good temperel;</L>
<L N="3913">How &thorn;e worlde schape, he taki&thorn; it ay wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="560" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(560)</HEAD>
<L N="3914">&para; But for to speke of corage of a kyng,<MILESTONE N="68b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he of his peple owe&thorn; be so cheer,</L>
<L>That hir profet he moot for any &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Promot&euml; wit his myght and his power.</L>
<L N="3918">&para; And for his reme and him take him so neer,</L>
<L>That vnto &thorn;e peril&euml;s of bataille</L>
<L N="3920">He moot him putt&euml;, and in hem trauaylle,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="561" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(561)</HEAD>
<L N="3921">&para; And in diffense of holy chirche also,</L>
<L>And for oure feith putte him in iupartye<NOTE PLACE="foot">iuperdie R, partye H.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Othir causes ben ther but few&euml; mo,</L>
<L>Whi a kyng aughte to batayl&euml; hym hye,</L>
<L N="3925">And in tho causes drede him not to dye,</L>
<L>But kythe hym a good knyght a-mong his foos:</L>
<L N="3927">Thus wonne is magnanymyte&euml;s loos.
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="142"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="562" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(562)</HEAD>
<L N="3928">&para; Right as we seen by reson and nat&uacute;re,</L>
<L>Part of mannys body diffendeth al;</L>
<L>As an arme putte&thorn; him in &aacute;uenture</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e body, &thorn;at nat perische it schal,</L>
<L N="3932">Right so a kyng&euml;s chert&euml; special,</L>
<L>If he god loue, and his peple, &amp; his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his, <I>om.</I> R.</NOTE> land,</L>
<L>Whan nede is, mot diffende hem wi&thorn; his hande.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="563" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(563)</HEAD>
<L N="3935">&para; Thoru&yogh; grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> emprises wonne is hy renoun;</L>
<L>Renoun is call&euml;d glorie &amp; honour;</L>
<L>Magnanimite ha&thorn; &thorn;is condic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>That in bataile, how scharp &thorn;at be &thorn;e stour,</L>
<L N="3939">Hym leuere is to suffre deth&euml;s schour,</L>
<L>Than cowardly and scham&euml;fully flee,</L>
<L N="3941">So manly of cur&aacute;ge and herte is he.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="564" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(564)</HEAD>
<L N="3942">&para; He medleth neuere but of &thorn;ing&euml;s grete,<MILESTONE N="69a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And hye, and vertuous; he neuere is meeved</L>
<L>With smal&euml; thing&euml;s, as the book&euml;s trete;</L>
<L>And swiche a drede ha&thorn; for to be repreued,</L>
<L N="3946">That vnto &thorn;ing &thorn;at may be knowe or preued</L>
<L>ffor vilonous, or foul, or r&eacute;preeu&aacute;ble,</L>
<L N="3948">He neuere obeie&thorn;, &thorn;is kny&yogh;t honur&aacute;ble.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="565" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(565)</HEAD>
<L N="3949">&para; Thane I rede of oon clepet<NOTE PLACE="foot">I haue yredde of one clept R.</NOTE> Coadrus,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De mag|nanimitate Coadri Prin|cipis excer|citus athe|niensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>That was prince of &thorn;e oost of Athinyens,</L>
<L>How in &thorn;e feeld a law&euml; made was &thorn;us</L>
<L>Twixt his host and hem of Polipolens&mdash;</L>
<L N="3953">With triumph&euml; schuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde R, schuld H.</NOTE> &thorn;at part go &thorn;ens,</L>
<L>Whos duc or Princ&euml; were vnarm&euml;d slawe</L>
<L N="3955">In habit straung&euml;; lo! swiche was &thorn;e lawe.
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="143"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="566" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(566)</HEAD>
<L N="3956">&para; Him leuer was him selfen for to dye,</L>
<L>And his men liu&euml;, &thorn;an se hem be-stad</L>
<L>So streit&euml;, &thorn;at by violent maistrie</L>
<L>His foos hadde hem venqwissht or ouer-lad.</L>
<L N="3960">A-day&euml;s now is non swiche chierte had;</L>
<L>Algat&euml;s I ne can nat seen it vsid,</L>
<L N="3962">Knyght&euml;s ben loth &thorn;erof to ben accused.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="567" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(567)</HEAD>
<L N="3963">&para; O worthi Prince! I truste in &yogh;our manhode,</L>
<L>Medlid wi&thorn; prudence and discrec&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>That &yogh;e schulle mak&euml; many a kny&yogh;tly rode,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pride of oure foos thristen adoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hoccleve's trust was fulfild at Agincourt, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3967">Manhode and witt conqu&eacute;ren hy renoun;</L>
<L>And qwo-so<NOTE PLACE="foot">who so R.</NOTE> lakki&thorn; outhir of &thorn;e tweyne,</L>
<L N="3969">Of arm&euml;s wanti&thorn; &thorn;e brid&eacute;l and reyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="568" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(568)</HEAD>
<L N="3970">&para; Yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">Yf R, Of H.</NOTE> &thorn;e ordre of knyghthode be resceyu&euml;d,<MILESTONE N="69b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>fful nedeful is a man to be prudent,</L>
<L>Ell&euml;s &thorn;at host may lightly be disceyu&euml;d</L>
<L>That is vnto his gouernance I-bent;</L>
<L N="3974">Presumpc&iuml;on<NOTE PLACE="foot">Presumptuous R.</NOTE> is disobedient</L>
<L>Al day, and by wisdom not will him gie,</L>
<L N="3976">All iustifieth his obst&yacute;nacie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="569" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(569)</HEAD>
<L N="3977">&para; Ofte in batail&euml;s hath be seen or this,</L>
<L>A syd&euml; suffred hath discomfiture,</L>
<L>Whiche an vnwys heed gi&euml;d hath amys.</L>
<L>What knyght on hym takith &thorn;at charge or cure,</L>
<L N="3981">If he in knyghtly honur schal endure,</L>
<L>Him oghte endow&euml;d ben of sapience,</L>
<L N="3983">And haue in arm&euml;s greet experience.
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="144"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="570" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(570)</HEAD>
<L N="3984">&para; Experience and art in a<NOTE PLACE="foot">a R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> bataille,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e prudent knyght mor&euml; may profite,</L>
<L>Than hardinesse or forc&euml; may auaille</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at &thorn;erof knowe&thorn; noght or lite.</L>
<L N="3988">Hardinesse, in effecte, nat worth a myte</L>
<L>Is to victorious conclus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="3990">But wi&thorn; hym medle art, wit, and resoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="571" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(571)</HEAD>
<L N="3991">&para; Whan reueled wit and manly<NOTE PLACE="foot">reuled . . manly R, reueled . . namly H.</NOTE> hardynesse</L>
<L>Ben knytte to-gidre, as &yogh;ok of mariage,</L>
<L>Ther folowe&thorn; of vict&oacute;rie &thorn;e swetnesse;</L>
<L>ffor to sette on hym whettith his cor&aacute;ge,</L>
<L N="3995">And wit restreyne his wil can &amp; aswage</L>
<L>In tym&euml; du&euml;, and in<NOTE PLACE="foot">due and R.</NOTE> couen&aacute;ble;</L>
<L N="3997">And thus tho two ioynt ben ful profitable.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="572" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(572)</HEAD>
<L N="3998">But be a knyght wys or corag&euml;ous,<MILESTONE N="70a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or haue hem bothe at on&egrave;s at his lust,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at his herte of good be d&eacute;sirous,</L>
<L>On his manhode is ther but litel trust.</L>
<L N="4002">God graunt&euml; knyght&egrave;s rubbe away the rust</L>
<L>Of couetise, if it hir hert&euml;s cancre,</L>
<L>And graunte hem picche in souffisance hir ancre.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="10" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 10.] Quod rex non debet felicitatem suam ponere in diuiciis.</HEAD>
<LG N="573" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(573)</HEAD>
<L N="4005">Now, for as moche as magnanymyte</L>
<L>May no foot holde, if &thorn;at &thorn;e herte of man</L>
<L>Gretly vnto richesse enclyn&euml;d be,</L>
<L>Than is &thorn;e best&euml; reed &thorn;at I see can,</L>
<L N="4009">A kyng &thorn;er-in delyte hym naght; for whan</L>
<L>His herte is in &thorn;at vic&euml; ficched hye,</L>
<L N="4011">Smal prowesse in hym wole it signifie.
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="145"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="574" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(574)</HEAD>
<L N="4012">And if a kyng&euml;s honour schal be queynt</L>
<L>With a foul and a<NOTE PLACE="foot">a R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> wrecched couetise,</L>
<L>His peples trust in hym schal be ful feynt;</L>
<L>A kyng may naght gou&eacute;rne hym in &thorn;at wise;</L>
<L N="4016">The coueitous may do no gret emprise;</L>
<L>ffor whan his hert&euml; lurketh in his cofre,</L>
<L N="4018">His body to batayle he dar not profre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="575" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(575)</HEAD>
<L N="4019">If &thorn;at a kyng sette his felicite</L>
<L>Principally on rychesse &amp; moneye,</L>
<L>His peple it torne&thorn; to aduersite,</L>
<L>ffor he ne rekke&thorn; in what wise or weye</L>
<L N="4023">He pile hem: allas! &thorn;at kyng&euml;s nobleye<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Turn&euml; schulde into style of tirannye!</L>
<L N="4025">Allas! the peril, harme, and vilenye!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="576" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(576)</HEAD>
<L N="4026">&para; God I byseeche, your hert to<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert to R, herte H.</NOTE> enlumyne,</L>
<L>Grac&iuml;ous princ&euml;, &thorn;at &thorn;e feend our foo</L>
<L>No power hau&euml; so your hert&euml; myne,</L>
<L>But of his grac&euml; kep&euml; yow ther-fro,</L>
<L N="4030">And grant&euml; yow to gouern&euml; yow so</L>
<L>As most holsom is for bod&yacute; and soule;</L>
<L N="4032">That desire I, by God and by seynt Poule.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="577" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(577)</HEAD>
<L N="4033">&para; Whan that Marcus Curcius, a Romeyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Qualiter Marcus Cur|cius dixit, quod mallet diuites ha|bere suo man|dato obedi|entes, quam diues ipsemet esse.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Beneventans seeg&euml; leide,</L>
<L>ffor he was poore, as &thorn;at &thorn;ey herd&euml; seyn,</L>
<L>They a grete somme of gold hym sente, &amp; preyde</L>
<L>Withdrawe his seege; and he answerde and seide,</L>
<L>"To hem retourneth / &thorn;at yow hider sente,</L>
<L N="4039">And thus to hem declareth myn entente:
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="146"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="578" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(578)</HEAD>
<L N="4040">&para; "Seye hem, Marcus Curc&iuml;us leuer is</L>
<L>Rich&euml; men haue at his command&euml;ment,</L>
<L>Than to be riche hym-self; tell&euml; hem this:</L>
<L>He may with gold not be corrupt, ne blent;</L>
<L N="4044">Of force of men eek, &thorn;ey ben impotent</L>
<L>To venqwisshe hym; for &thorn;ere hir art schal faile,</L>
<L N="4046">Hir blynd&euml; profers schal hem noght auaile."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="579" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(579)</HEAD>
<L N="4047">&para; To Alisaundre, as I schal tellen here,</L>
<L>A knyght, whiche was vnto hym spec&iuml;al,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Refert Va|lerius quali|ter quidam miles Alex|andri argue|bat eum de sua cupidi|tate.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thus spake, and blamed hym in &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>He seide, "if oure godd&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">goddes R, gooddes H.</NOTE> thy body smal,</L>
<L N="4051">To thi gredy desire had maad egal,<MILESTONE N="71a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;e world hadd&euml; nou&yogh;t be s&uacute;ffisant</L>
<L N="4053">To han receyu&euml;d so large a Geaunt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="580" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(580)</HEAD>
<L N="4054">&para; "ffor with &thorn;i ri&yogh;t honde, thow &thorn;e orient</L>
<L>Shuldest han touchid, I am sure of &thorn;at;</L>
<L>And with &thorn;i lift honde, eke &thorn;e occident;</L>
<L>Now, syn &thorn;at &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> body answ&eacute;rith nat</L>
<L N="4058">Vnto &thorn;i will&euml;, what may<NOTE PLACE="foot">shall R.</NOTE> I sey, what?</L>
<L>Ethir &thorn;ou art a man, or god, or nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="4060">Mechil of &thorn;e, merueyle I in my &thorn;ought.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="581" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(581)</HEAD>
<L N="4061">&para; "If &thorn;ou be god, thow folow most his trace,</L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t men of her gode robbe or be-reue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nor reue R.</NOTE></L>
<L>But hem releue, &amp; do hem ese and grace.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou be man, considere eke, by thy leue,</L>
<L N="4065">&THORN;ou art mort&eacute;l, &thorn;ou mayst be dede or eue.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou be no &thorn;ing, &thorn;e putte out of mynde,</L>
<L N="4067">Os<NOTE PLACE="foot">As R.</NOTE> he &thorn;at is of no nature or kynde.
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="147"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="582" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(582)</HEAD>
<L N="4068">&para; "Ther is no hye estate so sadde and stable,</L>
<L>Remembre wele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wele R, wile H.</NOTE> lat it nat be for-&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>But he to falle in perile is ful able.</L>
<L>By deeth, a leon maad is bridd&euml;s mete,</L>
<L N="4072">And best&euml;s also his flessh gnawe &amp; frete."</L>
<L>&THORN;e answere of &thorn;e kyng, naught haue I herde;</L>
<L N="4074">My booke not telleth how he was answerde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="583" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(583)</HEAD>
<L N="4075">&para; Senek seith, the po&euml;r<NOTE PLACE="foot">poore R.</NOTE> Diogenes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Pauper diogenes dicior erat Alexandro.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kyng Alisandre in richess&euml; past,</L>
<L>ffor he ne my&yogh;t, as he seith dout&euml;les,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue hym so mochil golde, ne on hym cast,</L>
<L N="4079">&para; As he refus&euml; wolde: O! at the last,<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Men &thorn;inke shullen &thorn;ei to mochil<NOTE PLACE="foot">moche R.</NOTE> haue had,</L>
<L N="4081">And of &thorn;is worldys muk be ful vnglad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="584" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(584)</HEAD>
<L N="4082">Desire of good, a king mot leye apart,</L>
<L>And peyne him to purch&aacute;se him a good fame;</L>
<L>Ther-in lat him laboure, and doon his art;<NOTE PLACE="foot">part R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther nys no &thorn;ing vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto = comparable to.</NOTE> a worthi name;</L>
<L N="4086">And if a kyng it lakke, it were his shame,</L>
<L>And shame is contrarie vnto worthynesse;</L>
<L N="4088">Gode lose desserued,<NOTE PLACE="foot">loos decerued R.</NOTE> is grettest richesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="585" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(585)</HEAD>
<L N="4089">&para; And for largess&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">largesse R, larges H.</NOTE> wynne&thorn; gode renoun,</L>
<L>Ther-of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Therof, <I>pron.</I> throf.</NOTE> &thorn;ink I now, to trete a litil stounde;</L>
<L>A prince &amp; kyng of al a regioun</L>
<L>Mot avaric&euml; thrist a-doune to grounde;</L>
<L N="4093">To hym &thorn;at lith in hell&euml; depe I-bounde,</L>
<L>The,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or is 'the' an article?</NOTE> auarice, by-tak&euml; I to kepe;</L>
<L N="4095">Thow pyn&euml;peny,<NOTE PLACE="foot">pynchepeny R.</NOTE> ther ay mot &thorn;ou slepe!
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="148"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="586" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(586)</HEAD>
<L N="4096">&para; Golde wolde, for<NOTE PLACE="foot">for R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> false enprisonyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fals prisonyng R.</NOTE> a writ</L>
<L>Sue agayn &thorn;e, if he at larg&euml; were;</L>
<L>But he so fast is in &thorn;i cofre shit,</L>
<L>He may not out. O fals enprisonere,</L>
<L N="4100">Largess&euml; wold&euml; be with shelde &amp; spere</L>
<L>Euen in &thorn;i berde, if he brake out to-morwe,</L>
<L N="4102">And for his sak&euml; do th&euml; care and sorwe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="587" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(587)</HEAD>
<L N="4103">&para; &THORN;ou to largess&euml; dost ful muchil wronge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hast R.</NOTE> hir seruant vndir &thorn;i seruage;</L>
<L>On the, and noght on hir, is it a-longe</L>
<L>&THORN;at golde is lette to goon on hir message.</L>
<L N="4107">She ha&thorn; hym sent in many a viage<MILESTONE N="72a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Or this, &amp; that was the comoun profyte,</L>
<L N="4109">The whiche to lette, is euere &thorn;i delyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="588" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(588)</HEAD>
<L N="4110">Largesse only noght list golde seruant be</L>
<L>Vnto hir self; but the peple, she wolde</L>
<L>Had as gode part of hir seruyce as she;</L>
<L>To hir is al the comoun peple I-holde,</L>
<L N="4114">But &thorn;ou makest &thorn;e pepl&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">peples R, peple H.</NOTE> hert&euml;s colde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou slest an hep&euml; which &thorn;at she wolde saue;</L>
<L N="4116">&THORN;ou no wyte helpest, <SUP>5</SUP>&thorn;ow he &thorn;i help<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 though he &thorn;yne help R. &thorn;ow he &thorn;i peple H.</NOTE> craue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="589" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(589)</HEAD>
<L N="4117">Me list no mor&euml; speke of &thorn;e this tyme,</L>
<L>But of myne helply lady souereyne</L>
<L>Largess&euml;, my lad&yacute;, now wil I ryme,</L>
<L>And aftirward of &thorn;i curs&euml;d careyne</L>
<L N="4121">I spek&euml; shal; nought o worde wol I feyne,</L>
<L>But as scriptur&euml;s treten of the, wrecche,</L>
<L N="4123">I touch&euml; shal; &thorn;e feende<NOTE PLACE="foot">devell R.</NOTE> the henn&euml;s fecche!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="11" TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000215.tif" N="149">
<HEAD>[&sect; 11.] De Virtute Largitatis, &amp; De Vicio Prodigalitatis.</HEAD>
<LG N="590" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(590)</HEAD>
<L N="4124">Aristotil, of largesse, telleth this:<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated, like the other section-head ones are.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Aristoteles de regimine principum, capitulo de largitate. 'Si vis virtutem largitatis ad|quirere, con|sidera posse tuum, tem|pora necessi|tatis &amp; merita hominis,' &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Who vertuously larg&euml; list to be,</L>
<L>Concider first of what power he is,</L>
<L>And eke the tym&euml;s of necessite;</L>
<L N="4128">And as &thorn;e men disseruen, so be fre;</L>
<L>Yif in mesure vn-to &thorn;e indigent</L>
<L N="4130">And the worthi, and &thorn;at is wel dispent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="591" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(591)</HEAD>
<L N="4131">&para; And who doth othir wyse in his &yogh;euyng,<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[R, <I>om.</I> H] Qui aliter dat, regulam ex|cedit largita|tis. Qui lar|giter bona sua hominibus non indigen|tibus nulla; et quicquid datur indig|nis perditur; <I>et</I> qui fundit ultra modum diuicias suas, cito veniet ad amara litora paupertatis, <I>et</I> assimilatur illi qui victo|riam super se dat inimicis suis &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Largesses rul&euml; passith and excedith;</L>
<L>He nouther worthi is &thorn;ank ne preysyng,</L>
<L>That to hym &thorn;at no nede hath, &yogh;ift&euml;s bedith.</L>
<L N="4135">Of verray folye also it procedith</L>
<L>To &yogh;eu&euml; the onworthi; for &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i R.</NOTE> cost</L>
<L N="4137">All mysse dispendid is, for it is lost.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="592" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(592)</HEAD>
<L N="4138">&para; And he &thorn;at d&iacute;spendith out of mes&uacute;re</L>
<L>Shal tast a-none pou&eacute;rtes bitternesse;</L>
<L>ffoole largesse is ther-to a verray lure.</L>
<L>Of hem also he berith the lyknesse,</L>
<L N="4142">That on him self, as &thorn;e booke berith witnesse,</L>
<L>Vict&oacute;rie &yogh;eueth to his enemys;</L>
<L N="4144">And he &thorn;at so dispendith, is not wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="593" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(593)</HEAD>
<L N="4145">&para; Largess&euml; stant noght in mochil &yogh;euynge,</L>
<L>But it is aftir &thorn;e wille &amp; &thorn;e myght</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;at &yogh;eueth aftir his hauynge;</L>
<L>ffor it may som tyme happ&euml; &thorn;at a wight,</L>
<L N="4149">Which of richess&euml; berith nat but light,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eueth but smal; &amp; &yogh;it larger is he</L>
<L N="4151">Than he &thorn;at &yogh;eueth gretter quantite.
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="150"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="594" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(594)</HEAD>
<L N="4152">&para; Aftir his goode, man may &yogh;eue &amp; dispende</L>
<L>Wher as nede is; but he &thorn;at al<NOTE PLACE="foot">all R, hath al H.</NOTE> dispendith,</L>
<L>And wastith al, shal him-selue first offende.</L>
<L>ffool&euml; largesse al day wrycch&eacute;dly endith<NOTE PLACE="foot">Foole large . . . wrecchedly endith R, Fool largesse . . . wrycchedly enditith H.</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="4156">Many a man hir foule outrag&euml; shendith;</L>
<L>But of largesse is goode &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">of largesses goode R.</NOTE> gouernaunce;</L>
<L N="4158">Both&euml; to god and man<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bothe . . . to man R, Both . . . man H.</NOTE> it is plesaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="595" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(595)</HEAD>
<L N="4159">&para; Evene as a mann&euml;s blood is norisshyng<MILESTONE N="73a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To his body, if it corrupt naght be,</L>
<L>So ben richesses to soul&euml;s feedynge</L>
<L>Holsom, if &thorn;ei, were-as necessite</L>
<L N="4163">Axith, despent ben, and also if he</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at hem wan, gat hem with ri&yogh;twisnesse;</L>
<L N="4165">ffor heuene and helle is got&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben goten R.</NOTE> by richesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="596" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(596)</HEAD>
<L N="4166">&para; A crookid hors neuere is the bet<NOTE PLACE="foot">the better is R.</NOTE> entecched,</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;ogh his bridel glistre of gold, and schyne;</L>
<L>Right so a man &thorn;at vicious is, &amp; wrecched,</L>
<L>And his rich&eacute;sses gote ha&thorn; of rapyne,</L>
<L N="4170">And also euele as man can &yacute;magyne,</L>
<L>Despendith hem / naght for hem &thorn;e bet is,</L>
<L N="4172">But mochil wers; good is<NOTE PLACE="foot">gode is to R.</NOTE> take hede of &thorn;is.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="597" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(597)</HEAD>
<L N="4173">&para; He &thorn;at his flesche dispendith, and his blood,</L>
<L>Mi lorde, in &yogh;our seruice, him &yogh;ift&euml;s bede;</L>
<L>There is largess&euml; mesur&aacute;ble good;</L>
<L>A kyng so bounde is, he moot doo so nede;</L>
<L N="4177">Seruice vnquyt and murdre, it is no drede,</L>
<L>As clerkes writen, and desheritaunce,</L>
<L N="4179">Bifore al-mighty god auxen<NOTE PLACE="foot">axen.</NOTE> vengeaunce.
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="151"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="598" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(598)</HEAD>
<L N="4180">&para; Of fool largess&euml; wole I talke a space;</L>
<L>How it befil, I not in what contree,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ere was oon named Iohn of Canace,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This story, under different forms, was a very common one in the Middle Ages. One version will be found in my Latin stories, p. 28 . . . . the story of King Lear and his daughters is another version.&mdash;T. Wright, <I>De Reg.</I>, p. 199.</NOTE></L>
<L>A rich&euml; man, &amp; two dou&yogh;tres had he,</L>
<L N="4184">That to two worthy men of a Citee</L>
<L>He wedded<NOTE PLACE="foot">wedden R.</NOTE> leet; and &thorn;er&euml; was gladnesse</L>
<L N="4186">And reuel, mor&euml; than I can expresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="599" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(599)</HEAD>
<L N="4187">&para; The fadir, his doughtres and hir husbondes<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Loued ful wele, and had hem leef &amp; dere;</L>
<L>Tyme to tyme he &yogh;af hem with his hondes</L>
<L>Of his goode passyngly; &amp; &thorn;ei swich chere</L>
<L N="4191">Him made, &amp; were of so plesant manere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne wist how be bettre at ese,</L>
<L N="4193">&THORN;ei couden hym so wele cheryssh &amp; please.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="600" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(600)</HEAD>
<L N="4194">&para; ffor he as mochil hauntid in partie</L>
<L>Hir house, as &thorn;at he did his own&euml; house;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei held hym vp so with her flaterye,</L>
<L>That of dispens he was outrag&euml;ous,</L>
<L N="4198">And of good&euml; &thorn;ei were ay desirous;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;ei axed, haden &thorn;ei redy;</L>
<L N="4200">&THORN;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">And they R.</NOTE> euer weren on hym right<NOTE PLACE="foot">right, <I>om.</I> R H.</NOTE> gredy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="601" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(601)</HEAD>
<L N="4201">7 &THORN;is sely man contynued his outr&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>Tyl al his good&euml; was disshid<NOTE PLACE="foot">wasted R.</NOTE> &amp; goone;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ei felt his dispenses a-swage,</L>
<L>Thei wax to him vnkynd&euml; right<NOTE PLACE="foot">right R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> anone;</L>
<L N="4205">ffor after hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hade R, had H.</NOTE> he cherishing none,</L>
<L>Thei wery weren of his companye:</L>
<L N="4207">And he<NOTE PLACE="foot">And he R, He H.</NOTE> was wyse, and shope a remedye.
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="152"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="602" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(602)</HEAD>
<L N="4208">&para; He to a marchaunt goose, of his notise,</L>
<L>Wich &thorn;at his trusty frende had be ful &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>Besechyng hym, &thorn;at he wold hym cheuyse</L>
<L>Of <I>ten thousand</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">'x. Ml.' H, ten thousand R.</NOTE> pounde, ne lenger ne more</L>
<L N="4212">Than day&euml;s thre, and he wolde it restore</L>
<L>At his day; &thorn;is was done; &thorn;e summe he hent,</L>
<L N="4214">And to his own&euml; house &thorn;er-with he went.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="603" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(603)</HEAD>
<L N="4215">&para; And on the morn&euml;, prayde he to soupere<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His sonn&euml;s both &amp; his doughtres also.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei to him cam, with-owten any daungere:</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;ei ferden, lat I passe and goo;</L>
<L N="4219">Thei ferden wel, with-outen word&euml;s moo;</L>
<L>To his konyng, he grete disport hem made,</L>
<L N="4221">He did his myght to chere hem, &amp; to glade.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="604" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(604)</HEAD>
<L N="4222">&para; Aftir souper, whan &thorn;ei hir tym&euml; sye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei toke her leue, &amp; home &thorn;ei wolde al-gate;</L>
<L>And he answerd, and seyde hem sekirly,</L>
<L>"This ny&yogh;t ye shul nat passe out of the gate;</L>
<L N="4226">Your house is fer, and it is dyrke and late;</L>
<L>Neuen it nat, for it shal nat be-tyde;"</L>
<L N="4228">And so al ny&yogh;t he made hem to abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="605" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(605)</HEAD>
<L N="4229">&para; The fadir log&euml;d hem, of sly purp&oacute;se,</L>
<L>In a chambre next to his ioynyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ioynyng R, ionyng H.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor by-twix hem nas &thorn;er but a parclose</L>
<L>Of bord&euml;, nau&yogh;t but of homly<NOTE PLACE="foot">bord . . . homely R.</NOTE> makyng;</L>
<L N="4233">&THORN;urgh out &thorn;e which, at many a chynnyng,</L>
<L>In ech&euml; chambre &thorn;ei myghten<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghten R, myght H.</NOTE> beholde,</L>
<L N="4235">And see what othir dyden, if &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolde.
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="153"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="606" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(606)</HEAD>
<L N="4236">&para; I kan nat sey how &thorn;ei slepten &thorn;at ny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Also it longith<NOTE PLACE="foot">longeth R, logith H.</NOTE> nat to my matere;</L>
<L>But on &thorn;e morw&euml;, at brod&euml; day li&yogh;t</L>
<L>The fadir roose; and for &thorn;ei shulden here</L>
<L N="4240">What &thorn;at he dyd, in a boystous manere</L>
<L>Vnto his chist, which &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> three lokkys hadde,</L>
<L N="4242">He went, and &thorn;er-at wrested he ful sadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="607" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(607)</HEAD>
<L N="4243">&para; And when it was I-opned &amp; vnshytte,<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bagged gold by &thorn;e marchaunt hym lent</L>
<L>He hath vncofred, and streyte for&thorn; with it</L>
<L>Vnto his beddis feete gone is &amp; went.</L>
<L N="4247">What doth &thorn;an &thorn;is fel<NOTE PLACE="foot">felle R.</NOTE> man &amp; right<NOTE PLACE="foot">right, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> prudent,</L>
<L>But out &thorn;is golde on a tippet hath shotte,</L>
<L N="4249">That in &thorn;e bagg&euml;s left&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">left H R.</NOTE> &thorn;ere no grotte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="608" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(608)</HEAD>
<L N="4250">&para; And al &thorn;is did he noght but for a wyle,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at ye shul wel knowen aftirwarde;</L>
<L>He shope his sonn&euml;s &amp; doughtres begile.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to begile R.</NOTE></L>
<L>His noys&euml; made hem dressen hem vpwarde;</L>
<L N="4254">&THORN;ei cast her er&euml;s to his chambre-warde,</L>
<L>And herd of golde &thorn;e russhyng and the soun,</L>
<L N="4256">As that he rud&euml;ly threwe hem adoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="609" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(609)</HEAD>
<L N="4257">&para; And to &thorn;e parclos &thorn;ei hem hast and hye,</L>
<L>To wyte and know&euml; what her fadir wrought.</L>
<L>In at &thorn;e chynn&euml;s of &thorn;e borde &thorn;ei prye,</L>
<L>And sigh how he amonge &thorn;e nobles sought</L>
<L N="4261">If d&eacute;fectif were any, as hem &thorn;ought;</L>
<L>And on his nayl he threwe hem oft &amp; cast,</L>
<L N="4263">And bagg&euml;d hem and cofred at the last;
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="154"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="610" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(610)</HEAD>
<L N="4264">&para; And opned his dore, &amp; doun&euml; goth his wey.</L>
<L>And aftir blyue, out of hir bedde &thorn;ei rise,</L>
<L>And cam doune eke: hir fadir &thorn;anken &thorn;ey</L>
<L>Of his gode cher&euml;, in hir best&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">best H R.</NOTE> wyse,&mdash;</L>
<L N="4268">And al was for &thorn;e gold&euml;s couetyse,&mdash;</L>
<L>And to gon hoom, &thorn;ei axid of hym leue;</L>
<L N="4270">Thei ben departyd, and &thorn;ei &thorn;ere hym leue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="611" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(611)</HEAD>
<L N="4271">&para; Walkyng homward, &thorn;ei iangeld fast, &amp; speeke<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e golde which &thorn;ei sey hir fadir haue.</L>
<L>Oon seyd, "I wondre ther-on;" "and I eke,"</L>
<L>Quod a-nothir, "for, also god me saue,</L>
<L N="4275">&YOGH;istir-day, thogh I shuld in-to my graue</L>
<L>Haue crept, I durst on it haue leyde my lyfe,</L>
<L>That golde with hym nought hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hade R, had H.</NOTE> ben so ryfe."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="612" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(612)</HEAD>
<L N="4278">&para; Now lat hem muse on &thorn;at, what so hem list;</L>
<L>And to hir fadir now wol I me dresse.</L>
<L>He al &thorn;is golde takith out of his chist,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e marchaunt payde it more &amp; lesse,</L>
<L N="4282">&THORN;ankyng hym often<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte R, oft H.</NOTE> of his kynd&euml;nesse;</L>
<L>And &thorn;enn&euml;s goth he hom&euml; to his mete,</L>
<L N="4284">And to his sonn&euml;s house when he had ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="613" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(613)</HEAD>
<L N="4285">&para; When he cam thidir, thei made of hym more</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;at &thorn;ei wer&euml; wont, by many folde;</L>
<L>So gret disport &thorn;ei made hym no&yogh;t ful &yogh;ore.</L>
<L>"ffadir," quod &thorn;ei, "&thorn;is is your owne housholde;</L>
<L N="4289">In feith, &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing within oure holde,</L>
<L>But it shal be at your comand&euml;ment;</L>
<L N="4291">Wolde god &thorn;at ye weren at<NOTE PLACE="foot">werest H, were of R.</NOTE> oure assent,
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="155"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="614" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(614)</HEAD>
<L N="4292">&para; &THORN;enn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;en H, Than R.</NOTE> we shulden ay to-gedir dwelle."</L>
<L>Al what &thorn;ei menten, wist he wel I-now:</L>
<L>"Sonn&euml;s and doughtres," quod he, "soth to telle,</L>
<L>Mi wille is goode also to be with yow.</L>
<L N="4296">How shuld I myrier be? nat wot I how,</L>
<L>Than with yow for to be continuel;</L>
<L N="4298">Your company&euml; liketh me ful wel."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="615" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(615)</HEAD>
<L N="4299">&para; Now shope it so, &thorn;ei helden house in fere,<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sauf &thorn;e fadir; and as &thorn;ei lough &amp; pleyde,</L>
<L>His doughtres both&euml; with a<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe with R, both with H.</NOTE> lawghyng chere</L>
<L>Vn-to hir fadir spake, and &thorn;us &thorn;ei seyde,</L>
<L N="4303">And to assoile hir quest&iuml;oun hym preyde:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>As lines 4304-5, MS. Reg. 17 D vi, has:</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"What so euer it be, koth the fader, now</L>
<L>And I kan or may, I shall it telle yow."</L>
</LG><P>And for lines 4310-12 it has&mdash;</P><L>"As ye haue done, ye shull haue alle tho."</L></NOTE></L>
<L>"Now, god&euml; fadir, how mochil monye</L>
<L>In your strong bounden chist is, we yow preye?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="616" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(616)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "<I>Ten thousand</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">'X<SUP>m.</SUP>' H, Ten thousand R.</NOTE> pounde," he seide, &amp; ly&euml;d lowde,</L>
<L>"I told hem," quod he, "nat ful long agoo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at as redely as &thorn;at I cowde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ye wil aftir &thorn;is do to me so</L>
<L N="4310">As ye haue done by-forn&euml;, &thorn;an al tho</L>
<L>I in my testament dispos&euml; shal</L>
<L N="4312">ffor your profyt&euml;; yours it shal ben al."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="617" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(617)</HEAD>
<L N="4313">&para; Aftir &thorn;is day, &thorn;ei all in oon house were,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e day com of &thorn;e fadirs deying.</L>
<L>Goode mete and drynke, and cloth&euml;s for to were</L>
<L>He had, and pay&euml;d nat to his endyng.</L>
<L N="4317">When he sey &thorn;e tyme of his d&eacute;partyng,</L>
<L>His son&euml;s and his doughtres did he calle,</L>
<L N="4319">And in this wise he spak&euml; to hem alle:
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="618" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(618)</HEAD>
<L N="4320">&para; "Nat purpose I make othir testament,</L>
<L>But of &thorn;at is in my strong chist I-bounde;</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t anone, or I be henn&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">hens H R.</NOTE> hent,</L>
<L>An <I>hundred pound</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">'C. li' H, hundred pounde R.</NOTE> of nobles gode and rounde,</L>
<L N="4324">Takith to prechours; tarryeth it no stounde;</L>
<L>An <I>hundred pound</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">'C. li' H, hundred pounde R.</NOTE> eke to &thorn;e frer&euml;s grey,</L>
<L N="4326">And carm&euml;s <I>fifty</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>MS.</I> 'l,' fifty R.</NOTE>: tarrye it nought, I sey.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="619" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(619)</HEAD>
<L N="4327">&para; "And when I buried am, of hem the keyes<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of my chist takith, for &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> &thorn;ei hem kepe;</L>
<L>By euery key&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">key H R.</NOTE> writen ben the weyes</L>
<L>Of my wille." &thorn;is golde was nat suffred slepe;</L>
<L N="4331">It was anone dalt, for hir hertis depe</L>
<L>Stak in his bounden cofre, and al hir hope</L>
<L N="4333">Was god&euml; bagges &thorn;erin for to grope.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="620" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(620)</HEAD>
<L N="4334">&para; To euery chirche and recluse of &thorn;e toune,</L>
<L>Bad hem eeke of golde &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">yeue eke of golde R.</NOTE> a quantite:</L>
<L>Al as he bad, &thorn;ei weren prest and boune,</L>
<L>And did it blyu&euml;; but, so mot I the,</L>
<L N="4338">fful slily he disceyuyd &thorn;is meyne,</L>
<L>His sonn&euml;s and his doughtres bo&thorn;, I mene;</L>
<L N="4340">Hir berd&euml;s shau&euml;d he right smothe &amp; clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="621" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(621)</HEAD>
<L N="4341">&para; When he was dede, and his ex&eacute;quies do,</L>
<L>Solenily<NOTE PLACE="foot">Solempnely R.</NOTE> &thorn;ei to &thorn;e frer&euml;s &yogh;ide,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;o keyes delyuere hem vn-to;</L>
<L>And as &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> &thorn;ei hem beden, so &thorn;ei dide.</L>
<L N="4345">Tho ioyful son&euml;s dresse hem to &thorn;e stide</L>
<L>Wher as &thorn;is strong&euml; bounden chist&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">strong . . . chist H (chest) R.</NOTE> stoode;</L>
<L N="4347">But or &thorn;ei twynned &thorn;ens, &thorn;ei pekkid moode.
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="157"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="622" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(622)</HEAD>
<L N="4348">&para; Thei opneden &thorn;e chist, &amp; fonde ri&yogh;t nought</L>
<L>But a passyngly greet serge&aacute;nt&euml;s mace,</L>
<L>In which ther gaily made was and I-wrought</L>
<L>This sam&euml; scripture: "I, Iohn of Canace,</L>
<L N="4352">Mak&euml; swhich testament here in &thorn;is place;</L>
<L>Who berith charge of othir men, &amp; is</L>
<L N="4354">Of hem despis&euml;d, slayn be he with this."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="623" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(623)</HEAD>
<L N="4355">&para; Among fol&iuml;es all is noon, I leue,<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>More &thorn;an a<NOTE PLACE="foot">a R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> man his gode ful larg&euml;ly</L>
<L>Despende, in hop&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hope R, hop H.</NOTE> men wol hym releue</L>
<L>Whan his gode is despendid vtterly<NOTE PLACE="foot">vttirly R, viterly H.</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="4359">The indig&eacute;nt men setten no &thorn;ing by.</L>
<L>I, Hoccleue, in swich<NOTE PLACE="foot">suche R, swich H.</NOTE> case am gilty, &thorn;is me touchith,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See "am gilty / &thorn;is me touch / ith."</NOTE></L>
<L>So seith pouert, which oon foole large him vouchith.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hoccleve de seipso.<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. has Nota de prodigalitate Occleve.</NOTE> (<I>In a later hand.</I>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="624" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(624)</HEAD>
<L N="4362">&para; ffor &thorn;ogh I neuer were of hy degree,</L>
<L>Ne hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hade R, had H.</NOTE> mochil gode ne gret richesse,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it hath &thorn;e vice of prodigalite</L>
<L>Smerted me sore, &amp; done me hevynesse.</L>
<L N="4366">He &thorn;at but litil hath, may done excesse</L>
<L>In his degree, as wel as may &thorn;e riche,</L>
<L N="4368">Thogh hir dispenses wer&euml; nat elyche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">be not eliche R, were not lyche H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="625" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(625)</HEAD>
<L N="4369">&para; So haue I plukked at my purs&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">purses R, purs H.</NOTE> strynges,</L>
<L>And made hem often for to<NOTE PLACE="foot">for to R, for H.</NOTE> gape &amp; gane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his smal stuf hath take hym to his wynges,</L>
<L>And hath I-sworne to be my welth&euml;s bane,</L>
<L N="4373">But if releef a-way my sorowe plane;</L>
<L>And whens it com&euml; shal, can I nought gesse,</L>
<L N="4375">Mi lorde, but it procede of your hynesse.
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="158"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="626" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(626)</HEAD>
<L N="4376">&para; I me repent of my mysrewly lyfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Hoccleve's 'Male Regle' in his <I>Minor Poems</I>, I, p. 25.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Wherfor, in &thorn;&eacute; wey of sauac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>I hope I be; my dotage &eacute;xcessyfe</L>
<L>Hath put me to swich castigac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="4380">&THORN;at indigence hath dominac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>On me; o! had I help, now wolde I thryue,</L>
<L N="4382">And so ne did<NOTE PLACE="foot">so did R.</NOTE> I neuer &yogh;it in my lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="627" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(627)</HEAD>
<L N="4383">&para; My yeerly guerdoun, myn annuite,<MILESTONE N="77a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That was me graunted for my long lab&oacute;ur,</L>
<L>Is al behynde, I may naght pay&euml;d be,</L>
<L>Whiche causeth me to lyuen<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyue H, liue R.</NOTE> in langour.</L>
<L N="4387">O liberal prince! ensample of honour!</L>
<L>Vnto your grac&euml; lyke it to promoote</L>
<L N="4389">Mi poore estat, and to my woo beth boote!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="628" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(628)</HEAD>
<L N="4390">&para; And, wor&thorn;y prince, at crist&euml;s reuerence</L>
<L>Herkeneth what I schal seyn, and be noght greued,</L>
<L>But lat me stande in your beneuolence;</L>
<L>ffor if myn hert&euml;s wil wiste were, and preeued,</L>
<L N="4394">How yow to loue it stir&euml;d is and meeved,</L>
<L>Ye schulden knowe, y your honour and wel&thorn;e</L>
<L N="4396">Triste and desire, and eek your soul&euml;s hel&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="629" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(629)</HEAD>
<L N="4397">&para; In al my book ye schul naght see ne fynde,</L>
<L>That I youre ded&euml;s lakke, or hem despreise;</L>
<L>But for I wold&euml; &thorn;at ye hadde in mynde</L>
<L>Swich thyng as your renoun myghte vp areyse,</L>
<L N="4401">I write as my symple conceyt may peyse;</L>
<L>And trustith wel, al &thorn;at my penn&euml; seith,</L>
<L N="4403">Proceedith of good herte and trewe, in feith.
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="159"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="630" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(630)</HEAD>
<L N="4404">&para; What kyng &thorn;at dooth more &eacute;xcessif despenses<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Aristoteles de regimine, capitulo de vicio super|fluitatis. "O Alexander, firmiter dico tibi, quod quis rerum superflue con|tulerit domi|naciones, vl|tra quod reg|num suum possit suffi|cere, talis Rex procul dubio destruit &amp; destruitur.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Than his land may to suffice or atteyne,</L>
<L>Schal be destru&euml;d, after &thorn;e sentences</L>
<L>Of Aristotle; he schal naght fle &thorn;e peyne.</L>
<L N="4408">ffool&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Foole R, Fool H.</NOTE> larg&eacute;sse and avarice, &thorn;o tweyne,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at a kyng eschue, &amp; larg&euml; be,</L>
<L N="4410">Reioyse he schal his r&euml;al dignite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="631" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(631)</HEAD>
<L N="4411">&para; How fool largesse a kyng destroy&euml; may,<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As blyu&euml; wole I vnto yow declare:</L>
<L>ffool largess&euml; yeue&thorn; so moche a-way,</L>
<L>That it &thorn;e kyng&euml;s cofres make&thorn; bare,</L>
<L N="4415">And &thorn;anne awaki&thorn; poor&euml; peples care;</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;at sche dispendid ha&thorn; &amp; wastid,</L>
<L N="4417">They moot releu&euml;, therto be &thorn;ey hastid.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="632" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(632)</HEAD>
<L N="4418">&para; The Tylere<NOTE PLACE="foot">tilyer R.</NOTE> with his por&euml; cote and land,</L>
<L>That may vnneth&euml;s gete his sustenance,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at naght ha&thorn; but lab&oacute;ur of hand,</L>
<L>Ben often put vnto ful smert nusance.</L>
<L N="4422">Good is be-ware of godd&euml;s long suffrance;</L>
<L>Thogh he to venge hym tarie, &amp; be suffr&aacute;ble,</L>
<L N="4424">Whan his strook cometh, it is import&aacute;ble.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="633" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(633)</HEAD>
<L N="4425">&para; Naght speke I ageyn eid&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">dysmes (tenths) R.</NOTE> vttirly,</L>
<L>In sum cas &thorn;ey ben good and necess&aacute;rie;</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;ey goon to custum&aacute;blely,</L>
<L>The peple it maki&thorn; for to curse and warie:</L>
<L N="4429">And if &thorn;ey ben despended in contr&aacute;rie</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;ey graunted of &thorn;e peple were,</L>
<L N="4431">The mor&euml; grucchen &thorn;ey &thorn;e cost to bere.
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="160"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="634" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(634)</HEAD>
<L N="4432">&para; The pot so long&euml; to &thorn;e watir goth,</L>
<L>That hoom it cometh at &thorn;e laste y-broke.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e peple, with a cher&euml; loth,</L>
<L>Hir purs y-emptid<NOTE PLACE="foot">purses empted R.</NOTE> haue, &amp; eek hir poke,</L>
<L N="4436">Hem &thorn;ynkith &thorn;at &thorn;ey ouer nyh ben soke.</L>
<L>What harm of &thorn;at to kynges ha&thorn; be-tid,</L>
<L N="4438">Scriptur&euml;s tellen; it may nought<NOTE PLACE="foot">nough H. It may not be be heled in no wise ne hidde R.</NOTE> ben hid.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="635" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(635)</HEAD>
<L N="4439">&para; But fauel naght reportith tho scripturis;<MILESTONE N="78a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; <SUP>3</SUP> Aristoteles eodem capit|ulo.<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 For this, R. has: Deficientibus redditibus et expensis, Reges extenderunt manus suas ad res et redditus alienorum.</NOTE> Subditi vero propter iniuriam cla|mauerunt ad deum ex|celsum &amp; gloriosum.</NOTE></L>
<L>His lord&euml;s soul&euml; salue, he from hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">soules salve fro hym he R.</NOTE> hydith;</L>
<L>He besieth hym so in sly portraituris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at homly trouth&euml; naght with hym abidith;</L>
<L N="4443">The swet&euml; venym of his tong&euml; gydeth</L>
<L>His lord vnto &thorn;e valeie of dirknesse,</L>
<L N="4445">If he gou&eacute;rne hym by his fykilnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="636" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(636)</HEAD>
<L N="4446">&para; The trew&euml; man, if he may apparceyue</L>
<L>A d&eacute;faute in his lord, as othir while</L>
<L>It happith, he his lord it redith weyue,</L>
<L>And bit hym to vertu hym reconsile;</L>
<L N="4450">And yit fauel, &thorn;e net of fraude and gile,</L>
<L>The &thorn;ank hath, and &thorn;at othir &thorn;e maugree:</L>
<L N="4452">O god! &thorn;at verray trou&thorn;e art for to see.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="637" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(637)</HEAD>
<L N="4453">&para; Who &thorn;at, fro<NOTE PLACE="foot">for R.</NOTE> drede of any lord or syre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augusti|nus. Quis|quis metu alicuius po|testatis veri|tatem occul|tat, iram dei super se pro|uocat, quia magis timet hominem quam deum. &para; libere veri|tatem pre|dicantes &amp; praue vite gesta argu|uentes, non habent gra|tiam apud homines, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hydeth &thorn;e trouthe, and naght wil it out seie,</L>
<L>He vppon hym prouokith godd&euml;s yre,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at he more of man than god<NOTE PLACE="foot">of man than god R, of god and man H.</NOTE> hath eye.</L>
<L N="4457">They &thorn;at &thorn;e trouth&euml; of hir hertes bywreye</L>
<L>To lord&euml;s, and telle hem hir wicked lyf,</L>
<L N="4459">No grace in hem fynden for hir motyf.
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="161"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="638" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(638)</HEAD>
<L N="4460">&para; But bet, for trouthe is to suffre turment,</L>
<L>Than rich&euml;ly enhaunc&euml;d be for glose.</L>
<L>If &thorn;is lyf her&euml; be naght wel dispent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Augusti|nus. Melius est pro veri|tate pati sup|plicium, quam adula|cione bene|ficium, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wot it wel, I wele it naght suppose,</L>
<L N="4464">God wole his regn&euml; from vs schitte<NOTE PLACE="foot">hide R.</NOTE> &amp; close.</L>
<L>Here is &thorn;e way to peyn&euml;, or to blisse;</L>
<L>Who so wel dooth, of yoye<NOTE PLACE="foot">ioye R.</NOTE> he may naght misse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="639" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(639)</HEAD>
<L N="4467">Eternel god, the blessid trinite,<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">that R, &thorn;a H.</NOTE> euery man of cristen byleeue</L>
<L>Knoweth an vndyuyded vnite,</L>
<L>His mercy and his grac&euml; kythe &amp; preeue</L>
<L N="4471">In yow, my lord; &thorn;at so your ded&euml;s cheeue</L>
<L>As &thorn;at your soule, aftir &thorn;is lyf present,</L>
<L N="4473">To heuene blisse vp may be take &amp; hent.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="12" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 12.] De Vicio Auaricie.<NOTE PLACE="foot">'De vicio auaricie' is also in black in the margin, as a di|rection to the rubricator.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="640" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(640)</HEAD>
<L N="4474">Now go<NOTE PLACE="foot">go R, ga H.</NOTE> we to &thorn;e Aueric&iuml;ous,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated.</NOTE></L>
<L>To whom non h&aacute;bundanc&euml; may suffice.</L>
<L>A chynch&euml; neuere can be plentevous</L>
<L>Thogh al were his; swiche is his couetise;</L>
<L N="4478">To thriste ay aftir more, it is his gyse;</L>
<L>He is &thorn;e swolwe &thorn;at is neuere ful:</L>
<L N="4480">At Aueric&euml; now haue here a pul.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="641" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(641)</HEAD>
<L N="4481">Sche may, as god forbede, vndo a<NOTE PLACE="foot">a R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> kyng</L>
<L>Thurgh hire insaciable gredynesse.</L>
<L>Hire herte is sette vppon non o&thorn;er &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But how sche may golde hepe; al in dirknesse</L>
<L N="4485">Lurkith &thorn;e purchas of hire egrenesse;</L>
<L>In bagges vndir lok, hir gold sche thristeth;</L>
<L N="4487">Al to &thorn;e cofre it<NOTE PLACE="foot">it R, sche H.</NOTE> goth, and al sche chistith.
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="162"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="642" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(642)</HEAD>
<L N="4488">There is it hidde; no sonne it see&thorn;, ne moone;</L>
<L>Thogh al &thorn;e world steru&euml; schulde on a day</L>
<L>ffor lak of good, naght were it for to done</L>
<L>To borwe of hire; euere is hir answere nay;</L>
<L N="4492">That sche naght ha&thorn;, also sche swerith ay.</L>
<L>Hir nature is to kepe, and naght despende,<MILESTONE N="79a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4494">And hir desir of good ne hath non ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="643" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(643)</HEAD>
<L N="4495">&para; Auarice is a loue inmoderat,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est, Auaricia est amor im|moderatus adquirendi temporalia, &amp; est pestis fere omnes homi|nes solicitans. Vnde pro|pheta ait Ieremie vj<SUP>o</SUP> A maiori vs|que ad min|orem omnes student Auariciam &amp;c.<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. adds: Avaricia est ydolorum servitus.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>Rich&eacute;sses temporel for to purch&aacute;ce;</L>
<L>Sche besieth hir<NOTE PLACE="foot">desireth hye R.</NOTE> in euerych estat;</L>
<L>Sche shapith<NOTE PLACE="foot">shapeth R, shapit H.</NOTE> hir al &thorn;e world to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> embrace</L>
<L N="4499">ffro<NOTE PLACE="foot">For R, Fro H.</NOTE> &thorn;e mor&euml; to &thorn;e less&euml;; hir trace</L>
<L>To su&euml;, studien men, seith Ysaye,</L>
<L N="4501">And sche &thorn;e thraldom is of Maumetrye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mawmetrie R, Maumetye H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="644" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(644)</HEAD>
<L N="4502">&para; Sche is a couetys&euml; &eacute;xcessyf</L>
<L>Of othres good; &amp; of hire own&euml;, sche</L>
<L>So streit and hard is, and so r&eacute;tentyf,</L>
<L>That it profyt&euml; may in no degree.</L>
<L N="4506">O aueric&iuml;ous, what eilith &thorn;ee?</L>
<L>&THORN;e good&euml;s whyich&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">which &thorn;at R.</NOTE> ben vnto &thorn;e lent,</L>
<L N="4508">Why hydest &thorn;ou? I-wis &thorn;ou wilt be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="645" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(645)</HEAD>
<L N="4509">&para; Weenest &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ou doost naght wickedly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so many a manys sustenance</L>
<L>Thi self wi&thorn;-holdest soul<NOTE PLACE="foot">so R.</NOTE>? yis, hardily.</L>
<L>Thow &thorn;at of richesse hast greet habundaunce,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iterum scriptum est Neque enim minus est criminis ha|benti tollere, quam cum possis &amp; ha|bundans sis, indigentibus necessaria denegare.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4513">And to &thorn;e nedy yeuest no pitaunce,</L>
<L>No lesse offendist &thorn;ou than he &thorn;at schakith</L>
<L>Men out of hire good, and from hem it takith.
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="163"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="646" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(646)</HEAD>
<L N="4516">&para; Thus may thy styl&euml; likned be to thefte;</L>
<L>As a theef in &thorn;is world is hangid here,</L>
<L>ffor good whiche &thorn;at he of &thorn;e peple refte,</L>
<L>So schalt &thorn;ou honge in helle, and bye it deere,</L>
<L N="4520">But if so be, or &thorn;ou goo to &thorn;i beere,</L>
<L>Thow c&oacute;rrect&euml; thy greedy appetyt,<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4522">And of streit kepynge empt&euml; &thorn;y delyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="647" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(647)</HEAD>
<L N="4523">&para; The breed of hungry peple &thorn;ou with-holdist,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Item scrip|tum est. Esuriencium panis est quem tu de|tines; nu|dorum vesti|mentum est quod tu re|cludis.</NOTE></L>
<L>And schutest vp the nakid menn&euml;s cloth</L>
<L>That keuere hem sholde; if &thorn;ou oght of god toldist,</L>
<L>ffor to doo so, &thorn;ou woldest be ful loth.</L>
<L N="4527">Al &thorn;at &thorn;ou getist, to hid place it goth.</L>
<L>As many men, hir good &thorn;ow hem byreuest<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iterum scriptum est, Tantoium ergo te scias inuadere bona, quan|torum de pos|sessione tua poteris sub|uenire, &amp; non vis. Prouerbia|rum xxvij. Qui odit aua|riciam, longi fient dies eius.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4529">As &thorn;ou releu&euml; myghtest, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and thou R.</NOTE> it leuest.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="648" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(648)</HEAD>
<L N="4530">&para; Who so &thorn;at fro &thorn;e poor&euml; mann&euml;s cry<NOTE PLACE="foot">R. has "Prov. xx<SUP>o</SUP>. Qui obturat aurem suam ad clamorem pauperis, ipse clamabit, et non exaudietur."</NOTE></L>
<L>Stoppith his er&euml;s, &thorn;ogh he lowd&euml; crye,</L>
<L>Schal naght be herde; and more ouer, rede y,</L>
<L>His day&euml;s schulle encresse &amp; multiplie</L>
<L N="4534">That auerice hatith, &thorn;is is no lye.</L>
<L>Werse is no &thorn;ing &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">than R, &thorn;at H.</NOTE> to loue moneye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ecclesias|tici x. Nichil iniquius quam amare pecuniam.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4536">As &thorn;at Ecclesiasticus can seye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="649" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(649)</HEAD>
<L N="4537">&para; Ambros&euml; seith, war, man, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne schitte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ambrosius de officiis. Caueas ne in|tra loculos tuos includas salutem in|opum, &amp; tan|quam in tu|milo ne sepe|lias vitam pauperum.</NOTE></L>
<L>With-in &thorn;i purs &thorn;e nedy peples<NOTE PLACE="foot">peples R, peple H.</NOTE> hele,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e buriell&euml;s naght committe</L>
<L>The lyf of poor&euml; men; &yogh;eue hem, &amp; dele</L>
<L N="4541">Part of &thorn;i good; o, &thorn;y bagg&euml;s vnsele;</L>
<L>Opne hem; hir knyttynge al to sore annoyeth;</L>
<L N="4543">Thy pyn&euml;d stuf, many a man destroyeth.
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="164"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="650" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(650)</HEAD>
<L N="4544">&para; Thow seist per cas, "yf I no man byreue</L>
<L>His good, what wrong, myn owne is it to hyde</L>
<L>And multiplie?" o, chynch&euml;! by &thorn;i leue,</L>
<L>What seist<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyest R.</NOTE> &thorn;ou is &thorn;in? what was &thorn;in, &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L N="4548">Thow cam in-to &thorn;is world, &thorn;ou homycide?</L>
<L>Thow broghtist naght; claym&euml; no propertee<MILESTONE N="80a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">Scilicet tem|pore necesci|tatis R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4550">Of thing &thorn;at oght&euml; commun&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">oght comon R.</NOTE> to be.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="651" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(651)</HEAD>
<L N="4551">&para; Thi talkinge and &thorn;i clap is al of erthe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ysaie xix<SUP>o</SUP>. de terra lo|queris &amp; de humo audie|tur eloquium tuum propter amorem quem habes ad sordes. Luce xij. Cui multum da|tum est mul|tum queretur ab eo a deo &amp; hominibus.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e ground for-&thorn;i schal answere the,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at &thorn;e loue of muk sittith so neer &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at hath of good&euml;s gret plentee,</L>
<L N="4555">Of god and man mochil axid schal be;</L>
<L>Thow schalt be rekned with, heer-aftir,<NOTE PLACE="foot">there as a R.</NOTE> chynche,</L>
<L>Where as &thorn;ou schalt not at &thorn;e acount&euml;s pynche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="652" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(652)</HEAD>
<L N="4558">&para; By what<NOTE PLACE="foot">what R, &thorn;at H.</NOTE> title &thorn;at &thorn;ou getist &thorn;i good,</L>
<L>Thow countist naght &thorn;e value of a myte;</L>
<L>Thyn hert is euermore on gold so wood,</L>
<L>That no thing ell&euml;s canst &thorn;ou in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in, <I>om.</I> H, That in no . . . thow R.</NOTE> delite;</L>
<L N="4562">Of consc&iuml;enc&euml; rekkist &thorn;ou so lite,</L>
<L>What goodis &thorn;at &thorn;ou getist of rapyne,</L>
<L N="4564">&THORN;ou hem affermest by good title &thorn;yne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="653" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(653)</HEAD>
<L N="4565">&para; ffeith and prowess&euml;, leist &thorn;ou vndir foote,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salustius dicit: Aua|ricia fidem &amp; probitatem subpeditat, &amp; docet homi|nem in se habere super|biam &amp; cru|delitatem.</NOTE></L>
<L>And techist folk to haue in hem-self pride;</L>
<L>And cruelte hath caght in &thorn;e swiche roote,</L>
<L>That sche noght slipp&euml; may fro &thorn;e, ne slyde;</L>
<L N="4569">And euery vertu throwest &thorn;ou a-syde.</L>
<L>O, euery prince and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and R, or H.</NOTE> kyng moot ben eschu,</L>
<L N="4571">In al maneere, of &thorn;i lym and &thorn;i glu.
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="165"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="654" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(654)</HEAD>
<L N="4572">&para; ffor ell&euml;s is it light to vndirstonde,</L>
<L>To euery man &thorn;at wit can &amp; resoun,</L>
<L>It is nat likly, &aacute; kyng for to stonde</L>
<L>In his welth&euml; but a litil sesoun,</L>
<L N="4576">ffor Auaric&euml; may ben &eacute;nchesoun</L>
<L>His peple to destroyen<NOTE PLACE="foot">distroien R, destoyen H.</NOTE> and oppresse;<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4578">And, as I sayd&euml;, so may fool largesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. wrongly puts st. 659 here, before sts. 655-8. R. puts st. 659 in its right place.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="655" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(655)</HEAD>
<L N="4579">&para; ffool largesse is a sekenesse curable,</L>
<L>Outhir of indigence, othir ell&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">or elles of R.</NOTE> age;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Dicit idem philosophus, quod prodi|galitas est morbus cura|bilis, ab egestate vel etate.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;at fool large in &yogh;outhe is, is ful able</L>
<L>In eld&euml; to abate it and aswage,</L>
<L N="4583">ffor agid folk ben more in &thorn;e seruage</L>
<L>Of auaric&euml; &thorn;an ben folk in yowthe;</L>
<L>And what I schal eek seyn, herkneth wel now&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="656" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(656)</HEAD>
<L N="4586">&para; Of nede eek may it curid ben, and helid;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Auaricia est morbus incurabilis, vt idem dicit.</NOTE></L>
<L>A man may so larg&euml; despenses make,</L>
<L>Til al is good be d&iacute;spendid and delid;</L>
<L>And whan his purs y-emptid is, and schake,</L>
<L N="4590">Than, begynne&thorn; indigence a-wake,</L>
<L>By whiche he cured is of &thorn;e seekenesse</L>
<L N="4592">Of prodigalitee, or fool<NOTE PLACE="foot">foole R, ful H.</NOTE> largesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="657" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(657)</HEAD>
<L N="4593">&para; But auarice, he seith, incurable is;</L>
<L>ffor ay &thorn;e more a man &thorn;erin procedith</L>
<L>And wexith olde, so mochil more I-wys,</L>
<L>He auaricious is; in him naght breedith</L>
<L N="4597">But thoght<NOTE PLACE="foot">thought R, toght H.</NOTE> and woo, for ay his hert&euml; dreedith</L>
<L>His good to leese; and mor&euml; for to hepe<MILESTONE N="81a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4599">His thoght&euml;s stirten heere &amp; &thorn;ere, and lepe.
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="166"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="658" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(658)</HEAD>
<L N="4600">&para; Now if &thorn;e heed of al a regioun,</L>
<L>By whom &thorn;at al gou&eacute;rned is and gyed,</L>
<L>Be of so seekly a condic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>That it may by no cur&euml; be maistryed,</L>
<L N="4604">Thanne is he to &thorn;e wers&euml; part applied;</L>
<L>And as the philosofre seith vs to,</L>
<L N="4606">The less&euml; wikke is fool largesse of two.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="659" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(659)</HEAD>
<L N="4607">&para; The philosofre preeueth Auarice<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Respice in Egidio de regimine principum: 'probat phi|losophus iiij<SUP>to</SUP> ethicorum, iij<SUP>o</SUP> racione, quod auaricia peior est pro|digalitate. [R adds] primo enim melius est infirmari morbo cura|bili quam incurabili.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel wers&euml; &thorn;an is prodigalite:</L>
<L>By thre causes he halt it gretter vice:</L>
<L>ffirst, he seith, it is better seek to be,</L>
<L N="4611">Of a sekenesse or infirmite</L>
<L>Of whiche a man may haue rekeueryng,</L>
<L N="4613">&THORN;an of swiche on as &thorn;er is non helyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="660" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(660)</HEAD>
<L N="4614">&para; The seconde cause is, prodigalitee<MILESTONE N="83(81)a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Secundo, probat quod prodigalitas est magis propinqua virtuti quam Auaricia, nam liberalis non libenter recipit, sed libenter dat, quorum vtrumque fa|cit prodigus;</NOTE></L>
<L>Is mor&euml; ny to vertu many del</L>
<L>Than Auerice; and why, ye schul wele see:</L>
<L>He &thorn;at is liberal, naght list so wel</L>
<L N="4618">ffor to receyue any good or catell</L>
<L>As yeu&euml;, but what man &thorn;at is fool large</L>
<L N="4620">To take and yeu&euml;, yeueth he no charge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="661" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(661)</HEAD>
<L N="4621">&para; Wherfore he sei&thorn;, &thorn;ere is no difference<NOTE PLACE="marg">non ergo differt prodi|gus a liber|alitate, nisi quod prodi|gus non dat vt debet, &amp; quibus debet, nec cuius gratia debet,</NOTE></L>
<L>Twixt<NOTE PLACE="foot">Twixit H, Betwixt foole large R.</NOTE> fool largesse and liberalitee,</L>
<L>Sauf &thorn;e fool larg&euml;, &oacute;f his imprud&eacute;nce,</L>
<L>Of his dispenses is to dislauee,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Hoccl. <I>Min. Poems</I> I.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4625">And yeueth there as oght&euml; naght to be;</L>
<L>And for what cause also, and for what skile</L>
<L N="4627">He yeu&euml; schal, non hede he tak&euml; wile.
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="167"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="662" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(662)</HEAD>
<L N="4628">&para; And syn fool large, on gold setti&thorn; his herte<NOTE PLACE="marg">quare cum prodigus non sit amator pecunie sicut nec liberalis, de facili pro|digus fieri possit liber|alis &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>No mor&euml; &thorn;an &thorn;e liberal, &thorn;an may</L>
<L>ffool large into liberalite<NOTE PLACE="foot">liberalitee R, liberte H. (Scan 'lib&eacute;r / ali / te').</NOTE> sterte</L>
<L>lightly ynow.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ynough R, now H.</NOTE> for vertu is kynges pray,</L>
<L N="4632">He Auerice eschu&euml; mot alway,</L>
<L>By caus&euml; sche more is contrarious<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4634">To vertu, &thorn;an the large outrag&euml;ous.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="663" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(663)</HEAD>
<L N="4635">&para; The &thorn;ridd&euml; skile is, for a kyng is set<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Tercio, quia rex est positus in regno prop|ter salutem regni, &amp; vt prosit hijs qui in regno sunt; auarus autem nulli prodest.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his rem&euml; for his peples<NOTE PLACE="foot">peples ese and R.</NOTE> releef,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ey schulden for hym fare &thorn;e bet;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e streyt chynch&euml; qwenche&thorn; neuere greef;</L>
<L N="4639">His gold is neuere salu&euml; to myschef;</L>
<L>Only to gadre and kepe, he hym delitith;</L>
<L N="4641">But &thorn;e fool larg&euml;, many man profitith;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="664" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(664)</HEAD>
<L N="4642">&para; Yit vices ben &thorn;ey gret&euml; both&euml; tweyne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Idem dicit quod largitas est ad similitudi|nem vaso|rum; vasa enim haben|cia os largum, abunde emit|tunt quod in eis est.</NOTE></L>
<L>O! wor&thorn;y princ&euml;, take on yow largesse;</L>
<L>Dooth so, o gracious lord, for godd&euml;s peyne!</L>
<L>Largesse I-put is vnto &thorn;e liknesse</L>
<L N="4646">Of vessels, whos mouth&euml;s han gret wydnesse,</L>
<L>And hilde out hir lic&oacute;ur habundantly;</L>
<L N="4648">Thus seith &thorn;e philosofre trew&euml;ly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="665" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(665)</HEAD>
<L N="4649">&para; And in as mochil as a welle also,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Cumergo tanto deceat fontem ha|bere largum os, quanto ex eo plures participare debent, tanto decet regem largiorem esse, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>At &thorn;e whiche many folk hir water fecche,</L>
<L>Nedith to han the larger mouth; right so</L>
<L>The largesse of a kyng moot fer&thorn;er strecche,</L>
<L N="4653">If he of his estat any &thorn;ing recche,</L>
<L>Than o&thorn;er menn&euml;s; for hir<NOTE PLACE="foot">hir, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> impotence</L>
<L N="4655">Strecchi&thorn; naght so fer as his influence.
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="168"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="666" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(666)</HEAD>
<L N="4656">&para; Largesse is 'liberalitee' y-callid,</L>
<L>And likned is vnto hem &thorn;at ben free;</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at auaricious is, is thrallid</L>
<L>To moneie. a kyng moot algat&euml;s flee</L>
<L N="4660">A chynch&euml;s hert&euml;, for his honeste</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e profyte, as I seide aboue,<MILESTONE N="82a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4662">Of his peple, if he &thorn;ynke wynne here loue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="667" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(667)</HEAD>
<L N="4663">&para; Victorie and honour, he schal hym purch&aacute;se<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prouerbi|arum xxij. Victoriam &amp; honorem ad|quiret qui dat munera. Item: ne dicas amico tuo 'vade &amp; reuertere, &amp; cras dabo tibi,' cum statim possis dare.</NOTE></L>
<L>That is of yift&euml;s fre; but war alway</L>
<L>That he naght tarye ne delaye his grace;</L>
<L>Dryue it noght forth vnto ano&thorn;er day,</L>
<L N="4667">Whan, if hym list, anon he yeu&euml; may;</L>
<L>Yeue it as blyue, hys &thorn;ank is wel &thorn;e more;</L>
<L N="4669">This vouche I on holy scriptur&euml;s lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="668" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(668)</HEAD>
<L N="4670">&para; The vertu is of liberalitee,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De virtute liberalitatis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yeue and dispende, in place and in tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">n tyme and place R.</NOTE> due;</L>
<L>Right as largess&euml; dooth in swiche degree,</L>
<L>They both&euml; moot in hir conseytes chue</L>
<L N="4674">Where is good yeue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">to yeue R.</NOTE> and wher&euml; to eschue,</L>
<L>The persone, and &thorn;e somme, and caus&euml; why:</L>
<L N="4676">What &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye R.</NOTE> yeuen, yeue it vertuously.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="669" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(669)</HEAD>
<L N="4677">&para; But it naght longeth to &thorn;e liberal</L>
<L>To yeue hym good &thorn;at vse&thorn; flaterie;</L>
<L>His menynge and his &eacute;ntenc&iuml;oun final</L>
<L>On fals plesance, is set for briberie;</L>
<L N="4681">He is &thorn;e verray cofre of treccherie;</L>
<L>His doublenesse his lord doun ouerthrowe&thorn;;</L>
<L N="4683">The seed of his confus&iuml;oun he sowe&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="169"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="670" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(670)</HEAD>
<L N="4684">&para; That man I-born is in a blissed hour,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota quod laudandus est ille quem pietas mouet reuelamen prestare indi|genti: nota bene hic!</NOTE></L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at pitee, dissert, or kynd&euml;nesse,</L>
<L>Stiren to yeue, or mynystre hym socour,</L>
<L>That infortun&euml;s strok&euml;s bitternesse</L>
<L N="4688">I-woundid hath wi&thorn; pouertes scharpnesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">sikenesse R.</NOTE>:</L>
<L>Nat mene I hem &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nought yeue hem R.</NOTE> hire, and fees and wages,<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4690">Hath<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hat H, That han R.</NOTE> at &thorn;e dees loost, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">dice lost.</NOTE> hir herit&aacute;ges;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="671" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(671)</HEAD>
<L N="4691">&para; But &thorn;o &thorn;at men welthy han<NOTE PLACE="foot">han R, and H.</NOTE> ben byfore,</L>
<L>And vertuous ben, and han hir good&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">goode R, good H.</NOTE> lost,</L>
<L>And can not begg&euml;, to be deed &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L>On hem ful wel bystow&euml;d is &thorn;e cost.</L>
<L N="4695">But welaway! as harde as is a post&mdash;</L>
<L>A post? nay, as a stoon&mdash;ben hert&euml;s now!</L>
<L N="4697">Lord&euml;s, for scham&euml;! what &thorn;ing eyleth yow?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="672" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(672)</HEAD>
<L N="4698">&para; A gentil hert&euml;, for to begge ha&thorn; schame;</L>
<L>His rody schamfastness&euml; dar not preye.</L>
<L>Ye &thorn;at of gentillesse han stile &amp; name,</L>
<L>Lat nat your poor&euml; bretheren by yow deye!</L>
<L N="4702">Se vnto hem, thogh &thorn;ey nat speke or seie.</L>
<L>Is pitee fro yow fled? calle hir agayn!</L>
<L N="4704">ffor hir absence ha&thorn; many good man slayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="673" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(673)</HEAD>
<L N="4705">&para; Senek seith, h&eacute; ha&thorn; nat &thorn;at &thorn;ing for noght,</L>
<L>That byeth it by speche and by prayere.</L>
<L>There is no thyng &thorn;at is in eerth&euml; wroght,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at he seith, &thorn;at is y-bought so deere;</L>
<L N="4709">It standith streyt&euml;, whan it schal apere,</L>
<L>ffor it is vois of wrecchidnesse and sorwe,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at a man schal praye, or begge, or borwe.
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="170"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="674" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(674)</HEAD>
<L N="4712">&para; Allas! &thorn;ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">though R, &thorn;oght H.</NOTE> &thorn;at a man disceuere &amp; pleyne</L>
<L>To many a lord his m&eacute;scheuous myserie,</L>
<L>The lord naght deyneth vndirstonde his peyne;</L>
<L>He settith noght &thorn;erby a blakberie.</L>
<L N="4716">Welthe in &thorn;e lord&euml;s sayl blowe&thorn; ful merye;</L>
<L>But the nedy berith his sail so lowe,<MILESTONE N="83a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4718">That no wynd of comf&oacute;rt may in hit blowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="675" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(675)</HEAD>
<L N="4719">&para; Of liberalitee yit forthermore<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Hic caueant capitanei, quod non retineant vadia.</NOTE></L>
<L>I tell&euml; wole, as &thorn;at I haue herd seyn</L>
<L>Among&euml;s wys&euml; folk, gon is ful yore.</L>
<L>What man a ledere is, or a chiefteyn</L>
<L N="4723">Of peple, his labour is al wast and veyn,</L>
<L>But he be fre vnto his sowd&euml;ours,</L>
<L N="4725">If &thorn;at he sek&euml; conquest of<NOTE PLACE="foot">or R.</NOTE> honours.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="676" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(676)</HEAD>
<L N="4726">&para; And specialy &thorn;at he hir du&euml;tee</L>
<L>Abrigg&euml; naght, ne naght syncope hir wages</L>
<L>That hem assigned ben: in certeyntee,</L>
<L>Peril of scham&euml; folwen swiche vs&aacute;ges.</L>
<L N="4730">Whan al a-counted is, tho auant&aacute;ges</L>
<L>That founded ben of wrong and on repreef,</L>
<L N="4732">Ben naght but auant&aacute;ges of mescheef.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="677" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(677)</HEAD>
<L N="4733">&para; This makith couetise or Auarice</L>
<L>Roote of al harm&euml;s, fo to consc&iuml;ence;</L>
<L>Of wikked purchas is sche Emperice,</L>
<L>And mochil hath, and ay ha&thorn; indigence.</L>
<L N="4737">Sho rather wil lyuen<NOTE PLACE="foot">live R, lyue H.</NOTE> in abstinence</L>
<L>Of mete and drynk&euml;, for hert&euml;s scantnesse,</L>
<L N="4739">Than for &thorn;e soule or bodyes holsumnesse.
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="171"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="678" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(678)</HEAD>
<L N="4740">&para; Prince excellent! so moot ye wirke and wilne<NOTE PLACE="foot">wille R.</NOTE></L>
<L>As may your soul&euml;s helth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">helthe R, helth H.</NOTE> edifie;</L>
<L>And a-mong othir &thorn;ing&euml;s, &thorn;at your wilne<NOTE PLACE="foot">wille R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be infecte wi&thorn; no wrecched chyncherie.</L>
<L N="4744">Largesse mes&uacute;rable vnto yow tye,</L>
<L>And fool largess&euml; voydeth fro yow clene<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4746">ffor free largess&euml; is a vertuous mene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="13" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 13.] De regis prudencia.</HEAD>
<LG N="679" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(679)</HEAD>
<L N="4747">Now, gracious princ&euml;, lyke it yow to wyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated.</NOTE></L>
<L>That touche I thynke of a kyng&euml;s prudence,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at I ther-of fynde in book&euml;s write.</L>
<L>Prudence is callid wit and sapience,</L>
<L N="4751">And need&euml;s moot r&euml;al magnificence</L>
<L>Be prudent, as &thorn;at &thorn;&eacute; scripture vs lereth,</L>
<L N="4753">If he schal ben as his estate<NOTE PLACE="foot">estate R, state H.</NOTE> requerith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="680" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(680)</HEAD>
<L N="4754">Prudence, attemperanc&euml;, strengthe, and right,</L>
<L>Tho four&euml; ben vertu&euml;s principal<NOTE PLACE="foot">These are the Four Moral Virtues, as contrasted with the Seven Cardinal ones. In "Jacob's Well" (man's conscience) Salisbury Cathedral MS. 103, lf. 215 bk., col. 2, the writer says "I teld &yogh;ou &thorn;is welle muste be made foure sqware with iiij vertuys, &thorn;at is, with a-vysement, &amp; tempure, &amp; gostly my&yogh;t, &amp; with ry&yogh;tfulnes."</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Prudenc&euml; gooth by-fore, and &yogh;eueth light</L>
<L>Of counseil, what &thorn;o other thre do schal,</L>
<L N="4758">That &thorn;ey may wirk&euml;, be it greet or smal,</L>
<L>Aftir hir reed, wi&thorn;-outen whom no man</L>
<L N="4760">Wel vnto god, n&eacute; &thorn;e world lyu&euml; can.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="681" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(681)</HEAD>
<L N="4761">Prudence is vertu of entend&euml;ment;</L>
<L>She makith man by resoun him gou&eacute;rne.</L>
<L>Who-so &thorn;at list to be wys and prud&eacute;nt,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e light folwe wole of hir lanterne,</L>
<L N="4765">he most&euml; caste his look<NOTE PLACE="foot">looke R, book H.</NOTE> in euery herne
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;yng&euml;s past, and ben, &amp; &thorn;at schul be:</L>
<L N="4767">The end&euml; see&thorn;, and eek mes&uacute;reth, sche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="682" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(682)</HEAD>
<L N="4768">There is no wight &thorn;at sche schapi&thorn; disceyue,</L>
<L>And, thogh men casten hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">men casten hem R, man cast hym H.</NOTE> hire to begile,<MILESTONE N="84a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Naght wole it be; by wit sche wole it weyue.</L>
<L>Eek sche obserueth so wele trouth&euml;s style,</L>
<L N="4772">And &thorn;erto can so wel her tonge affyle,</L>
<L>That, lest &thorn;e fauour of frendschip&euml;s corde,</L>
<L N="4774">Othir &thorn;an trouth&euml; can sche not recorde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="683" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(683)</HEAD>
<L N="4775">&para; Sche b&yacute;-heetith by good avis&euml;ment,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eueth mor&euml; &thorn;an hir list promette;</L>
<L>Scho yeueth t&oacute; men eek command&euml;ment</L>
<L>'Naght in fortune truste, or by hir sette;</L>
<L N="4779">And al &thorn;e truste, out of hir hert&euml; schette,</L>
<L>Of myght of worldly dominac&iuml;oun:'</L>
<L N="4781">Vertu gyeth hir operac&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="684" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(684)</HEAD>
<L N="4782">&para; Prudence hath leuer lou&euml;d be &thorn;an drad;</L>
<L>Ther may no prince in his estate endure,</L>
<L>Ne ther-yn any whil&euml; stand&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">endure R.</NOTE> sad,</L>
<L>But he be lou&euml;d; f&oacute;r loue is armure</L>
<L N="4786">Of seur&euml;te. o! take on yow &thorn;e cure,</L>
<L>Excellent princ&euml;, lou&euml; to embrace,</L>
<L N="4788">And &thorn;an your herte is sette in siker place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="685" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(685)</HEAD>
<L N="4789">&para; Now, if &thorn;at ye graunten by your patente</L>
<L>To your seruaunt&euml;s a yeerly guerdoun,</L>
<L>Crist scheeld&euml; &thorn;at your wil or your entente</L>
<L>Be sette to maken<NOTE PLACE="foot">make H R.</NOTE> a restriccioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">retraccioun R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4793">Of pai&euml;ment; for &thorn;at condic&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Exile&thorn; &thorn;&eacute; peples beneuolence,</L>
<L N="4795">And kyndele&thorn; hate vndir priue scilence.
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="173"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="686" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(686)</HEAD>
<L N="4796">&para; Beeth wel avis&euml;d, or your graunt out go,</L>
<L>&para; How ye &thorn;at charg&euml; may performe and bere;<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan it is past, obserue it wel also,</L>
<L>ffor ell&euml;s wole it yow annoye and dere;</L>
<L N="4800">ffor your honur it muchel bettre were,</L>
<L>No graunt to graunt at al, &thorn;an &thorn;at your graunt</L>
<L N="4802">Yow preeue a brekere of a couenaunt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="687" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(687)</HEAD>
<L N="4803">&para; He &thorn;at is lou&euml;d, men drede hym offende;</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at drad, &amp; naght by-lou&euml;d is,</L>
<L>As Tull&iuml;us seith, lightly may descende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lordschip&euml; lees&euml; &thorn;at was his;</L>
<L N="4807">And Senek also seith as<NOTE PLACE="foot">as, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> touchyng &thorn;is,</L>
<L>The sogett hateth whom he ha&thorn; in drede;</L>
<L N="4809">And hate is hard, if it his venym schede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="688" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(688)</HEAD>
<L N="4810">&para; Was neuere dred&euml; yit a good wardeyn,</L>
<L>To hold&euml; lordschepe in his sikernesse,</L>
<L>But only loue is &thorn;ing most souereyn;</L>
<L>Loue is norice of wel&thorn;e and of gladnesse,</L>
<L N="4814">But out of lou&euml; sprynge&thorn; ferdfulnesse,</L>
<L>And feere is good, whiche &thorn;at on loue hym groundeth,</L>
<L N="4816">But othir feer&euml; naght heli&thorn;, but woundeth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="689" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(689)</HEAD>
<L N="4817">&para; Lou&euml;, withouten a good gouernaille,</L>
<L>A kyng ha&thorn; non; for thogh men no word seye,</L>
<L>If he his peple oppresse, it is no faile</L>
<L>They loue hym noght, in no manere of weie;</L>
<L N="4821">They may his hest&euml;s outward wel obeie,</L>
<L>But in hir hertes is smal obediaunce,</L>
<L N="4823">And vnto god &thorn;ey c&oacute;mpleyne hir grevaunce.
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="174"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="690" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(690)</HEAD>
<L N="4824">&para; And swich a kyng is naght prudent ne wys,</L>
<L>&para; That of his peple purchaseth hym hate,<MILESTONE N="85a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor loue excedith al tresour in prys;</L>
<L>So hath it ben, and so be wole algate.</L>
<L N="4828">Whan &thorn;at rich&eacute;sses ebben &amp; abbate,</L>
<L>If loue endur&euml;, it may hym restore,</L>
<L N="4830">And loue is goten by prud&eacute;nces<NOTE PLACE="foot">prudences R, prudentes H.</NOTE> lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="691" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(691)</HEAD>
<L N="4831">&para; By wise conseil, settith your hy estat</L>
<L>In swhiche an ordre as ye lyu&euml; may</L>
<L>Of your good propre, in reule moderat;</L>
<L>Is it knyghtly lyue on rapyn&euml;? nay!</L>
<L N="4835">ffor Crist&euml;s sak&euml;, so yow gyeth ay,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at may strecch&euml; to your peples ese,</L>
<L N="4837">And &thorn;erwith-al ye schul god hily plese.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="692" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(692)</HEAD>
<L N="4838">&para; It apparteneth a kyng for to be<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Egidius in ij<SUP>a</SUP> parte j. libri politi|corum: Aris|toteles ad Re|gem maxime spectat vt sit rex secun|dum rei veri|tatem.</NOTE></L>
<L>A kyng in verray soth and &eacute;xist&eacute;nce.</L>
<L>A kyng, of office and of dignite</L>
<L>The name is; he moot don his diligence</L>
<L N="4842">His peple for to gy&euml; by prud&eacute;nce;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at he rule hem schuld&euml; du&euml;ly,</L>
<L N="4844">The stile of a 'kyng' he berith certeynly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="693" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(693)</HEAD>
<L N="4845">&para; As an archer may naght his arwe schete<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Eodem ca|pitulo: sicut sagittator non potest sagittam sufficienter dirigere in signum, nisi ipsum sig|num viderit, sic nec Rex &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euene at a merk, b&uacute;t he &thorn;e merk see,</L>
<L>No mor&euml; may a kyng, I yow byhete,</L>
<L>Gouerne his peple in rigth<NOTE PLACE="foot">right H.</NOTE> and equitee,</L>
<L N="4849">But by prud&eacute;nce he reule his hyghe degree;</L>
<L>If &thorn;at be wel, his peple hath sikernesse</L>
<L N="4851">Of reste and pees, wel&thorn;e, ioy&euml;, and gladnesse.
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="175"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="694" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(694)</HEAD>
<L N="4852">&para; Bygynnynge of wisdom is, god to drede;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Inicium sapiencie, timor domini.</NOTE></L>
<L>What kyng &thorn;at dredith god, is good and iust<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To his peple; bee&thorn; swiche, my lord, I rede!</L>
<L>In<NOTE PLACE="foot">In R, I H.</NOTE> loue and in awe of god, ficche&thorn; your lust;</L>
<L N="4856">Than be ye wys, and &thorn;an yow need&euml;s must,</L>
<L>Aftir your worldly sceptre transit&oacute;rie,</L>
<L N="4858">In heuene regne in p&eacute;rpetuel glorie.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="14" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 14.] De consilio habendo in omnibus factis.</HEAD>
<LG N="695" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(695)</HEAD>
<L N="4859">Now purpose I, to trete how to a kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated.</NOTE></L>
<L>It nedeful is to do by consail ay;</L>
<L>With-outen whiche, good is he do no &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>ffor a kyng is but a man soul, parfay!</L>
<L N="4863">And be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be R, he H.</NOTE> his witt neuere so good, he may</L>
<L>Erre and mistake hym o&thorn;er while among,</L>
<L>Where-as good counsail may exclude a<NOTE PLACE="foot">all R.</NOTE> wrong.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="696" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(696)</HEAD>
<L N="4866">Excellent princ&euml;, in axynge of reed,</L>
<L>Descouere&thorn; naght your wille in no maneere;</L>
<L>What &thorn;at ye &thorn;ink&euml; doo, lat it be deed</L>
<L>As for &thorn;e tym&euml;, lat no word appere;</L>
<L N="4870">But what euery man seith, wel herkne &amp; here;</L>
<L>And yit whan good counsail is yeuen yow,</L>
<L N="4872">What ye do wol&euml;, kepe it close y-now</L>
</LG>
<LG N="697" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(697)</HEAD>
<L N="4873">Til &thorn;at yow lyk&euml; p&aacute;rforme it in dede;</L>
<L>And if it schal be don, lat it noght tarie,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at is perillous with-out&euml; drede;</L>
<L>Ther is no &thorn;ing may make a lond myscarie</L>
<L N="4877">Mor&euml; than swiche delay; ful necess&aacute;rie</L>
<L>It is, a gode purpos parforme as bliue,<MILESTONE N="86a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4879">As, if it naght be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And that ye not R.</NOTE> out of mynde it dryue.
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="176"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="698" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(698)</HEAD>
<L N="4880">&para; And if &thorn;at &aacute; man of symple degree,</L>
<L>Or pore of birth, or &yogh;onge, be wel conseile,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be, goode counseile Yow yeve R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Admytte his resoun and take it in gre:</L>
<L>Why naght, my god&euml; lorde? what shuld yow eyle?</L>
<L N="4884">But men do naght so; where-of I merueyle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e worlde fau&oacute;rith ay &thorn;e rich&euml;s sawe,</L>
<L N="4886">&THORN;ow &thorn;at his conseil be noght worth an hawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="699" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(699)</HEAD>
<L N="4887">&para; What he seith, is vp to &thorn;e clowd&euml;s bore;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ecclesias|tici xiiij<SUP>o</SUP> diues locutus est, &amp; omnes tacuerunt, &amp; verbum illius vsque ad nu|bes perdu|cunt: pauper locutus est, &amp; dicunt, 'quis est hic?' &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>But and &thorn;e por&euml; spek&euml; worth &thorn;e twey,</L>
<L>His seed naght spryng&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">spryng H R.</NOTE> may, it nys but lore;</L>
<L>Thei seyen, "what is he, &thorn;is? lat hym goo pley!</L>
<L N="4891">O! worthi princ&euml;, beth wel ware, I prey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at your hye dygnite and sad prud&eacute;nce</L>
<L N="4893">No desdein haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> of &thorn;e por&euml;s sent&eacute;nce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="700" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(700)</HEAD>
<L N="4894">&para; Thogh men contr&aacute;rie eek your &oacute;ppynyoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei may, per cas, conseil&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">counceile R, conseil H.</NOTE> yow &thorn;e best;</L>
<L>Also ye ben at your eleccioun</L>
<L>To doo or leu&euml;, as your seluen lyst.</L>
<L N="4898">If it be gode, impresse it in &thorn;e chest</L>
<L>Of your mem&oacute;rie, and excusith it<NOTE PLACE="foot">execute R</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="4900">If it naght be, to leue it, is a wyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="701" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(701)</HEAD>
<L N="4901">&para; And if yow list your c&oacute;nseilere to preue,</L>
<L>Ye feyn&euml; mot ye haue necessite</L>
<L>Of golde; and if he ster&euml; yow, and meeue,</L>
<L>Your Iewels ley in wedd&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wedde R, wed H.</NOTE> certeyn he</L>
<L N="4905">Loueth your &eacute;state and prosperite;</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at redith yow, your peple oppresse,<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4907">He hatheth<NOTE PLACE="foot">hateth R.</NOTE> yow, cert&eacute;yne, it is no lesse.
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="177"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="702" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(702)</HEAD>
<L N="4908">&para; And if a man, in tyme of swich a nede,</L>
<L>Of his goode &yogh;eu&euml; yow a goode substaunce,</L>
<L>Swich oon cherich, and ell&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">Suche non cherissheth and elles R, els H.</NOTE> god forbede,</L>
<L>Konneth hym &thorn;ank of his goode cheuesaunce,</L>
<L N="4912">ffor him is leuer to suffre penaunce</L>
<L>Him-self, &thorn;an &thorn;at your peple shuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde R, shuld H.</NOTE> smert;</L>
<L N="4914">Ther is a preef of trew&euml; louyng hert.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="703" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(703)</HEAD>
<L N="4915">&para; In auxenge<NOTE PLACE="foot">axyng R.</NOTE> eeke of reed, ware of fauel;</L>
<L>Also ware<NOTE PLACE="foot">beware R.</NOTE> of &thorn;e auaric&iuml;ouse;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Non exiga|tur consilium ab adulatore nec de auaro.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor none of &thorn;o two can conseil&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">counceille R, conseil H.</NOTE> wel;</L>
<L>Hir reed &amp; conseil is envenymouse;</L>
<L N="4919">&THORN;ei both&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe R, bot H.</NOTE> ben of golde so d&eacute;sirous,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei rekk&euml; naght what bryge<NOTE PLACE="foot">brike R.</NOTE> her lorde be Inne,</L>
<L N="4921">So &thorn;at &thorn;ei mowen golde &amp; siluyr wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="704" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(704)</HEAD>
<L N="4922">&para; And if your conseil which &thorn;at ye haue take,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e knowlech or &thorn;e audience</L>
<L>Of your foos comen be, &thorn;an lat it slake,</L>
<L>And witterly putte it in abstinence;</L>
<L N="4926">ffor execute it were an<NOTE PLACE="foot">and H (it/it were grete prudence R!).</NOTE> inprudence;</L>
<L>In swich a caas, is wisdam it to chaunge;</L>
<L>Goode is, your conseil be to your foes straunge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="705" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(705)</HEAD>
<L N="4929">&para; Conseil may wel be likend to a bridil,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est, quod consilium bene potest freno com|parari.</NOTE></L>
<L>Which &thorn;at an hors vpkepeth fro fallyng,</L>
<L>If man do by conseil; but al in Idel</L>
<L>Is reed, if<NOTE PLACE="foot">yf R, of H.</NOTE> man naght folwe it in wirkyng.</L>
<L N="4933">Do no &thorn;ing redeles, do by conseylyng</L>
<L>Of hed&euml;s wyse, and than<NOTE PLACE="foot">than R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> noo r&eacute;pentaunce<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sine con|silio nichil facias, &amp; post factum non penitebis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4935">&THORN;er folwe yow schal in your gouernaunce.<MILESTONE N="87a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="178"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="706" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(706)</HEAD>
<L N="4936">&para; Comm&eacute;ndable is, cons&eacute;il take &oacute;f &thorn;e wyse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Thobie 4<SUP>o</SUP>. Consilium semper a sa|piente per|quire, &amp; non a fatuo, &amp;c. &para; Scriptum est, Cum fa|tuis non ha|beas consili|um, quia nou possunt dili|gere nisi quod eis placet. &para; Iterum Thobie 4<SUP>o</SUP>. Omnia con|silia tua in deo perma|neant, &amp;c. &para; Scriptum est, Cum bo|nis fac tuum consilium, non cum impiis, &amp;c. &para; Prouerbia|rum 12<SUP>o</SUP>. con|silia impior|um fraudu|lenta. &para; 3<SUP>o</SUP> Regum 12<SUP>o</SUP>. Ad Ro|boam dixer|unt Iuuenes qui nutriti erant cum eo, 'sic loqueris ad eos; Mini|mus digitus meus est grossior dor|so patris mei; &amp; nunc pater meus posuit super vos iu|gum graue, ego autem addam super iugum ves|trum; pater mens cecidit vos flagellis, ego autem cedam vos scorpionibus.'</NOTE></L>
<L>And noght of fool&euml;s, for &thorn;ei may noght loue</L>
<L>But<NOTE PLACE="foot">But R, And H.</NOTE> swich &thorn;ing as hem likyth. in al wyse,</L>
<L>Your conseiler, chesith our lorde god a-boue;</L>
<L N="4940">Chesith eke god&euml; men; &aacute;nd awey shoue</L>
<L>The wykkyd, whos conseyl is d&eacute;ceyu&aacute;ble;</L>
<L N="4942">&THORN;us byddyth holy writ, it is no fable.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="707" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(707)</HEAD>
<L N="4943">&para; Chesith men eke of olde experience;</L>
<L>Hir wit and intellect is gloriouse;</L>
<L>Of hir conseil, holsome is &thorn;e sentence;</L>
<L>&THORN;e old&euml; mann&euml;s rede is fructuouse;</L>
<L N="4947">Ware of yong c&oacute;nseyl, it is perilouse;</L>
<L>Roboas fonde it so, whan he forsoke</L>
<L N="4949">Old&euml; conseil, and to &thorn;e yong hym toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="708" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(708)</HEAD>
<L N="4950">&para; The &eacute;ntente, wot I wele, of &thorn;e yong man</L>
<L>As louyng is and trewe, as of the olde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;at he noght so wele conseilen can.</L>
<L>Yong men, strong ben, hardy, and bolde,</L>
<L N="4954">And more weldy to fight, if &thorn;at &thorn;ei sholde;</L>
<L>But aske<NOTE PLACE="foot">aske R, &thorn;ow H.</NOTE> &thorn;e olde in tyme of pees or werre</L>
<L N="4956">Rede &amp; conseil; it schal naght be &thorn;e werre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="709" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(709)</HEAD>
<L N="4957">&para; He &thorn;at is fressh and lusty now &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>By lengthe of yerees shal no &thorn;ing be so;</L>
<L>ffresshnesse &amp; lust may naght endure al-wey;</L>
<L>Whan age is comen, he commaundeth, ho!</L>
<L N="4961">But lat see, who considereth &thorn;is two,<NOTE PLACE="foot">who R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Goode is &thorn;at ag&euml; sette a gouernayle,<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4963">And youthe it sue: thus may al avayle.
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="179"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="710" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(710)</HEAD>
<L N="4964">Excellent prince, eeke on the holydayes<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Mandatum est, sabata sanctifices.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beth war&euml; &thorn;at ye nat your conseilles holde;</L>
<L>As for tho tym&euml;s,<NOTE PLACE="foot">the tyme R.</NOTE> put hem in deleyes;</L>
<L>Thenketh wel this, ye wel apayed be nolde</L>
<L N="4968">If your soggettes not be your hest&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">by your hest R.</NOTE> tolde,</L>
<L>Right so our lorde god, kyng &amp; commaundour</L>
<L N="4970">Of kynges al,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle R.</NOTE> is wroth with &thorn;at errour.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="711" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(711)</HEAD>
<L N="4971">&para; In &thorn;e longe &yogh;ere be werk&euml; daye<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben werke dayes R.</NOTE> I-nowe,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei be wel despent, for to entende</L>
<L>To conseil&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">counceiles R, conseils H.</NOTE>: to god your hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> bowe,</L>
<L>If ye desire men hir hert&euml;s bende</L>
<L N="4975">To yow. What kyng nat dredeth god offende,</L>
<L>Ne naght rekk&eacute;th do hym des&oacute;beisaunce,</L>
<L N="4977">He shal be disobei&euml;d eeke perchaunce.<NOTE PLACE="foot">perchaunce R, perchaunche H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="712" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(712)</HEAD>
<L N="4978">&para; The first&euml; fyndere of our faire lang&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>Hath seyde in caas sembl&aacute;ble, &amp; othir moo,</L>
<L>So hyly wel, &thorn;at it is my dot&aacute;ge</L>
<L>ffor to expresse or touche any of thoo.</L>
<L N="4982">Alasse! my fadir fro &thorn;e worlde is goo&mdash;</L>
<L>My worthi maister Chaucer, hym I mene&mdash;</L>
<L N="4984">Be &thorn;ou adu&oacute;ket for hym, heuenes<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuen R.</NOTE> quene!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="713" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(713)</HEAD>
<L N="4985">&para; As &thorn;ou wel knowest, o blissid virgyne,</L>
<L>With louyng hert, and hye deuoc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>In &thorn;yne honour he wroot ful many a lyne;</L>
<L>O now &thorn;ine helpe &amp; &thorn;i promoc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="4989">To god &thorn;i son&euml; make a moc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>How he &thorn;i seruaunt was, mayd&eacute;n marie,<MILESTONE N="88a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4991">And lat his lou&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">soule R.</NOTE> floure and fructifie.
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="180"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="714" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(714)</HEAD>
<L N="4992">&para; Al-&thorn;ogh his lyfe be queynt, &thorn;e r&eacute;semblaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the MS. Chaucer's carefully drawn and colourd likeness is in the right margin. At the top of the much commoner full-length figure in the left margin of MS. Reg. 17 D 6, is "&para; Chaucers yn age."</NOTE></L>
<L>Of him ha&thorn; in me so fressh lyflynesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, to putte othir men in r&eacute;membraunce</L>
<L>Of his pers&oacute;ne, I haue heere his lyknesse</L>
<L N="4996">Do mak&euml;, to &thorn;is ende in sothfastnesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at haue of him lest<NOTE PLACE="foot">lost R.</NOTE> &thorn;ought &amp; mynde,</L>
<L N="4998">By &thorn;is peyntur&euml; may ageyn him fynde.<FIGURE>
<P>[Grass-green background, black hood and gown, gray hair, hazel eyes, red lips, paleish face and hands; black beads and penner on red strings.]</P>
</FIGURE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="715" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(715)</HEAD>
<L N="4999">&para; The ymages &thorn;at in &thorn;e chirch&euml; been,</L>
<L>Maken folk &thorn;enke on god &amp; on his seyntes,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e ym&aacute;ges &thorn;ei be-holden &amp; seen;</L>
<L>Were oft vnsyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wher as vnsight R.</NOTE> of hem causith restreyntes</L>
<L N="5003">Of &thorn;ought&euml;s god&euml;: whan a &thorn;ing depeynt is,</L>
<L>Or &eacute;ntail&euml;d, if men take of it heede,</L>
<L N="5005">Thoght of &thorn;e lyknesse, it wil in hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem R, hym H.</NOTE> brede.
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="181"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="716" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(716)</HEAD>
<L N="5006">&para; Yit somme holden oppyn&yuml;oun, and sey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none ym&aacute;ges schuld I-maked be:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei erren foule, &amp; goon ont of &thorn;e wey;</L>
<L>Of trouth haue &thorn;ei scant sensibilite.</L>
<L N="5010">Passe ouer &thorn;at: now, blessid trinite,</L>
<L>Vppon my maistres soul&euml;, mercy haue,</L>
<L N="5012">ffor him, lady, eke &thorn;i mercy I craue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="717" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(717)</HEAD>
<L N="5013">&para; More othir &thorn;ing, wolde I fayne speke &amp; touche</L>
<L>Heere in &thorn;is booke; but such<NOTE PLACE="foot">such R, schuch H.</NOTE> is my dulnesse&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at al voyde and empty is my pouche,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at al my lust is queynt with heuynesse,</L>
<L N="5017">And<NOTE PLACE="foot">An R.</NOTE> heuy spirit c&oacute;maundith stilnesse.</L>
<L>And haue I spoke of pees, I schal be stille;<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5019">God sende vs pees, if &thorn;at it be his wille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="15" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&sect; 15. OF PEACE.]</HEAD>
<LG N="718" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(718)</HEAD>
<L N="5020">Touche I wol heere, of pees, a worde or two,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This page is illuminated</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est, Qui am|plectitur pa|cem in mentis hospicio <SUP>4</SUP> mansionem preparit Christo, &amp;c.<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 added in R.</NOTE> leronimus: Qui sine pace est, christum non habet. apud christi|anos non qui patitur sed qui facit con|tumeliam miser est.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;at scriptur&euml;s maken menc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">And R, An H.</NOTE> &thorn;an my boke is endid al, and do.</L>
<L>To crist ordeyne&thorn; he a manc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="5024">Which in his hert&euml;s habitac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Embraceth pees. wher pees is, crist is there,</L>
<L N="5026">ffor crist nat lyst a-byden ell&euml;s-where.<NOTE PLACE="foot">elleswhere R, els where H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="719" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(719)</HEAD>
<L N="5027">A-mong&euml;s cristen folk, wreche is he none<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prouerbia|rum 12<SUP>o</SUP>. Qui pacis ineunt consilia, se|quitur eos gaudium. Ciprianus dicit, Sacri|ficium deo est pax nos|tra &amp; fraterna concordia.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at pac&iuml;&eacute;ntly suffreth a duresse;</L>
<L>But sikirly a wrecch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrecche R, wrecch H.</NOTE> is he one</L>
<L>&THORN;at maki&thorn; strife; &amp; hym sueth gladnesse</L>
<L N="5031">Which &thorn;at of pees cons&eacute;ilith &thorn;e suernesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">swetnesse R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Our pees also and concorde brothirly</L>
<L N="5033">Is sacrific&euml; to god &aacute;l myghty.
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="182"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="720" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(720)</HEAD>
<L N="5034">Thyng&euml;s &thorn;at leden men to pees be thre:<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est, Tria sunt pacis subsidia &amp; ad pacem ducencia, scilicet con|formitas in deo, humilitas in seipso, &amp; tranquillitas cum proximo, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Conformyng in god; in our self humblesse;</L>
<L>And with<NOTE PLACE="foot">with R, wit H.</NOTE> our neigh&euml;boures tranquillite.</L>
<L>ffirst seye I &thorn;at we moot our will&euml;s dresse,</L>
<L N="5038">And hem conformen all&euml; more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>To goddis wil; al &thorn;ingis<NOTE PLACE="foot">all thyng R.</NOTE> is in his myght,</L>
<L N="5040">Sauf only &thorn;at he m&aacute;y done non vnright.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="721" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(721)</HEAD>
<L N="5041">Euene as a man is euer in werre and strife,</L>
<L>&THORN;at besieth hym withstande a man, which he</L>
<L>&para; Nat may; right so hathe he peisible<NOTE PLACE="foot">pesible R, preisible H.</NOTE> lyfe<MILESTONE N="89a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Continuelly, whos will&euml;s fully be</L>
<L N="5045">To godd&euml;s wille conformyng: o, pardee!<NOTE PLACE="marg">[R] Iob <I>iiij</I><SUP>to</SUP> Quis resistit Deo, et pacem habuit? quasi diceret nullus.</NOTE></L>
<L>A-geyn god helpeth &thorn;ere no r&eacute;sistence,</L>
<L N="5047">So strong and my&yogh;ty is his excellence.<NOTE PLACE="foot">residence R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="722" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(722)</HEAD>
<L N="5048">&para; Humilite, to pees eke may men lede;</L>
<L>Men say two gret&euml; may nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete may evill R, gret may nat H.</NOTE> in o sak;</L>
<L>But symple humblesse is of such<NOTE PLACE="foot">such R, schuch H.</NOTE> godely-hede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at she of troubly hat&euml; ha&thorn; no smak;</L>
<L N="5052">She stryueth nat; of discorde hath she lak;</L>
<L>She voyde and empty is of cruelte:</L>
<L N="5054">Humble spirit desirith vnite.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="723" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(723)</HEAD>
<L N="5055">&para; The thrid is eke tranquillite of &thorn;ought,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gydeth man to pees; for as a wight</L>
<L>May in a bedde of &thorn;orn&euml;s rest&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">rest H R.</NOTE> noght,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so, who<NOTE PLACE="foot">who &thorn;at H, he that R.</NOTE> is with greuous &thorn;ought&euml;s twight,</L>
<L N="5059">May with himself nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">nor R, non H.</NOTE> othir folk a-ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Hau&euml; no pees; a man mot nedys smert</L>
<L N="5061">Whan irous &thorn;ought&euml;s occupye his hert.
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="724" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(724)</HEAD>
<L N="5062">&para; And euene as vppon a pillow softe,</L>
<L>Man may him rest&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">rest H R.</NOTE> wele, and take his ese,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so &thorn;at lorde &thorn;at sittith in heuen a-lofte,</L>
<L>Hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hert H R.</NOTE> peisible can so like and plese,</L>
<L N="5066">&THORN;at he wol entre &thorn;&eacute;r-in, and it sese,</L>
<L>And occupie it as iust p&oacute;ssessoure;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Scriptum est, In pace factus est locus eius, &amp;c. [R] Est enim pax mala, que est vere paci contra|ria; &amp; hoc est quando corda sunt in mala concor|dancia, &amp;c. Talem pacem habuit Pila|tus cum Herode, &amp;c. &para; De tali pace loquitur psalmista, Zelam super iniquos pa|cem pecca|torum videns.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5068">In place of pees, resteth our sav&iuml;our.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="725" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(725)</HEAD>
<L N="5069">&para; But al an othir pees &thorn;er is also,</L>
<L>Which is naght worth; it is envenymouse;</L>
<L>ffor it is vnto verray pees a foo;<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whan R, Wham H.</NOTE> men in a purp&oacute;s malic&iuml;ouse</L>
<L N="5073">Acorden, &thorn;&aacute;t pees is to god greuous:</L>
<L>Swich pees was twix Her&oacute;des &amp; pilat;</L>
<L N="5075">And in swich caas, pees is wers &thorn;anne debat.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="726" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(726)</HEAD>
<L N="5076">&para; A feyn&euml;d pees, eeke is to pees verray,</L>
<L>A foo; and swich was &thorn;e pees of Iudas</L>
<L>Kissyng crist. Lord! whedir &thorn;at &thorn;is day</L>
<L>Any swich pees vs&euml;d is as<NOTE PLACE="foot">as R, os H.</NOTE> &thorn;at was!</L>
<L N="5080">&YOGH;e, so I drede me, by seynt Thomas,</L>
<L>The kus of Iudas is now wid&euml; sprad,<SUP>5</SUP></L>
<L N="5082">Tokenes of pees ben, but smal loue is had.<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 spradde . . hadde R, sparde . . had H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="727" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(727)</HEAD>
<L N="5083">&para; Men contrefete in wordis Tull&iuml;us,</L>
<L>And folwe in werke Iudas or Genyloun<NOTE PLACE="foot">The traitor at Roncesvalles. See Chaucer's <I>Monk's Tale,</I> Pedro of Spayne.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Many an hony<NOTE PLACE="foot">hony R, heny H.</NOTE> worde and many a kus</L>
<L>Ther is; but wayte on &thorn;e conclus&iuml;oun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Et de tali pace loquitur psalmista. Qui loquun|tur pacem cum proximo suo, mala autem, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5087">And pryue galle all turnyth vp-so-doun;</L>
<L>Ther leueth naght of pees, but contenance,</L>
<L N="5089">ffor al &thorn;e peyntyd chere and daliance.
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="728" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(728)</HEAD>
<L N="5090">&para; Ther is also a pees inordinat,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e grett&eacute;r obeith to &thorn;e lesse;</L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="foot">As R, And H.</NOTE> &thorn;us, whan to his soget a prelat</L>
<L>Obeyeth; and whan reson, &thorn;e blyndnesse</L>
<L N="5094">Sueth of sensualitees madnesse,</L>
<L>Obeying it: al swich pees is haynous,</L>
<L N="5096">ffor it is good&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to god. R.</NOTE> pees contrarious.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="729" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(729)</HEAD>
<L N="5097">&para; Right swich a pees, Adam had with Eue,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he vnto hir desire obeyde;</L>
<L>He was, per caas, adradd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">adredde R, adrad H.</NOTE> for to greue;<MILESTONE N="90a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Where-for he did as &thorn;at she to<NOTE PLACE="foot">as that she R, at &thorn;at she H.</NOTE> hym seide:<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Contra talem pacem loquitur christus, Matthaei 10. Non veni, inquit, pacem mittere, sed gladium. &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5101">In &thorn;at obedienc&euml; he foleyde,</L>
<L>ffor god hir him bytoke him to obeye;</L>
<L N="5103">But I a-drad am &thorn;at I &thorn;us fer seye<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferre sey R, fer seide H.</NOTE>;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="730" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(730)</HEAD>
<L N="5104">&para; If &thorn;at &thorn;is come vnto the audience</L>
<L>Of women, I am sure I shal be shent:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at I touche of swich obedience,</L>
<L>Many a brow&euml; shal on me be bent;</L>
<L N="5108">Thei will&euml; wayten been<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolden waite to ben R, wil . . . H.</NOTE> equipollent,</L>
<L>And sumwhat mor&euml;, vnto hir housbondis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">husbondis R, housbond (es <I>scratcht out</I>) H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sum men seyn swich vsage in &thorn;is lond is.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lond is R, lond(es <I>scratcht out</I>) H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="731" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(731)</HEAD>
<L N="5111">&para; And it no wonder is, as semeth me,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at I me be-&thorn;ought haue al aboute,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;at wom&eacute;n desiren souereynte,</L>
<L>And hir housbond&euml;s mak&euml; to hem loute;</L>
<L N="5115">Thei made ware of a ribbe, it is no doute,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Genesis 20. Mulier facta fuit de costa Ade; homo vero de limo terre, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Which more strong is, and s&uacute;bstancial,</L>
<L N="5117">&THORN;an slyme of eerthe, &amp; clenner &thorn;er-with-al.
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="185"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="732" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(732)</HEAD>
<L N="5118">&para; Wher-for it semeth &thorn;at &thorn;e worthynesse</L>
<L>Of women, passyth menn&euml;s encerteyne;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it sum nys&euml; men, of lewd&euml;nesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lewdenesse R, lewenes H.</NOTE></L>
<L>In r&eacute;pref of hem holden ther-a-geyn,</L>
<L N="5122">ffor crokid was &thorn;at ribbe; and speke &amp; seyne,</L>
<L>That also crokid is hir curtaisie;</L>
<L N="5124">But a-gayn &thorn;at, strongly wil I replie;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="733" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(733)</HEAD>
<L N="5125">ffor in the writyng and in &thorn;e scripture</L>
<L>Of Philosophers,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Philosofres R, Philosophes H.</NOTE> men may see &amp; reede,</L>
<L>&para; Cercly<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cerclelyk R.</NOTE> shap is most perfite fig&uacute;re,<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Secundum omnes phi|losophos, ffigura circu|laris est per|fectissima figura, &amp; significat in geometria vnitatem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi-tokenyng, in g&eacute;metrie, onhede;</L>
<L N="5129">And crokydnesse a part is, &thorn;at may lede</L>
<L>Sumwhat vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto (<I>overline,? later</I>) R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> cercle or a cumpas:</L>
<L>What so men seyen, women stonde in gode caas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="734" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(734)</HEAD>
<L N="5132">&para; ffor ther-by shewith it, &thorn;at crokydnesse</L>
<L>Streccheth vnto &thorn;e gretter perfeccioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;an doth a &thorn;ing &thorn;at is of euenesse;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is helpith no contradicc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="5136">ffor it soth is;<NOTE PLACE="foot">is R, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> it is no ficc&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>Euery perfit body &thorn;at man kan neuene,</L>
<L>Is rounde and crokyd, and noght<NOTE PLACE="foot">not R, nogh H.</NOTE> streghte ne euene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="735" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(735)</HEAD>
<L N="5139">&para; By-gynn&euml; first at heuen, &amp; rounde it is;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sonne and mone, &amp; &thorn;e sterr&euml;s also;</L>
<L>Hed of man, &thorn;en mouth, &amp; hert, I-wisse,</L>
<L>Ben all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle R, al H.</NOTE> rounde; and othir ben &thorn;er moo</L>
<L N="5143">Than I expresse as<NOTE PLACE="foot">as R, os H.</NOTE> now; but or I goo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it shal I bet wommann&euml;s part sustene;</L>
<L N="5145">So biddeth pees, &amp; &thorn;at to folwe I mene.
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="736" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(736)</HEAD>
<L N="5146">&para; Now for to speke or touchen of &thorn;e place</L>
<L>In which &thorn;at man &amp; womman <SUP>1</SUP>fourmed were:</L>
<L>Almyghty God to womman<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 H <I>om.</I></NOTE> shope swich grace,</L>
<L>That she was form&euml;d in the worthier;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Mulier fuit formata in paradiso, &amp; homo in agro damaseeno, qui locus est extra paradi|sum, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5150">In paradys men wot wel he made here;</L>
<L>But man ymade<NOTE PLACE="foot">ymade R, made H.</NOTE> was out of paradys,</L>
<L N="5152">In place of less&euml; worthinesse &amp; prys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="737" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(737)</HEAD>
<L N="5153">&para; And of &thorn;e maner of formac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Of both&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe two herkeneth R, both . . . H.</NOTE> two herken&thorn; now wel I prey;</L>
<L>The token or &thorn;e significacioun<MILESTONE N="91a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of making of Ad&aacute;m, may be no way</L>
<L N="5157">Strecch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Strecche R, Strecch H.</NOTE> to so perfyte a goode, I say,</L>
<L>As did&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">did H R.</NOTE> &thorn;e formac&iuml;oun of Eue;</L>
<L N="5159">And &thorn;at as swith&euml; here I schal it preue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="738" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(738)</HEAD>
<L N="5160">&para; ffor mor&euml; haue I for hir partye &yogh;it:<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Secundum augustinum &amp; omnes doc|tores catho|licos, ffor|macio Eue significauit formacionem ecclesie &amp; sa|cramentorum eius; Nam sicut, Adam dormiente, formabatur Eua &amp; mem|bra eius de latere ipsius Ade, sic <I>christo</I> dor|miente in cruce, forma|batur de latere &amp;c. [R eius ec|clesia et eius sacramenta.] Beatus ber|nardus dicit. &para; A tempore quo christus erat duoden|nis, vsque ad annum xxx<SUP>ti</SUP>, fuit cum ma|tre sua, ser|uiens ei in omnibus que sciuit sibi placitura, eo quod ad hoc venerat in mundum, vt doceret ver|am humili|tatem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Making of Eu&euml; tokned &thorn;e makyng</L>
<L>Of holy chirche, and sacramentes of it;</L>
<L>As of &thorn;e syde of Adam, him slepyng,</L>
<L N="5164">Eu&euml; vas<NOTE PLACE="foot">was R.</NOTE> made, so our lorde crist deyeng</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e crois, hol&yacute; chirche, of his syde,</L>
<L N="5166">And &thorn;e sacr&aacute;mentes made were in &thorn;at tyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="739" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(739)</HEAD>
<L N="5167">&para; ffro tyme eeke crist was of xij &yogh;er&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">twelve yere of R.</NOTE> age</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;ritty, he with his modir ay</L>
<L>Was seruyng hir with right<NOTE PLACE="foot">right, <I>om.</I> H R.</NOTE> plesant cor&aacute;ge;</L>
<L>To teche humilite, he tooke &thorn;e way</L>
<L N="5171">ffro heuen hiddir, and mek&euml;nesse verray</L>
<L>Tau&yogh;t he, &thorn;e most&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">most H R.</NOTE> partie of his lyf,</L>
<L N="5173">Whil he was with his modir &amp; his wyfe;
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="187"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="740" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(740)</HEAD>
<L N="5174">&para; ffor she was both&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">both H R.</NOTE> two; and syn she had</L>
<L>So long of hir housbond&euml; &thorn;e maystrie,</L>
<L>Women, I trow&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowe R, trow H.</NOTE> be nat now so mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at styl&euml; to for-go; nay, swich folye,</L>
<L N="5178">What man &thorn;at can in a wom&aacute;n espye,</L>
<L>Is worthi shryn&euml;d be; god saue hem alle,</L>
<L N="5180">And graunt hir hy&euml; corage nat to palle!<NOTE PLACE="foot">This is a faint imitation of Chaucer.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="741" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(741)</HEAD>
<L N="5181">&para; Holy writ seith, 'if women souereynte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ecclesi|astici. 25<SUP>o</SUP>. Mulier, si primatum habeat, con|traria est viro suo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of hir housbond&euml;s haue, how &thorn;at &thorn;ei</L>
<L>Vnto housbond&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">her husbondes R.</NOTE> contrar&iuml;ous be:'<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e text is such,<NOTE PLACE="foot">is such I wote wele R, I woot wel is schuch H.</NOTE> I woot wel, but what &thorn;ei?</L>
<L N="5185">That text I vndir-stond&euml; &thorn;us al-wey:</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at housbond&euml;s hem mys-take and erre,</L>
<L N="5187">Ageyn &thorn;at vic&euml; wyu&euml;s maken werre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="742" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(742)</HEAD>
<L N="5188">&para; Thogh a woman hir housbonde contrarie</L>
<L>In his oppynyoun erroneous,</L>
<L>Shul men for &thorn;at deme hir his aduersarie?</L>
<L>Straw! be he neuer so harrageous,<NOTE PLACE="foot">outrageous R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5192">If he &amp; she shul dwellen in on house,</L>
<L>Goode is he suffre; therby pees may spring;</L>
<L N="5194">Housbond&euml;s pees is pesible suffryng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="743" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(743)</HEAD>
<L N="5195">&para; By concorde, smal&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">smale R, smal H.</NOTE> &thorn;ing&euml;s multiplien;</L>
<L>And by discorde, hate, ire, and rancour,</L>
<L>Perysshen &thorn;ing&euml;s grete, &amp; wast &amp; dyen.</L>
<L>Pees hath &thorn;e fruyt of eese<NOTE PLACE="foot">oseese H, ese R.</NOTE> in his fauour;</L>
<L N="5199">To get&euml; pees hols&oacute;me is &thorn;e labour,</L>
<L>And kepe it wel, whan a<NOTE PLACE="foot">that a R, a <I>rubd out of</I> H.</NOTE> man hath it cau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5201">That ire ne disc&oacute;rde bannysshe it naght.
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="744" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(744)</HEAD>
<L N="5202">&para; How plesant to god, is of pees &thorn;e myrthe!</L>
<L>What delyte eeke in pees and vnioun<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Et in terra pax homini|bus. Pax vobis. Pacem relin|quo vobis.</NOTE></L>
<L>The prince of pees hath shew&euml;d in his birth,</L>
<L>By angels delit&aacute;ble song and soun;</L>
<L N="5206">Also, aftir his resurrecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>He pees bad; and whan vnto heuen he stigh,</L>
<L N="5208">He left&euml; pees in erth&euml; tru&euml;ly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lefte . . . truly R, left . . . truly H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="745" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(745)</HEAD>
<L N="5209">&para; &THORN;at &yogh;ift of pees, &thorn;at prec&iuml;ouse Iewel,</L>
<L>If men it kepe, &amp; do it naght away,</L>
<L>Son&euml;s of crist &thorn;ei may be clept<NOTE PLACE="foot">clept R, clepyd H.</NOTE> ful wel;<MILESTONE N="92a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Beati paci|fici &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>But strif, which moche is to &thorn;e fend&euml;s paye,</L>
<L N="5213">Among vs feruent is so, welawey!</L>
<L>We<NOTE PLACE="foot">We R, Whe H.</NOTE> cristen folk, with-inne vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">what within R.</NOTE> and with-out,</L>
<L>Haue so gret stryfe, &thorn;at &thorn;er may no pees rout.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="746" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(746)</HEAD>
<L N="5216">&para; The ryot &thorn;at ha&thorn; ben with-in &thorn;is lande<NOTE PLACE="foot">lande R, londe H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Among our-self, many<NOTE PLACE="foot">full many R.</NOTE> a wyntr&euml;s space,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The rebellions of the Percies against Henry IV.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hath to &thorn;e swerd put many a thousand:</L>
<L>The gredy hert, &thorn;at wold&euml; al embrace,</L>
<L N="5220">With<NOTE PLACE="foot">With R, Wit H.</NOTE> irous wil, and crabbed pal&euml; face,</L>
<L>And swypir<NOTE PLACE="foot">swepir R.</NOTE> feendly hand with strook venge&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; many a woman maad hem clo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">made clothed R, maad hem clo&thorn; H.</NOTE> in sable.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="747" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(747)</HEAD>
<L N="5223">&para; &THORN;is is no dout&euml;, &thorn;at ambic&iuml;oun</L>
<L>And couetys&euml; fyre al &thorn;is debate;</L>
<L>Tho two be of wikk&eacute;d condic&iuml;oun.</L>
<L>No wight halt hym content of his estate;</L>
<L N="5227">Euery man wilne&thorn; to ben &eacute;xaltat;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh he be gret, &yogh;it hir&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hier R.</NOTE> wolde he goo,</L>
<L N="5229">And &thorn;eis aren causes of our stryues<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben . . . stryfe R.</NOTE> &amp; woo.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="189"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="748" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(748)</HEAD>
<L N="5230">&para; Werr&euml; within our-Iself is most harmf&uacute;l</L>
<L>And perillous, &amp; most is a-gayn kynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-with &thorn;is land hath wrastled many a pul;</L>
<L>&THORN;e smert is swich, it may nat out of mynde,</L>
<L N="5234">ffor it ha&thorn; cast our welth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">welthe R, welth H.</NOTE> far be-hynde,</L>
<L>And ferther wol&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wole R, wold H.</NOTE> but thoo werr&euml;s stynt;</L>
<L>No goode may come of werr&euml;s wrathful dynt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="749" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(749)</HEAD>
<L N="5237">&para; Whil&euml;s &thorn;at Romaynes were in hert al oon,</L>
<L>And vndeuydid, al<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle R.</NOTE> hool stode, &thorn;ei were</L>
<L>Lord&euml;s of al &thorn;e worlde; foo was &thorn;er non<MILESTONE N="92b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Out-warde, as who seith, myght hem greue or dere;</L>
<L N="5241">But al sauf welth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">welthe R, welth H.</NOTE> may men suffre and bere;</L>
<L>With<NOTE PLACE="foot">With R, Wit H.</NOTE>-Inne hym-self sprang such deuys&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="5243">&THORN;at it hem brought&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">brought H R.</NOTE> to confusioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="750" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(750)</HEAD>
<L N="5244">&para; What causyd hir inw&aacute;rd werre and rumour<NOTE PLACE="foot">murmur R.</NOTE></L>
<L>But aueric&euml;? she reft hem her wele;</L>
<L>Whil&euml;s &thorn;ei had in cheerte and fauour</L>
<L>Profit commun, thei hadden bi &thorn;e stele</L>
<L N="5248">Prosperite; but it a-way gan stele</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei him drough to profyte singuler,<NOTE PLACE="foot">syngulere R, singurer H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5250">And of profyt commun nat weren cheer.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="751" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(751)</HEAD>
<L N="5251">&para; By-hold how<NOTE PLACE="foot">how R, of H.</NOTE> auaric&euml; crepith inne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota de Auaricia.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kyndlith werre, and quenchi&thorn; vnite!</L>
<L>O fauel! &thorn;ou myght&eacute;st ben of hir kynne,</L>
<L>ffor swich a breek&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">breke pees R, breek pees H.</NOTE>-pees as &thorn;at is she,</L>
<L N="5255">Right swich a-nothir, may I nam&euml; &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou rekkest nat, ne dredest nat, to wende</L>
<L N="5257">ffor muk to helle, vnto &thorn;e ferthest<NOTE PLACE="foot">into the ferrest R.</NOTE> ende.
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="190"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="752" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(752)</HEAD>
<L N="5258">&para; This fauel is of pees a d&eacute;stourbour;</L>
<L>Twix god and mann&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">mannes R, man H.</NOTE> soule he werr&euml; reisith;</L>
<L>This worlde is blent by &thorn;is dissymulour;</L>
<L>Vert&uacute; he blame&thorn;, &aacute;nd vic&eacute;s he preysith;</L>
<L N="5262">Sore in &thorn;e bowe of treccherye he teisyth;</L>
<L>His shot is gay, but it is &eacute;nvenymed;</L>
<L N="5264">His fikil art may nat a-ryght be rymed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="753" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(753)</HEAD>
<L N="5265">&para; Vertuouse trouth&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">trouthe R, trouth H.</NOTE> hyd&euml; &thorn;ou &thorn;ine heede!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst as wele, thyn art may nat a-vayle;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world&euml;s grace art &thorn;ou as dede:<MILESTONE N="93a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But fauel, traitour! &thorn;i fals gouernaile</L>
<L N="5269">Makith ful manny shipp&euml;s for to saile</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;i cofre; warme is &thorn;ine office;</L>
<L N="5271">&THORN;at trouth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">trouthe R, trouth H.</NOTE> lesith, wynn&euml; can &thorn;i vice.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="754" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(754)</HEAD>
<L N="5272">&para; Alas! so manny a worthi clerk fam&oacute;use,</L>
<L>In Oxinford, and in Cambrigge also,</L>
<L>Stonde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Stonde R, Stode H.</NOTE> vn-avanc&euml;d, wher the viciouse</L>
<L>ffauel hath chirches. &amp; preuendres,<NOTE PLACE="foot">prebendes R.</NOTE> moo</L>
<L N="5276">&THORN;an god is plesid with;<NOTE PLACE="foot">with R, wit H.</NOTE> alasse! of thoo</L>
<L>&THORN;at weiuen vertu so to be<NOTE PLACE="foot">wernen . . . so to be R, weiuen (<I>or</I> weinen) . . . so be H.</NOTE> promoted;</L>
<L N="5278">And &thorn;ei helples, in whom vertu is rooted.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="755" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(755)</HEAD>
<L N="5279">&para; The knyght or sqwier, on &thorn;at othir syde,</L>
<L>Or Ieman, &thorn;at ha&thorn; in pees or in werris</L>
<L>Dispent with his lorde his blode, but he hyde</L>
<L>&THORN;e trouth, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and R, an H.</NOTE> can currey fauel, he nat &thorn;e nere is</L>
<L N="5283">His lord&euml;s grace; and vn-trouth ful fer is</L>
<L>ffrom him, &thorn;at worthy corage hath hon&oacute;ured;</L>
<L N="5285">Grace of his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his R, &thorn;is H.</NOTE> lorde by fauel is deu&oacute;ured.
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="191"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="756" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(756)</HEAD>
<L N="5286">&para; Now vnto my mateere of werre inwarde</L>
<L>Resort I; but to sek&euml; stories olde</L>
<L>Non nede is, syn &thorn;is day sharp werre &amp; harde</L>
<L>Is at &thorn;e dore here, as men may be-holde:</L>
<L N="5290">ffraunc&euml;, no wondir &thorn;ogh &thorn;ine hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> colde,</L>
<L>And brenne also:<NOTE PLACE="foot">also sithen R, also seith H.</NOTE> swich is &thorn;ine agonye,</L>
<L N="5292">Thi self manaseth &thorn;i self for to dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="757" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(757)</HEAD>
<L N="5293">&para; Thi self destroye, and feble is &thorn;i vict&oacute;rye!</L>
<L>Thow hast in &thorn;i self stryven oft<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte R, of H.</NOTE> or nowe,</L>
<L>And hast appesid al,<NOTE PLACE="foot">all R.</NOTE> haue in mem&oacute;rie,<MILESTONE N="93b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;i prudence; wost &thorn;ou nat wel how</L>
<L N="5297">Slaghtre is defendid? and nat rekkest &thorn;ow</L>
<L>To rebelle a-geyn god &thorn;at it forbedith?</L>
<L N="5299">ffor the, myne heuy gost bisily dredith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="758" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(758)</HEAD>
<L N="5300">&para; What any part offendid hath to othir,</L>
<L>Redresse it faire and charytablely;<NOTE PLACE="foot">charitably R, charytably H.</NOTE></L>
<L>By lawe of god, ye ben ech others brothir.</L>
<L>O! now aday&euml;s is noon enemye</L>
<L N="5304">Lyke oon &thorn;at is to othir of blood&euml; nye;</L>
<L>Beth ware! correct it! lest men of yow seye,</L>
<L>'lo! whilom this was ffraunce of hye nobley!'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="759" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(759)</HEAD>
<L N="5307">&para; I am an Englyssh-man, &amp; am &thorn;i foo,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou a foo art vnto my lyge&aacute;nce;</L>
<L>And yit myn hert&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hert H R.</NOTE> stuffid is with woo</L>
<L>To see &thorn;yn vnkyndly disseueraunce:</L>
<L N="5311">Accordeth yow! girde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">gurdeth R.</NOTE> yow with suffraunce!</L>
<L>Ye greu&euml; god, and your-self harme &amp; shame,</L>
<L N="5313">And your foos ther-of han disport &amp; game.
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="760" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(760)</HEAD>
<L N="5314">&para; Alase! Also, &thorn;e greet dissenc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>The pitous harme, &thorn;e hat&euml;ful discorde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hath endur&euml;d twix &thorn;is regioun</L>
<L>And othir land&euml;s cristen! he, &thorn;at lorde</L>
<L N="5318">Of Remes al is &thorn;e auctor of<NOTE PLACE="foot">all is the actour and R.</NOTE> concorde</L>
<L>And pees, sore is meeu&euml;d &thorn;er-with; but we</L>
<L N="5320">Naght dreden for to offend his mageste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="761" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(761)</HEAD>
<L N="5321">&para; Off fraunce and englonde, o cristen princes,</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at your style of worthynes is ronge</L>
<L>Thurgh-out &thorn;e world, in al &thorn;e prouinces,<MILESTONE N="94a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If &thorn;at of yow myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">myght H R.</NOTE> be red<NOTE PLACE="foot">radde R.</NOTE> or songe</L>
<L N="5325">That ye were oon in herte, ther nys no<NOTE PLACE="foot">is no R, nys H.</NOTE> tonge</L>
<L>That myghte expresse, how profitable and good</L>
<L N="5327">Vnto al peple it were of cristen blood.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="762" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(762)</HEAD>
<L N="5328">&para; Yeue hem ensamplen!<NOTE PLACE="foot">ensample R.</NOTE> ye ben hir mirrours;</L>
<L>They folowen yow: what sorwe lamentable</L>
<L>Is caus&euml;d of youre werr&euml;s scharp&euml; schoures</L>
<L>Ther wot no wight, it is irr&eacute;parable!</L>
<L N="5332">O noble cristen Princes honurable,</L>
<L>ffor him &thorn;at for yow suffred pass&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="5334">Of cristen blod, haue&thorn; compass&iuml;oun!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="763" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(763)</HEAD>
<L N="5335">&para; Allas! what peple ha&thorn; your werr&euml; slayn!</L>
<L>What corn&euml;s wast, and doun&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wasted and doune R, wast and doun H.</NOTE> trode &amp; schent!</L>
<L>How many a wif and maide ha&thorn; be by layn!<NOTE PLACE="foot">forlayne R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Castels doun bette, and tymbred houses brent,</L>
<L N="5339">And drawen downe, and al to-torn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">all to-tore R, also torne H.</NOTE> and rent!</L>
<L>The harm ne may nat rekened be, ne told;</L>
<L N="5341">This werr&euml; wexi&thorn; al to hoor and old.
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="764" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(764)</HEAD>
<L N="5342">&para; To wynn&euml; worldly tresour and richesse,</L>
<L>Is of your strif &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">your R.</NOTE> longe continuaunce;</L>
<L>Wherby it semeth &thorn;at ye han scantnesse</L>
<L>Of good, or ye konne haue no s&uacute;ffisaunce</L>
<L N="5346">Of plente; and if &thorn;&eacute;r be h&aacute;bundaunce</L>
<L>In youre cofres, and in your hert&euml;s nede,</L>
<L N="5348">Of lordly<NOTE PLACE="foot">lordes R.</NOTE> c&oacute;nceit may it not procede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="765" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(765)</HEAD>
<L N="5349">&para; Whan Alisaundre deed was, and y-graue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in his graue R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And his toumbe &oacute;f gold wroght ful rich&euml;ly,</L>
<L>As kyng&euml;s dignite wole axe and craue,<MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Dyuerse philosophres droghen<NOTE PLACE="foot">drowe R, drogh H.</NOTE> hem nygh</L>
<L N="5353">Therto; and as oon of hem stood &thorn;erby,</L>
<L>he seid&euml; &thorn;us among &thorn;e folk&euml;s alle:&mdash;</L>
<L>"See&thorn; swiche a chaunge is new&euml; now byfalle!<NOTE PLACE="foot">chaunce now newe is falle R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="766" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(766)</HEAD>
<L N="5356">&para; "This Alisaundre mad&euml; yistirday</L>
<L>Of gold his tresor, but gold maki&thorn; now</L>
<L>Tresor of him, as ye be-hold&euml; may."</L>
<L>An<NOTE PLACE="foot">An R, And H.</NOTE> othir philosopher seide eek how</L>
<L N="5360">"Al &thorn;is world yistirday was nat y-now</L>
<L>To stoppen<NOTE PLACE="foot">stoppen R, stoppe H.</NOTE> Alisaundres couetise,</L>
<L N="5362">And now thre elnes of clo&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cloth hym do, clo&thorn; him H.</NOTE> him suffice."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="767" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(767)</HEAD>
<L N="5363">&para; O worthi princes two, now taki&thorn; hede!</L>
<L>As hardy, deth is yow for to assaille</L>
<L>As sche<NOTE PLACE="foot">he R.</NOTE> dide Alisaundre, whom in drede</L>
<L>Hadde al &thorn;is world; what myght his force auaille</L>
<L N="5367">A-gayn &thorn;e deth? no thing, san&yogh; faille;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ogh &thorn;at he swerd wer<NOTE PLACE="foot">were R.</NOTE> of chiualrie,</L>
<L>Deth threwe him doun to grounde, &amp; lete him lye.
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="194"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="768" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(768)</HEAD>
<L>&para; With how<NOTE PLACE="foot">out R.</NOTE> grete labour, or wi&thorn; how<NOTE PLACE="foot">out R.</NOTE> gret peyne,</L>
<L>Men wynn&euml; good, to &thorn;e world [&thorn;ey] leue it schal;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e pitte go&thorn; nought but &thorn;e careyne:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ogh gold wer&euml; grauen &thorn;er-with-al,</L>
<L N="5374">Naght myght it help&euml;: beth nat gold&euml;s thral!</L>
<L>Suffiseth to your good,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Chaucer, <I>Truth</I> 'Suffiseth to your good, thogh it be smal.'</NOTE> ye princes bo&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="5376">With pees and rest&euml;, arm&euml; yow and clothe!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="769" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(769)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan ye haue stryue and foughten al your fille,</L>
<L>Pees folwe moot; but good were it, or thanne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; ffinis belli pax.</NOTE></L>
<L>That pees were hadde: what lust han ye to spille<MILESTONE N="95a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The blood &thorn;at crist with his blood boghte, whanne</L>
<L N="5381">He on &thorn;e croys starf? o lady seint Anne,</L>
<L>Thi doughter prey&euml; to beseche hir sone</L>
<L N="5383">To stynte of werr&euml;s &thorn;e dampn&aacute;ble wone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="770" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(770)</HEAD>
<L N="5384">&para; The book of reuelac&iuml;ouns of Bride<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; libro 4<SUP>o</SUP> de reuelacioni|bus sancte Brigide, ca|pitulo cv<SUP>o</SUP> Christus di|cit, "ego sum pax," &amp;c. &para; Si reges ffrancie &amp; Anglie volue|rint habere pacem, ego dabo eis per|petuam pa|cem: sed pax vera non po|test haberi, nisi veritas &amp; iusticia diligantur. Ideo quia al|ter Regum habet iustici|am, placet mihi quod per matrimo|nium fiat pax, &amp; sic regnum ad legitti|mum here|dem poterit peruenire &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Expressith how crist &thorn;us seide hir vnto:</L>
<L>"I am pees verray; &thorn;ere I wole abide,</L>
<L>Where as pees is; non o&thorn;er wole I do.</L>
<L N="5388">Of ffraunce and Eng&euml;lond &thorn;e kyng&euml;s two,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei wole haue pees, pees perpetuel</L>
<L>Thei schul han"; thus hir book sei&thorn;, woot I wel;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="771" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(771)</HEAD>
<L N="5391">&para; "But verray pees may be had by no way,</L>
<L>But if trouth&euml; and Iustice lou&euml;d be;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at &aacute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">o R.</NOTE> kyng ha&thorn; right, forthi may</L>
<L>By matrimoign&euml; pees and vnite</L>
<L N="5395">Ben had;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Henry V's marriage with Francis's daughter Katherine. 'Cesynge' (l. 5397) turnd out in the end to be 'aggravating.'</NOTE> crist&euml;s plesance is swiche; &thorn;us he</L>
<L>That right heir is, may &thorn;e rem&euml; reioyse,</L>
<L N="5397">Cesynge al strif, debate, or werre, or noyse."
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="195"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="772" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(772)</HEAD>
<L N="5398">&para; Now syn &thorn;e wey is open, as ye see,</L>
<L>How pees to gete in vertuous manere,</L>
<L>ffor loue of him &thorn;at dide vppon &thorn;e tree,</L>
<L>And of Mary, his blysful modir dere,</L>
<L N="5402">ffolwe&thorn; &thorn;at way, and your strif leye on bere;</L>
<L>Purchaseth pees by wey of mar&iuml;age,</L>
<L N="5404">And ye &thorn;erinne schul fynden auauntage.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="773" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(773)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now, pees! approche, and dryue out werre &amp; strif!</L>
<L>ffrenchepe! appere, and bannyssh&euml; thow hate!</L>
<L>Tranquillite! reu&euml; &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">thou reve R.</NOTE> ire hir lif<MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That feruent is, and leef for to debate!</L>
<L N="5409">Ye thre vertu&euml;s, now late see abate</L>
<L>The malice of &thorn;e foul&euml; vices thre,</L>
<L N="5411">&THORN;at verray foos ben to al christiante.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="774" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(774)</HEAD>
<L N="5412">&para; O cristen princes! for &thorn;e loue and awe</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at is &thorn;e king of king&euml;s al,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle, falle, galle R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nessheth<NOTE PLACE="foot">Softeth R.</NOTE> your hert&euml;s, and to pees yow drawe!</L>
<L>Considereth what good may &thorn;erof fal!<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle, falle, galle R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5416">The hony taki&thorn;, and leuyth &thorn;e gal!<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle, falle, galle R.</NOTE></L>
<L>The stern&euml; iug&euml; in his iug&euml;ment</L>
<L N="5418">May doo but right for his punysch&euml;ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="775" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(775)</HEAD>
<L N="5419">&para; What desobe&iuml;ssance and r&eacute;bellioun,</L>
<L>What wil vnbuxum, what vnkynd&euml;nesse,</L>
<L>May he preue in yow, &thorn;at destrucc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Don of men, his handwerk, soothly, I gesse.</L>
<L N="5423">It most&euml; ned&euml;s stire his rightwisnesse</L>
<L>A-geyn yow; stinte&thorn; at his reuerence,</L>
<L N="5425">Sueth his grace and his beneuolence!
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="196"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="776" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(776)</HEAD>
<L N="5426">&para; ffrom henn&euml;s-forth lat &thorn;ere by-twixe yow be</L>
<L>So vertuous a strif,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyfe R.</NOTE> for crist&euml;s sake,</L>
<L>That ye of pees and loue and charite</L>
<L>May striu&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">be R.</NOTE>; lat your pite now a-wake,</L>
<L>That longe ha&thorn; slept; and pees bytwixt yow make;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e foos of crist, your r&eacute;demptour,</L>
<L N="5432">Werreth! th&eacute;re kitheth your vigour!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="777" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(777)</HEAD>
<L N="5433">&para; Vppon &thorn;e mescreantys to mak&euml; werre,</L>
<L>And hem vnto the feith of crist to brynge,</L>
<L><SUP>3</SUP>Good were; therynne may ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">he R.</NOTE> no thyng erre,</L>
<L>That were a merit&oacute;rye werrying;<NOTE PLACE="foot">werreying R, werryng H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5437">That is the wey vn-to the conqueryng</L>
<L>Of hevenes<NOTE PLACE="foot">heven R.</NOTE> blyss&euml;, that is end&euml;les,</L>
<L>To which yow bryng&euml; the<NOTE PLACE="foot">the Actour R, thauctour H.</NOTE> auctour of pees. Amen!<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 In the much later hand than the rest of the poem, the same as wrote the first leaf.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="envoy">
<HEAD>[THE ENVOY<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Hoccleve's Minor Poems, i. 61.</NOTE>]<NOTE PLACE="head">from MS. Reg. 17 D vi, lf. 101 bk.&mdash;The last leaf has been torn out of Harl. 4866. Note the change of rymes.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="778" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(778)</HEAD>
<L N="5440">Olitell booke, who yafe the hardynesse</L>
<L>Thy word&euml;s to pronounce in the presence</L>
<L>Of kyng&euml;s Impe, and princes worthynesse,</L>
<L>Syn thou all naked art of eloquence?</L>
<L N="5444">And why approchest thou his excellence</L>
<L>Vnclothed, saue thy kirtell bare allone?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Also Phillipps MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>I am right sure his humble pac&iuml;ence</L>
<L N="5447">The yeueth hardyness&euml; so to done.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to do so, Phil.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="197"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="779" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(779)</HEAD>
<L N="5448">But o thyng wote I wele: go where thou go,</L>
<L>I am so priu&euml; [un]to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vn-to, Phillipps MS.</NOTE> thy sentence,</L>
<L>Thou hast, and art, and wolt ben euermo</L>
<L N="5451">To his hyenesse, of suche beneuolence,</L>
<L>Though thou not do to hym due reuerence</L>
<L>In wordes, thy cheerte not is the lesse.</L>
<L>And yf lust be, to his magnificence,</L>
<L>Do by thy rede: his welthe it shall witnesse!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="780" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(780)</HEAD>
<L N="5456">Beseche hym, of his gracious noblesse,</L>
<L>The holde excused of thyne Innocence</L>
<L>Of endityng; and with hertes mekenesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">humblesse, Phil.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5459">If ony thyng the passe of necligence,</L>
<L>Beseche hym of mercy and indulgence,</L>
<L>And that, for thy gode hert,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wil, Phil.</NOTE> he be not fo</L>
<L>To the &thorn;at all seest of loues feruence!</L>
<L>That knoweth he, that<NOTE PLACE="foot">god whom, Phil.</NOTE> no thyng is hidde fro.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Cest tout.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
